<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Prosecutor: Arrest Milosevic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) -- The new chief prosecutor of the  
Yugoslav war crimes tribunal said Wednesday her top priority was 
the arrest and trial of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and 
two Bosnian Serb warlords. 
</P>
<P>
	Carla Del Ponte, a former Swiss federal prosecutor, was on her  
first tour of the Balkans since she succeeded Louise Arbour of 
Canada last month at the international court in The Hague, 
Netherlands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Public indictments against war criminals my office already  
made are my top priority,'' Del Ponte said at a news conference in 
the Macedonian capital, Skopje. She planned to travel to Kosovo on 
Thursday, and then to Bosnia and Croatia later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribunal has indicted dozens of Serbs, Croats and Muslims  
for war crimes committed during the conflicts in Bosnia, Croatia 
and Kosovo. Many of those suspects, including Milosevic and Bosnian 
Serb wartime leaders Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic, remain at 
large. 
</P>
<P>
	``Milosevic, Karadzic and Mladic must be arrested and brought  
for trial,'' Del Ponte declared. ``Please write it down, so it 
might help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Del Ponte said more than 400 forensic experts had completed  
investigations at a quarter of the 450 alleged mass graves and war 
crimes sites in the Serbian province of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now our forensic investigative work will slow down during the  
winter months,'' she said. ``But we will return to Kosovo next 
spring because we have a lot of work to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic and four top associates were indicted for war crimes  
in connection with Yugoslavia's crackdown against Kosovar Albanians 
earlier this year. The crackdown led to NATO's bombing of 
Yugoslavia, which forced the Serb army and police out of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of ethnic Albanians are believed to have been killed  
by Serb forces. Del Ponte said the tribunal was also looking into 
possible crimes by ethnic Albanians against non-Albanians in 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was an armed conflict we found responsibility on both  
sides,'' Del Ponte said. ``We are concerned especially about high 
level responsibility in the military and political section.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Netherlands, the tribunal accused Serbia and Croatia  
Wednesday of hampering efforts to bring suspected criminals to 
justice. 
</P>
<P>
	In its sixth annual report, the tribunal said 35 people named in  
public indictments remained at large, mostly in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	But Serbia ``persists in its disregard for the rule of law,''  
refusing to extradite suspects or allow investigators access to 
potential crime scenes, the report said. Croatia, it said, was 
stalling on extraditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Croatia protested in a letter to the tribunal's president,  
Gabrielle Kirk McDonald, that said Zagreb had surrendered one 
suspect in August and approved the extradition of another, though 
the suspect's transfer was suspended because of illness. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
