<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Nears Crucial Budget Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House leaders readying for a crucial budget  
vote searched for support Wednesday as both parties vied to define 
the GOP's spending plans. Republicans said their proposed 
across-the-board cuts were prudent while Democrats called them 
destructive. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders tried putting the finishing touches on their  
effort to pare federal agencies' spending by about 1 percent across 
the board. At the same time, they lashed out at critics who said 
the GOP effort was drastic. 
</P>
<P>
	In particular, they attacked Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the  
Joint Chiefs of Staff, who told the Senate Armed Services Committee 
on Tuesday that the across-the-board reductions would have a 
``devastating'' effect on the military. Even with the cuts, they 
noted, the Pentagon spending bill that President Clinton signed 
Monday would be about $265 billion -- nearly $2 billion higher than 
the amount Clinton requested in February. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was political rhetoric coming out of the Pentagon,'' said  
GOP Sen. Ted Stevens of Alaska, chairman of the Senate 
Appropriations Committee. ``I've got to tell you, this has gone too 
far now for us to not remember.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, said accusations the  
cuts would hurt defense were ``nothing but hogwash.'' He said the 
criticism was coming from ``the same officials who have sat by idly 
as the president has hollowed out the armed forces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP comments came as party leaders hunted for votes for a  
massive bill that includes the cuts, about $314 billion for labor, 
health and education programs, plus money for the District of 
Columbia's budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans leaders want Congress to vote Thursday on the  
measure, which would let them say they have sent Clinton all 13 
spending bills for the new fiscal year. But they continued to find 
resistance from lawmakers reluctant to expose highway projects, 
defense or other programs to the cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has promised to veto the measure because of the spending  
cuts and the bill's failure to provide $1.4 billion he wants to 
hire teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are even set to enact an across-the-board spending cut  
that would have a destructive impact on our efforts to educate our 
children, protect our environment, and modernize our military,'' 
Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans say the across-the-board savings could come from  
federal waste. Their plan is designed to let them claim they are 
not dipping into Social Security surpluses to pay for government 
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats criticized other GOP proposals for saving money as  
well. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Institutes of Health's budget for fiscal 2000 would  
be $17.9 billion, $2.3 billion more than this year. But Republicans 
would require that $7.5 billion of it not be spent until next Sept. 
27, just four days from the end of the fiscal year, preventing most 
of it from being charged to fiscal 2000's books. 
</P>
<P>
	``What you're doing is destroying the continuity of research in  
this country over a political fiction,'' said Rep. David Obey of 
Wisconsin, the top Democrat on the House Appropriations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said the delayed spending would have little effect  
on scientists, who could maneuver around it. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans also were claiming $877 million in savings by using  
a computer database of newly hired workers to track down people who 
defaulted on student loans. The nonpartisan Congressional Budget 
Office says the idea would only save $130 million, but Republicans 
are using a more generous estimate used by Clinton's White House 
budget office. 
</P>
<P>
	Both parties have pledged to leave Social Security surpluses  
alone to position themselves as defenders of the pension system, 
even though both have routinely spent the money for decades without 
weakening the program. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, congressional leaders prepared to vote Thursday or  
Friday on another week-long extension of the authority many 
agencies need to keep functioning through the budget impasse. 
Clinton is expected to sign it.	   The most recent extension, the second so far this year, expires 
Friday night. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
