<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Irvin's Return to Game Clouded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Michael Irvin's return to the Dallas Cowboys from  
a spinal injury earlier this month was clouded as the team 
announced that Irvin was born with a spinal condition that 
increases his risk of further injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mike was born with a different-looking spine,'' Cowboys owner  
Jerry Jones said on Tuesday. ``How does that impact any decision he 
might make? To me, I've heard more discussed about what he was born 
with than I have about any damage'' incurred from the spinal 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	The condition, known as cervical stenosis, is basically a  
narrowing of the spinal canal. The congenital defect is relatively 
safe, team officials said, but the condition puts Irvin's spinal 
cord at greater risk because serious trauma can increase pressure 
and damage to the injured area. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1986, Green Bay cornerback Tim Lewis and Houston Oilers  
linebacker Frank Bush retired finding out they had narrow spinal 
canals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I'm concerned,'' Jones said. ``They're addressing  
everything. I don't see this as necessarily totally decided by 
whether or not the swelling goes down. Right now, I don't know if 
that's the issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cervical stenosis was initially revealed along with the  
spinal swelling when Irvin had a MRI exam after being knocked out 
of the game against Philadelphia on Oct. 10. Jones refused to say 
if the 33-year-old all-time leading receiver will return. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin was unavailable for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	``There are still more questions that need to be answered over  
the next several weeks,'' Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer said. 
</P>
<P>
	A few days after the injury, Maurer said Irvin had been cleared  
to ride a stationary bicycle and do other conditioning exercises. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin is scheduled for another MRI tomorrow. X-rays taken Monday  
showed nothing new in terms of Irvin's genetic condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones told reporters surgery is not an option for Irvin.  
</P>
<P>
	The 12-year veteran said said last week that no one had advised  
him to retire. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin's injury occurred when he awkwardly fell headfirst into  
the Veterans Stadium artificial turf as he was being tackled. He 
immediately lost feeling in his extremities and couldn't move his 
hands or legs for more than 15 minutes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
