<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Up 92.76 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *By EILEEN GLANTON    	
</P>
<P>
                         *AP Business Writer    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A late rally in the bond market carried over to  
Wall Street Wednesday, lifting financial stocks and pulling the Dow 
industrials out of the narrow range where they had traded most of 
the session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 92.76 to close at  
10,394.89. Much of the Dow's gains came in the final hour of 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
rose 14.80 to 1,296.71, but the Nasdaq composite index fell 8.95 to 
2,802.52. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices rose for the first time in a week after a report in  
Europe suggested the European Central Bank may raise interest rates 
on Nov. 4, making its own effort to hold off inflation before it 
endangers economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are signs that the falling inflation rate has begun to  
turn higher in some countries,'' said Thomas M. McManus, equity 
portfolio strategist at NationsBanc Montgomery Securities. 
``Clearly, it's happening in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But while fears of inflation have pounded bond and stock prices  
in recent months, analysts said bonds benefited Wednesday from the 
sense that central bankers around the world are working to hold off 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond fell to 6.33 percent,  
from 6.37 percent late Tuesday. Rising yields can make bonds more 
attractive than stocks, so the drop Wednesday heartened Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists expect the Federal Reserve to raise interest  
rates for the third time this year when its Open Market Committee 
meets Nov. 16. Speculation that Europe will move first on interest 
rates fostered hopes that resolution of the inflation problem is 
drawing near, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank stocks rose solidly. J.P. Morgan soared 7 1/8 to 128 1/2,  
Citigroup gained 2 13/16 to 51 5/16 and Chase Manhattan rose 4 
15/16 to 82 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those stocks have really been laggards'' due to fears of  
rising rates, McManus said. ``It finally appears that it's time for 
them to come back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks got a modest lift from a Commerce Department report that  
showed orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured goods 
fell 1.3 percent in September, the first decline in five months. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline was sharper than many analysts had expected, and  
offered some indication that the pace of U.S. economic growth may 
be tapering off. But analysts said Thursday's reports on the 
employment cost index and the gross domestic product will provide a 
clearer indication of the nation's economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were mostly lower. Hewlett-Packard, a Dow  
component, fell 6 1/4 to 70 3/8 after a Merrill Lynch analyst raised 
concerns about sales and earnings in the company's fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel fell 2 to 69 7/16 after Salomon Smith Barney cut its  
earnings estimates for the fourth quarter and for 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Online auctioneer eBay fell 13 5/16 to 138 11/16. The company  
said after the close of trading Tuesday its quarterly operating 
profits rose, beating analysts' expectations, after it signed up a 
record number of new users. But the company's profit margin fell, 
which caught some investors by surprise. EBay also recorded fewer 
transactions for new users, raising concerns about future growth. 
</P>
<P>
	After the market closed, online retailer Amazon.com reported a  
third-quarter loss that was narrower than most analysts had 
expected. Amazon shares, which lost 5 5/16 to 75 15/16 during the 
regular session, rose to 77 1/8 in after-hours trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past two weeks, corporate earnings reports have given the  
market some sporadic relief from the lingering worries about 
inflation. But as the profit reports end and are no longer a 
distraction, the market may remain in a relatively narrow range, 
said Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum 
&AMP; Co. in Kansas City, Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	``With most of the third-quarter earnings news out, stocks will  
likely return to an interest rate and Fed-watch stance over the 
next several days,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange. On the Nasdaq, decliners outnumbered 
advancers by a 10-to-9 margin. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE composite volume totaled 1.12 billion shares, compared with  
1.06 billion in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.98 to 416.77.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.6 percent.  
Germany's DAX index fell 0.5 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 
0.8 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.3 percent. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
