<DOCNO> APW19991027.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 08:03:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 77 Pitches One Too Many for Glavine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As each inning went by, Atlanta manager Bobby  
Cox and pitching coach Leo Mazzone marveled at their good fortune. 
</P>
<P>
	Tommy Glavine, who spent the weekend in bed with the flu, was  
cruising by the New York Yankees in Game 3 of the World Series, 
using remarkably few pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox, taking a conservative position, had hoped for seven innings  
from the left-hander, and he got that with very little trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he pressed for one more, and that got him in very big  
trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	In seven innings, Glavine threw just 73 pitches. He was leading  
5-3 and looked extremely comfortable, even after surrendering home 
runs to Chad Curtis and Tino Martinez. 
</P>
<P>
	``The home run by Martinez was a hanging slider,'' Glavine said.  
``It was the only mistake I made all night,'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the dugout as the Braves batted in the eighth, the manager  
and his pitcher talked. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was discussion, yes,'' Glavine said. ``I felt fine. I  
went back out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just in case, though, Cox had closer John Rocker warming up.  
</P>
<P>
	``Tommy Glavine was throwing great,'' the manager said. ``Didn't  
want to come out of the game. I asked him if he was tired, and he 
said no. We all thought he was throwing great. Tommy thought he was 
throwing great himself and I thought he was throwing good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With all precincts agreeing, Rocker stayed in the bullpen and  
Glavine went to the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	The first batter in the eighth was Joe Girardi, and he lined  
Glavine's first pitch, No. 74 of the game, into right field for a 
single. Glavine never flinched and Cox never moved. 
</P>
<P>
	Next up was Chuck Knoblauch.  
</P>
<P>
	Pitch No. 75 was outside and so was No. 76, putting the pitcher  
in a 2-0 hole, the kind of count hitters love. Still, Cox sat stone 
still in the dugout. This was obviously Glavine's game. He was six 
outs away from a win, three outs away from Rocker. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought Tommy could get at least a couple of outs,'' Cox  
said. ``He was throwing real good. There was no reason to take him 
out, really.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then Knoblauch provided a reason.  
</P>
<P>
	He hit Glavine's 77th pitch to right field. Brian Jordan went  
back as far as he could and jumped as high as he could. The ball 
hit his glove and caromed over the wall for the two-run homer that 
tied the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine was flabbergasted.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was down and away, pretty much where I wanted it,'' he said  
of the turning-point pitch. ``A pop fly to right field turns out to 
be a two-run homer. Here, it's a home run. Everywhere else, it's an 
out. The game was played here. It counted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cox came and got Glavine at that point, bewildered at what he  
said was a 315-foot home run, convinced that his pitcher really got 
the out the manager thought he would. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's an out in my book,'' Cox said. ``But here, it's not.''  
</P>
<P>
	After that, it seemed just a matter of time. Curtis' second home  
run of the game settled the issue in the 10th inning against 
reliever Mike Remlinger, giving the Yankees a 6-5 victory and 
positioning them for their second straight World Series sweep. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got beat by two pop flies to right field that carried,'' he  
said. ``It was bad luck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's the only kind the Braves have had in this World Series.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
