<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Deadlocks in Hirschfeld Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A mistrial was declared Tuesday after a jury was  
unable to reach a verdict on whether real estate developer Abe 
Hirschfeld tried to hire a hitman to kill his business partner. 
</P>
<P>
	State Supreme Court Justice Harold Beeler declared the mistrial,  
the second in a Hirschfeld trial this year, on the sixth day after 
deliberations began. Jurors said the final vote was six for 
conviction, six to acquit. 
</P>
<P>
	Hirschfeld, 79, did not comment. Prosecutors said a retrial is  
likely. 
</P>
<P>
	Beeler allowed the parking garage magnate to remain free on $1  
million bail pending a hearing Friday on whether he violated a 
court order against commenting publicly about the case during the 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Hirschfeld, former owner of the New York Post, was charged with  
second-degree criminal solicitation. He allegedly gave Joseph 
Veltri, one of his building contractors, $75,000 in 1996 as a down 
payment to a hit man to kill his real estate investment partner of 
40 years. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sept. 2, a jury was unable to reach a verdict on whether  
Hirschfeld evaded millions of dollars in state and city personal 
and corporate income taxes. Prosecutors say that case will be 
retried. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
