<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing, Airbus Sweeten El Al Offers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- U.S. aircraft manufacturer Boeing and its  
European competitor Airbus have improved their bids to replace part 
of the Israeli airline El Al's passenger fleet, a spokesman said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The new bids came as El Al continues to delay deciding whether  
to buy the Boeing 777 airliner or the Airbus A330, a tactic that 
Israel's transportation minister recommended to induce 
manufacturers to sweeten their offers. 
</P>
<P>
	El Al's decision was originally to have been taken by early  
spring but has been postponed repeatedly. 
</P>
<P>
	Airbus is battling to break Boeing's hold on the Israeli market.  
El Al's present fleet consists entirely of Boeing aircraft, and 
Israel is under strong pressure from the U.S. to keep it that way. 
</P>
<P>
	If Israel -- which receives $3 billion annually in U.S. foreign  
aid -- were to buy the less expensive Airbus jets, it could pave the 
way for other countries that receive substantial U.S. aid to grant 
more military contracts to non-U.S. manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	El Al executives were to have convened Tuesday evening to make  
the choice. On Monday, however, the two manufacturers made new, 
more favorable offers verbally, El Al spokesman Nachman Klieman 
said. The bids were submitted in writing Tuesday, Klieman said, and 
the meeting was postponed to give the executives time to analyze 
the new figures. 
</P>
<P>
	El Al executives were to meet again Wednesday evening, Klieman  
said, though a decision may not come until later. 
</P>
<P>
	El Al has said the four Airbus planes will cost $350  
million-$400 million. However Airbus was offering to subcontract 35 
percent of the contract value to Israel Aircraft Industries, the 
European consortium's commercial director John Leahy said last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Airbus bid offered to direct 50 percent of the contract  
value to IAI, the Israeli daily Haaretz said. Neither Klieman nor 
officials from either company would release details of the new 
bids. 
</P>
<P>
	Leahy has said Airbus is prepared to take a loss to break the  
Boeing monopoly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
