<HEADLINE> Soybeans Rise on U.S. Export Talk / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures rose Wednesday, buoyed by talk  
that China may be buying several shipments of U.S. soybeans. Grains 
were mostly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The advance in soybeans came a day after the price fell to an  
eight-week low. But gains were limited by welcome rains in Brazil 
and Argentina that soaked dry growing areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said China was reported to have bought one cargo of  
American soybeans and may purchase three or four more by week's 
end. 
</P>
<P>
	The corn futures market was stagnant again, with prices stuck on  
about $2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also was little changed, halting the slide of the day  
before with relatively light trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 1/4 cent to $2.56 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1 1/4 cent to $2.00 1/2 a bushel; December oats were 
unchanged at $1.10 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1 cent to 
$4.69 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	December live cattle fell .37 cent to 67.90 cents a pound;  
November feeder cattle fell .48 cent to 79.52 cents a pound; 
December lean hogs fell 1.85 cents to 46.40 cents a pound; February 
frozen pork bellies fell 2.33 cents to 62.02 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
