<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stockbrokers Found Shot to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLTS NECK, N.J. (AP) -- Two stockbrokers were found shot to  
death at the estate where one lived with his girlfriend, and 
authorities had few leads in what they consider an ``execution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a definite `whodunit.' In the majority of homicides we  
have a pretty clear-cut idea, even if we can't prove who did it 
right away, we at least have a pretty good idea who did it,'' 
Monmouth County Prosecutor John Kaye said. ``This is very 
different.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police called to the house early Tuesday found Alan Chalem, 41,  
and Mayir Lehmann, 37, shot to death in the foyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Chalem lived on the 16-acre property with his girlfriend,  
Kimberly Scarola, and her 13-year-old son. Lehmann lived in 
Woodmere, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Both were stockbrokers and dealt in penny stocks, but Kaye  
didn't know whether their profession had anything to do with their 
deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know, but there was no burglary involved,'' Kaye said.  
``That was never a thought. This was an execution. Reasons, we're 
not certain yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kay said two workmen made the emergency call to police in this  
community of 8,500 about 10 miles northwest of Asbury Park. The men 
had arranged to pick up some molding at the house at 1 a.m., Kaye 
said, adding that both were friends of Chalem's. 
</P>
<P>
	Lehmann had been shot once in the back of the head, while Chalem  
had been shot repeatedly, Kaye said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Scarola was in Florida, where she had gone several days  
earlier. Her son was with her ex-husband. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
