<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Gaining in New Hampshire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Told that a New Hampshire voter had just  
attended his fifth John McCain town meeting, the Republican 
presidential candidate said: ``There is one thing about New 
Hampshire that I've always believed and now I'm totally sure: They 
want to see you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added, chuckling, ``Although it may also be testimony to my  
inability to close the deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Laughing aside, McCain's attention to the nation's first primary  
state appears to be paying off. 
</P>
<P>
	A Research 2000 survey released last weekend by the Concord  
Monitor showed Texas Gov. George W. Bush retaining his front-runner 
status with 39 percent of the vote, but McCain in a solid second 
place with 27 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll confirmed a steady upward creep since August, when Bush  
had 45 percent of the vote and McCain had just 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A New Hampshire poll released last Thursday showed Bush with 42  
percent of the vote and McCain with 26 percent. That was virtually 
unchanged for Bush since August, but a 10-point improvement for 
McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark Hubbard, a political science professor at the University  
of New Hampshire, said would-be voters undoubtedly like the Arizona 
senator's personality. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got an image of being a Republican iconoclast, a party  
maverick. That's the kind of politician that the voters want to 
hear from,'' Hubbard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Vavreck, an assistant government professor at Dartmouth  
College, said McCain's numbers have crept upward simply because 
more people have gotten to know him. 
</P>
<P>
	The senator, the descendant of Navy admirals and a former  
prisoner of war, has been riding a wave of publicity since the 
release of his memoirs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this is just a natural thing,'' Vavreck said.  
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, McCain's improvement has set off alarm bells within  
the Bush organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush advisers concede privately there is a perception that the  
governor is being handled too much and needs to get out in public 
more, especially in early voting states like New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain has decided to skip the Iowa caucuses on Jan. 24 and  
focus on the Feb. 1 New Hampshire primary. Bush aides are concerned 
that a strong showing by McCain there, coupled with a strong finish 
South Carolina's Feb. 19 primary, where McCain also is 
concentrating, could propel him into a slugfest with the governor. 
</P>
<P>
	There is also concern that Bush has been distracted by  
fund-raising as he has generated $57 million for his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the governor visited Massachusetts Sept 26 to  
attend the Ryder Cup golf tournament -- and a fund-raiser. On Sept. 
29, he visited Riverside, Calif. -- and attended a fund-raiser. 
Neither state holds its primary until March 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's lack of attention to New Hampshire has been publicly  
criticized state Republican party activists and would-be voters 
alike. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like so far the publicity is selling him to us,'' said  
Volker Bradley, 62, a doctor from Newport, N.H., as he waited for 
Bush to appear last week at a town diner called the Country 
Kitchen. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's visit to Newport and Keene, N.H., was just his fifth trip  
to the state this year. He has spent less time campaigning in New 
Hampshire than all his rivals except Sen. Orrin Hatch, who recently 
scored a zero in a public opinion poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's opponents lambasted him for leaving New Hampshire last  
Friday just hours before they gathered for their first debate in 
Durham, N.H. He also will miss a debate Thursday in Manchester, 
N.H. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking with reporters after visiting the restaurant and  
shaking hands for over an hour at the Newport fire house, Bush 
explained that he was missing the debates because of prior 
commitments. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week's debate conflicted with a party fund-raiser in  
Vermont; this week's conflicts with a ceremony in which Bush's 
wife, Laura, will receive an alumni award from Southern Methodist 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said he should be judged on the quality of his visits, not  
the quantity. He spoke about the size of his crowds and the 
personal attention he paid to everyone attending. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question that frequency of visits are important,  
and I'll be here a lot, but as importantly is, how many people have 
I seen and what kind of organization do we have, and we're really 
well organized,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a state that sends messages all the time, and I'm  
going to work hard to make sure it doesn't send a message to me,'' 
Bush said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
