<DOCNO> APW19991027.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 07:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Galapagos Film Shows Islands in 3-D </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new look at the exotic Galapagos Islands  
brings viewers face to face with wildlife and lets them swim with 
the fishes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Galapagos,'' an IMAX giant-screen movie in 3-D, opens today at  
the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of Natural History. 
</P>
<P>
	Co-produced by the Smithsonian and the IMAX Corp., the film uses  
real scientists on screen -- showing their joy of discovery. 
</P>
<P>
	And discover they did, squeezing in enough research to identify  
more than a dozen new marine species during the 14 weeks of 
filming. 
</P>
<P>
	The new 3-D technology places viewers in a school of fish,  
brings them face to face with a moray eel and close to hammerhead 
sharks. And on land, lizards leer at the camera while tortoises 
ramble on past, seeming oblivious. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, a fish scooped up by researchers with an  
underwater vacuum opens its mouth wide in seeming surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	Star of the film is marine biologist Carole Baldwin, the camera  
following her first visit to the strange islands that inspired 
Charles Darwin to develop his theory of evolution. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I was chosen because I had never been there, and they  
wanted a scientist with fresh eyes, someone the audience could 
follow,'' she said in an interview. ``It was fantastic. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing missing in the theater is the cold and wet,''  
she said. ``Otherwise, you're there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Baldwin didn't settle for just making a movie.  
</P>
<P>
	``My goal was science,'' she said. ``The filmmaker's goal was  
certainly to make a film. The film was being funded by the 
Smithsonian Institution and IMAX, so the idea was to make the film 
about research.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The scientists, now back at the museum, must take each of their  
new finds and compare it with thousands of others in the 
Smithsonian collection to verify it was not previously known. 
Baldwin estimated that there were ``dozens'' of new finds. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers used a submersible vessel to study the largely  
unexplored waters 200 feet to 1,000 feet deep. The area is too deep 
for scuba diving, and previous studies using submersibles 
concentrated on deeper waters. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers and film crews stayed 14 weeks in the Galapagos with  
the only two IMAX 3-D cameras in the world. They visited more than 
80 locations, including dives in the four-person submersible. 
</P>
<P>
	The new species found, including a new cat shark, several new  
scorpion fish, new types of bass and new types of sponges, urchins 
and gastropod mollusks, will be added to the Natural History 
Museum's 8 million-specimen collection of preserved fish. They also 
will be added to the collections of the Charles Darwin Research 
Station in the Galapagos, the California Academy of Sciences and 
the Ecuadorian Navy Oceanographic Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Located on the equator 600 miles west of South America, the  
Galapagos have been called the laboratory of evolution because of 
its strange plants and animals. The islands are owned by Ecuador. 
</P>
<P>
	The new film will alternate with other films at the museum's  
IMAX theater. Admission is free. Later, it will tour other IMAX 
theaters around the world. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
