<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves' Plan Falls Apart in Game 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Atlanta Braves had a plan to make this a  
competitive World Series. The hitters had to be more patient. Tom 
Glavine had to come through with seven solid innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Everything was going just as they hoped in Game 3 Tuesday night.  
</P>
<P>
	Until it all fell apart.  
</P>
<P>
	Now, the Braves find themselves all but buried in a 3-0 hole, as  
the New York Yankees rallied from a 5-1 deficit to beat Atlanta 6-5 
on Chad Curtis' 10th-inning homer. 
</P>
<P>
	``That game was ours to win,'' Glavine moaned.  
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the Braves are one loss from spending the offseason  
trying to figure out how they came up short once again, a decade of 
excellence impaired by only one World Series title. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was a big one to lose,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``We  
were going to get back in this thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a lost weekend at Turner Field, in which Atlanta managed  
only seven hits and three runs in two dreary losses, the Braves 
spent their day off taking some extra batting practice at Yankee 
Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	It paid off. Every starter had at least one hit, including three  
straight doubles by Bret Boone, who just happened to be one of 
three players benched for Game 2 in a futile attempt to jumpstart 
the offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking a page from New York, the Braves kept working the count  
to three balls and hitting toward the opposite field. By the fourth 
inning, they had knocked out New York starter Andy Pettitte. At the 
end, they had 14 hits. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were patient and driving the ball the other way,'' Brian  
Jordan said. ``That's what you have to do with Andy Pettitte.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves left eight runners on base through the first five  
innings, but it didn't seem all that important with Glavine 
producing a gutsy effort that belied his fragile health. 
</P>
<P>
	The left-hander was supposed to start Game 1, but wound up  
watching from bed with a debilitating case of stomach flu. 
</P>
<P>
	The bug knocked seven pounds off Glavine's slender frame, and he  
was still a few pounds short when he walked to the mound three days 
later than expected. At least some of the color had returned to his 
face, a ghastly shade of pale just a day earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt fine,'' Glavine said. ``I felt better than I probably  
anticipated and felt sharper than I anticipated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, Cox expressed confidence that his pitcher  
could come through with seven solid innings. Then, presumably, the 
game would be turned over to the bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine walked off the mound at the prescribed moment with a 5-3  
lead. Unfortunately for the Braves, Cox sent his starter back to 
the mound for the eighth, convinced he could last one more inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Two batters later, the two-run cushion was gone, wiped out by  
Joe Girardi's single and Chuck Knoblauch's two-run homer that 
barely cleared the 314-foot sign down the right-field line and 
deflected off the glove of leaping Brian Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tommy Glavine was throwing great tonight,'' Cox said,  
defending his decision. ``I know everybody's going to ask why I 
left him in, this and that, but Tommy was throwing great. He didn't 
want to come out of the game. I asked him if he was tired and he 
said no.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine threw only 77 pitches, which turned out to be one too  
many. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tonight was bad luck,'' he said. ``A 315-foot pop-up turns  
into a home run. That ball is not a home run anywhere but here. 
They took advantage of it and we didn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two innings later, Curtis put the Braves out of their misery  
with his second homer of the game, a mammoth shot on the third 
pitch from reliever Mike Remlinger. 
</P>
<P>
	After throwing a couple of fastballs, Remlinger tried to fool  
Curtis with a changeup. But the pitch hung over the plate and 
didn't come down until it landed in the Atlanta bullpen, more than 
430 feet away. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no better situation to throw a changeup,'' Remlinger  
said. ``But it didn't have the down action I wanted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Curtis was carried off on the shoulders of his teammates, while  
the Braves trudged off the field with Frank Sinatra's rendition of 
``New York, New York'' and chants of ``Sweep! Sweep! Sweep!'' 
ringing in their ears. 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't part of the plan. No team has ever rallied from an  
0-3 deficit in a best-of-7 series. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, do we want to go home or do we want to face the  
challenge,'' Remlinger asked. ``Do we want to fight or fold? Do we 
want to lose four in a row or do we want to put up a fight? It's a 
similar situation to where the Mets were, and they showed a lot of 
heart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was referring to the NL Championship Series, when New York's  
other team lost the first three games to Atlanta, then rallied for 
two thrilling victories. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, it must be noted that the Mets lost the series in  
Game 6. Still, the Braves would gladly take their chances if they 
could get back to Atlanta. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
