<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seattle Times To Be Morning Only </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle Times will become an all-morning  
newspaper on March 6, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times, now an afternoon publication on weekdays and a  
morning paper on weekends and holidays, announced earlier this year 
that it would switch to all-morning publication and compete 
head-to-head with the Seattle Post-Intelligencer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times cited two reasons for the change: traffic congestion  
made it harder to deliver its afternoon editions and readers 
increasingly prefer morning papers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times, owned by the Blethen family, has a daily circulation  
of about 230,000 and a Sunday circulation of about 504,000. The 
P-I, owned by the Hearst Corp., has a daily circulation of about 
200,000. Under a 16-year-old joint operating agreement, the Times 
is responsible for selling advertising as well as printing and 
distributing both newspapers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
