<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Derrick Coleman Arrested for DWI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Charlotte Hornets power forward Derrick  
Coleman was arrested early today for driving while under the 
influence after the car he was driving collided with a 
tractor-trailer, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coleman, Hornets backup guard Eldridge Recasner and a third  
passenger in Coleman's vehicle, Ebony Kimbrough, were injured in 
the accident which occurred at 12:51 a.m. and taken to Carolinas 
Medical Center, Charlotte-Mecklenburg police spokesman Tom Barry 
said. The truck driver was unhurt. 
</P>
<P>
	After being booked at the Charlotte jail for DWI, Coleman was  
taken to the medical center, where Recasner also was a patient. 
Officials at the center referred calls on the players' conditions 
to the Hornets, where a spokesman said he would release information 
later today. Kimbrough was in fair condition, center spokesman 
Scott White said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coleman, a nine-year pro signed by the Hornets last year, has  
averaged 12.2 points, 6.0 rebounds and 2.3 assists in six 
exhibition games. Last season, he was limited to 37 games because 
of foot and ankle problems. 
</P>
<P>
	In August, Coleman was accused of urinating in front of patrons  
at a downtown Detroit restaurant and charged with disorderly 
conduct. Coleman denied any wrongdoing, saying he spilled a drink 
on himself. 
</P>
<P>
	He also faces a civil lawsuit in Michigan in which he is accused  
of trespassing and battery at a Detroit woman's home in 1997. 
Coleman's attorney in that case has said the allegation is untrue. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Coleman was arrested and charged with refusing to move  
his truck and swearing at a police officer in Detroit. The jury 
failed to reach a verdict and the case ended in a mistrial. 
</P>
<P>
	Recasner was signed by the Hornets as a free agent last January.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
