<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates Skip Over Some Realities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore declared Wednesday that  
he has high standards in campaign fund-raising but neglected to 
mention the controversy he got into over money and politics in the 
1996 election. 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, rival Bill Bradley projected ``enormous savings''  
in administrative costs from his health care plan -- savings that 
analysts say he may be hard-pressed to find. 
</P>
<P>
	The rivals for the Democratic nomination did not appear to make  
any major mistakes in their Wednesday night debate in Hanover, N.H. 
But they skipped over some uncomfortable realities. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore attacked Bradley for supporting school vouchers that would  
use tax money to send children to private schools. ``That's one 
area where we disagree,'' the vice president said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bradley has not endorsed school vouchers. He says he doesn't  
think they are the answer to the problems of public education, but 
is awaiting results from a few experimental voucher programs. He 
had voted in the Senate for some pilot projects using school 
vouchers. 
</P>
<P>
	The former New Jersey senator, under attack from Gore for his  
plan to expand health insurance to all children and many more 
adults, estimated the cost at $65 billion a year, to come largely 
from the budget surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said huge savings would be achieved by program  
efficiencies and transferring paperwork to the Internet. He 
estimated administrative costs in health care at $250 billion a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The implication that there is a lot of that to save is one  
that is questionable,'' said Kathleen Jamieson, dean of the 
Annenberg School of Communication, who is tracking the candidates 
on issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Health reformers often talk of saving money by cutting waste,  
she said. ``But when people start looking at that, they don't find 
(that much) waste, fraud and abuse to eliminate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley used the $250 billion figure before -- in a Sept. 28  
health care speech, but said then that figure included more than 
just administrative overhead, such as redundant tests and 
unnecessary care. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamieson also found rhetorical excess in Gore's accusation that  
Bradley would ``shred the safety net'' by using up the budget 
surplus with his social spending programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's overstatement,'' she said. Bradley's programs -- for  
health care, anti-poverty and more -- by definition are part of a 
safety net, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You haven't shredded the safety net. You've created an  
alternative safety net.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore used an Emory University report to suggest Bradley has  
underestimated his $65 billion-a-year health plan. Gore said the 
report showed Bradley's plan over 10 years would cost closer to 
$1.2 trillion and eat up the entire projected federal budget 
surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't mention the study was written by a former Clinton  
administration health-policy analyst, Kenneth Thorpe. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, when his turn rolled around again, rose to dispute  
Gore's figure, saying he had his own analysts who put the costs of 
his plan much lower. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, Gore said, ``I follow a higher standard in my  
campaign'' by refusing political action committee donations from 
special interests. 
</P>
<P>
	But he made no mention of his own fund-raising troubles during  
the 1996 election, when he played a key role raising Democratic 
money for Clinton's re-election. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore was forced to admit that he made fund-raising calls from  
his White House office despite federal laws barring fund-raising on 
federal property. He said his lawyers had advised him there was no 
illegality in his calls but said in hindsight he wished he hadn't 
made them. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also was forced to belatedly acknowledge that he knew an  
event he attended at a Buddhist temple was a fund-raiser. He 
originally tried to portray it as a ``community outreach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors concluded that donations made at the event were  
illegal, but Gore was accused of no wrongdoing in either the temple 
event or the fund-raising calls. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes, the bottom line got lost in the proposals of both  
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore and Bradley touted the likely effects of their health care  
reforms, often failing to note the improvements would be phased in 
over many years. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, Gore said his plan ``gives coverage to 100 percent  
of all children.'' He didn't note that universal access wouldn't be 
reached until 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
