<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sony Profits Rise in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese electronics powerhouse Sony Corp.'s profit  
rose 3.1 percent in the second fiscal quarter but plunged nearly 25 
percent for the first half, depressed by the strong yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The results disclosed today come as Sony faces a sluggish  
economy at home and a surging yen that threatens to damage exports 
by making Japanese products more expensive overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony earned 46.5 billion yen, or $445 million, in the three  
months ended Sept. 30 compared with 45.1 billion yen a year 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales and operating revenue fell 6.8 percent to 1.6 trillion  
yen, or $15.3 billion, for the quarter from 1.7 trillion yen a year 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong yen not only hurts exports, it also means that  
dollars and other currencies earned overseas are worth less when 
converted into the home currency. 
</P>
<P>
	In the July-September quarter, for example, the yen averaged  
112.7 to the U.S. dollar -- 23.3 percent stronger than the same 
quarter a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony estimated that if the yen had held steady, sales would have  
increased 9 percent and sales would have risen 25 percent in the 
July-September quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``This rise in the yen had a significant negative impact on the  
reported financial results translated into yen,'' Sony said in its 
earnings statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The report says that sales in Sony's movie business decreased 19  
percent in the quarter. The second quarter got a boost from the Box 
Office success of ``Big Daddy' and ``Blue Streak'' but was hurt by 
``Muppets From Space'' and ``Jakob the Liar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Operating income from Sony's TV business, which is part of Sony  
Pictures, fell because of the loss of the sundication sales of 
``Seinfeld'' from last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for Sony Pictures would have been flat if the currency  
rate had remained the same. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half, consolidated net profits plunged 24.5  
percent to 64.9 billion yen, or $607 million, compared to 86.1 
billion yen last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales and operating revenue fell 7.6 percent to 3.1 trillion  
yen, or $29.1 billion in the first half from 3.4 trillion a year 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony is moving through a major transition. It announced in March  
that it would lay off 17,000 of its 170,000 workers and cut 
manufacturing plants from 70 to 55 during the next four years. Sony 
is trying to make computers and video games a bigger part of its 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony expects group operating profit for the full year to be less  
than previously forecast. The company did not release an updated 
forecast on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong yen has prompted calls for the government to  
intervene, since many fear it could stifle Japan's recovery from 
its worst economic downturn in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar figures provided by Sony were based on a calculation  
from yen using an average dollar-yen exchange rate for the period. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
