<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Catholic Priest Has TV Talk Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Father Alberto Cutie seems like a  
normal Catholic priest. He loves his congregation, counsels young 
people, marries couples and baptizes babies. 
</P>
<P>
	But he also has lots in common with Jerry Springer, Oprah  
Winfrey and Ricki Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	Just ask the fans who mob him after he wraps up filming a  
segment of Telemundo's new TV talk show ``Padre Alberto.'' Cutie's 
a star in the making, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	``A priest can give you a spirituality a psychologist can't,''  
said 58-year-old Carmen Torres, as she waits outside the studio of 
the Spanish-language network to get a photo snapped with the talk 
show priest. ``He is so cute, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cutie, who was born in San Juan, Puerto Rico, of Cuban parents  
30 years ago, said he was minding his own business when a network 
producer asked him to audition for the job. Cutie (pronounced 
Coo'-Tee'-AY), a priest at St. Patrick's Church on Miami Beach, 
beat 500 others who tried out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never pictured myself to be involved in television,'' he  
said, laughing. ``God surprises you all the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The one-hour show is a round-table discussion between Cutie and  
his guests on subjects ranging from domestic abuse and racism to 
youth violence and family relations. Guests include kids, mothers, 
psychologists, Latin celebrities and victims of bigotry. 
</P>
<P>
	The show is part confessional, part entertainment.  
</P>
<P>
	On a recent segment about teen violence, Alida Miranda brought  
her 17-year-old son, Jose, and asked Cutie for help. She said she 
was feeling desperate because she couldn't control her son. She 
feared he was a danger to others. 
</P>
<P>
	Cutie asked Jose why his mother felt this way. Jose admitted he  
stole things with his friends and sometimes carried a handgun. He 
said at times he felt like killing people. 
</P>
<P>
	``What do we do in a case like this?'' a startled Cutie asked  
clinical sociologist Gloria Rodriguez, a guest expert on 
relationships between parents and kids. 
</P>
<P>
	The expert urged Jose to stop hanging around friends or  
acquaintances who were a bad influence. She encouraged Jose to try 
to work on his relationship with his mother by talking and 
listening instead of arguing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know he is a good kid,'' Cutie told Jose's mother. ``If he  
really tries he can change his ways.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jose promised Cutie he would try to be a better son and turn his  
life around. He started to cry. 
</P>
<P>
	Nely Galan, Telemundo's president of entertainment, was  
vacationing in Mexico last year when she got the idea to have a 
priest as host of a talk show about common issues and problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kept thinking, 'What would I want to watch on TV? What would  
make me feel good?''' she said. ``I thought if I can find a priest 
to host a show it would be really great because they can guide you 
spiritually. It was not easy to convince people that a priest would 
work for a show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The show airs Monday through Friday at 4 p.m. EDT and, according  
to Telemundo, can be seen in at least 240,000 households in 63 U.S. 
cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Galan said Telemundo tapped Cutie because he was young, funny,  
energetic and in touch with young people. 
</P>
<P>
	At a recent taping, Cutie was a lively host, getting the  
audience of about 100 pumped up by dancing the hokeypokey and 
telling them jokes. 
</P>
<P>
	But as a talk show host, Cutie said he's not out to offend  
anyone. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is the one thing that I am afraid of,'' he said. ``I am  
not going to sit down with someone and exploit their problems. We 
want to solve them. The program is about the human heart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before leaving the studio, Cutie walks across the studio floor  
and praises crew members. Outside, dozens of fans wait to greet 
him. After listening patiently, he heads to his church to prepare 
for a busy weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't half as busy as I am in the parish,'' said Cutie.  
``This is like the sideshow. The parish is the big show.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	REAGAN ON `BIOGRAPHY': Anchor Harry Smith will interview Edmund  
Morris, the author of the controversial biography ``Dutch: A Memoir 
of Ronald Reagan,'' for Friday's ``Biography'' repeat of ``Ronald 
Reagan: The Role of a Lifetime.'' The program traces Reagan from 
his working-class childhood in Illinois, through his career as a 
Hollywood actor, to his two-term Presidency that helped define the 
legacy of the 1980s. The program, which includes interviews with Ed 
Meese, George Schultz, Michael Reagan and others, airs on A&AMP;E at 8 
p.m. EDT. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
