<DOCNO> APW19991027.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 16:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Surprises for These Coaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Coaching in the NFL these days is  
sometimes like a poker game in which every player can see the 
others' cards. 
</P>
<P>
	The coaching lineage that extends from Bill Walsh's San  
Francisco 49ers staffs of the 1980s and early 1990s has become 
crisscrossed and tangled throughout the league. Coaches who worked 
together in San Francisco before going on to larger 
responsibilities run into each other on the field almost every week 
during the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Holmgren, Ray Rhodes, Sherman Lewis, Steve Mariucci, Jon  
Gruden, George Seifert, Mike Shanahan and many others have taken 
the gospel of the West Coast offense and fanatical attention to 
detail throughout the nation in the last 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhodes and Lewis, the Green Bay Packers' coach and offensive  
coordinator, realize they can't show Holmgren much he hasn't seen 
when the Packers play host to the Seattle Seahawks on Monday night. 
But they also know their former boss and colleague won't have that 
many cards up his own sleeve, either. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we're going to trick each other,'' said Lewis,  
the Packers offensive coordinator under both Holmgren -- who left 
last January after seven seasons to become the Seahawks coach and 
GM -- and Rhodes, who was Holmgren's defensive coordinator for two 
seasons before head coaching stops in Philadelphia and Green Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to come down to what team executes the best,''  
Lewis said. ``They know what we do and we know what they do. We'll 
just try and disguise it a little bit with formations, (but) I'm 
sure they know that, and I know it, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many coaches also have moved on since working under Holmgren in  
Green Bay, where they turned a perennially mediocre franchise into 
a Super Bowl champion. When something works, coaches tend to stick 
with it -- and now variations of the same offense that worked so 
well for the 49ers and the Packers are being used throughout the 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you look at (the Seahawks) offense, it's a mirror of our  
offense,'' Rhodes said. ``You're dealing with a different cast, but 
it's a mirror.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In their preparations for Monday night's game, the Packers  
aren't trying to reinvent themselves. They simply hope better 
execution and quarterback Brett Favre make the difference. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've still got to win this football game,'' Favre said. ``I  
can't care less who's coming back. I love Mike to death, but that's 
the way it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers might have a slight edge in preparing for the  
Seahawks defense. Seattle defensive coordinator Jim Lind -- and the 
late Fritz Shurmur -- installed a system similar to the one they 
used while coaching under Holmgren in Green Bay, while the Packers 
have a largely new defense under coordinator Emmitt Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmgren has spent twice as much time in the film room in  
Seattle this week, trying to help Lind devise a scheme to stop 
Lewis' offense. He also has been working on a game plan against 
Thomas' defense, which stopped the San Diego Chargers cold in Green 
Bay's 31-3 win last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got a lot of talent on that coaching staff, and it's  
people who I know and respect very much,'' Holmgren said. ``It's 
going to be difficult to find ways of doing things that they 
haven't already thought of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And though the bonds of friendship also run deep through this  
coaching lineage, it won't affect what happens on the field. Rhodes 
and Gruden didn't take any hard feelings away from the Packers' 
victory over the Raiders earlier this season, and Rhodes and 
Holmgren will treat this game the same way. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody knows each other very well, and when you know each  
other this way, it makes for an interesting ballgame,'' Rhodes 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
