<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doubts Arise in S.C. Death Row Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- A woman's confession that she killed a  
state trooper has come days before a man is to be executed for that 
crime, but South Carolina's attorney general said Wednesday that 
the execution should go forward because the woman has a history of 
mental illness and is not credible. 
</P>
<P>
	The trooper's mother, however, said Richard Charles Johnson  
should not die Friday as scheduled while there were questions about 
his guilt and the state's Roman Catholic bishop joined Johnson's 
clemency plea to the governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Trooper Bruce K. Smalls was shot in 1985 after pulling over a  
motor home on Interstate 95 that Johnson and the woman were in. 
Johnson's first conviction in 1986 was overturned by the state 
Supreme Court. He was sentenced again to die after a 1988 trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 36, was convicted with the help of statements from  
Connie Sue Hess at his first trial, and her statement that he 
killed Smalls was used against Johnson at his second trial. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a sworn statement last week against the advice of a  
lawyer, Hess, now of Norfolk, Neb., said she killed Smalls. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess, who was 17 at the time, said she confessed now to ease her  
conscience. She said she lied originally ``because I did not want 
to die. The solicitor told me I would fry if I had anything to do 
with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Charlie Condon said, however, that Hess lacked  
credibility because of a history of mental illness. She currently 
lives in supervised housing for the mentally ill. 
</P>
<P>
	``Two juries have considered a mountain of evidence against  
Johnson and found him guilty,'' he said as he asked the state 
Supreme Court to reject a stay of execution. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess' statement prompted Bishop Robert J. Baker and Smalls'  
mother to ask for Gov. Jim Hodges for clemency for Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Hodges' spokeswoman said he would not comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson's lawyer questioned why Hess' testimony at the 1986  
trial was considered credible, but her latest statement was not. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't have it both ways,'' lawyer John Blume said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
