<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blackmun Honored at Court Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The late Supreme Court Justice Harry A.  
Blackmun was praised for his ``decency, modesty and civility'' 
Wednesday in a ceremonial session of the nation's highest court. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno and Solicitor General Seth Waxman,  
representing lawyers who practice before the court, said the 
Supreme Court bar was saddened by Blackmun's death at age 90 last 
March. 
</P>
<P>
	They presented to the court a formal resolution conveying that  
sentiment, a tradition after a justice's death. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackmun had retired from the court in 1994 after a 24-year  
tenure. 
</P>
<P>
	``He epitomized the highest ideals of public service,'' Reno  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Waxman, recalling Blackmun's ``passion for hard work,'' said the  
justice is remembered ``with deep respect and affection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blackmun is best remembered as author of the court's 1973  
decision in Roe vs. Wade, which legalized abortion nationwide and 
touched off a still-raging moral and political debate. That ruling 
was prominently mentioned Wednesday, but so were Blackmun's 
opinions on immigrants' rights, commercial speech and race 
relations. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist grinned broadly when Waxman  
recalled Blackmun's practice of referring to himself as ``Old No. 
3.'' He was President Nixon's third choice for the court in 1970, 
nominated after the Senate rejected two other nominees. 
</P>
<P>
	Rehnquist called his former colleague ``a pensive and  
compassionate man,'' adding, ``He was the personification of 
decency, modesty and civility.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
