<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Oct. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clemens Pitches Yanks to Series Sweep  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Roger Clemens shut down the Atlanta Braves 4-1  
Wednesday night, pitching the New York Yankees to their second 
straight World Series sweep. The Yankees won their record 25th 
championship. Mariano Rivera who had two saves and a win in the 
Series was selected as MVP. At 37, Clemens won his first 
championship -- John Elway was the same age when he won his first 
Super Bowl. Showing the form that earned him five Cy Young Awards 
and 247 wins in 16 seasons, Clemens shut out Atlanta into the 
eighth to outduel John Smoltz. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley, Gore Face Off in New Hampshire  
</P>
<P>
	HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- In the first debate of the Democratic  
presidential campaign Wednesday night, Vice President Al Gore and 
Bill Bradley pledged their support to an overhaul of campaign 
finance laws, and agreed, in general terms, about the need to 
expand health care coverage. On military involvement overseas, 
Bradley advocated a United States role -- but not ``full 
responsibility'' -- in multilateral groups like the United Nations 
and NATO. Asked to describe the characteristics of effective 
leadership, Gore said a president must have a ``vision of the 
future'' and feel compelled to strive towards it. Bradley said 
``absolute integrity'' is essential. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Prosecutor: Arrest Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) -- The new chief prosecutor of the  
Yugoslav war crimes tribunal said Wednesday her top priority was 
the arrest and trial of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and 
two Bosnian Serb warlords. Carla Del Ponte was on her first tour of 
the Balkans since she succeeded Louise Arbour last month at the 
international court. She planned to travel to Kosovo Thursday, and 
then to Bosnia and Croatia later this week. Many of those suspects 
indicted for war crimes by the tribunal, including Milosevic and 
Bosnian Serb wartime leaders Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic, 
remain at large. 

</P>
<P>
	Siege in Armenia Leaves 8 Dead  
</P>
<P>
	YEREVAN, Armenia (AP) -- Gunmen seized Armenia's parliament in a  
torrent of automatic weapons fire Wednesday, killing the prime 
minister and seven other politicians. The attackers were still 
barricaded in the building with dozens of hostages shortly before 
dawn Thursday. During the night, the gunmen released three 
hostages, all of them reportedly suffering heart trouble, but 
continued to press their demand for talks with President Robert 
Kocharian, the country's leader. The president promised to take all 
possible steps to end the crisis. 

</P>
<P>
	GAO Cites Broken Army Trailers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army spent $50.6 million for 6,700  
two-wheeled trailers that now cannot be used unless the jeeps and 
trucks that pull them are modified, congressional investigators 
said Wednesday. The Army plans to pay an additional $640 per 
trailer to correct the flaw, said the General Accounting Office, 
the auditing and investigative arm of Congress. ``This isn't rocket 
science, these are simple trailers. If the Army couldn't properly 
manage this contract, how can we expect them to handle high-tech 
missiles and other weapons,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, who 
requested the study. 

</P>
<P>
	Sick Cuban Boy Arrives in U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- An ailing 7-year-old Cuban boy traveled with  
Illinois' governor to the United States Wednesday, after leaders on 
both sides briefly dropped their differences to help the child. 
Raudel Medina Alfonso suffers from portal hypertension, a 
potentially fatal disease. Cuban doctors don't have the facilities 
to treat him. On his arrival back in Chicago, Gov. George Ryan said 
his trip was ``more than a success.'' But Clinton administration 
officials criticized Ryan's trip, the first visit by a U.S. 
governor since Fidel Castro's 1959 revolution. 

</P>
<P>
	Marilyn Monroe Dress Fetches $1.2M  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dress Marilyn Monroe wore in 1962 to  
serenade President Kennedy sold Wednesday night for a record 
$1,267,500. The dress was the highest-priced item at the first 
session of a two-day Manhattan auction. The winning bid was made by 
the Manhattan-based Gotta Have It! Collectibles. It set a new 
record for an auctioned dress, obliterating the $222,500 paid for 
an ink blue Princess Diana gown sold in 1997. Meanwhile, a platinum 
eternity ring, encrusted with 34 diamonds, given to Monroe by 
ex-husband Joe DiMaggio, sold for $772,500. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Up at Midday  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices rose moderately Thursday  
morning, helped by gains on Wall Street. The benchmark 225-issue 
Nikkei Stock Average gained 69.35 points to 17,451.75 at the end of 
the morning session. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average 
gained 92.76 points to 10,394.89 on Wednesday. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
  	   	
</P>
