<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Treadmill May Be Better Heart Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	An often-ignored measurement taken during routine treadmill  
``stress tests'' can predict a heart patient's risk of early death 
even better than many expensive, high-tech approaches, researchers 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland Clinic researchers found that the heart's recovery  
rate -- how much the heartbeat slows after someone exercises to 
exhaustion and stops -- can help doctors spot those patients needing 
aggressive treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	That, in turn, could save health care dollars by sparing  
healthier patients risky follow-up tests and procedures for heart 
disease, the nation's biggest killer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have so many sophisticated tests to do that we sometimes  
overlook the obvious,'' said Dr. Gerald F. Fletcher, a professor at 
the Mayo Medical School in Jacksonville, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	The study is reported in Thursday's New England Journal of  
Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's already changed my clinical practice,'' said Dr. Michael  
S. Lauer, director of the Cleveland Clinic's exercise laboratory. 
``It's terrific news.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exercise stress tests, used since the 1960s, involve having a  
patient walk on a treadmill while his or her heart rate, blood 
pressure and the heart's electrical currents are monitored. The 
test costs about $600. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the mid-1980s and early '90s, however, doctors have used  
more sophisticated tests also involving a treadmill: stress 
echocardiograms, or ultrasound images of the heart pumping, costing 
around $1,500; a nuclear imaging technique called thallium 
scintigraphy, costing about $2,400; and a nuclear ``video'' showing 
sections of the heart that are not pumping properly. 
</P>
<P>
	Normally, when someone exercises to exhaustion and then stops,  
the heart rate drops 15 to 25 beats per minute. Lauer and 
colleagues found that for patients whose heart rate fell less than 
12 beats one minute after exercising, the risk of dying within six 
years was four times greater than for those above the cutoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was the number that best discriminated between people who  
were going to live and people who were going to die,'' Lauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Normally doctors focus on other results from a treadmill test:  
how the patient feels, his endurance, how much his heart rate 
increases, and changes in the heart's electrical currents. 
</P>
<P>
	Fletcher said the study convinced him doctors should add  
heart-rate recovery to those four factors to get the best picture. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers studied records from standard treadmill stress  
tests of 2,428 adults treated at the clinic for suspected heart 
problems from 1990 through 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers found 19 percent of patients whose heart slowed  
less than 12 beats per minute in the first minute after exercise 
were dead within six years. Of those with a normal heart-rate 
recovery, only 5 percent died in that time. 
</P>
<P>
	After adjusting for the patients' age, medication use, heart  
rate during exercise and at rest, and other factors, the patients 
with abnormally low heart-rate recovery still were twice as likely 
to die. 
</P>
<P>
	``That may throw a flag up that maybe this person's at greater  
risk and they need to be watched closely,'' said John M. Jakicic, a 
professor at Brown University School of Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	Lauer said the recovery rate as measured by a treadmill test was  
twice as good as thallium scintigraphy at predicting death. 
</P>
<P>
	Patients who are thought to have heart problems during initial  
testing sometimes undergo heart bypass operations or angioplasty, 
in which a tiny balloon is threaded into an artery to clear away a 
clog. These procedures can cost tens of thousands of dollars, and 
the complications can include bleeding, heart attack, stroke and 
death. 
</P>
<P>
	Heart-rate recovery could be an indicator of some other risk  
factor, given that scientists don't fully understand how hormones 
and electrical signals from the brain tell the heart when to speed 
up or slow down, said Dr. Edward M. Dwyer, chief of cardiology at 
New Jersey Medical School in Newark, N.J. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 12:40:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lions' Running Backs Move On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- No one ever thought it would be easy  
replacing Barry Sanders. Many thought it would be downright 
impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, how do you replace one of the best ever?  
</P>
<P>
	``You don't,'' Detroit Lions coach Bobby Ross said. ``We have  
never tried to replace Barry. He's not here. You play with the 
people you have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So the Lions have had to go on without Sanders. So far, it's  
working. 
</P>
<P>
	Things aren't the same without Sanders, of course. But nobody  
expected they would be. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the first six games last season, Sanders was averaging  
just over 100 yards per game. He had rushed for 638 yards and four 
touchdowns. The Lions were 2-4, on their way to a 5-11 finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he quit. Sanders, needing only 1,458 yards to pass Walter  
Payton as the NFL's all-time rushing leader, retired on the eve of 
training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial reaction was shock. After that wore off, however,  
the next reaction on the part of the players was anger. Many of 
them didn't like the fact that Sanders would turn his back on them 
without warning. They also didn't like the fact they were being 
written off as having no chance without their superstar. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Rivers, who had been the backup to Sanders for four years,  
was suddenly thrust into the starter's role. The Lions, who had 
drafted Sedrick Irvin almost as an afterthought in the fourth 
round, traded for Greg Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	It became tailback by committee, with fullback Cory Schlesinger  
added. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the first six games without Sanders, the committee is  
averaging just over 100 yards per game, the same as Sanders did. 
The Lions have rushed for 604 yards and have three rushing 
touchdowns -- two by Irvin and one by quarterback Charlie Batch. 
</P>
<P>
	More importantly, the Lions are 4-2. That means they have 10  
games to match their win total for all of 1998, a season in which 
Sanders rushed for 1,491 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Things are going to get a little tougher from now on, however.  
</P>
<P>
	Rivers, leading the team with 289 yards rushing on 71 carries,  
fractured his right ankle last Sunday at Carolina. He's probably 
out for the season. 
</P>
<P>
	With Rivers gone, Hill will take over the starter's role. This  
is something Hill has lobbied for all along. Now, he has to 
produce. He has rushed for 137 yards in the last two games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do have more depth,'' Ross said. ``We wouldn't be surviving  
if we didn't. Some of that is simply the fact that some young guys 
have made a commitment and stepped up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin also should see more action with Rivers out. His best  
statistical game came Sept. 26 at Kansas City where he carried 
three times for 20 yards and caught a pass for 21 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Ross has been using Irvin to return punts, too. But that's a  
risky job. Now that he's down to two healthy running backs, Ross is 
looking for someone else to play on the punt-return unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Schlesinger, used mostly as a blocker, has 20 carries for 55  
yards. He also has caught five passes for 58 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody likes what happened to Ron Rivers,'' Hill said.  
``Nobody wants to get the starting job that way. But football is a 
team game and when one guy goes down, the rest of us have to step 
up and fill in the best way we know how.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, it seems to be working.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's always a chance you might think you're better than you  
are, or the other way around,'' Ross said. ``Right now, I think 
we're getting better.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
