<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Free Encyclopedia Site Still Jammed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- For 10 million Internet surfers a day, a free  
Encyclopaedia Britannica apparently is worth waiting for. But for 
how long? 
</P>
<P>
	One of the year's most-touted Internet sites remains clogged  
nine days after the debut of free online encyclopedias -- brought to 
a virtual standstill by huge worldwide demand and insufficient 
hardware and software. 
</P>
<P>
	Britannica.com Inc., hoping to assuage the roughly 10 million  
people who have been trying daily to get into www.britannica.com, 
posted its third apology at the entrance to the blocked site 
Wednesday. The Chicago publisher promised to make it accessible 
``soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Our teams have been busy unpacking crates, installing  
hardware, configuring software and boosting capacity worldwide,'' 
said the statement, describing a round-the-clock repair effort. 
</P>
<P>
	But an executive acknowledged the problems will take weeks to  
fully fix. While many users should be able to get in by next week, 
redesigning the system to increase capacity several-fold will take 
longer, said Jorge Cauz, senior vice president for sales and 
marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	The cyber troubles, at nine days and counting, have marred an  
innovation that had succeeded in drawing attention to the 
struggling publisher as it tries to shake its stodgy image and get 
with the electronic program. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which says only 100,000 people have managed to  
reach the site's first page, admits it underestimated the early 
public response. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one in his right mind would have built an infrastructure  
capable of handling the initial demand we had,'' Cauz said. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts say the bottom line is poor planning.  
</P>
<P>
	``For this to be your core site, you can't make a mistake like  
this,'' said Rob Enderle, a consultant for the Giga Information 
Group in Santa Clara, Calif. ``If they were a startup company, we'd 
probably be talking about them going out of business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the rocky debut may not be harmful over the long haul  
because of Britannica's prestigious brand name. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think consumers will give them a few more chances than they  
would some nameless, unheard-of Internet startup with a premature 
product launch,'' said Emily Meehan, analyst for the Boston-based 
Yankee Group. ``There are too many educational institutions out 
there that want to get their hands on a free Encyclopaedia 
Britannica that are willing to wait.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The longer the tie-up lasts, the greater the chances that some  
would-be customers will vanish for good, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of Britannica's printed sets have fallen off by an  
estimated 80 percent since peaking at about $650 million in 1990 as 
knowledge-seekers turn to computer versions, mostly Microsoft's 
Encarta. Chicago-based Britannica is counting on advertising, 
sponsorship and e-commerce to make the venture pay off. 
</P>
<P>
	It is still available in the printed version, at $1,250 per set,  
as well as on CD-ROM. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 15:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SBC, Global Crossing Top Forecasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Profits rose 22.5 percent at SBC Communications in the third  
quarter -- just before the merger with Ameritech, a fellow Baby 
Bell, and its crowning as the biggest U.S. phone company and one of 
four new stocks in the Dow Jones industrial average. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest Communications International, the long-distance company  
that's acquiring another Baby Bell, U S West, met most Wall Street 
forecasts for the third-quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing, the company that Qwest outbid to purchase U S  
West, posted a smaller loss than expected. 

</P>
<P>
                        *SBC Communications    	
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio-based SBC, which completed its $74 billion purchase  
of Chicago-based Ameritech on Oct. 8, earned $1.28 billion, or 64 
cents a share, in the three months ended Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	That compares with a profit of 1.04 billion, or 53 cents a  
share, SBC earned in the third quarter of 1998, excluding a 
one-time gain of $219 million from the sale of certain businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had expected  
operating earnings of 61 cents a share from SBC, the local phone 
company for most of the Southwest and Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	SBC's revenues rose 7.6 percent to $7.77 billion, up from $7.22  
billion in last year's third quarter, driven by the rapid growth of 
the company's Internet, wireless and international operations. 
</P>
<P>
	To provide a sense of how SBC and Ameritech might have fared in  
the third quarter as a single company, SBC said the companies 
earned a combined $1.97 billion, or 57 cents a share, excluding 
one-time factors. That's 17.4 percent better than the combined 
operating profit of $1.68 billion, or 49 cents a share, the 
companies reported in the third quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Combined revenues for the companies totaled $12.45 billion in  
the third quarter, up 9.4 percent from $11.38 billion a year 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	``These results confirm our confidence that by bringing SBC and  
Ameritech together, we have joined two strong businesses capable of 
performing very well for our customers and shareowners,'' said SBC 
chairman and chief executive Edward E. Whitacre Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	SBC rose $2.43 3/4 to $48 in Wednesday's trading on the New York  
Stock Exchange, extending Tuesday's rally on news the stock will be 
added to the Dow Jones industrial average beginning next week. 

</P>
<P>
                 *Qwest Communications International    	
</P>
<P>
	Qwest Communications International earned $19.8 million, or 3  
cents a share, in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	That excludes one-time costs of $25 million related to the U S  
West buyout that left the Denver-based company with a net loss of 
$1.8 million -- almost break-even in per-share terms. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same period last year, before the acquisitions of the  
long-distance company LCI and other companies, Qwest lost $6.9 
million, or 1 cent per share. If LCI and the other companies had 
already been acquired, the net loss in last year's third quarter 
would have totaled $11.4 million, or 2 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues in the just-ended quarter totaled $1.02 billion, a 26  
percent increase over the combined $807 million generated by the 
same operations in last year's third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Communications services revenue grew by 69 percent. Internet and  
data services operations remained the fastest-growing segment, more 
than tripling from year-ago levels. 
</P>
<P>
	The highlight of the quarter, however, was Qwest's victory in a  
bidding war with Global Crossing for U S West, the Baby Bell phone 
company for most of the Rocky Mountains and Pacific Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	In Wednesday's Nasdaq trading, Qwest's fell 56 1/4 cents a share to  
$33.87 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Global Crossing Ltd.    	
</P>
<P>
	Bermuda-based Global Crossing lost $34.1 million, or 4 cents a  
share, in the third quarter, weighed down by heavy spending on the 
company's bid to build a global fiber optic network for high-speed 
Internet traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	Those figures are adjusted to include a full-quarter of results  
from Frontier Corp. and Global Marine Systems, both of which were 
acquired after the three-month period began. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had expected the combined operations to show a loss of  
10 cents a share, according to a survey by First Call/Thomson 
Financial. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same period last year, Global Crossing would have had a  
profit of $11.7 million, or 2 cents a share, when combined with 
1998's third-quarter results from Frontier and Global Marine. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues for the combined operations totaled $929 million in the  
just-ended quarter, up from $863 million a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In Wednesday's Nasdaq trading, shares of Global Crossing rose  
$1.06 1/4 to $35.18 3/4. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 07:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sports Memorabilia Dealer Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A sports memorabilia dealer was charged with mail  
fraud in a federal investigation of the alleged selling of jerseys, 
shoes and other items containing the forged signatures of Michael 
Jordan and other former and current sports stars. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven Ryan, also known as Steven Levine, 41, is the 13th  
defendant to be charged in federal court in Chicago as part of the 
nationwide Operation Foul Ball investigation. The other 12 have 
been convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities estimate that forgeries make up as much as 70  
percent of the sports memorabilia market and generate millions of 
dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan, who lives in the Chicago suburb of Wheeling, was to appear  
in federal court today. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities allege that Ryan, who does business as  
Northbrook-based North Shore Sports, auctioned items purported to 
be autographed by Jordan. Authorities said four pairs of shoes 
purportedly worn by Jordan in games and autographed by him weren't 
even the same size worn by the ex-Bulls superstar. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan continued to sell hundreds of allegedly forged items even  
though he has known for more than two years that he was under 
investigation by the FBI, and despite repeated warnings to cease 
and desist by Jordan's representatives and the Bulls, according to 
the charge. 
</P>
<P>
	A jersey worn by Jordan in a game can fetch more than $20,000.  
</P>
<P>
	Ryan's lawyer, George Pappas, said his client is innocent,  
adding the auction items were ``100 percent authentic.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
