<HEADLINE> Dayton Won't Dispute NCAA Rulings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- The University of Dayton expects the NCAA to  
rule that the school committed four rules infractions, including 
$32,000 in loans a university trustee made to the father of a 
basketball recruit, a school official said today. 
</P>
<P>
	However, investigators concluded that basketball player Brooks  
Hall is eligible to play because he did not know about the loans or 
directly benefit from them, Ted Kissell, director of athletics, 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The university will not contest the findings and awaits  
sanctions, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although we had concluded differently, we decided there was  
not a great likelihood that our position would prevail in front of 
the infractions committee,'' Kissell said. ``We decided it was in 
our best interests to put this behind us, to accept the enforcement 
staff's conclusion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Penalties for a major violation can include a two-year  
probation, cuts in the number of expenses-paid recruiting visits to 
the school or a reduction in the number of scholarships. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA's Committee on Infractions meets Nov. 5-7.  
</P>
<P>
	University officials declined to say what penalties they  
recommended to the NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we put forth a very good set of recommendations,''  
Brother Raymond Fitz, the university's president, said. ``We're 
hopeful that they'll accept them as they are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several weeks ago, the university learned that the NCAA would  
not accept their characterization of the violations as 
``inadvertent and secondary.'' The NCAA concluded that one major 
infraction and three secondary infractions occurred: 
</P>
<P>
	-- In August and September 1998, Clayton Mathile made personal  
loans totaling $32,000 to Chuck Hall, father of Brooks Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	--Mathile made impermissible contacts with Hall's family; he made  
impermissible contact with another unnamed recruit; and the radio 
station that carries Flyers basketball games posted a sign at the 
Troy Strawberry Festival in June 1998, associating Hall's name with 
the university. 
</P>
<P>
	NCAA rules prohibit schools from publicizing an unsigned  
prospect. 
</P>
<P>
	Wally Renfro, director of public relations for the NCAA, said  
the NCAA cannot comment on any case. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Hall declined to comment on the case.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
