<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lithuanian Prime Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VILNIUS, Lithuania (AP) -- Lithuania's prime minister resigned  
today, taking his government with him, after a controlling share in 
a state-owned oil company was sold to American investors over his 
objection. 
</P>
<P>
	The 18-member Cabinet automatically disbanded with Prime  
Minister Rolandas Paksas' resignation, prompting President Valdas 
Adamkus to cut short a visit to Canada to deal with the government 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	The president immediately named outgoing Labor Minister Irena  
Degutiene as the acting prime minister of the tiny Baltic country. 
</P>
<P>
	Paksas, 43, sparked a political revolt last week when he  
rejected the $650 million sale of a majority stake in the 
state-owned Mazeikiai Oil to the U.S.-based Williams International. 
</P>
<P>
	Degutiene was one of 13 ministers who backed the sale. Despite  
Paksas' objections to the deal, only 3 voted against it. 
</P>
<P>
	Paksas said he didn't oppose the sale in principle, but that the  
country could not afford it. Struggling with a budget deficit, the 
government would be hit harder by the loss of the oil company -- a 
cornerstone of the Lithuanian economy, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Backers of the sale said Williams' investment would revitalize  
the loss-making Mazeikiai Oil. The American connection also would 
lessen what they said was a dangerous dependence on Russia, which 
provides most of the former Soviet republic's crude oil. 
</P>
<P>
	But many nationalists opposed, demanding that key industries  
remain in state hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Paksas, a professional stunt pilot, was mayor of Vilnius before  
becoming prime minister five months ago, and some doubted whether 
he had the experience to run the country. 
</P>
<P>
	But others have praised his performance. His popularity, already  
high in polls, was expected to increase as a result of his 
outspoken opposition to the Mazeikiai Oil deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was scheduled to be signed October 29.  
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear when Degutiene would announce a new  
Cabinet. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
