<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Small Businesses Cope With Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- What happens to a small business when mom and  
pop go their separate ways and need to sell the company, or when 
it's time to pass the reins over to the next generation? 
</P>
<P>
	How about when a privately held company needs to raise capital  
or address a lawsuit? 
</P>
<P>
	To deal with these issues, owners must first determine just how  
much their businesses are worth -- and that's not an easy task to 
take on alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Many small business owners don't know where to begin. There may  
be too many assets to value, too many changes within their industry 
during years of operation, or their emotional attachment may bring 
a distorted view of the company's worth. 
</P>
<P>
	That's where an independent business appraiser can come in  
handy. There are numerous certified public accountants, valuation 
firms and investment banking companies that specialize in this 
area. The cost: around $10,000 for an average small business. The 
time to complete: between one and two months on average. 
</P>
<P>
	For a separate commission, some business appraisers may even be  
able to broker a deal. (The American Society of Appraisers, based 
in Washington, D.C., can provide names of business appraisers 
accredited through the trade group at its Web site, 
www.appraisers.org, or by calling 1-800-ASA-VALU.) 
</P>
<P>
	Business valuation is a mix of art and science. Appraisers  
provide an estimate or opinion of value based on prevailing market 
conditions, income and assets of a company, although many factors 
in between come into play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Typically, the goal is to arrive at the fair market value of  
the business ... which is basically what a buyer is willing to pay 
after both sides have had reasonable access to all the available 
information,'' said Martin D. Hanan, president of Business 
Valuation Services Inc. in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	There are three basic approaches taken by valuation  
professionals: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Market. What comparable companies, public and private, in the  
same industry have sold for. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Income. Both current income and projected income of a company  
over a period of time. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Assets. That includes assets which are tangible -- inventory,  
real estate, receivables or equipment -- and intangible -- employees, 
customer loyalty or a trademark. 
</P>
<P>
	``We try to use all three ... whenever we can, although in  
different industries, we may weigh them differently,'' said Robert 
F. Reilly, managing director of Willamette Management Associates in 
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``income'' approach may be favored more for service  
businesses, like financial consultants or medical professionals, 
while the ``asset'' approach better geared toward asset-intensive 
businesses, like construction companies or real estate developers. 
</P>
<P>
	Most valuations are done because owners want to sell or merge  
with another company, business appraisers say. Both sells and 
buyers often will request independent valuations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in a period of another merger and acquisition frenzy as  
we were in the mid-80s,'' Hanan said, attributing to the trend to 
the strong economy and rising stock market, both of which have 
helped increase the value of many businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Hanan said many mom-and-pop operations are being bought by  
larger public companies. The small business owners are receiving 
cash and stock in the public company. 
</P>
<P>
	There are other reasons to seek a formal valuation.  
</P>
<P>
	It's crucial for estate planning purposes or if owners ever  
intend to go public to raise more capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Business owners who are buying insurance coverage also may need  
to establish current market value to cover operating expenses in 
the event of an extraordinary loss or to replace a key employee in 
the even of death for example. 
</P>
<P>
	If a business has been sued, a valuation can help determine  
economic damage or resolve bankruptcy issues or partner disputes. 
</P>
<P>
	 *End adv for release anytime    	
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
