<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Freed Immigrant Angered at U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- On his first day of freedom in 19 months, a  
Palestinian emigrant once suspected of plotting to kill Attorney 
General Janet Reno criticized the government's reliance on secret 
evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't believe that such allegations were being pointed at  
me,'' Hany Mahmoud Kiareldeen said Tuesday. ``Such a use of secret 
evidence really astonished me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kiareldeen, 31, said he would probably try to force the  
government to provide him copies of the evidence. He and his 
lawyers haven't seen it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to be skeptical of government claims of national  
security,'' said David Cole, a Georgetown law professor who worked 
for Kiareldeen and others jailed on secret evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Non-classified summaries of evidence collected by the FBI  
alleged Kiareldeen was a member of a terrorist group who made a 
``credible threat'' to murder Reno because of her role in 
prosecuting the bombers of the World Trade Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiareldeen has testified that he does not know any of the men  
convicted in the bombing and did not know who Reno was until he was 
arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	Immigration judges this month found that secret evidence  
``unreliable'' and a federal judge ruled last week that his 
detention was unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiareldeen, who managed an electronics shop before his detention  
on charges he overstayed his student visa, was never charged with a 
terrorist act. The FBI closed its investigation in July. 
</P>
<P>
	He and his supporters said the suspicions stemmed from false  
claims made by his ex-wife. Her charges of domestic abuse during a 
continuing battle over visitation were dismissed by judges. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiareldeen conceded that he overstayed his visa. An immigration  
judge this spring found that was not reason to deport him, since 
Kiareldeen was now married to a U.S. citizen and others in similar 
circumstances are often not punished. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiareldeen, who was born on the Gaza Strip and came to the  
United States in 1990, said he hopes to become a citizen, ``Because 
I am proud of America. I like America because it is a free 
country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was freed about midnight Monday from the Hudson County Jail  
just after the Justice Department announced it had dropped efforts 
to deport him. 
</P>
<P>
	Advocates say Kiareldeen is the first of about two dozen people,  
nearly all Arab or Muslim, detained by secret evidence to win 
release. 
</P>
<P>
	``Time after time, secret evidence is being revealed as evidence  
that isn't sensitive, but weak,'' said Hussein Ibish, a spokesman 
for the American Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee in Washington, 
who called it a ``highly abusive and totally un-American 
practice.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
