<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Letters Threaten Primate Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Dozens of researchers working on monkeys  
at universities across the country received threatening letters 
booby-trapped with razor blades, and an animal rights group claimed 
responsibility on an Internet site. 
</P>
<P>
	There had been no reports of injuries Wednesday, but FBI  
investigators were warning scientists to take precautions. 
</P>
<P>
	The group ``Justice Department,'' believed to be based in  
Britain, claimed it sent letters to more than 80 scientists at 
schools including Tulane University in New Orleans, Emory 
University in Atlanta and state universities in California, 
Wisconsin, Minnesota, Oregon and Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	A typewritten letter sent to one Harvard University researcher  
said: ``You have been targeted and you have until autumn of 2000 to 
release all your primate captives and get out of the vivisection 
industry. If you do not heed our warning, your violence will be 
turned back upon you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A list of its intended targets was discovered on the Web site  
over the weekend by a watchdog group, which notified the targeted 
schools. It was unclear how many letters were opened. 
</P>
<P>
	At least six Harvard researchers received booby-trapped letters,  
as did six at Emory, four at the University of Wisconsin, six at 
the University of Washington, four in the state of Oregon, and 
three at the University of California at Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's immoral, it's uncivilized,'' said Kevin Smith, vice  
chancellor of research at the University of California at Davis. 
``It's terrorism from people who say, `We value life -- but if you 
don't stop, we'll kill you.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The blades were concealed in plain white envelopes bearing Las  
Vegas postmarks, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The razor blades were inside the top flap so that if you were  
to run your finger through the envelope the way most people do, you 
would have been cut,'' said Dr. Peter Gerone of the Delta Regional 
Primate Center in Covington, La., whose secretary used a letter 
opener to open the rigged envelope Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Much of what they've (scientists) accomplished is very good,''  
said psychology professor Gene Sackett, who does behavioral 
research with macaque monkeys at the University of Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the treatment of animals in labs had improved and with  
the advent of genetic medicine, primate research will become even 
more important. 
</P>
<P>
	``With genetic approaches to everything from cancer to behavior,  
the safety of these things have got to be tested on primates,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A fact sheet on an animal rights Web site claims the group has  
carried out attacks in Britain, Canada and British Columbia, 
including sending out envelopes with ``rat poison covered razor 
blades'' to hunting guides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0081 </DOCNO>
