<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Purchase of King Papers Negotiated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Members of Congress and the family of Martin  
Luther King Jr. are negotiating a multimillion dollar deal that 
could make the Library of Congress the repository for the slain 
civil rights leader's most recent papers. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. James Clyburn, D-S.C., chairman of the Congressional Black  
Caucus, said Tuesday that Sotheby's auction house in New York has 
appraised the 80,000 pages of documents from King's last six years 
at $30 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Clyburn said King's widow, Coretta Scott King, and sons Dexter  
King and Martin Luther King III have indicated in discussions with 
him a willingness to sell the papers to the library for $10 million 
below that appraisal. Clyburn introduced legislation last month 
authorizing the acquisition of the papers. 
</P>
<P>
	``All three seem willing to pursue that course,'' he said. ``We  
are still in negotiation but I feel relatively sure that if we can 
get the authorization done, we can move forward and get a number we 
can ask Congress for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the Martin Luther King Jr. Center for Non-violent  
Social Change did not return telephone calls Tuesday seeking 
comment on the negotiations, the existence of which was first 
reported this week by Roll Call, a biweekly newspaper that covers 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The authorizing legislation is co-sponsored by Rep. J.C. Watts,  
R-Okla., chairman of the House Republican Conference; Rep. John 
Lewis, D-Ga., a civil rights leader who was an associate of King; 
and Rep. Cynthia McKinney, D-Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	Clyburn said both Republican and Democratic leaders in the House  
support the idea. He said he's hopeful Congress can complete the 
legislative work for the purchase before it leaves for the year in 
the next few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers have asked Library of Congress officials to inspect  
the papers this week and ``stipulate to Congress that this $30 
million is what they're worth,'' Clyburn said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the deal Clyburn envisioned is completed, it would be far  
more than Congress has ever paid for a manuscript collection for 
the Library of Congress. The largest previous such outlay, said 
library spokeswoman Jill Brett, was $1.5 million in the early 1930s 
for the Vollbehr Collection of about 3,000 books from the 15th 
century, including one of three perfect copies of the Gutenberg 
Bible. 
</P>
<P>
	With inflation, that $1.5 million would be about $14.6 million  
in today's dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Most documents in the library's manuscripts collection have been  
donated, Ms. Brett said, including the papers of 23 presidents, 38 
Supreme Court justices, and famous Americans such as Susan B. 
Anthony and Frederick Douglass. 
</P>
<P>
	``The manuscript collection is probably unparalleled in the  
world,'' she said. ``Martin Luther King was one of century's great 
figures, and certainly his papers would enhance our collection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Brett said the library first expressed an interest in  
acquiring King's papers two years before his assassination in 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	King gave thousands of documents from the early years of his  
career to his alma mater, Boston University, which has housed them 
since 1964. The King family lost a lawsuit in 1993 to gain 
possession of those papers. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Emory University in Atlanta and Stanford University in Palo  
Alto, Calif., tried in 1997 to negotiate a deal with the King 
family for the 80,000 documents from the final six years of King's 
life, but neither school could close the deal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
