<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> British Minister Urges Irish Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Failure to enact Northern  
Ireland's peace accord would be an ``unforgivable crime,'' 
Britain's senior minister here warned today. 
</P>
<P>
	Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Mandelson told political  
leaders that their failure to compromise now -- after two months of 
mediation by former U.S. Sen. George Mitchell -- would mean 
``betrayal of another generation. It would be an absolutely 
unforgivable crime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``No one should underestimate just how important are the next  
few days for Northern Ireland,'' said Mandelson, whom Prime 
Minister Tony Blair appointed earlier this month to oversee policy 
in the province. 
</P>
<P>
	All eight parties that back last year's Good Friday accord  
gathered today for what they expect will be Mitchell's last few 
days trying to resolve bitter arguments about what the peace 
document actually means. 
</P>
<P>
	They were expecting Mitchell to put his own written suggestions  
on the table and to achieve a final verdict by this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell primarily is trying to resolve the polarized positions  
of the Ulster Unionists, who represent most of Northern Ireland's 
British Protestant majority, and Sinn Fein, the Irish Republican 
Army-linked party rooted in the province's most hard-line Catholic 
districts. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past year, Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble has  
refused to form the new Protestant-Catholic government upon which 
so much of the accord depends. It would have 12 Cabinet posts, 
including two for Sinn Fein, and gradually receive powers from the 
British government. 
</P>
<P>
	Trimble insists the IRA must first start to disarm in  
cooperation with international weapons experts, which is another 
goal contained in the accord. 
</P>
<P>
	Sinn Fein's negotiators insist they should receive government  
positions regardless of the IRA's rejection of the accord's section 
on disarmament. 
</P>
<P>
	The accord also expected the disarmament of Northern Ireland's  
two major outlawed pro-British groups -- the Ulster Defense 
Association and Ulster Volunteer Force, who are jointly observing a 
1994 cease-fire. Both say they won't start disarming until the IRA 
does. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
