<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Howard Said Probing NCAA Violations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Howard University is conducting an  
investigation into possible NCAA rules violations in its men's 
basketball and baseball programs, The Washington Post reported 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA sent Howard an official letter of inquiry concerning  
the baseball program, university spokeswoman Donna Brock said. 
Sources told the Post the investigation concerns the use of 
ineligible players several years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The possible violations in the men's basketball program came to  
light more recently and would have occurred since Kirk Saulny 
became coach last season, the sources said. The areas of inquiry 
are academics, recruiting and extra benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	The university hired Robert L. Clayton, a New Orleans-based  
attorney, to conduct the investigation into the basketball program. 
The inquiry is in such early stages and Clayton and Howard 
officials are uncertain about the seriousness or scope of any 
possible violations, the sources said. Clayton confirmed he was 
retained by the university to conduct the internal investigation, 
but did not comment further. 
</P>
<P>
	University President H. Patrick Swygert and athletic director  
Hank Ford did not respond to phone messages. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
