<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 15:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles' QB Questions 'Getting Old' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Donovan McNabb practically guffaws every  
time he hears it. Philadelphia Eagles coach Andy Reid twitches his 
mustache, scrunches his chin and composes what seems like his 
1,000th answer to the same question. 
</P>
<P>
	When will McNabb play?  
</P>
<P>
	Even McNabb, the No. 2 draft pick who wants to play more than  
anything, seems tired of the quarterback quagmire. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not my call,'' McNabb said Wednesday, repeating himself  
for the umpteenth time. ``If it happens, it happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the day's mental calisthenics were done, an  
ever-so-miniscule bit of news emerged: Though Doug Pederson will 
start at quarterback against the New York Giants on Sunday, Reid is 
not averse to giving McNabb more playing time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would not be out of place for him to play in the first half  
if I feel that the time's right and the situation's right for 
him,'' Reid said. ``That's why it virtually becomes a game-day 
decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reid is either unsure of how he wants to work McNabb into the  
rotation, or he's merely giving the Giants something extra to worry 
about. Given Reid's strict attention to detail and meticulous 
planning, the latter is the obvious answer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm truly not opposed to putting Donovan in the game, giving  
him a little time and then replacing him with Doug,'' Reid said. 
</P>
<P>
	Every week, Reid's vague answers open the door to a laundry list  
of questions. How will he decide? Is McNabb ready? Is he a slow 
learner? Is there a chance he won't start a single game this 
season? 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, there is,'' Reid said flatly, further fueling the debate.  
</P>
<P>
	McNabb clearly isn't holding his breath for an extended chance.  
</P>
<P>
	``Whether you play a quarter, play a half, play a series, it's  
just getting out there,'' McNabb said. ``You want to play more, but 
if you don't play at all you've just got to get ready for next 
week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Couch, the quarterback picked ahead of McNabb, is starting  
for Cleveland. Akili Smith, the quarterback picked after McNabb, is 
starting for Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	``To see that and not be part of that, it might hit you hard,''  
McNabb said. ``But they're in a different situation than I am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York (4-3) and Philadelphia (2-5) meet for the second time  
in less than a month. The Giants won the first game 16-15 at the 
Meadowlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Pederson had a terrible game, going 6-for-15 for 75 yards and  
two interceptions. He all but benched himself after the game, 
saying he would understand if Reid made a quarterback change. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid didn't, and the Eagles won two straight before losing to  
Miami 16-13 on Sunday. The loss, and a mediocre performance by 
Pederson, led to more quarterback questions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be shocked if there weren't a quarterback  
controversy,'' center Steve Everitt said. ``I've been playing seven 
years, and I've always been involved in one. It's just different 
characters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Pederson, ``You lose on Sunday, all that stuff creeps back  
in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even Reid had to admit that the speculation about who plays  
quarterback ``gets old.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The quarterbacks couldn't agree more.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
