<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida State Senator Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A state senator pleaded guilty to conspiracy in a  
Medicare fraud case and must resign from the Legislature, where he 
has served for 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	State Sen. Alberto Gutman and his wife, Marci, were charged last  
year as the secret owners of companies that billed Medicare for 
health care services that were not performed, sometimes for clients 
who did not exist. 
</P>
<P>
	The Miami Republican maintained his innocence until his plea  
deal was announced Tuesday in the second week of his federal trial. 
Prosecutors said Gutman and his wife collected at least $2 million 
from fraudulent billings while he served in the Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	Gutman, 40, declined comment Tuesday. He is expected to be given  
a two-year prison term at his sentencing Jan. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	As a convicted felon, Gutman must relinquish his Senate seat.  
Gov. Jeb Bush will set a special election once Gutman's resignation 
letter is received, a spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gutman, 40, pleaded guilty last month to a misdemeanor  
Medicare fraud charge and was sentenced to three years' probation 
and six months' home confinement. She also agreed to pay $15,000 in 
restitution. The Gutmans have two children. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gutmans were indicted along with 23 other defendants in the  
investigation of Mederi of Dade County Inc., a home health care 
provider. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said they found no legitimate billings among $15  
million worth of Mederi claims. The company and its owner were 
acquitted in May; a physical therapist was convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Gutman used voter lists from his district to  
telemarket his home health-care companies and that checks from the 
enterprise were deposited in his personal accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys said key witnesses were trying to protect  
themselves by testifying against an innocent public official. 
</P>
<P>
	Gutman was elected to the state House in 1984 and moved on to  
the state Senate in 1992. He narrowly won another four-year term 
while under indictment last November. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
