<HEADLINE> Omaha Stockyards Closes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- The last cattle auction in the Omaha  
Stockyards' 116-year history ended Wednesday morning with the sale 
of a pregnant Longhorn cow. 
</P>
<P>
	About 50 people scattered around a horseshoe-shaped auction ring  
clapped, then began making plans for a goodbye toast to what was 
once the largest livestock market in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of these people are here to party,'' said Gary Heuwinkel,  
a commission agent at the stockyards for 23 years. ``They wanted to 
be here for the last day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Omaha Livestock Market will move Monday to Red Oak, Iowa.  
The city of Omaha will tear down the stockyards' pens and barns to 
make way for a business park. 
</P>
<P>
	During the last live auction at the institution, 56 cows, bulls  
and feeder cattle were sold. 
  	   	
</P>
