<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Purchase of King Papers Negotiated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The family of Martin Luther King Jr. has  
indicated a willingness to sell 80,000 pages of the slain civil 
rights leader's papers to the Library of Congress for $10 million 
below their appraised value, the chairman of the Congressional 
Black Caucus says. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. James Clyburn, D-S.C., said Tuesday he's discussed the  
purchase of the papers from the final six years of King's life with 
his widow, Coretta Scott King, and his sons, Dexter King and Martin 
Luther King III. And he's introduced legislation authorizing the 
purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	``All three seem willing to pursue that course,'' he said. ``We  
are still in negotiation but I feel relatively sure that if we can 
get the authorization done, we can move forward and get a number we 
can ask Congress for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clyburn said Sotheby's auction house in New York last week  
appraised the 80,000 pages of King documents at $30 million. He 
said lawmakers have asked officials from the Library of Congress to 
inspect the papers this week and tell Congress that they're worth 
$30 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the Martin Luther King Jr. Center for Nonviolent  
Social Change in Atlanta, where the documents now are housed, did 
not return telephone calls Tuesday seeking comment on the 
negotiations. The talks were first reported this week by Roll Call, 
a semiweekly newspaper that covers Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The authorizing legislation is co-sponsored by Rep. J.C. Watts,  
R-Okla., chairman of the House Republican Conference; Rep. John 
Lewis, D-Ga., a civil rights leader who was an associate of King; 
and Rep. Cynthia McKinney, D-Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	Clyburn said Republican and Democratic leaders in the House were  
supportive of the idea. He said he was hopeful that both the 
authorizing legislation and the actual appropriation to purchase 
the papers could be approved by Congress before it adjourned for 
the year in the next few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	If the deal envisioned by Clyburn is completed, it would be by  
far the most Congress has ever paid for a manuscript collection for 
the Library of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Jill Brett, a spokeswoman for the library, said the largest  
previous outlay by Congress was $1.5 million in the early 1930s for 
the Vollbehr Collection of about 3,000 books from the 15th century, 
including one of three perfect copies of the Gutenberg Bible. 
Adjusted for inflation, that would amount to $14.6 million today. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the documents in the library's manuscripts collection  
have been donated to the library, Ms. Brett said, including the 
papers of 23 presidents, 38 Supreme Court justices, as well as 
famous Americans such as Susan B. Anthony and Frederick Douglass. 
</P>
<P>
	``The manuscript collection is probably unparalleled in the  
world,'' she said. ``Martin Luther King was one of century's great 
figures, and certainly his papers would enhance our collection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Brett said the library first expressed an interest in  
acquiring King's papers two years before his assassination in 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	King donated thousands of documents from the early years of his  
career to his alma mater, Boston University, which has housed them 
since 1964. The King family lost a lawsuit in 1993 to gain 
possession of the papers at Boson University. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Emory University in Atlanta and Stanford University in  
California negotiated with the King family 1997 to become the 
repository for the 80,000 documents from the final six years of 
King's life, but neither school could close the deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
