<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Horses Moved After Nev. Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Federal officials say they need to move about  
1,500 wild horses from their traditional rangeland because fires 
burned the wild grasses they live on, but animal rights activists 
say authorities are evicting the horses to help ranchers. 
</P>
<P>
	Valerie Stanley, a lawyer for the Animal Rights Defense Fund,  
said Wednesday that the Bureau of Land Management is violating the 
National Environmental Policy Act and the Wild Free Roaming Horse 
and Burros Act. 
</P>
<P>
	The bureau said the herds of up to 1,500 mustangs and wild  
burros being rounded up by helicopters could starve because fires 
burned up their food supply -- more than 1 million acres of grass 
and brush. 
</P>
<P>
	Activists said enough grass survived to feed the herds, and the  
BLM just wants to get rid of the horses because ranchers see them 
as competition for livestock grazing forage. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's director for Nevada, Bob Abbey, issued a statement  
taking ``exception to the questioning of BLM's motives .... Our 
goal is to have viable and healthy wild horse and burro herds on 
public lands in Nevada where resources can sustain them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said younger horses will be sent to the BLM's  
Palomino Valley adoption center near Reno, while older horses will 
end up at a BLM sanctuary in Bartlesville, Okla. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Stanley said the agency failed to hold a required public  
hearing before using helicopters on the roundup, and also failed to 
prepare an environmental assessment of the roundups. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 40,000 wild horses roam the West, about half of  
them in Nevada. Roundups occur regularly to help guard against 
overpopulation and some mustangs are sold at auctions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
