<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Plans Worldwide Commercial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. plans to race the clock around  
the globe Monday evening by putting an unusually lengthy two-minute 
commercial before a potential audience of a billion viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's second-biggest automaker has cobbled together a  
global collection of television networks that will carry the ad 
aimed at raising its corporate profile at about 9 p.m. local time 
in most markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The commercial subtly showcases all seven of Ford's automobile  
brands, suggesting in a montage of emotional vignettes that its 
products fit seamlessly into people's lives around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, it shows a war veteran riding in a Ford Mustang  
convertible in a homecoming parade, an Italian couple embracing in 
front of a Volvo, a well-dressed woman putting her sleek dogs in 
the back seat of a Jaguar and Japanese girls playing in cherry 
blossoms near a Mazda. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad, shot in nine countries by the agency J. Walter Thompson,  
carries the Ford logo near the start and at the end but there is no 
narrator. 
</P>
<P>
	The often disconnected images are held together by the song  
``Just Wave Hello,'' written expressly for Ford and sung by the 
14-year-old soprano Charlotte Church. Waving people appear in many 
scenes, their actions sometimes matching the lyrics. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad is being shown two months ahead of the year 2000, and  
Ford officials said the timing signals their intent to make the 
company the global leader in automotive products and services. 
</P>
<P>
	James C. Schroer, vice president of global marketing for Ford,  
said Wednesday in an interview he hopes viewers ``come to the 
conclusion that Ford Motor Co. has a heart and soul and has the 
kind of people and products that people will want to get to know 
better and will trust us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schroer declined to say how much it cost to run the ad globally  
but he said one published estimate of $10 million was conservative. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Grubbs, who oversees the ad agency BBDO's purchases of  
national commercial time for clients like Pepsi-Cola, Visa and 
Federal Express, said Ford's plans represented ``a pretty big 
idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the most difficult things today is how to break through  
the clutter and get impact,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Monday nights typically attract TV's biggest audiences  
of the week, and he said a two-minute commercial is bound to get 
attention simply because it is four times longer than the typical 
30-second ad. Announcing the plans in advance will also help. 
</P>
<P>
	``You may actually get some people to tune in for curiosity's  
sake to see what is up with this,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad will run on 38 different networks in the United States  
alone, including the broadcast networks ABC, CBS, NBC, FOX and WB. 
Due to the time differences across the U.S., viewers in the 
ZMidwest will see the ad at 8 p.m. local time while those on the 
West coast could see it on some cable networks as early as 6 p.m. 
locally. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroer said he expects the ad will reach 300 million households  
and one billion people globally the first night. 
</P>
<P>
	After its initial run, Ford plans to continue running one-minute  
versions of the ad through the new year. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad wasn't designed to trigger an immediate sales surge,  
Schroer said. He intends to watch how many people go to Ford's Web 
sites for more information after the commercial runs and how many 
people mention the ad when they visit dealers selling Ford's brands 
which also include Lincoln, Mercury, and Aston Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	He also hopes Ford moves up in the ranking of most-trusted  
companies around the world, which he said will be key to competing 
in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are on the first page'' of such listings, he said. ``We  
would like to be at the top.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 07:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Economy Prompts Business Jet Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sales of business jets like Payne Stewart's  
have soared in recent years thanks to the nation's booming economy, 
corporate globalization and ever-increasing airline delays. 
</P>
<P>
	More companies and celebrities are jetting around in Learjets  
and Gulfstreams, also attracted by the ability to set their own 
schedules and travel with privacy, security and comforts like 
couches and wet bars. 
</P>
<P>
	While the planes can cost up to $45 million for the business  
version of the Boeing 737, sales have skyrocketed with an increase 
in ``fractional ownership'' plans. Under such arrangements, a group 
splits the cost and use of an airplane in exchange for an 
equivalent share of the tax benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, business aircraft -- jets and turboprops flown  
by professional crews -- have posted a safety record slightly better 
than that of the airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, for example, airlines had an accident rate of .291  
accidents per 100,000 hours. For business aircraft, the rate was 
.091 per 100,000 hours, according to the National Business Aviation 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	And before Stewart's Learjet 35 flew uncontrolled across the  
nation Monday and nosedived into a field in South Dakota, killing 
the golfer and five others presumed aboard, it had been two years 
since the last fatal business aircraft accident. That does not 
include private planes flown on business by part-time pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's another business tool,'' said NBAA spokeswoman Cassandra  
Bosco. ``As more and more companies ... expect more and more from 
less people, it's about time management and efficiency. These 
aircraft operate on their own schedule and can fly to 10 times the 
number of airports as the scheduled carriers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is not surprising that Stewart and his companions were on a  
Learjet. The needle-nosed, twin-engine aircraft was introduced in 
1963 and is considered the first true business jet. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, new models have been introduced, and Lears have  
now accumulated over 10.5 million flight hours, according to its 
manufacturer, Bombardier Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Today the world leader in business aircraft is Gulfstream  
Aerospace Corp. The company, based in Savannah, Ga., has delivered 
over 1,000 jets since 1958, including what is considered the Rolls 
Royce of the sky -- the new Gulfstream V. 
</P>
<P>
	It can fly nonstop from New York to Tokyo at altitudes up to  
51,000 feet. The company pitches it as indispensable to business as 
the pad and paper. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I can be there in one hop compared to hop-scotching through  
hub airports around the world, I'm going to have more face time 
with the client and be on the way home with a signed contract 
before you even make it there,'' said Gulfstream spokesman Pat 
Coulter. 
</P>
<P>
	One reason corporate aviation is so safe is it can afford to  
skim the cream of the crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Fortune 500 companies hire only former military pilots,  
many of whom have flown military versions of corporate jets. Most 
companies have formal business plans, complete with contingencies 
for aircraft security, fleet maintenance and accident response. 
</P>
<P>
	Because many business aircraft have wealthy owners, they usually  
come stocked with the latest safety features. Among them are 
heads-up displays that project the proper flight path and critical 
instrument data onto a clear lens that folds down in front of the 
cockpit window. 
</P>
<P>
	Fractional ownership has only served to increase the number of  
people who can enjoy those benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, there were 32 such planes with 140 shareholders,  
according to AvData Inc. As of Sept. 1, there were 329 fractional 
ownership planes with 1,567 shareholders. Stewart was one of them. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to a rising stock market and a surging economy,  
which has provided the money for business aircraft, the Gulfstream 
spokesman said the airlines have also helped fuel aircraft sales 
and fractional ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time they cancel flights, every time they treat people  
poorly, those people with options come looking to Gulfstream or a 
shares program,'' Coulter said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 11:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brunell, Taylor Probable for Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Jaguars quarterback Mark Brunell and  
running back Fred Taylor are both listed as probable for Sunday's 
game at Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Brunell has a strained muscle near his ribs that he aggravated  
two weeks ago while throwing a long pass against Cleveland. Taylor 
has been out since Oct. 3 with an aggravated hamstring. 
</P>
<P>
	Brunell threw less than usual in practice Wednesday. He said he  
needs to know he can make all the throws if he's to start. 
</P>
<P>
	``But you don't make them all now,'' Brunell said. ``You make  
them as you get closer to the game. The long ball is certainly 
something I've got to be able to throw Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor's injury has progressed steadily since he left in the  
middle of a game against the Steelers. Coach Tom Coughlin said some 
of Jacksonville's troubles on offense might be solved with Taylor 
back in the lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully he'll be ready to perform this weekend,'' Coughlin  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coughlin said backup quarterback Jay Fiedler would get more  
repetitions than usual in practice this week. He said a final 
decision on Brunell's status would be made later in the week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
