<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Series Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Three Latin-American reporters sent a letter  
Wednesday to commissioner Bud Selig ``to express the most fervent 
disappointment for the unjustifiable exclusion of Roberto 
Clemente'' from the All-Century team. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying they were speaking for 21 Latin-American reporters who  
met and voted before Game 4 of the World Series, Jaime Jarrin, 
Billy Berroa and Manolo Hernandez-Douen included a Latin-American 
All-Century team with the letter they sent to Selig. 
</P>
<P>
	It has Orlando Cepeda and Andres Galarraga at first, Rod Carew  
and Roberto Alomar at second, Tony Perez and Vinny Castilla at 
third, Luis Aparacio, Dave Concepcion and Chico Carrasquel at 
shortstop and Ivan Rodriguez and Manny Sanguillen at catcher. 
</P>
<P>
	The outfielders are Clemente, Sammy Sosa, Juan Gonzalez, Tony  
Oliva, Bernie Williams and Minnie Minoso. The pitchers are Juan 
Marichal, Luis Tiant, Fernando Valenzuela, Dennis Martinez, Pedro 
Martinez, Martin Dihigo, Mike Cueller, Mariano Rivera, Camilo 
Pascual and Roberto Hernandez. 
</P>
<P>
	Manny Mota was picked a pinch-hitter, and Edgar Martinez and  
Jose Canseco as designated hitters. Clemente was voted Latin 
American player of the century. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago Cubs star Sammy Sosa, speaking before the game, recalled  
watching Clemente. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody knows who Roberto Clemente was,'' Sosa said.  
``Roberto Clemente would have been on that team.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *AFTER THE HEROICS:* Chad Curtis said he didn't want to make too  
much of his game-winning homer in Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, the fun of the game is playing the game,'' he said,  
``not the trophies or the hype surrounding the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the Hall of Fame wants the bat he used for his  
10th-inning drive off Mike Remlinger. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ROCKET LAUNCH:* Roger Clemens didn't make his first World  
Series appearance in 13 years until starting Game 4 on Wednesday 
night. But he already has some fond memories. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens, one of the 30 players picked for baseball's All-Century  
Team, was on the field for the celebration before Game 2 with Ted 
Williams, Willie Mays, Sandy Koufax and other greats. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't look at myself in that way by any means,'' Clemens  
said. ``It was fun talking to a lot of those guys. It was just a 
special evening. Every time I see Ted Williams, I get choked up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seeing Williams brought back memories of one of their first  
meetings, when Williams was visiting Boston spring training in 1987 
and called Clemens in to talk. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said point blank, `What would you throw me?' -- real loud  
with that booming voice. I had marbles in my mouth,'' Clemens 
recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Clemens could respond, Williams provided his own answer.  
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `I would look for your slider, Kid, because I know I  
can hit your fastball.' I said, `Yes, sir, Mr. Williams.' I got my 
sanitary socks and went the other way.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HANK AARON AWARDS:* Baseball presented its inaugural Hank Aaron  
awards to Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs and Manny Ramirez of the 
Cleveland Indians. The awards, which are for hitting and are based 
on statistics, are given by the commissioner's office. 
</P>
<P>
	The Baseball Writers' Association of America will announce the  
traditional awards -- Rookie of the Year, Cy Young and MVP -- next 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron repeated that he expects Ken Griffey Jr. will break his  
record of 755 home runs ``because of his age, and he's going to be 
around awhile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It really doesn't matter who breaks it,'' Aaron said. ``That  
just means progress in baseball and Sammy Sosa, (Mark) McGwire, Ken 
Griffey Jr., whoever break it, fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *JOB HUNTING:* Yankees hitting coach Chris Chambliss got his  
chance to interview for the Milwaukee Brewers managing job 
Wednesday, one day after New York third base coach Willie Randolph 
did. 
</P>
<P>
	``They told me they'd get back to me after the season,''  
Chambliss said. ``I go through this every season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees manager Joe Torre is prepared to lose at least one of  
his coaches before next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a happy loss,'' Torre said. ``They're going on to  
something they always wanted to do. It's replacing them in a nice 
way, though, because they're going on to do things I feel they're 
both capable of doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *KERRY'S COMEBACK:* Kerry Ligtenberg was doing his best to enjoy  
the World Series, even though he can only watch from the bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who's to say if I'll ever get another chance to be around the  
World Series,'' said Ligtenberg, who saved 30 games for the Braves 
in 1998 but missed this season with a torn ligament in his elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	The right-hander threw on the side for the final six weeks of  
the regular season and was encouraged by how he felt. 
</P>
<P>
	``It progressed rapidly, to the point where I felt like I was  
throwing 70 percent,'' Ligtenberg said. ``Honestly, I think if I 
wanted to play winter ball, I could pretty easily.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, his focus will be on getting ready for the start of  
spring training. Ligtenberg is willing to take whatever role is 
available, knowing that his successor, John Rocker, will be hard to 
unseat as the closer after saving 38 games, one short of the 
franchise record. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, I just want to be healthy,'' Ligtenberg said. ``If  
I got to spring training at 100 percent and show them that 
everything is normal, that other stuff will take care of itself. 
I'm not worried about (his role) at all.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
