<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq To Link to Online Brokerages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq Stock Market's Web site will soon  
offer links to online brokerage firms that will allow investors to 
jump directly to their online trading account. 
</P>
<P>
	National Association of Securities Dealers Chairman Frank Zarb  
announced the Mybroker service Wednesday during a speech in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	Zarb said no date has been set for when the service will begin.  
He said some online brokerage firms need time to get their 
technology connected to the Nasdaq's Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	Online brokerage firms that participate in the service will  
benefit by getting the added exposure of being linked to the 
Nasdaq's site, which draws 23.5 million visitors a day. 
</P>
<P>
	More information will be released in two or three weeks.  
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, Zarb detailed a plan announced in June to open a  
Japanese version of the Nasdaq's computerized trading system. 
</P>
<P>
	Zarb said the Internet-based system is being designed by  
Japanese banking giant Softbank. He said the move is intended to 
create a partnership with the Japanese, rather than compete with 
existing Japanese exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese Nasdaq system will hopefully be the first step in  
creating an interconnected, 24-hour global exchange, Zarb said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ideally, the Japanese Nasdaq system would be open to both  
Japanese and American companies that met similar standards 
established by both countries, Zarb said. ``That would allow 
investors to trade large, liquid stocks equally in both markets 
using the same system,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, a combined U.S. and Japanese Nasdaq would create  
more liquid markets -- meaning more money is circulating -- which 
would attract additional companies to list on the dual exchange, 
Zarb said. 
</P>
<P>
	The statements by Zarb on a Japanese Nasdaq came the same day  
The Wall Street Journal reported that the Nasdaq was also seeking 
to create a linked computerized trading market in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Zarb acknowledged his desire to move into Europe and said he  
hoped all three continents -- the United States, Europe and Asia -- 
would one day be linked by a single computerized trading system. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
