<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Compaq Beats Expectations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Compaq Computer Corp. reported flat third quarter  
operating profits that beat analysts' expectations, but revenue 
fell 2 percent from the second quarter as the company lost its U.S. 
leadership in personal computer sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq, which is still the largest seller of PCs on a worldwide  
basis, reported net income Tuesday of $140 million, or 8 cents per 
share, compared to results in the year-ago quarter of $115 million, 
or 7 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	But not counting $868 million in charges related to a  
restructuring and a $1.2 billion one-time gain on the sale of its 
AltaVista Internet portal, Compaq earned $117 million, or 7 cents a 
share in the recent quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial expected  
Compaq to earn 5 cents per share in the July-September period. The 
results, which were released at the close of financial markets, 
mark a return to profitability after the company's stunning $184 
million in losses last quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading this morning on the New York Stock Exchange, Compaq  
was up 2.6, or by 50 cents, at $20 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq reported revenue of $9.21 billion, up 5 percent from  
$8.79 billion a year ago but down slightly from $9.4 billion last 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael D. Capellas, promoted to president and chief executive  
in July following the ouster of Eckhard Pfeiffer last spring, said 
he was disappointed in revenues but encouraged by a drop in 
operating costs from the second quarter to $1.97 billion from $2.2 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``While our revenue numbers were down sequentially, we achieved  
our earnings per share target, gross margin was up and operating 
expenses were down,'' Capellas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Capellas added that he is satisfied the company, which has  
fallen behind Dell Computer Corp. in U.S. personal computer sales, 
is on track to further streamline its operations while staying 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ashok Kumar, an analyst with U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffrey, saw  
little upside in the earnings report. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the earnings are clearly a disappointment. The  
earnings are inflated by accounting,'' Kumar said. ``The key issues 
going forward are the company has completely lost traction in the 
commercial desktop line, the company does not have a strategy for 
its service division ... and because of the deep budget cuts, 
Europe is in complete disarray. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is there's no catalyst that indicates any  
imminent turnaround.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts have faulted in part Compaq's inability to emulate the  
efficient sales model of Dell and Gateway, which sell products 
directly to customers and avoid retailers and wholesalers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Changes in the personal computer business are not just about  
sales and distribution models,'' Capellas said, adding that Compaq 
is banking on an array of upcoming computer models. ``We intend to 
drive a new generation of products, from desktops to palmtops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq earned $237 million, or 15 cents per share, in the nine  
months ended Sept. 30. Last year at that time, the company lost 
$3.5 billion, or $2.21 cents per share, stemming from its 
acquisition of Digital. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose to $28.05 bill from $20.31 billion.  




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 10:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rams' Line Coach Hospitalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- St. Louis Rams offensive line coach Jim Hanifan  
will be back on the sideline Friday after being hospitalized for 
chest pains. 
</P>
<P>
	Hanifan, 66, was in good condition Wednesday at Missouri Baptist  
Hospital after undergoing a coronary artery angiogram. The 
procedure showed a blockage in a small artery that was opened by 
balloon angioplasty. 
</P>
<P>
	He will be released Thursday, the hospital said, and coach Dick  
Vermeil said Hanifan would make the trip for Sunday's game at 
Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll be back on Friday and he has to quit smoking,'' Vermeil  
said. ``It's good for all of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hanifan joined the team two years ago when Vermeil became coach.  
Hanifan also was head coach of the St. Louis Cardinals from 
1980-85. 
</P>
<P>
	Vermeil said Hanifan had chest pains Tuesday night. Later that  
night at the hospital, Hanifan continued to work on the game plan 
for the Tennessee game. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
