<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Oct. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clemens Pitches Yankees to Series Sweep  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Roger Clemens pitched the New York Yankees to  
their second straight World Series sweep Wednesday night, shutting 
down the Atlanta Braves 4-1. The Yankees won their record 25th 
championship. Mariano Rivera who had two saves and a win in the 
Series was selected as MVP. At 37, Clemens won his first 
championship -- John Elway was the same age when he won his first 
Super Bowl. Showing the form that earned him five Cy Young Awards 
and 247 wins in 16 seasons, Clemens shut out Atlanta into the 
eighth to outduel John Smoltz. 

</P>
<P>
	Congress Nears Crucial Budget Vote  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House leaders prepared Wednesday for a crucial  
vote in their budget battle with President Clinton as both parties 
vied to define the GOP's spending plans. Republicans said their 
proposed across-the-board cuts were prudent; Democrats called them 
destructive. Republican leaders put the finishing touches on their 
effort to pay for spending bills without touching Social Security 
surpluses through reductions in agencies' budgets of just under 1 
percent. Republican leaders planned for the House to vote tomorrow 
on a massive bill that includes the cuts, $314 billion for labor, 
health and education programs, plus money for the District of 
Columbia's budget. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley, Gore Hold First Debate  
</P>
<P>
	HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- In the first debate of the Democratic  
presidential campaign Wednesday night, Vice President Al Gore and 
Bill Bradley pledged their support to an overhaul of campaign 
finance laws, and agreed, in general terms, about the need to 
expand health care coverage. On military involvement overseas, 
Bradley advocated a United States role -- but not ``full 
responsibility'' -- in groups like the United Nations and NATO. 
Asked to describe the characteristics of effective leadership, Gore 
said a president must have a ``vision of the future'' and feel 
compelled to strive towards it. Bradley said ``absolute integrity'' 
is essential. 

</P>
<P>
	Siege in Armenia Leaves 8 Dead  
</P>
<P>
	YEREVAN, Armenia (AP) -- Gunmen seized Armenia's parliament in a  
torrent of automatic weapons fire Wednesday, killing the prime 
minister and seven other politicians. The attackers were still 
barricaded in the building with dozens of hostages shortly before 
dawn Thursday. During the night, the gunmen released three 
hostages, all of them reportedly suffering heart trouble, but 
continued to press their demand for talks with President Robert 
Kocharian, the country's leader. The president promised to take all 
possible steps to end the crisis. 

</P>
<P>
	White House Maintains Sudan Stance  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House said Wednesday that President  
Clinton's national security advisers have not second-guessed the 
decision to bomb a pharmaceutical factory in Sudan in retaliation 
for terrorist bombings of two U.S. embassies in Africa. Spokesman 
Joe Lockhart said Clinton's national security team recommended 
unanimously last year to proceed with plans for a missile attack on 
the factory, which was supposedly linked to Osama bin Laden, the 
suspected mastermind behind the embassy attacks. The plant's owner 
is thinking of suing the United States to recover the $30 million 
cost of rebuilding the plant. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Prosecutor: Arrest Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) -- The new chief prosecutor of the  
Yugoslav war crimes tribunal said Wednesday her top priority was 
the arrest and trial of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and 
two Bosnian Serb warlords. Carla Del Ponte was on her first tour of 
the Balkans since she succeeded Louise Arbour last month at the 
international court. She planned to travel to Kosovo Thursday, and 
then to Bosnia and Croatia later this week. Many of those suspects 
indicted for war crimes by the tribunal, including Milosevic and 
Bosnian Serb wartime leaders Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic, 
remain at large. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford Plans Worldwide Commercial  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. hopes to reach a billion viewers  
Monday evening in a rare global advertising gamble aimed at raising 
its corporate profile as the millennium approaches. The world's 
second-biggest automaker has cobbled together an unusual collection 
of television networks that will carry an unusually long two-minute 
commercial at about 9 p.m. local time in most markets around the 
world. Ford's strategy is to get the widest possible exposure for a 
single airing of a commercial. The commercial subtly showcases all 
seven of Ford's automobile brands. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Up at Midday  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices rose moderately Thursday  
morning, helped by gains on Wall Street. The benchmark 225-issue 
Nikkei Stock Average gained 69.35 points to 17,451.75 at the end of 
the morning session. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average 
gained 92.76 points to 10,394.89 on Wednesday. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
















</P>
