<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybean Futures Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures were mixed in early  
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, with the market 
struggling to break out of its recent price slump. 
</P>
<P>
	Rains forecast for soybean-growing areas of Brazil and Argentina  
weighed on the market, sending soybeans initially lower today 
before the price rebounded. Soybeans hit an eight-week low on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn also was pressured by soybeans' slide.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures inched higher despite the overnight purchase by  
Algeria of 125,000 tons of German wheat, a slight to the U.S. 
export market. Analysts said U.S. wheat sales remain solid, with 
recent purchases by Taiwan, South Korea and Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 3/4 cent to $2.57 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1 cent to $2.00 3/4 a bushel; December oats fell 1/2 
cent to $1.10 1/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1/4 cent to $4.68 1/2 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
pork futures fell sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	December live cattle fell .85 cent to 67.42 cents a pound;  
November feeder cattle fell .58 cent to 79.42 cents a pound; 
December lean hogs fell 1.08 cent to 47.17 cents a pound; February 
frozen pork bellies fell 1.75 cent to 62.60 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
