<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Montana City Debates `Living Wage' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MISSOULA, Mont. (AP) -- John Leathers makes $6.15 an hour as a  
cemetery groundskeeper for the city, a job that will last only 
until winter comes. He moonlights as a bowling alley mechanic at 
$6.75 an hour. He puts in 80 hours a week and still lives paycheck 
to paycheck. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm tired a lot,'' Leathers said. ``I'm 21 and I feel like I'm  
40.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leathers and others like him see some hope in a proposal on the  
Nov. 2 ballot that would set a ``living wage'' of $8 an hour for 
all Missoula municipal employees and workers whose employers get 
grants or other assistance from the city. The federal minimum wage 
is $5.15. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 40 other U.S. cities and counties have ``living wage''  
laws, including Minneapolis, Kankakee County, Ill., and Portland, 
Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	Missoula, population 52,000, is a liberal college town in one of  
the poorest states. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, Montana stood 47th in per capita income at $20,172.  
Only New Mexico, Mississippi and West Virginia were lower. Montana 
was also second in the percentage of workers holding down more than 
one job: 10.6 percent, behind North Dakota at 10.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Montana People's Action, an activist group backing the living  
wage, says government grants and other incentives awarded to 
businesses to spur economic development should start yielding some 
benefit for people on the bottom rungs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The living-wage movement is an alternative to the  
better-business climate that says we improve the business climate, 
we get rich and prosper and pass it on to you,'' said the 
organization's Jim Fleischmann. ``We've had two decades of 
business-climate improvement, and look where we stand now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents -- mostly businesses -- say the new minimum would throw  
people out of work as employers cut jobs to offset the higher pay. 
And they say that nonprofit organizations that get city assistance 
and help the poor would have to reduce programs because of higher 
operating costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the end, it is going to hurt the people they're trying to  
help,'' City Councilwoman Tracey Turek said. 
</P>
<P>
	The wage plan would affect the equivalent of up to 30 full-time  
municipal jobs that are held by dozens of people and pay less than 
$8 an hour, said Brenda Camilli, city personnel director. Montana 
People's Action estimates the plan would also apply to 100 jobs 
with nonprofit organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	To Leathers, the effect is obvious: Earning $8 an hour would  
allow him to work shorter hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it would be wonderful. It would be fair,'' he said. As  
it is now, he said, neither job provides health insurance. ``I pay 
for housing and food,'' he said. ``I can't afford dental care and 
other things that are important to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is a plight shared by Nora Walsh, a 19-year-old single mother  
laid off this month as fall arrived in the Northern Rockies and 
ended her $6.15-an-hour job as a city park attendant. 
</P>
<P>
	``Missoula's a great place,'' she said. ``I just wish I could  
afford to live here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
