<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chargers To Stay With QB Kramer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Despite throwing seven interceptions in a span  
of five quarters -- something that not even Ryan Leaf has done -- 
Erik Kramer remains the San Diego Chargers' starting quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	However, coach Mike Riley said Wednesday he'll have a faster  
hook if Kramer struggles again this Sunday when the Chargers visit 
the AFC West rival Kansas City Chiefs. 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer was intercepted three times in three quarters Sunday, all  
of them setting up touchdowns as the Green Bay Packers humbled the 
Chargers 31-3. The previous week, he threw four interceptions in 
the second half against Seattle before leading drives that John 
Carney capped with the tying and winning field goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a team, we did not play very well at all this last week,  
which was fairly, painfully obvious,'' Riley said. ``I want to give 
Erik the chance to start in this next ballgame to remedy those 
problems with the rest of our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer threw his third interception midway through the third  
quarter. After Brett Favre led the Packers on a 99-yard drive to 
take a 28-3 lead, Jim Harbaugh came in and promptly threw an 
interception on his first play. He also finished with three 
pickoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not anticipating anything bad happening,'' Riley said.  
``I'm looking forward to having a good, efficient ballgame, but I 
also think that if the situation arises, Jim should play earlier 
than he did in the last game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harbaugh hadn't played since cracking two ribs in the first  
quarter against the Chiefs in San Diego on Oct. 3. Kramer came in 
with the Chargers trailing 14-0 and led them to a 21-14 win. 
Starting the next two games, he helped them to a 4-1 record and 
sole possession of the division lead. 
</P>
<P>
	After the debacle against the Packers, San Diego dropped into a  
tie with Kansas City and Seattle at 4-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer, who signed with San Diego the night before training camp  
opened, appreciates the chance to redeem himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've just got to get back to playing smart football,'' said  
Kramer, who hasn't thrown a touchdown pass in three games and has 
nine interceptions to just two TD passes. 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer also fumbled two snaps against the Packers and made a  
costly error by letting the clock run out at the end of the first 
half by scrambling inside the Packers' 10-yard line instead of 
taking a shot into the end zone or throwing it away. Kramer said it 
was a poor decision on his part, probably because he was thinking 
of his two earlier pickoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer said he won't play as if there's a gun to his head and  
one mistake will get him pulled. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think just the opposite. I have to play more relaxed,'' he  
said. ``I've got to just settle down and not press, not try to make 
more happen than what's there. I think I probably tried to do a 
little too much, tried to move things along a little faster and 
paid the price for trying to force a couple of things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Riley said Harbaugh will get more practice time this week.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a new week and I plan on playing better,'' said Harbaugh,  
who's thrown five interceptions and two TDs. ``That's not the way I 
want to think of myself as a player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leaf, meanwhile, was in the Los Angeles area Wednesday getting a  
second opinion on his surgically repaired right shoulder from Dr. 
Lewis Yocum of the Anaheim Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chargers hoped to have Leaf practicing full-time by now, but  
he overdid a workout before the Seattle game on Oct. 17 and 
reported soreness. 
</P>
<P>
	Several weeks ago, Leaf said he hoped to be suited up by  
Sunday's game at Arrowhead Stadium. That was the site of Leaf's 
biggest meltdown during his troubled rookie season, when he 
completed just 1 of 15 passes for 4 yards, threw two interceptions 
and lost three fumbles in a 23-7 defeat. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
