<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Co. Uses Sesame St. To Educate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Elmo, Big Bird and the other Sesame Street  
characters are teaming up with drugmaker Pfizer Inc. to educate 
parents about antibiotics and reduce kids' fears about going to the 
doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer, maker of the blockbuster antibiotic Zithromax, and the  
Children's Television Workshop, which produces the famous kid's 
television show, are distributing ``Sesame Street Goes to the 
Doctor'' kits to pediatricians and child care providers. Parents 
will be able to order printed materials for free. 
</P>
<P>
	The kit includes a 15-minute video in which the Muppets learn to  
get through a visit to the doctor and about proper use of 
antibiotics. The story line revolves around Elmo's trip to the 
doctor to help treat an ear infection. 
</P>
<P>
	The kit also includes a special issue of Sesame Street Parents  
Magazine that gives advice on caring for young children with common 
respiratory infections. In addition, the kits includes a poster and 
a booklet that gives child care providers tips about how to work 
with families when a child is ill. 
</P>
<P>
	The information given to parents has two main messages: Parents  
should never insist on an antibiotic for a viral infection such as 
a cold, because antibiotics won't work. And when an antibiotic is 
prescribed, they should always make sure the child finishes all of 
the doses so the infection does not return. 
</P>
<P>
	The unnecessary use of antibiotics and patients not finishing  
their drug regimen are two reasons why bacteria have become 
increasingly resistant to antibiotics, rendering them less 
effective in treating bacterial illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The kits do not mention any of Pfizer's drugs by name. But  
reducing children's fears about going to the doctor and making sure 
they take antibiotics appropriately likely will indirectly help 
boost sales of Zithromax, which is used to help treat ear 
infections and pneumonia among other ailments. 
</P>
<P>
	Pharmaceutical companies increasingly do not mention the name of  
their drugs in marketing campaigns, partly because if they did, 
federal rules would require them to detail side effects. 
</P>
<P>
	Zithromax, which had $1 billion in sales last year, has steadily  
gained market share against its primary competitor, SmithKline 
Beachum's Augmentin, which had sales of $1.6 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who better than the trusted and well-loved Muppets to help  
children feel better about doctor visits and help parents 
understand how to use antibiotics appropriately,'' said Pat Kelly, 
a Pfizer spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer has also agreed to help underwrite the production of  
Sesame Street shows during the first half of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Pam Green, the workshop's vice president for outreach and  
strategic partnership, said her not-for-profit company has sought 
out opportunities to use their popular characters to educate young 
children on important issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer is not the first drug maker to work with Elmo and Big  
Bird. Merck &AMP; Co. published a special magazine a few years ago 
using the Muppets to help promote the importance of vaccines. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the workshop nor Pfizer would disclose how much the  
drugmaker is paying to support the project. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Eds: For more information on the kits, call 1-877-CHILDEAR.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
