<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Readiness Discussed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A smaller and busier U.S. military remains  
ready to fight in two major foreign battles at the same time, but 
with an increased risk in the potential second conflict, the Joint 
Chiefs of Staff told Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will take longer to respond to hostilities which, in turn,  
means territory lost and an increased potential for casualties,'' 
the chiefs' chairman, Army Gen. Henry Shelton, said Tuesday at a 
Senate Armed Forces Committee hearing on the readiness of the 
military. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton, in three hours of testimony flanked by the chiefs of  
the Army, Air Force, Navy and Marines, said officers rate the risks 
of fighting a single conflict as ``moderate,'' a second conflict as 
``high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This does not mean that U.S. forces would not prevail in  
either contingency,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He ascribed the increased risk to diminished readiness in both  
strength of U.S. forces and the condition of their equipment. 
Difficulties in recruiting and in getting personnel to stay in the 
military are major factors, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent increases in outlays for the military should begin to  
solve the problems, Shelton said, but all five chiefs complained of 
budgets that fall billions of dollars short of needs to maintain a 
ready, modern force. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no doubt that the force is much smaller than it was a  
decade ago, and also much busier,'' Shelton said. The total force 
is down 40 percent, yet faces increased requirements, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A major challenge cited by all four service chiefs is how to  
increase the number of soldiers and officers who make long-term 
commitments and step up recruitment at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton said proposals in congressional budget negotiations for  
across-the-board budget cuts would be ``devastating'' for the 
military, and cuts in the number of personnel available it would be 
``disastrous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the military is ``walking a personnel tightrope,'' but  
pay and retirement improvements are beginning to increase 
retention. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, we are better off today than we were last year,''  
Shelton said. But he said recruiting has been held back by a 
job-rich economy, larger numbers of high school students going to 
college and ``the smallest cohort of 18- to 23-year-olds to recruit 
from in the history of the all-volunteer force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adm. Jay L. Johnson, the chief of naval operations, said world  
events in the last few months ``should dispel any misconception 
that the demands on our Navy have diminished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Our battle force is getting older, and there is no  
shock-absorbency left,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force chief, Gen. Michael E. Ryan, cited a ``slow but  
steady decline'' in Air Force readiness -- down 5 percent since last 
year, 23 percent since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Eric K. Shinseki, the Army chief of staff, said there  
remains in his service ``a mismatch between what we are asked to 
do, and the troops we have to do it with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marine Commandant Gen. James L. Jones said the Marines face  
increased commitments with force reductions that have cut ``well 
into the muscle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he said, ``The cumulative effect of repeated  
short-notice deployments could result in continued degradation in 
overall readiness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite budget increases this year, the service chiefs each  
complained of shortfalls below needs to increase readiness: $2.6 
billion for the Navy, $2.5 billion for the Air Force, $2.4 billion 
for the Army, $1.4 billion for the Marines. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
