<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European share prices fell Wednesday, led down by  
banks and pharmaceuticals, over concerns about a possible interest 
rate rise from the European Central Bank next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology was the best performer of the day, rising 0.6  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the question isn't whether the ECB will lift rates  
next week, but by how much,'' said David Coleman, chief economist 
at CIBC. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks came under pressure because higher interest rates reduce  
borrowing demand. In London, Barclays fell 3.4 percent and NatWest 
Bank fell 2.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Other banks that fell included Deutsche Bank and HypoVereinsbank  
in Frankfurt, Societe Generale and BNP in Paris, and UBS in Zurich. 
</P>
<P>
	In the pharmaceutical sector, Glaxo Wellcome fell after the  
company said it withdrew its Raxar antibiotic because of emerging 
safety concerns. AstraZeneca lost 2.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 600 European companies fell 0.75  
points, or 0.2 percent, to close at 307.82, with the 
worst-performing sectors banks, down 0.8 percent, and 
pharmaceuticals, with the respective index down 0.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 310 companies in  
countries that joined the single currency, closed down 0.60 points 
at 323.69. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index fell 10.65 points to 3786.07,  
while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed down 6.04 points at 3765.42. 
</P>
<P>
	In domestic markets, London's Financial Times-Stock Exchange  
100-share index of leading blue-chip shares fell 0.8 percent to 
close at 6,045.7 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index was down 0.5 percent; the  
Paris CAC-40 index was 0.2 percent lower to 4,695.05; Milan's 
MIBtel index fell 0.1 percent to 32,165; and Amsterdam's AEX Index 
rose 0.02 percent to 6,873.90. 
</P>
<P>
	Among technology shares, gains in Ericsson and Nokia helped make  
the sector the best performer of the day, with the respective index 
up 0.6 percent, despite declines in the U.S. technology market. 
</P>
<P>
	In France, ParisBourse said late Wednesday that shares of French  
defense aerospace group Aerospatiale Matra will replace those of 
oil group Elf Aquitaine in the CAC 40 benchmark index from Nov.5. 
</P>
<P>
	Elf Aquitaine shares will be removed from the CAC 40 and also  
from the SBF120 and SBF250 indexes after Thursday's close. The 
decision was triggered by Total Fina's successful takeover bid for 
rival Elf Aquitaine. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
