<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sara Lee Earnings Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sara Lee Corp. reported a 3 percent increase in  
operating income Wednesday as strong sales in household goods, body 
care products and apparel overcame a down quarter for its food 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first quarter of fiscal 2000, which ended Oct. 2,  
operating earnings from continuing operations were $423 million, up 
3 percent from $411 million for the same period a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Net income for the quarter, which included a one-time $137  
million gain from the sale of Sara Lee's international tobacco 
business, came to $258 million, or 28 cents a share, down 24 
percent from $337 million, or 35 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings matched the 28 cents per share consensus forecast  
of Wall Street analysts, according to First Call/Thomson Financial. 
</P>
<P>
	Sara Lee stock rose $1.87 1/2 to $25.62 1/2 a share in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Sara Lee Foods, which includes the company's packaged meats and  
bakery operations, posted an 8 percent decline in sales and a 6 
percent drop in income for the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	But branded apparel sales were up 6 percent, boosted by  
double-digit gains by Hanes underwear, Playtex bras and other 
apparel items. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are especially pleased with the strong unit volume  
increases in our non-food operations,'' said John H. Bryan, 
chairman and chief executive officer. ``These gains are the direct 
result of targeted investments in marketing and new product 
development for our leading brands around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``The increase that we reported in the first quarter gives us  
further confidence that our company will produce a low double-digit 
earnings per share gain for the full year,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sara Lee's leading brands include Sara Lee, Douwe Egberts,  
Hillshire Farm, Hanes, Coach and Playtex. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
