<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A.H. Belo Earnings Up 21 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A.H. Belo Corp. reported Wednesday third quarter  
earnings from operations increased 21 percent, while revenue rose 5 
percent, compared to the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas-based media company, which owns 17 network-affiliated  
television stations and several large newspapers, said earnings 
from operations were $57.7 million, up from $47.8 million in the 
year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue increased from $328.5 million to $345.3 million.  
After-tax cash flow, a measure widely used by financial analysts, 
increased from $109.9 million, or 39 cents a share, to $97.5 
million, or 50 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Belo released its earnings report after the close of markets  
Wednesday. Belo's stock closed down 12 1/2 cents to $18.62 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue from Belo's broadcasting division increased 3.7 percent,  
to $138.7 million, while the newspaper division's revenue increased 
5.9 percent, to $203.5 million from a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman and chief executive Robert W. Decherd said the  
company's television revenue increase was ``at the top of the 
industry.'' On the publishing side, he said, there was double-digit 
cash-flow growth at the Providence (R.I.) Journal and Riverside 
(Calif.) Press-Enterprise and ``continued incremental improvement'' 
at The Dallas Morning News. 
</P>
<P>
	Decherd said advertising demand at the Dallas paper has improved  
since June, ``and our prospects going forward appear to be much 
improved.'' He also said he expects the television group to post 
strong sales in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Belo's third-quarter net earnings were $16.6 million, or 14  
cents a share, up from $9.7 million, or 8 cents a share in the 
third quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said net earnings in the first nine months of the  
year were $108.9 million, 91 cents a share, up sharply from $53.2 
million or 42 cents a share in the same period last year. 
Year-to-date revenue has increased less than 2 percent, to $1.04 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, Belo announced a deal with Geocast Network  
Systems to deliver programming to desktop computers. Belo said it 
will invest $10 million in the venture. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, Moody's Investors Service downgraded Belo  
senior unsecured debt. Moody's said it acted after Belo used debt 
financing to make stock repurchases and acquisitions over the past 
two years instead of cutting its debt load from the 1997 
acquisition of the Providence Journal Co. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
