<DOCNO> APW19991027.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 15:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sony Profits Plummet in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A surging yen sent profits at Sony Corp. tumbling  
for the first half of the fiscal year, though sales in its core 
electronics business would actually have risen by 11 percent in the 
second quarter if the yen had stayed steady. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half, Sony's group profits plunged 24.5 percent to  
64.9 billion yen ($622 million), compared to 86.1 billion yen ($825 
million) for the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales fell 7.6 percent, to 3.1 trillion yen ($29.7 billion) from  
3.4 trillion yen ($32.6 billion). 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings for the second-quarter rose 3.1 percent, however,  
rising to 46.5 billion yen ($445 million) from 45.1 billion yen 
($432 million) the previous year, the Japanese electronics giant 
said Wednesday. Revenue fell 6.8 percent, to 1.6 trillion yen 
($15.3 billion) for the three months ended Sept. 30, down from 1.7 
trillion yen ($16.3 billion) in the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the bad news was caused by the strengthening yen, which  
is devastating for exporters like Sony because it lowers the value 
of its overseas earnings when translated into yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In the July-September quarter, the yen averaged 112.7 yen to the  
U.S. dollar -- 23.3 percent higher than in the same quarter a year 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said Sony's business remained healthy, especially  
considering the slowdown in the economy at home that has crimped 
consumer spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``The results show that Sony's electronic business has truly  
recovered,'' said Hitoshi Kuriyama, an analyst for Merrill Lynch 
Japan in Tokyo. ``Sony outdid expectations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sony announced in March that it would reduce its work force of  
170,000 by 17,000 and cut manufacturing plants from 70 to 55 during 
the next four years. Sony is also trying to make computers and 
video games a bigger part of its business. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of electronics remained strong, especially personal  
computers and video cameras, both in Japan and the United States, 
and would have been up by 11 percent if the yen hadn't jumped, Sony 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the strong yen took its toll on all of Sony's main product  
lines except insurance, where revenue climbed by 11.7 percent on an 
increase in life insurance policies. 
</P>
<P>
	For the quarter ending in September, electronics sales fell 5  
percent, to 1.18 trillion yen ($11 billion) on the rising yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for Sony's movie business decreased 19 percent for the  
quarter. The second quarter got a boost from the box office success 
of ``Big Daddy' and ``Blue Streak'' but was hurt by ``Muppets From 
Space'' and ``Jakob the Liar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Income from Sony's TV business fell because of the loss of the  
syndication sales of ``Seinfeld'' from last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for Sony Pictures, which includes the movie and TV  
businesses, would have been flat had the yen not risen. 
</P>
<P>
	Its music business reported a sales drop of 12.8 percent, but it  
would have had flat sales if the yen had stayed at the same level. 
</P>
<P>
	Lower prices on game machines helped send sales in Sony's  
video-game business down by 4 percent for the latest quarter, even 
when keeping the currency constant. 
</P>
<P>
	``We acknowledge some areas of our business had problems other  
than the strong yen,'' said Sony spokesman Tomohiko Maeda. ``But we 
believe that electronics sales have turned around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. shares of Sony fell 37 1/2 cents to $151.37 1/2 in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 13:16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Irvin's Return to Game Clouded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Michael Irvin's return to the Dallas Cowboys from  
a spinal injury earlier this month was clouded as the team 
announced that Irvin was born with a spinal condition that 
increases his risk of further injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mike was born with a different-looking spine,'' Cowboys owner  
Jerry Jones said on Tuesday. ``How does that impact any decision he 
might make? To me, I've heard more discussed about what he was born 
with than I have about any damage'' incurred from the spinal 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	The condition, known as cervical stenosis, is basically a  
narrowing of the spinal canal. The congenital defect is relatively 
safe, team officials said, but the condition puts Irvin's spinal 
cord at greater risk because serious trauma can increase pressure 
and damage to the injured area. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1986, Green Bay cornerback Tim Lewis and Houston Oilers  
linebacker Frank Bush retired finding out they had narrow spinal 
canals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I'm concerned,'' Jones said. ``They're addressing  
everything. I don't see this as necessarily totally decided by 
whether or not the swelling goes down. Right now, I don't know if 
that's the issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cervical stenosis was initially revealed along with the  
spinal swelling when Irvin had a MRI exam after being knocked out 
of the game against Philadelphia on Oct. 10. Jones refused to say 
if the 33-year-old all-time leading receiver will return. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin was unavailable for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	``There are still more questions that need to be answered over  
the next several weeks,'' Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer said. 
</P>
<P>
	A few days after the injury, Maurer said Irvin had been cleared  
to ride a stationary bicycle and do other conditioning exercises. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin is scheduled for another MRI tomorrow. X-rays taken Monday  
showed nothing new in terms of Irvin's genetic condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones told reporters surgery is not an option for Irvin.  
</P>
<P>
	The 12-year veteran said said last week that no one had advised  
him to retire. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin's injury occurred when he awkwardly fell headfirst into  
the Veterans Stadium artificial turf as he was being tackled. He 
immediately lost feeling in his extremities and couldn't move his 
hands or legs for more than 15 minutes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 13:16:59 </DATE_TIME>
