<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gerald and Betty Ford Receive Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Deemed healers of Americans' bodies and souls,  
former President Ford and his wife, Betty, were awarded the 
Congressional Gold Medal on Wednesday, the highest civilian award 
given by Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is fitting that these partners in life are being honored  
jointly, for their partnership has enriched our democracy and our 
time,'' said House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	It was just over 25 years ago -- on Aug. 9, 1974 -- that Ford was  
thrust into the presidency when President Nixon resigned in the 
wake of the Watergate scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford served out the final 2 1/2 years of Nixon's second term. His  
pardon of Nixon earned him harsh criticism at the time from 
Democrats and Republicans alike. However, many now credit that 
action and Ford's quiet resumption of the nation's business with 
helping the shocked country move forward. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was easy for us to criticize you because we got caught up  
in the moment,'' President Clinton told Ford at Wednesday's 
ceremony on Capitol Hill. ``You didn't get caught up in the moment, 
and you were right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Ford was recognized for her candor about personal  
frailties, which has been a source of comfort and enlightenment to 
many Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	``If President Ford helped heal America's soul, Mrs. Ford helped  
heal our bodies,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D. 
</P>
<P>
	The same year her husband became president, Mrs. Ford announced  
that she had breast cancer and would undergo a mastectomy, an 
illness and procedure not often openly discussed at that time. Her 
action is credited with encouraging many women to seek lifesaving 
early detection of the disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Ford shared with Americans how, after her husband lost  
his 1976 bid for re-election to Jimmy Carter, she had become 
addicted to alcohol and pills her doctor had prescribed to help her 
ease sadness. 
</P>
<P>
	After recovering, she became the founder and president of the  
Betty Ford Center for alcohol and substance abuse in California, 
where the Fords now live. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's ceremony in the U.S. Capitol Rotunda was something  
of a homecoming for the Fords. The former president served in the 
House as representative for Michigan's 3rd District from 1949 and 
as minority leader from 1965. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert recalled how Ford's congressional  
colleagues voted overwhelmingly for him assume his fateful vice 
presidency under Nixon in 1973, after Spiro Agnew resigned under 
the shadow of scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gerald Ford did not become president because of polls, he did  
not become president because of campaign promises; he became 
president because of character,'' Hastert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Ford said that in spite of their unexpected years at the  
other end of Pennsylvania Avenue, in the White House, ``this House, 
to Gerry and me, the People's House, will always be our home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers initially used the Congressional Gold Medal to honor  
military leaders but began using it during the 20th century to 
recognize excellence in a range of fields. More than 320 medals 
have been awarded. 
</P>
<P>
	Honorees in recent years have included civil rights pioneer Rosa  
Parks, singer Frank Sinatra, Mother Theresa and South African 
President Nelson Mandela. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 16:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> O'Neill Plays After Father Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Paul O'Neill's father died early Wednesday  
morning after a long struggle with heart problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees outfielder was in the lineup in his usual  
spot, batting third and playing right field in Game 4 of the World 
Series against the Atlanta Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	``When he showed up, I assumed he was going to play,'' manager  
Joe Torre said. ``That's why he was here. This can keep his mind 
off the grieving for a couple of hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``Paulie does what he does. As George Steinbrenner likes to say,  
he's a warrior. He's here even though it is tough to concentrate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charles O'Neill, 79, died at 2:30 a.m. Wednesday at Lenox Hill  
Hospital in New York, about three hours after the Yankees beat the 
Braves 6-5 in 10 innings to take a 3-0 lead in the Series. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder O'Neill had come to New York from his Ohio home  
earlier this month for treatment for his heart. His son left the 
team for one day in June when his father underwent heart surgery in 
Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	``Paul has been carrying a heavy heart for a while now,'' Torre  
said. ``His dad has been suffering. He was not surprised by his 
passing because he had been in tough shape. It's a very sorrowful 
time for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Neill, who did not want to talk about his father's death  
before the game, stretched and took batting practice with his 
teammates on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	It was uncertain when the funeral would be held and whether  
O'Neill would have to leave the team if the World Series extended 
beyond Game 4. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's obviously free to do what he has to do for his family,''  
Torre said. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Neill is the third Yankee whose father has died in the past  
two months. Scott Brosius' father died of colon cancer on Sept. 12. 
Luis Sojo missed the first two games of the Series after his father 
died last Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you play this game you try to eliminate the highs and  
lows,'' Torre said. ``That has been difficult. There is nothing 
higher than playing in the World Series and nothing lower than 
mourning the loss of a family member. There has been a lot of this 
going on. We just have to fight through it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
