<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stewart Fans Flood Online Auctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A $9.99 golf ball suddenly was bid up to  
$202.50. An autographed score card, initially priced at just $1, 
rocketed to $103. 
</P>
<P>
	As news spread of golf champion Payne Stewart's death in a  
bizarre plane crash Monday, asking prices for the golfer's 
memorabilia began soaring on online auction sites as adoring fans 
and macabre collectors logged on to place their bids. 
</P>
<P>
	Online auction sites such as eBay, Yahoo! and Amazon.com were  
swamped. 
</P>
<P>
	At eBay, an autographed photo of Stewart decked out in his  
signature knickers and tam-o'-shanter hat went on the block last 
Tuesday for $9.95. And it stayed at that price, with only one bid, 
until 1:30 p.m. Monday -- when the value of Stewart's memorabilia 
started going up and authorities confirmed his plane had gone down 
in a South Dakota field, killing everyone on board. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-one bids and 27 hours later, frenzied fans had pushed the  
price for the photograph to $761.51. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the past it took people some time to realize the changing  
value of a baseball card or such,'' said Tom Churchill, a producer 
at Yahoo! Auctions. ``But with the Internet, you can see those 
values change in real time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Churchill said there was a surge in the number of searches for  
Payne Stewart at Yahoo! in the 24 hours following the plane crash 
and early indications showed a sudden increase in the number of 
Stewart's items being put up for sale immediately after the 
accident. He could not give specific figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The reaction is a common one, said Sharon Greenspan, a  
spokeswoman for Amazon.com. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have seen a trend of this with John F. Kennedy Jr. and Lady  
Diana or any events associated with a tragedy,'' she said. ``It's 
people's way of showing how they grieve or how they remember.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart's death was especially untimely. His plane was flying  
from Florida to Houston, where he was schedule to compete in the 
PGA Tour Championship. But shortly into the flight, it veered off 
course, hurtling pilotless 1,400 miles across the country and 
finally plummeting to earth after running out of fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators speculate that the cabin suddenly lost pressure  
causing all aboard to lose consciousness. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, 42, was a popular golf figure. He won 18 tournaments,  
including two U.S. Open titles and was part of the team that helped 
the United States stage a historic comeback to beat Europe last 
month for the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it's not always such fond memories of greatness that  
motivate collectors. According to the law of economics, the simple 
fact that no more autographs will ever be signed means the value of 
existing autographs naturally increases. 
</P>
<P>
	It's at that point, that something as sentimental as a baseball  
card or golf club can be transformed into a long-term investment, 
Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it's kind of ghoulish to think that way,'' she added.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
