<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sun Healthcare Makes Repayment deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE (AP) -- A nursing home company that filed for  
bankruptcy protection earlier this month has reached a tentative 
payment plan with holders of more than half of its debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement announced yesterday between Sun Healthcare Group  
Inc. and most of its senior creditors represents a potential 
restructuring of $1.3 billion of its $2.1 billion debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, however, would not provide any money for common  
stockholders or lesser creditors, the company said in a news 
release. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an unfortunate aspect of the bankruptcy that our stock  
does lose its value,'' Sun spokeswoman Karen Gilliland said 
Tuesday. ``We have many employees, including our CEO, that are 
affected by this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sun, based in Albuquerque, provides care to about 40,000 people  
in 369 nursing homes nationwide. The company and its affiliate 
firms employ about 80,000 people worldwide, including the United 
Kingdom, Spain, Germany and Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun listed more than $1.8 billion in assets and $2.1 billion in  
debts in its bankruptcy petition. When the company filed it Oct. 14 
in Delaware, it said it was close to a reorganization plan. 
Tuesday's agreement is a major step toward such a plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Reorganization is necessary for Sun to emerge from bankruptcy.  
</P>
<P>
	Sun said details of the agreement would not be available until a  
filing with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	But according to Sun's release, senior creditors have agreed  
there won't be enough money to pay anything to lesser creditors, 
the holders of $400 million in subordinated bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	It appears that the ``senior-most creditors all got together  
with the debtor and cut out the subordinated bond holders out of 
the picture,'' said Peter Chapman, president of New Jersey-based 
Bankruptcy Creditors Service Inc. and editor of Sun Healthcare 
Bankruptcy News. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts pointed out that the agreement also fails to mention  
what will happen to the real estate investment trust companies from 
which Sun leases nursing homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement still needs to be approved by a bankruptcy  
creditors committee and bankruptcy judge as part of Sun's 
reorganization plan. 
</P>
<P>
	If approved, it would provide Sun's banks and senior bondholders  
with a combination of cash, new senior long-term debt, new 
preferred stock and new common stock. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
