<DOCNO> APW19991027.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 01:00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Talking About Minn. Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- With his controversial comments on  
organized religion and a tell-all autobiography, Gov. Jesse 
Ventura's national image as a loudmouthed diversion has grown since 
his election a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	But back home in Minnesota, he's been talking mostly about  
policy lately. His major project is government reform, and the 
centerpiece is an idea only Nebraska has embraced: a single-house 
Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura says the issue should be a priority when state lawmakers  
reconvene in February. 
</P>
<P>
	``My point is let's get it on the ballot,'' Ventura said. ``The  
people have a right to choose and if I lose, I'll live with it. But 
at least we got it out there and at least the right people made the 
decision on what our government should be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The issue will go to the voters on the November 2000 ballot only  
if approved by both legislative chambers in the coming session. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor, a Reform Party member, says a change would save  
the state money and make the system more accountable, accessible 
and efficient. 
</P>
<P>
	He argues bills would follow a shorter, more understandable path  
if conference committees -- which work out differences between the 
chambers -- are eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
	Such committees give a handful of lawmakers too much power,  
Ventura believes. He also dislikes the gamesmanship he sees in the 
two-chamber system, which can let lawmakers cast politically 
correct votes secure in the knowledge a bill will die elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Some experts say the single-house idea is hardly innovative, and  
could merely be Ventura's search for a reform agenda in a state 
with little need for one. 
</P>
<P>
	``It did seem to come from nowhere,'' said Steven Smith, a  
University of Minnesota political science professor. ``There wasn't 
a public discussion of this idea. There wasn't a fiscal meltdown in 
the state from deadlock. To the contrary, things went smoothly'' in 
the 1999 Legislature, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska voters approved a one-House Legislature in 1934 after  
years of effort by George Norris, a populist who served in the U.S. 
House and Senate for a combined 40 years. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent poll showed Minnesotans almost evenly divided on the  
issue. And while a switch is a long shot, supporters say the idea 
might be lost for certain without a strong push from Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor has acknowledged the challenge of asking lawmakers  
to allow a vote that could eliminate some of their jobs, but says 
they should put that aside. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, Ventura's own controversies have made lawmakers  
less afraid of his bully pulpit. And with no fellow Reform Party 
members in the Legislature, he has no natural allies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly he's made it easier during the past few weeks for  
elected officials in both of the major parties to oppose him,'' 
Smith said Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
