<HEADLINE> Netscape Pioneer Forms New Startup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Web pioneer Marc Andreessen is launching a  
startup that will help other companies build Internet businesses, 
his first major venture since leaving America Online last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Andreessen, the 28-year old co-founder of Netscape  
Communications, formed the new company, called Loudcloud Inc., with 
a group of other Internet professionals from Netscape, Cisco 
Systems Inc., InfoSeek and other Web-related businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Andreessen, who helped build the world's first commercial  
Internet browser, had joined AOL when it bought Netscape 
Communications for $10 billion early this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The venture was vague about what it would sell. Loudcloud will  
supply ``technology and services high-growth Internet companies 
need to compete and win,'' Andreesseen said in a statement released 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, based in Menlo Park, Calif., planned to disclose  
more details early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Andreessen is chairman of Loudcloud. Ben Horowitz, another  
Loudcloud co-founder who also was a Netscape and AOL executive, is 
chief executive officer. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
