</P>
<P>
	Durable Goods Orders Fall 1.3 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Weaker demand for airplanes and cars led  
orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured goods down 1.3 
percent in September. The slide was about three times what analysts 
had been expecting. It was the first slump in five months. The 
Commerce Department reported today that orders for durable goods -- 
items expected to last at least three years -- declined to a 
seasonally adjusted $204.9 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Conoco Earnings Rise 39 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Conoco Inc. said its third-quarter earnings rose  
39 percent on gains in its exploration and production business. 
Conoco, whose spinoff from DuPont Co. was completed during the 
quarter, said it had earnings before one-time items of $261 
million, or 41 cents a share, compared with $188 million, or 30 
cents a share, in 1998 on a pro forma basis. Conoco A shares were 
at 27 3/16, up 1/4 

</P>
<P>
	eBay 3rd Q Results Top Expectations  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Online auction house eBay Inc. posted  
higher quarterly operating profits after it signed up a record 
number of new users and expanded its offerings to include cars and 
art. But its stock slumped as eBay also reported late yesterday on 
rising expenses to expand its computer systems. For the three 
months ended Sept. 30, San Jose, Calif.-based eBay reported net 
income of $1.35 million, or 1 cent a share. The earnings were up 
from $476,000, or break-even, a year earlier. Shares of eBay were 
at 137 3/4, down 14 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	National Geographic Goes High Tech  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Combining more than a century of traditional  
mapping with modern technology, the National Geographic Society is 
issuing a massive new world atlas and making its maps available on 
the Internet. ``It's a great day for maps,'' the society's chief 
cartographer, Allen Carroll, said. The new seventh edition of the 
atlas includes the breakup of Yugoslavia, the creation of the 
native territory Nunavut in Canada, new provincial boundaries in 
Poland and changing country names in Africa. 

</P>
<P>
	Free Encyclopedia Site Jammed  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- So far, Encyclopaedia Britannica's much-touted  
new Web site has been a real bomb.com. More than a week after the 
publisher put all of its volumes on the Internet for free, 
www.britannica.com remained jammed today, -- a victim of huge 
worldwide demand and inadequate hardware and software. An apology 
greeted Web users trying to visit the site, with the company 
explaining it is working around the clock to fix the glitches. An 
executive of Britannica.com Inc. acknowledged that the problems as 
a whole will take weeks to fix, although many users should be able 
to get in by next week. 

</P>
<P>
	Air Canada Reveals Stiff Penalties  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Air Canada disclosed today that it would face  
stiff penalties -- as much as $169 million in the first year alone -- 
if it leaves the Star Alliance of United Airlines and Lufthansa for 
rival Oneworld of American Airlines. The penalty provision was part 
of a 10-year deal Air Canada signed last week with the Star 
Alliance to help fight off a hostile takeover bid by Onex Corp., 
one of Canada's largest companies. Onex, which is backed by 
American Airlines, insists the penalties are a ``poison pill'' 
designed to thwart its offer to merge Air Canada with Canadian 
Airlines to create a single national airline linked with the 
Oneworld alliance. 

</P>
<P>
	Anheuser-Busch Earnings Rise  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Anheuser-Busch Cos. said its third-quarter  
earnings rose 13 percent on strong growth in domestic beer sales. 
The maker of Budweiser, Bud Light, Michelob and other beers earned 
$462 million, or 97 cents per share, on sales of $3.22 billion. 
That was up from earnings of $408 million, or 84 cents per share, 
on sales of $3.12 billion in the third quarter of 1998. The results 
were above analysts' expectations. 

</P>
<P>
	Sony Profits Plummet in 2nd Quarter  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A surging yen sent profits at Sony Corp. tumbling  
for the first half of the fiscal year, though sales in its core 
electronics business would actually have risen by 11 percent in the 
second quarter if the yen had stayed steady. For the first half, 
Sony's group profits plunged 24.5 percent to 64.9 billion yen ($622 
million). Earnings for the second-quarter rose 3.1 percent, 
however, to 46.5 billion yen ($445 million), the Japanese 
electronics giant said today. 

</P>
<P>
	Boeing, Airbus Sweeten El Al Offers  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- U.S. aircraft manufacturer Boeing and its  
European competitor Airbus have improved their bids to replace part 
of the Israeli airline El Al's passenger fleet, a spokesman said 
today. The new bids came as El Al continues to delay deciding 
whether to buy the Boeing 777 airliner or the Airbus A330, a tactic 
that Israel's transportation minister recommended to induce 
manufacturers to sweeten their offers. 

</P>
<P>
	NatWest Defends Against Hostile Bid  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Lifting a page from its pursuer's playbook,  
National Westminster PLC announced plans today to sell some of its 
businesses and trim 1,650 jobs in an effort to fend off a $34.4 
billion hostile bid by the Bank of Scotland. NatWest urged 
shareholders to reject its rival's offer -- one of the largest in 
British banking -- as it unveiled a defense strategy that Bank of 
Scotland dismissed as a pale imitation of its own proposal, and 
that did not seem to impress analysts and investors. 

</P>
<P>
	Wall Street Crash Anniversary Near  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Friday will be the anniversary of the stock  
market crash of 1929, which brought a halt to a a period of free 
spending and widespread optimism that stocks would keep going up 
and up. Many similar conditions prevail these days, but market 
watchers point out that for every similarity, there are also 
differences narrowing the odds of another catastrophic market 
decline. William C. Freund, director of the Center for the Study of 
Equity Markets at Pace University in New York says: ``The economy 
has become more and more stable, we know how to use fiscal policy, 
and there are whole new industries that contribute substantially to 
economic growth.'' 

</P>
