<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bethlehem Steel Reports Net Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Competition from steel imports and costs of  
modernization combined to give Bethlehem Steel a net loss of $90 
million, or 77 cents per share, for the third quarter of 1999, the 
company reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, Bethlehem reported net income of $37 million, 21  
cents a share, for the third quarter. Wednesday's results were 
below the 63 cents-per-share loss forecast by analysts surveyed by 
First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were very disappointed with our third quarter financial  
results,'' said Curtis H. Barnette, Bethlehem's chairman and chief 
executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our shipment levels and prices were depressed because of  
unfairly traded steel imports, and we incurred substantial 
additional costs in connection with extensive and planned 
modernization and other outages,'' Barnette said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the third quarter of 1999 were $958 million, compared  
to $1.14 billion for the third quarter of 1998. According to the 
company, average steel prices for domestic companies in 1999 are 
down seven percent from average 1998 prices, the largest such 
decline in 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, the company has been hurt by the very aggressive  
imports of steel into the U.S. However, they are generally looking 
for higher steel prices,'' said Todd A. Hinrichs, an analyst with 
ABN AMRO North America. 
</P>
<P>
	``The general consensus is that the market for steel is  
turning,'' Hinrichs said. ``The problem is, how quickly can it 
turn?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bethlehem's stock fell 25 cents to $6.50 on the New York Stock  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Bethlehem, based in Bethlehem, Pa., said its third-quarter  
results included about $50 million in additional operating costs 
associated with relining a blast furnace at Sparrows Point, Md.; 
with a temporary shutdown at a majority-owned iron ore operation in 
Hibbing, Minn., and other modernization and maintenance outages. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hibbing operation was idled because of high iron ore  
inventories. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of 1999, Bethlehem's net loss was $145  
million, or $1.35 per share, on sales of $2.90 billion, compared to 
a profit of $143 million, or 92 cents per share, on sales of $3.47 
billion for the first three quarters of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Looking ahead, Bethlehem said it expects competition to remain  
intense in its markets, because of excess global steel capacity, 
new domestic supply and continuing high inventories of steel plate. 
But it predicted the combination of current orders and better 
market demand will allow some restoration of prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Production has been resumed at Hibbing and most of the work at  
Sparrows Point has finished. Modernized facilities should result in 
improved competitiveness and profitability for the long term, 
provided fair trade in steel is restored, Bethlehem said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it would continue its strategy of concentrating  
on steel and rebuilding its financial strength, taking all steps 
needed to reduce costs and improve competitiveness. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
