<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Oct. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Governor Leaving Cuba With Sick Boy  
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Concern over a sick child's welfare triumphed over  
political differences today, as Fidel Castro granted Illinois' 
visiting governor permission to take an ailing 7-year-old boy back 
to the United States with him for treatment. The boy, Raudel 
Alfonso Garcia, suffers from portal hypertension, a potentially 
fatal disease that produces high pressure in blood flowing from 
several organs to the liver. Cuban doctors don't have the 
facilities to treat him. Castro ``has agreed to let him go back, 
and we are going to take him back with us tomorrow,'' Gov. George 
Ryan told an impromptu news conference early today after a meeting 
with the Cuban president. 

</P>
<P>
	China Police Seek End to Protests  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Chinese police stepped up patrols and  
surveillance of Tiananmen Square today, trying to put an end to 
three days of low-key protests by members of the banned spiritual 
movement Falun Gong. Group members staged no overt demonstrations 
and were not easily distinguished from the hordes of Chinese 
tourists normally wandering the square, China's symbolic political 
heart. But their presence there in defiance of a three-month 
crackdown against Falun Gong assured that they would be arrested, 
as dozens of others have been in the square in recent days. 

</P>
<P>
	Clintons Honor Annie Leibovitz  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and first lady Hillary  
Rodham Clinton honored photographer Annie Leibovitz at a White 
House ceremony that also recognized work to empower women. The 
event was held to highlight an exhibition of Leibovitz' photos 
hanging at the nearby Corcoran Gallery of Art. The exhibit and 
accompanying book, ``Women,'' produced with writer Susan Sontag, 
examine the accomplishments of women in the 20th century through 
portraits of female coal miners, judges, writers and other 
professionals. 

</P>
<P>
	Supreme Court To Review Electrocutions  
</P>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- The U.S. Supreme Court has agreed to  
consider whether electrocution amounts to cruel and unusual 
punishment, using a Florida case in its first evaluation of the 
controversial procedure in more than a century. The decision, 
announced yesterday, comes four months after the third botched 
electrocution in Florida this decade. It effectively shut down 
Florida's electric chair, granting open-ended reprieves to a man 
scheduled to die today and another who faced electrocution 
yesterday. The issue may not be resolved by the high court for 
months. 

</P>
<P>
	Rising River Threatens Mexican City  
</P>
<P>
	VILLAHERMOSA, Mexico (AP) -- The bloated Grijalva River, one of  
Mexico's largest, rose to dangerously high levels yesterday and was 
threatening to wipe out the heart of this already badly flooded 
city, the capital of Tabasco state. More than 22 miles of sandbags 
were the only thing holding it back. The crisis began three days 
ago, when authorities opened the floodgates of Las Penitas dam 
upstream in the neighboring state of Chiapas, releasing four times 
the amount of water normally discharged. The dam was beyond 
capacity and in danger of breaking. 

</P>
<P>
	Families Unhappy With Kid's Schools  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A third of the households with children in  
Cleveland and Oakland, Calif., are unhappy with their neighborhood 
elementary schools, and one-fifth of those families in those cities 
are so dissatisfied they want to move because of their schools, a 
survey found. Generally, however, parents across the nation view 
their schools favorably, according to a survey being released today 
by the Educational Testing Service. It said that in more than 
three-fourths of the cities surveyed, fewer than 10 percent of 
households indicated they wanted to move because of poor school 
quality. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Share Prices Fall Sharply  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices fell sharply today with  
investors discouraged by the U.S. dollar's weakening against the 
yen and an overnight decline on Wall Street. The Nikkei shed 289.43 
points to close at 17,382.36. 

</P>
<P>
	Oilers 3, Coyotes 1  
</P>
<P>
	EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Ethan Moreau had a goal and an assist  
as the Edmonton Oilers ended a three-game winless streak with a 3-1 
victory over the Phoenix Coyotes last night. Moreau scored 
Edmonton's first goal and assisted on the winning goal by Josef 
Beranek at 4:53 of the third period. Alex Selivanov scored the 
Oilers' final goal, on a power play with 5:27 remaining. 

</P>
<P>
	Yanks Take 3-0 Lead in World Series  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chad Curtis hit his second home run leading off  
the 10th inning last night and the New York Yankees beat the 
Atlanta Braves 6-5 to move within one victory of a World Series 
sweep. In the best-of-7 Fall Classic, the Yanks lead 3-0. Curtis 
had homered in the fifth inning to begin New York's comeback from a 
5-1 deficit. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
