<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Garage Olimpo' Recalls Dirty War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Marco Bechis knew he wanted to  
film ``Garage Olimpo'' back in 1977. In April of that year, army 
troops under the junta's command dragged him from school and hauled 
him off to a secret jail. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 20, and the 10 days of confinement had a lasting impact.  
In captivity he was blindfolded and kept isolated; all he heard 
were the sounds of doors being opened and shut brusquely, of chains 
clanking, of locks jangling. Bechis survived thanks to his Italian 
passport; he was expelled from the country and went to Italy, where 
he lives now. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the Argentine-Italian director has recaptured the terror  
of that violent era through ``Garage Olimpo,'' helping moviegoers 
revisit the atrocities of the 1976-83 dictatorship through a 1990s 
lens. 
</P>
<P>
	The movie re-creates the terror of the so-called Dirty War, when  
thousands were kidnapped or made to disappear during the military 
regime's hunt for leftist opponents and other dissidents. 
</P>
<P>
	Set in the time of the dictatorship, the film tells the story of  
Maria, a 19-year-old political activist who teaches poor shantytown 
workers to read and write. Played by Antonella Costa, the beautiful 
heroine lives in a decaying mansion in Buenos Aires, where her 
mother rents out rooms to make ends meet. One of the tenants is 
Felix, a shy young man who falls in love with Maria. 
</P>
<P>
	Played by Carlos Echevarria, Felix is without a past. He claims  
to work as a watchman in a garage. One morning, soldiers seize 
Maria and take her to ``Garage Olimpo'' -- a torture center. There, 
Maria is shocked to discover her interrogator is none other than 
Felix. 
</P>
<P>
	From there, their peculiar relationship unfolds as Maria fights  
for survival against the odds. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 350 detention centers were said to operate at the  
height of the dictatorship. An official report said at least 9,000 
people were killed in the junta's war on what it called leftist 
subversion. Human rights groups put the figure as high as 30,000. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was also a time when thousands of Argentines celebrated  
in the streets over their first World Cup soccer championship -- 
won, no less, in Buenos Aires -- while compatriots languished in 
detention centers in this capital. As the unusual love between 
Maria and Felix develops inside the center, one even hears the 
cheering from the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	Bechis said he sought to set that bleak period in a global  
context, ``to make a subtle connection between what happened in 
Argentina 20 years ago and ... what happened just a short while ago 
in Bosnia and Sarajevo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now 43, Bechis worries that memories of the junta years are  
fading. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is, someone in 100 years might say that none of this  
happened. If evidence and testimonies aren't left behind, it's 
perfectly possible that could happen,'' he said in an interview 
here. 
</P>
<P>
	Some reviewers charge that the film lacks the intensity and  
complexity of similar captor dramas. But a reviewer in Clarin, 
Argentina's largest newspaper, said the movie is a reminder of the 
deep injury that remains from that military era, writing: ```Garage 
Olimpo' is not only the story of Felix and Maria. It is the story 
of those who are no longer with us and those who managed to survive 
the horror -- of wounds felt deeply in all of society, of the 
nightmare that yet returns from the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1985, several former junta leaders were convicted and  
sentenced to life in prison, only to be pardoned by President 
Carlos Menem in 1990. Under a loophole in the amnesty, several of 
the former leaders are being prosecuted anew -- on charges of 
abducting infants born to women in captivity. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, ``Garage Olimpo'' has been presented in the  
noncompetitive section of the 52nd annual Cannes Film Festival as 
well as Toronto's film festival. But it finds resonance in 
Argentina, particularly among those who were only children at the 
time of the Dirty War. 
</P>
<P>
	Fabian Antonelli, 23, said he was disturbed by the film's  
graphic quality. Nonetheless, he said he had to see the movie. 
``They showed things one must never forget,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
