<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Hoyt Axton    	
</P>
<P>
	HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- Hoyt Axton, a folksy baritone, songwriter  
and actor who wrote Three Dog Night's No. 1 hit ``Joy to the 
World'' and songs that were performed by artists from Elvis Presley 
to Ringo Starr, died Tuesday. He was 61. 
</P>
<P>
	Axton had suffered a heart attack two weeks ago, and another  
during surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Three Dog Night's recording of his novelty ``Joy to the World''  
(``Jeremiah was a bullfrog ...'') topped the charts for six 
straight weeks in 1971, making it the biggest hit of the year. 
Axton had pitched the song to group members when he was their 
opening act in 1969-70. 
</P>
<P>
	He also wrote ``Never Been to Spain'' for the band, a song also  
recorded by Presley. 
</P>
<P>
	Axton's own singing hits include ``Boney Fingers'' and ``When  
the Morning Comes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A large man, Axton specialized in playing good ol' boys as an  
actor on TV and in films, including ``Gremlins'' and ``The Black 
Stallion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Axton's mother, Mae Boren Axton, had her own spot in popular  
culture history as the co-author of Presley's ``Heartbreak Hotel.'' 

</P>
<P>
                          *Michael Baring    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Michael Baring, a leading member of the British  
banking dynasty brought down by a rogue trader in 1995, died Oct. 
15, according to the ING Group, which took over the bankrupt 
Barings bank. He was 50. 
</P>
<P>
	News reports said he suffered a heart attack.  
</P>
<P>
	Baring played a key role in trying to steady nerves when a  
Singapore-based British trader, Nick Leeson, brought down the bank 
with bad bets on financial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Baring -- great-great-grandson of Sir Francis  
Baring, who founded the banking dynasty in the 18th century -- was 
head of international marketing at the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	He transferred to ING when the Dutch group bought the bank for  
$1.60 and took over its debts of some $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	His most recent appointment was head of a division responsible  
for ING Barings' relationships with clients and partners worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	He began work at Barings in a job in the mailroom, before  
becoming a trader. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Robert Caldwell    	
</P>
<P>
	SALINA, Kan. (AP) -- Robert Caldwell, the city's only black mayor  
and who served organizations from the Boy Scouts to the Kansas 
Board of Regents, died Wednesday. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldwell served eight years on the Salina City Commission --  
including three terms as mayor -- as well as a term in the state 
Legislature. He was a celebrated public school teacher, and was 
inducted into the state's Teachers Hall of Fame in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldwell worked with the Boy Scouts, was active in the National  
Association for the Advancement of Colored People and served on the 
Kansas Board of Regents. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Lucille B. Chapman    	
</P>
<P>
	KESHENA, Wis. (AP) -- Lucille B. Chapman, a five-time Menominee  
Indian tribal chairwoman, died Sunday of diabetes. She was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Chapman was a member of the old tribal council from before 1961,  
when the tribe's federal trust status ended and the reservation 
became Menominee County. Chapman was then elected to the Menominee 
County Board. 
</P>
<P>
	After the tribe regained its federal trust status in 1973,  
Chapman was elected to five one-year terms as chair between 1980 
and 1990. She was later a legislative secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	While serving as chairwoman, Chapman was a chief negotiator with  
the state to secure statutory recognition for tribal courts. 

</P>
<P>
                     *Monsignor Jeremiah Monahan    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Monsignor Jeremiah Monahan, a chancellor of the  
Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York who handled the church's 
financial matters, construction projects and administration, died 
Monday. He was 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Monahan had been chancellor since 1997. He oversaw the nearly  
1,000 workers in the Terrence Cardinal Cooke Catholic Center, the 
administrative headquarters of the archdiocese. He was also in 
charge of human resources policies. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the 413 parishes control their own budgets, Monahan  
oversaw every departmental budget and determined policies to ensure 
money was administered properly. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Wesley C. Mues    	
</P>
<P>
	GRAND ISLAND, Neb. (AP) -- Wesley C. Mues, a Nebraska State Court  
of Appeals judge who once acted as special counsel in impeachment 
proceedings against a former attorney general, died Monday night in 
a traffic accident. He was 51. 
</P>
<P>
	Mues, who joined the appeals court in 1994, was appointed  
special counsel for the state in the impeachment proceedings 
against then-Attorney General Paul Douglas. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas was impeached by the Legislature in 1984, partly over  
his conduct in office and personal dealings with a former officer 
of the failed Commonwealth Savings Co. in Lincoln. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Charles E. Simons Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	AIKEN, S.C. (AP) -- U.S. District Judge Charles E. Simons Jr.,  
for whom the Aiken courthouse is named, died Tuesday, months after 
suffering extensive head injuries in a fall. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the senior federal judge and former law partner of U.S.  
Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Simons received a lifetime appointment to the federal bench in  
1964. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Gerald H. Trautman    	
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Gerald H. Trautman, the retired head of The  
Greyhound Corp., the predecessor of current-day Viad Corp., died 
Monday. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	Trautman became president of Greyhound in 1966. He shepherded  
the company's move from Chicago to Phoenix, retiring in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	During his tenure, Greyhound purchased Armour/Dial, a company  
twice its size. He directed 150 companies and 57,000 employees 
during his time at the helm. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
