<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Said Obliged To Pay U.N. Dues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United States is obligated to pay its  
past dues to the United Nations under a precedent of international 
law that Washington helped set more than 30 years ago, the world 
court's president said. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States faces the loss of its seat in the U.N. General  
Assembly if it doesn't pay at least $350 million of its $1.8 
billion debt by Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Stephen M. Schwebel, speaking at a news conference  
Wednesday, said a 1962 case before the International Court of 
Justice had underpinned the requirement of U.N. members to pay 
their dues. 
</P>
<P>
	At that time, the United States led several U.N. member states  
in asking the court to clarify whether General Assembly members 
were obligated to pay assessments for U.N. peacekeeping operations, 
Schwebel said. And the United States argued that assessments made 
by the General Assembly were binding, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In an advisory ruling, the court held that members were bound to  
pay their peacekeeping assessments and made a more general 
statement about members' obligation to pay the portion of the U.N. 
budget apportioned to them. 
</P>
<P>
	``That statement of law is as good today as it was in 1962,''  
Schwebel said. The advisory was later ratified in essence by the 
General Assembly 
</P>
<P>
	The court only handles disputes between nations that agree to  
grant it jurisdiction. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States had long given the court that authority until  
it withdrew it in 1986 after Nicaragua brought an action against 
the U.S. government over its support of the contra rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton vetoed a budget bill Monday, giving as one  
reason that it would not have paid enough of the U.S. arrears to 
the United Nations to avoid losing the General Assembly seat. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also included only $200 million of the $485 million the  
Clinton administration asked for to cover the U.S. share of 
expected peacekeeping operations in East Timor, Sierra Leone, Congo 
and the Horn of Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress has held up payment of U.S. arrears for years,  
demanding that the United Nations streamline its organization. 
Legislation that would have paid off the bulk of the bills was 
vetoed last year by Clinton because it contained unrelated 
restrictions on U.S. spending for overseas family planning 
organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Reiterating U.S. concerns that the United Nations adopt a  
no-growth budget, Deputy Ambassador Peter Burleigh said Wednesday 
that the proposed U.N. spending plan for 2000-2001 was too large. 
</P>
<P>
	``We strongly believe that it needs to be brought down, at a  
minimum, to the level of the current budget,'' Burleigh told the 
committee that deals with U.N. budget matters. ``We will not 
support a higher level.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
