<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cocoa Futures Hit 6 1/2-Year Low  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Cocoa futures fell Wednesday to their lowest level since 1993 on  
the New York Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange as newly harvested 
cocoa arrived at West African ports in huge numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, natural gas futures touched a two-month high  
and gold bounced back after a long slide. 
</P>
<P>
	Uncertainties over the political liberalization in the Ivory  
Coast, the world's No. 1 cocoa-producing nation, have left cocoa 
prices unpredictable in recent months. Now the market is heading 
into its peak supply period this winter, with this year's cocoa 
crop shipped onward to foreign customers. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, news that cocoa had arrived in greater-than-usual  
quantities at Ivory Coast ports last week helped send the price to 
a 6 1/2-year low of $858 per ton before recovering. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa for December delivery closed down $9 at $867 a ton.  
</P>
<P>
	``The market is just reacting to the increasing pressure from  
Ivory Coast,'' said Luis Rangel of Fimat Futures Inc. in New York. 
``The season has just started, cocoa has come to port and there's 
going to be a greater amount of hedging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also pressuring the price are weather conditions that bode well  
for cocoa-growing areas over the next few days, according to 
meteorologists. 
</P>
<P>
	Port arrivals had lagged behind those of a year ago, with  
farmers withholding shipments due to dissatisfaction with prices 
under the new liberalized system. But the total of 33,765 tons that 
arrived last week pushed the season total to nearly double that of 
last year at this time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't anticipate any protest that would disrupt the flow of  
cocoa,'' Rangel said. ``They're not going to hinder that -- cocoa's 
the life blood of the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the New York Mercantile Exchange, a frenzy of late buying  
pushed the expiring November contract for natural gas to its 
highest level since late August, settling up 8.1 cents at $3.092 
per million British thermal units. 
</P>
<P>
	The buying was sparked by forecasts for high winter demand and  
by expectations that data to be released later in the day by the 
American Gas Association would heighten concerns about tight 
supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Other energy prices on the New York Merc were mixed. December  
crude fell 27 cents to $22.92 a barrel; November heating oil rose 
.23 cent to 60.76 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline rose .03 cent 
to 64.18 cents a gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent crude for December delivery fell 11  
cents to $22.59 a barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Comex division of the New York Merc, investors were split  
on whether gold's weeks-long decline was over after the metal's 
December futures contract rose $3.80 to $294.20 per troy ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	Some predicted a further slide to $275; others said it was bound  
for $300-plus territory again. They said the outlook may depend on 
plummeting near-term interest rates, which made it cheaper to 
borrow gold instead of buying it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
