<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 13:10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NatWest Defends Against Hostile Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Lifting a page from its pursuer's playbook,  
National Westminster PLC announced plans Wednesday to sell some of 
its businesses and trim 1,650 jobs in an effort to fend off a $34.4 
billion hostile bid by the Bank of Scotland. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest urged shareholders to reject its rival's offer -- one of  
the largest in British banking -- as it unveiled a defense strategy 
that includes stripping excess layers of management and tightening 
the focus on retail customers. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bank of Scotland dismissed the plan as a pale imitation of  
its own proposal, and analysts and investors seemed unimpressed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The defense document looks a little bit on the thin side,''  
said Simon Wills of Charterhouse Securities. ``I'm not sure that it 
changes things very much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest revealed its plan to shareholders and the London Stock  
Exchange in a long-awaited response to the takeover offer. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest scoffed at its Scottish rival's claim that $1.7 billion  
could be saved by merging the two companies and advised 
shareholders to spurn the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bank of Scotland is attempting to hijack cost savings that  
belong to NatWest shareholders and is claiming unrealistic merger 
benefits,'' chief executive David Rowland said in a statement. ``I 
urge NatWest shareholders to reject the offer which is 
ill-conceived and significantly undervalues NatWest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seeking to keep its shareholders loyal, the bank's management  
stressed that they would receive cash from any asset sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland startled the clubby world of British finance  
last month when it announced a takeover bid for NatWest and harshly 
criticized the London-based bank's executives for their 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Scottish bank's aggressive move triggered speculation that  
other bidders for NatWest might emerge with offers of their own. 
None has done so, although Royal Bank of Scotland PLC and Abbey 
National, a leading mortgage lender, are widely expected to join 
the fray. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts predicted that Bank of Scotland's bid also could  
trigger other takeover battles among the country's banks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does represent a watershed and potential catalyst for a  
further round of consolidation,'' Wills said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland dismissed NatWest's defense plan, which it said  
does nothing to detract from the logic of its takeover offer. The 
Scottish Bank said NatWest's latest ideas even concede the merits 
of key elements of its own proposed strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The credibility of NatWest's claims is undermined by its  
history of failure to deliver under substantially the same 
management team,'' Bank of Scotland said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Many investors appeared to share that opinion. NatWest stock  
closed 2.5 percent lower Wednesday, at $22.67 per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland shares rose 0.4 percent to finish at $11.86.  
</P>
<P>
	To streamline its operations, NatWest said it plans to slash the  
number of its business units to five from 13 and to ``de-layer'' 
management to allow for speedier decision-making. 
</P>
<P>
	It aims to concentrate on serving business clients and wealthy  
individuals along with its retail customers. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its defense, NatWest said it plans to sell off  
Gartmore, its institutional fund management arm; Greenwich NatWest, 
its capital market business; NatWest Equity Partners, its venture 
capital unit; and Ulster Bank in Northern Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland, for its part, has said it intends to unload  
three of those businesses -- Gartmore, Greenwich and Ulster Bank -- 
if its bid succeeds. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest also plans to cut 1,650 jobs, most of them by year's  
end. These cuts, amounting to 2 percent of its work force, would be 
in addition to a planned reduction of 10,000 jobs announced 
previously. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
