<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jet Pressure Valves Are Critical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The pressure inside an aircraft cabin is  
regulated by carefully balancing the air flowing in and out. 
</P>
<P>
	In the case of the Learjet that crashed Monday, killing golfer  
Payne Stewart and five others aboard, air was siphoned off the two 
jet engines, adjusted for the proper temperature and then piped 
into the cabin. 
</P>
<P>
	Along the route, the air flowed through valves on each side of  
the aircraft. One of them, the left-hand modulator valve, was 
replaced Saturday, Bob Benzon, chief investigator of the Stewart 
crash, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Once air has entered an aircraft cabin, other valves in the  
front and rear of the aircraft automatically open and close as the 
altitude increases or decreases. That balances the amount of air in 
the cabin and maintains a pressure that is survivable for the 
passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	In November 1995, the FAA ordered that outflow/safety valves  
made by Allied Signal Aerospace be replaced in Lear 35 jets within 
18 months. The agency ordered the replacement to ``prevent rapid 
decompression of the airplane due to cracking and subsequent 
failure'' of the valves. 
</P>
<P>
	The outflow/safety valves are different from the left- and  
right-hand modulator valves. They are the valves in the nose and 
tail of the aircraft that ensure the proper cabin environment is 
maintained. 
</P>
<P>
	The owner of the jet carrying Stewart, Sunjet Aviation of  
Sanford, Fla., said Wednesday that log books show previous owners 
completed the mandatory valve replacement in 1995. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
