<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Oct. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Gore, Bradley Spar in N.H. Debate  
</P>
<P>
	HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- Pressed in campaign debate about President  
Clinton's personal behavior, Vice President Al Gore said tonight 
that he understood the public disappointment and anger and sought 
to provide ``as much continuity and civility'' as possible during 
the Monica Lewinsky controversy. ``He's my friend,'' Gore said of 
the president, fielding the first question from a voter in the 
first debate with campaign rival Bill Bradley. In the opening 
moments of the debate, Bradley touted his $65 billion plan for 
universal access to health insurance. Both men pledged to work for 
an overhaul of the campaign finance laws to reduce the role of big 
money. 

</P>
<P>
	Hostages Held in Armenian Parliament  
</P>
<P>
	YEREVAN, Armenia (AP) -- Gunmen inside Armenia's parliament were  
still holed up early Thursday with dozens of hostages. On Wednesday 
afternoon the men seized parliament, killing Prime Minister Vazgen 
Sarkisian and at least six other people. Three hostages were 
released about 10 hours after the assault, but the gunmen continued 
to demand talks with President Robert Kocharian. In a televised 
statement early Thursday, Kocharian promised to take ``all measures 
to control the situation and free the hostages.'' But there no 
immediate signs of a resolution to the standoff. 

</P>
<P>
	House Enters Assisted Suicide Debate  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House stepped into the emotional debate of  
physician-assisted suicide today, voting to bar doctors from using 
federally controlled drugs to help patients die. The House voted 
271-156 for a bill sponsored by House Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde 
that penalizes doctors who aid in a suicide but encourages them to 
treat the pain of dying patients. Opponents said doctors will be so 
worried about losing their licenses to prescribe drugs, and 
spending at least 20 years in jail for aiding in a suicide, that 
they will decline to dispense needed medication. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Gov't Posts Surplus Again  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States posted a record $123 billion  
federal budget surplus last year. It marked the first back-to-back 
surpluses since 1956 and 1957. The announcement sparked a battle 
for bragging rights today between the White House and the 
Republican-led Congress, with both sides hoping to reap political 
dividends in next year's elections. President Clinton, battling 
Republicans over spending, accused the GOP of writing a budget that 
siphons $18 billion from the Social Security surplus. 

</P>
<P>
	Hewlett-Packard Stock Falls Sharply  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Hewlett-Packard Co.'s stock fell sharply  
today after it told analysts it was uncomfortable with current 
estimates for fourth-quarter earnings, prompting several to sharply 
reduce their expectations. Hewlett-Packard fell $6.25 to $70.37 1/2 a 
share and was the third biggest declining issue on the New York 
Stock Exchange. In after hours trading, the shares fell to $67. The 
company blamed its problems on weaker-than-expected sales of its 
Unix servers line. The company slashed it's per share earnings 
prospects by 5 cents, to 73 cents a share and cut the company's 
prospects for revenue growth to 6 percent, or $10.8 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Marilyn Monroe Items Get High Bids  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Thirty-seven years after her death, Marilyn  
Monroe grabbed the spotlight again today at an auction featuring 
her furs, hundreds of books and the dress she wore to serenade 
President Kennedy in 1962. The dress, so tight she had to be sewn 
into it, was expected to draw the most spirited bidding. Another 
dress -- believed to have been worn to entertain U.S. soldiers in 
Korea in 1954 -- sold for $112,000. The first big-ticket item -- a 
platinum eternity ring, encrusted with 34 baguette-cut diamonds, 
given to Monroe by ex-husband Joe DiMaggio -- sold for $772,500. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Rises 92.76  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average gained 92.76 to  
close at 10,394.89 today. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 
1,735-1,310. The Nasdaq fell 8.95 to 2,802.52. 

</P>
<P>
	Raptors Cut Rapper Master P  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Multimillionaire rap artist and producer Master  
P, whose real name is Percy Miller, was waived by the Toronto 
Raptors today. The 29-year-old Miller, who has parlayed his music 
success into a successful recording label and a financial interest 
in a sports agent business was a training camp invitee by the 
Raptors. Miller, who played briefly in the CBA last year after 
being cut by the Charlotte Hornets in training camp, averaged 2.2. 
points in six exhibition games with Toronto. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  



  	   	
