<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Treasury Head Optimistic About Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Key Democratic lawmakers, worried about  
consumers' privacy, are calling on President Clinton to veto 
sweeping legislation to overhaul the financial services laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration is pushing on with the bill -- which has  
divided congressional Democrats -- in hopes it will soon be enacted 
by the Republican-controlled Congress, officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would lift Depression-era barriers and allow  
banks, securities firms and insurance companies to merge and sell 
each other's products. With the White House having lifted its 
long-standing veto threat and now supporting it, the measure is 
being given the best chance ever of adoption after 20 years of 
battling. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and other officials told a  
group of financial industry lobbyists the administration was 
optimistic about the bill's prospects and would continue to work 
toward its passage, a Treasury official, who spoke on condition of 
anonymity, said Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't immediately clear whether House Minority Leader Dick  
Gephardt, D-Mo., would endorse the measure or break with the White 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	Many moderate Democrats in the House support the legislation.  
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., has been leading the fight for  
liberal House Democrats on the privacy issue as Congress has edged 
close to enacting the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Markey on Tuesday enlisted the aid of Rep. John Dingell of  
Michigan, senior Democrat on the House Commerce Committee, and 
Reps. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., and Bill Luther, D-Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	They circulated a letter to Clinton among their colleagues in  
the House. 
</P>
<P>
	The overhaul legislation ``does not go nearly far enough in  
ensuring that American consumers receive strong privacy 
protections,'' the letter says. ``We do not believe the bill ... 
adequately protects American consumers from the wholesale 
networking of their personal, private information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Barry Toiv had no immediate comment on the  
letter. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks would not be allowed to provide customers' data to  
telemarketers under the new legislation, but would be able to share 
it with affiliated financial companies under the same corporate 
ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	Data sharing is a major reason why financial companies want to  
merge, as it opens numerous opportunities for the companies to 
market a range of products and services. 
</P>
<P>
	Many consumers are alarmed, however, at the prospect that their  
personal financial data could be shared by companies. Consumer 
activists such as Ralph Nader also have criticized the legislation 
on privacy grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	A broad coalition of consumer groups, privacy advocates, the  
American Civil Liberties Union and Phyllis Schlafly's conservative 
Eagle Forum sent its own letter to Clinton Tuesday urging his veto. 
``This bill fails to give consumers real choice about the sharing, 
selling or using of their personal information among (financial) 
affiliates,'' they said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, conservative Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., has  
broken with Banking Committee Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, over 
the privacy issue and said he would vote against the bill. Shelby 
served notice on Monday that he will try to force changes in the 
privacy provisions and failing that, attempt to derail the measure. 
Under Senate rules, a single senator can hold up action for hours 
or days if he chooses to. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
