<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minnesota Bans Team From Postseason </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The University of Minnesota wants to show the  
NCAA it is serious about dealing with an academic cheating scandal 
by banning itself from postseason basketball tournaments for one 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The university barred itself from any possible berth in the NCAA  
tournament or the NIT in 2000, although it can still compete in the 
Big Ten tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA is to complete its investigation of the school months  
from now and could hand out out its own sanctions then. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must demonstrate good faith and take meaningful action to  
repair the damage that has been done by others,'' Minnesota 
president Mark Yudof said Tuesday. ``It's the right thing to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The university also is placing the program on probation for an  
unspecified period. That will mean more stringent reporting to the 
NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	No current players were involved in the scandal, and Yudof is  
aware the players may regard the sanctions as unfair. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NCAA has to worry about deterrents,'' Yudof said. ``I have  
to worry about deterrents in the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An investigation of the men's basketball team began in March  
after former tutor Jan Gangelhoff claimed she did more than 400 
pieces of course work for at least 20 basketball players from 1993 
to 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Yudof has said the investigation revealed ``numerous, maybe even  
massive'' instances of academic fraud. It has since widened to 
include accusations of improper payments and travel irregularities, 
and alleged sexual and other misconduct in the men's athletics 
department. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said the university and the NCAA could impose more  
sanctions after the final university report is completed, probably 
by Nov. 10. The report is expected to be made public about 10 days 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	NCAA spokeswoman Jane Jankowski said the organization would not  
comment specifically on the sanctions. But she said schools often 
come up with their own punishments. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA is supposed to have an infraction hearing next spring  
and could issue sanctions then or wait until the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's just the beginning,'' said Gangelhoff, who now  
works at a casino in Danbury, Wis. ``President Yudof must have 
enough information to realize these two things (sanctions) were 
going to happen regardless of whether or not he has the complete 
report in hand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yudof did not say whether jobs might be lost because of the  
findings. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Clem Haskins resigned under pressure in June and accepted  
a $1.5 million buyout. He has said he had no knowledge of any 
academic cheating on the basketball team. Dan Monson of Gonzaga 
replaced Haskins. 
</P>
<P>
	One reason to come out with sanctions now was to improve team  
morale, Yudof said. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the staff and our team, it's the beginning of the end,''  
Monson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Monson said he would be open with prospective players about the  
sanctions, which he and Yudof acknowledged would hurt recruiting. 
However, if they end after one year, they may not have as great an 
impact, Monson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA's 64-team tournament determines the national champion.  
The NIT is held for 32 teams that don't qualify for the NCAA 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota has won the NIT twice and qualified for the NCAA Final  
Four in 1997. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
