<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Shipyard Strike Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Striking workers agreed Wednesday to  
return to work in Halla Heavy Industries Co., South Korea's third 
largest shipyard, which had been paralyzed by a two-month-long 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of Halla workers went on strike in early August,  
demanding that the ailing company guarantee job security and hire 
back all labor leaders fired for illegal labor activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Management reached a compromise with labor leaders on Tuesday,  
agreeing to gradually hire back fired labor activists. On 
Wednesday, rank-and-file union members voted for the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Police had threatened to raid Halla's Youngam shipyard on the  
south coast. Halla workers erected barricades at the shipyard's 
entrances. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers said they will return to work this week and clean up the  
shipyard for operation. 
</P>
<P>
	The shipyard is an affiliate of Halla Group, South Korea's  
12th-largest conglomerate, which collapsed under $4 billion in debt 
in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks took over the shipyard and asked Hyundai, South Korea's  
largest shipbuilder, to operate it on their behalf. 
</P>
<P>
	Layoffs aimed at restructuring South Korea's inefficient  
industries were among conditions set by the International Monetary 
Fund when it bailed out the country's battered economy in late 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	But that prescription was anathema to union members accustomed  
to lifetime employment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
