<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Concerned About Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. Population Fund is grappling with  
a serious drop in income, requiring program cuts that will result 
in an additional 1.4 million unwanted pregnancies, its executive 
director says. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of celebrating the 30th year of operations and  
widespread acceptance of its programs to curb the population, Dr. 
Nafis Sadik said the fund is scrambling for resources and cutting 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund's income has dropped 14 percent in two years -- from  
$290 million in 1997 to $277 million in 1998 to $248 million in 
1999, she said Tuesday. As a result, it can only cover two-thirds 
of its commitments to programs worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund is financed by voluntary contributions from the 188  
U.N. member states. 
</P>
<P>
	Sadik said the shortfall was due to exchange rate fluctuations,  
a drop in the dollar value of Japan's contribution which is the 
fund's largest -- and most importantly a drop in U.S. funding to $20 
million last year and zero this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The funding crisis has delayed plans to include family life  
education in the school curriculum in Tanzania, postponed plans for 
operations in remote villages in India, suspended training of 
health workers in Vietnam, and canceled the purchase of 
contraceptives for some 200,000 women in Ecuador, Sadik said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just when these programs are being effectively implemented,  
the brakes are being put on and resources are being cut,'' she told 
a news conference. ``It is both ironic and tragic ... as we move 
into what should be a new era of harmony and cooperation, that a 
shortage of funds is tying our hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to Sadik, the shortfall in funds this year will mean  
over 1 million people who might have used modern contraceptive 
methods will use less-effective traditional methods -- and 1.5 
million people will continue to use no method of family planning. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be 1.4 million additional unwanted pregnancies each  
year, 570,000 induced abortions and over 670,000 unwanted births -- 
and these unwanted pregnancies will be linked to over 3,300 
maternal deaths, nearly 41,000 infant deaths and 15,000 child 
deaths, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	A bill that would authorize $25 million for the fund in the next  
fiscal year is awaiting approval by the U.S. Congress. Rep. Carolyn 
Maloney, a New York Democrat, said she got assurances Tuesday from 
White House chief of staff John Podesta and House minority leader 
Richard Gephardt that the money would be approved. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
