<DOCNO> APW19991027.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 06:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sony Profits Rise in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese electronics powerhouse Sony Corp.'s profit  
rose 3.1 percent in the second fiscal quarter but plunged nearly 25 
percent for the first half, depressed by the strong yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The results disclosed today come as Sony faces a sluggish  
economy at home and a surging yen that threatens to damage exports 
by making Japanese products more expensive overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony earned 46.5 billion yen, or $445 million, in the three  
months ended Sept. 30 compared with 45.1 billion yen a year 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales and operating revenue fell 6.8 percent to 1.6 trillion  
yen, or $15.3 billion, for the quarter from 1.7 trillion yen a year 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong yen not only hurts exports, it also means that  
dollars and other currencies earned overseas are worth less when 
converted into the home currency. 
</P>
<P>
	In the July-September quarter, for example, the yen averaged  
112.7 to the U.S. dollar -- 23.3 percent stronger than the same 
quarter a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony estimated that if the yen had held steady, sales would have  
increased 9 percent and sales would have risen 25 percent in the 
July-September quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``This rise in the yen had a significant negative impact on the  
reported financial results translated into yen,'' Sony said in its 
earnings statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The report says that sales in Sony's movie business decreased 19  
percent in the quarter. The second quarter got a boost from the Box 
Office success of ``Big Daddy' and ``Blue Streak'' but was hurt by 
``Muppets From Space'' and ``Jakob the Liar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Operating income from Sony's TV business, which is part of Sony  
Pictures, fell because of the loss of the sundication sales of 
``Seinfeld'' from last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for Sony Pictures would have been flat if the currency  
rate had remained the same. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half, consolidated net profits plunged 24.5  
percent to 64.9 billion yen, or $607 million, compared to 86.1 
billion yen last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales and operating revenue fell 7.6 percent to 3.1 trillion  
yen, or $29.1 billion in the first half from 3.4 trillion a year 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony is moving through a major transition. It announced in March  
that it would lay off 17,000 of its 170,000 workers and cut 
manufacturing plants from 70 to 55 during the next four years. Sony 
is trying to make computers and video games a bigger part of its 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony expects group operating profit for the full year to be less  
than previously forecast. The company did not release an updated 
forecast on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong yen has prompted calls for the government to  
intervene, since many fear it could stifle Japan's recovery from 
its worst economic downturn in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar figures provided by Sony were based on a calculation  
from yen using an average dollar-yen exchange rate for the period. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 21:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBC, Yanks Work Out Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A day after NBC sports reporter Jim Gray was  
snubbed on live TV, the network threw him right back into the thick 
of things with the New York Yankees -- and everyone talked this 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC even made a last-minute change and allowed Gray to present  
the World Series trophy to the Yankees in their clubhouse after 
they beat the Atlanta Braves 4-1 for a sweep Wednesday night. 
Hannah Storm had presented the trophy in previous years. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray interviewed team owner George Steinbrenner, manager Joe  
Torre, World Series MVP Mariano Rivera, Derek Jeter and Roger 
Clemens after the game -- without a hitch. 
</P>
<P>
	At Game 3 Tuesday night, some members of the Yankees wouldn't  
talk to Gray because of a contentious live interview he had with 
Pete Rose on Sunday night regarding accusations Rose gambled on 
baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	After Chad Curtis hit his game-winning homer in Game 3, he  
refused to be interviewed by Gray and walked away from him in front 
of millions of TV viewers. But Steinbrenner and commissioner Bud 
Selig intervened to resolve the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talked about it late last night and they both jumped into  
it,'' NBC Sports chairman Dick Ebersol said. ``George walked into 
the situation and took control. ... He made it abundantly clear 
that nothing like that would happen again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ebersol, who admitted the Rose interview might have gone on too  
long, called Gray ``the best reporter in the business, maybe 
ever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gray apologized for the Rose interview on the air before Game 3.  
At one point before Game 4, he left Yankee Stadium for the NBC 
trailer escorted by security men as fans shouted insults. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre had criticized Gray's interview of Rose but said the issue  
was in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a certain obligation to NBC,'' he said. ``I just wish  
Chad would have said it was his choice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Curtis said Gray shouldn't take his actions on Tuesday night  
personally. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope it didn't come across that way,'' Curtis said. ``It  
seemed to me that he stepped out of bounds on the interview with 
Pete. It was something that needed to be done. ... I don't think 
we'll do it again because my personal feeling is we've made our 
point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NBC World Series analyst Joe Morgan, who played with Rose with  
the Cincinnati Reds, refrained from putting blame on either side. 
</P>
<P>
	``All this stuff is taking away from the World Series and none  
of this is good for the game,'' Morgan said. ``All the players are 
individuals. I heard they took a vote, but I don't believe it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
