<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Publisher Denies Plotting Murders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- A leading Israeli publisher confirmed today he  
is being accused of plotting murders -- reportedly those of his two 
main media rivals -- and dismissed the claims by a convicted 
wiretapper as a ``terrible web of lies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ofer Nimrodi, until last week the publisher of the Maariv daily  
newspaper, broke his silence today after a court lifted a gag order 
and the allegations became front-page news in Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	According to media reports, a private investigator who bugged  
phones at a rival newspaper at Nimrodi's request several years ago, 
now accuses him of having plotted to kill publishers Amos Schocken 
of Haaretz and Arnon Mozes of Yediot Ahronot. 
</P>
<P>
	Police have been investigating the allegations by the  
wiretapper, Rafi Pridan, for three months, but have not called 
Nimrodi in for questioning because they lacked evidence, said the 
reports in Israel's major dailies and radio stations. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said they would not comment on an ongoing investigation.  
</P>
<P>
	Emerging today from his villa in the posh Tel Aviv suburb of  
Savyon, Nimrodi said: ``I am being accused of being connected with 
murder ... I am simply in a state of shock.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nimrodi said Pridan, who is serving a four-year sentence for  
wiretapping, repeatedly tried to blackmail him. The publisher said 
Pridan threatened to spread fabrications that would wreck Nimrodi's 
reputation unless he was paid millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Maintaining his innocence, the publisher said he wanted police  
to ``investigate the terrible web of lies that has been spun above 
my head, to investigate whether I have any connection with 
murder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nimrodi said the case has taken a severe toll on him and his  
family. ``I just want my life back,'' said Nimrodi, who bought 
Maariv in the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, he suspended himself as Maariv publisher and director  
of the Israel Land Development Corp., a holding company for a 
variety of commercial interests, including Maariv. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Ministry officials were not available for comment today.  
However, they said last week that police were investigating whether 
Nimrodi had plotted to kill a third person, private investigator 
Yaakov Tzur, who had become a witness for the prosecution in the 
wiretapping scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Nimrodi hired Pridan and Tzur to wiretap the offices of Yediot  
Ahronot in the early 1990s, during a bitter circulation war between 
the tabloids. 
</P>
<P>
	Police began investigating the charges in 1994. Tzur turned  
state witness in 1995. Ultimately, Nimrodi was sentenced to eight 
months in prison and Pridan to four years. In exchange for his 
testimony, Tzur was not tried. 
</P>
<P>
	Nimrodi was released in February after serving more than four  
months. Pridan, who started his sentence last month, began 
cooperating with police in August, the Jerusalem Post daily 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the media reports, Pridan told police that Nimrodi  
hoped to lure Tzur to Indonesia in 1996, by getting a Thai-based 
Israeli businessman to hire the detective to run a security check 
on his operations in the region. Pridan was to arrange the killing. 
Tzur turned down the job offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The media reports, quoting police and prosecution officials, did  
not say if Pridan explained why Nimrodi would want to kill Mozes or 
Schocken. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
