<HEADLINE> Delays Haunt America's Cup Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- America True and Nippon asked for  
delays because of gear failures, Young America turned up late, and 
the Swiss and French teams didn't show at all. 
</P>
<P>
	The challenger series for the America's Cup fell into disarray  
today as on-board problems, blustery weather and officials' 
decisions left only one real race out of a scheduled 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials cut short celebrations for Italy's Prada team, voiding  
the result of the race which completed the team's sweep of 
round-robin 1 of the regatta to decide who will face Team New 
Zealand for sailing's prized trophy next year. 
</P>
<P>
	In its afternoon race, Prada easily beat Hawaii's Abracadabra  
2000, Italian skipper Francesco de Angelis' 10th win in 10 starts. 
But Abracadabra successfully protested, complaining it had not had 
enough time to prepare for its second race after the morning 
matchups were postponed because of strong wind conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	For the same reason, officials also voided the result of the  
afternoon race between Dennis Conner's Stars and Stripes and Young 
Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	The two races are scheduled to be rerun Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	After a three-day postponement because of collision and mishap  
damage to two boats, racing resumed today on Hauraki Gulf in winds 
of about 20 knots and choppy seas. 
</P>
<P>
	In the morning races, Stars and Stripes easily defeated Young  
America, which missed the start after returning to port because of 
a gear failure and started the race a full leg behind. 
</P>
<P>
	Prada, the Spanish team and Japan's Nippon all received wins  
after the teams they were supposed to race -- the French and the 
Swiss -- effectively forfeited by staying in port to work on their 
boats. 
</P>
<P>
	AmericaOne's final two races Tuesday were postponed until  
Thursday while the team repairs damage from a collision with Stars 
and Stripes Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	America True and Nippon met in the only real race of the  
morning, and even that was delayed after gear failures on both 
boats. 
</P>
<P>
	Nippon skipper Peter Gilmour beat Dawn Riley's America True in  
pre-start maneuvers, leaving the Americans stalled as the gun 
fired. Gilmour took the wind advantage and finished the first 
upwind leg 10 boat lengths in front. 
</P>
<P>
	Nippon had a clear lead until the last downwind leg, when, with  
both boats plunging though the chop under spinnaker, America True 
trimmed 57 seconds off Nippon's lead and crossed just one second 
behind. 
</P>
<P>
	In more than 700 races over four months, the 11 challenger teams  
from seven countries receive one point for each victory in the 
first of three round-robins, four points in the second and nine in 
the third. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner of a finals series will meet defending champion Team  
New Zealand in a best-of-9 regatta starting in February for the 
America's Cup. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
