<HEADLINE> Two-Year Treasury Note Yields Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Yields on two-year Treasury notes rose in  
Wednesday's auction to the highest level in more than two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield was 5.935 percent, up from 5.665 percent at the last  
auction on Sept. 29. It was the highest rate since two-year notes 
sold for 5.998 percent on Aug. 26, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The notes will carry a coupon interest rate of 5 7/8 percent with  
each $10,000 in face value selling for $9,988.80. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of $15 billion in notes were sold out of bids totaling  
$40.3 billion. 
  	   	
</P>
