<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing, Airbus Split El Al Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli airline El Al has decided to split a  
contract to replace its passenger fleet between the U.S. aircraft 
manufacturer Boeing and the European consortium Airbus, an El Al 
spokesman said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	El Al will buy three Boeing 777 planes and three or four Airbus  
330 planes, spokesman Nachman Klieman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to buy the Airbus planes still requires final  
approval by the company management, expected in two weeks, Klieman 
said in a statement. The decision to buy the Boeing planes has been 
approved. 
</P>
<P>
	El Al will pay $400 million to replace its 747 planes with the  
Boeing 777's. Airbus spokesman Dan Arkan said the Airbus deal would 
be worth about $250 million, depending on the number of planes 
purchased and the maintenance agreements reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Klieman said the company decided to split the contract because  
the 300-seat Boeing 777's were more suitable for long flights, 
while the 250-seat Airbus 330's were a better choice as a 
medium-sized airplane used for shorter flights. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies welcomed the decision.  
</P>
<P>
	Boeing Senior Sales Vice President Thomas Basacchi in a  
statement thanked El Al for its ``continued expression of 
confidence in the Boeing company.'' He said the first 777 would be 
delivered in February, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Airbus Vice President John Leahy said in a statement that his  
company was happy with the contract, ``but we are a lot more happy 
with the new partnership between Airbus and El Al.'' If the Airbus 
deal is approved, the first plane would arrive by February 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition of the Airbus aircraft will break Boeing's  
monopoly at El Al, which currently uses only Boeing planes. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel was under strong pressure from the United States to give  
the contract to the Seattle-based manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	By awarding part of its contract to Airbus, Israel -- which  
receives $3 billion annually in U.S. foreign aid -- could pave the 
way for other countries that receive substantial U.S. aid to grant 
more military contracts to non-U.S. manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	El Al's decision, announced following a late night meeting  
Wednesday, was originally to have been taken by early spring but 
has been postponed repeatedly. 
</P>
<P>
	As El Al continued to stall, both companies gave sweeter and  
sweeter offers, most recently offering improved bids on Monday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	In its new bid, Airbus agreed to subcontract 50 percent of the  
contract value to Israel Aircraft Industries, company spokesman Dan 
Arkan said, up from its initial offer to direct 35 percent of the 
contract value to IAI. 
</P>
<P>
	Klieman said Boeing had also pledged to spend at least 50  
percent of the contract value to buy products from Israeli 
companies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
