<HEADLINE> Trail Blazers Cut Two Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Portland Trail Blazers cut two players  
Wednesday, including promising rookie Roberto Bergersen, to trim 
their roster to the NBA-required 15 players. 
</P>
<P>
	Bergersen, a 6-foot-6, 200-pound guard who was drafted by  
Atlanta in the second round out of Boise State, had an impressive 
debut for Portland, hitting a 3-pointer in overtime to help the 
Blazers beat the Seattle SuperSonics 124-115 in the exhibition 
opener. 
</P>
<P>
	But he never distinguished himself as a shooter after that. In  
his next game against Golden State he was 0-for-5, missing all four 
3-point attempts in 12 minutes. He didn't score again the rest of 
the preseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a good kid, and he works hard, but it's tough being a  
draft pick on this team,'' said Blazers guard Steve Smith, noting 
Portland's talent and depth. 
</P>
<P>
	Monty Buckley, a 6-6, 210-pound journeyman guard-forward, played  
in four preseason games, averaging 2.3 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Bergersen averaged 17.3 points over three seasons at Boise  
State, finishing fourth on the Broncos' career scoring list with 
1,485 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Bergersen was selected by Atlanta with the 52nd pick in the  
draft, then traded to Portland for future considerations. 
</P>
<P>
	Buckley was undrafted out of California and spent the past three  
seasons with the CBA's Sioux Falls Skyforce. 
</P>
<P>
	Portland is allowed to carry 15 players on its roster, three of  
whom will be placed on the injured list before next Tuesday's 
season opener at Vancouver. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
