<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Grain System May Help Farmers / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) -- North Dakota farmers irked by inaccurate  
and burdensome tests for grain damage could benefit from new 
technology that seeks to streamline the process, a Fargo company 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Bandy Technology Systems has developed a system that enables  
elevators to essentially test for sprout damage with the push of a 
button, said president Mark Bandy. The company also has received 
$25,000 from the North Dakota Agricultural Products Utilization 
Commission for research on a vomitoxin testing system for wheat and 
barley. 
</P>
<P>
	APUC provides grants to developers of North Dakota farm  
products. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers complain that they often get unfair prices for their  
crops because existing testing systems are inaccurate. The testing 
process also is complicated for elevator managers who do not have 
the technical expertise, Bandy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The sprout-testing machine is on the market, he said. The  
systems cost from $10,000 to $30,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both of those systems replace laborious, inaccurate testing  
systems,'' Bandy said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The existing tests require extremely well-trained technicians.  
It requires a great deal of knowledge in terms of things that are 
normally taught to chemists.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Diepolder, a Willow City farmer who has spoken out against  
inaccurate testing, said he welcomes any improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it was consistent and they could sample a load and get it  
accurate and consistent ... I'd welcome it because the current 
situation is inadequate,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprouting of crop kernels, which can significantly damage grain,  
occurs under excessively wet conditions. Vomitoxin is a byproduct 
of scab disease, which has ravaged North Dakota crops in the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Animals that eat infected grain can become sick, and beer made  
from barley with high levels of vomitoxin can foam excessively. 
</P>
<P>
	Elevators discount the price they pay for lower-quality grain,  
and some farmers question the test results. A study by a federal 
grain inspection agency last year said elevators did not have the 
technology to offer pinpoint accuracy needed in evaluating barley 
quality. 
</P>
<P>
	``(The) tests are for baloney, not for barley. Frustrated  
farmers are boiling over, and it will come to a head soon,'' 
Diepolder said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bandy said his company's system not only will eliminate  
inaccuracies, but also allow for quick tests. He said current tests 
can run up to an hour, while the new technology does it in about 
five minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	That would make it easier for farmers who want to test just a  
truckload to eliminate what Bandy calls the 
``one-bad-apple-in-a-barrel'' scenario. 
</P>
<P>
	``You take one truckload and put it in with 10 loads and you can  
end up with all 11 loads not meeting milling specifications,'' 
Bandy said. ``The idea here is to ... give the farmer and elevator 
more control over their process, rather than mixing good grain with 
bad.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 10:10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Power Giant AES Buys Brazil's Tiete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Global power giant AES Corp. on  
Wednesday bought a controlling stake in Brazilian energy company 
Tiete for $470 million. 
</P>
<P>
	AES, based in Arlington, Va., bid 30 percent more than the  
minimum asking price for Tiete, which can produce 2,600 megawatts 
of energy and serves Brazil's most heavily industrialized state, 
Sao Paulo. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts originally had predicted a much higher selling price,  
but many potential bidders dropped out because of recent legal 
problems involving the privatization of the Cemig power company in 
the neighboring state of Minas Gerais. 
</P>
<P>
	Minas Gerais had sold a 30 percent stake in Cemig to private  
shareholders, including AES, Southern Co. and the Brazilian bank 
Opportunity. But the current governor wants to bring Cemig back 
under full state control and is trying to restrict the power of 
minority shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiete was the second of three Sao Paulo generators to be  
privatized. The third one, Cesp Parana, is to be sold in the first 
quarter of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	AES owns power-generating plants around the world and sells  
wholesale power in bulk. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
