<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fat-Cell Hormone Shows Promise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A hormone naturally produced in fat cells  
showed promise in helping people lose weight, though a small 
portion of those studied gained weight during a six-month study. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the 47 adults injected with varying dosages of the  
hormone leptin lost weight, with those getting higher dosages 
losing the most -- as much as 15.6 pounds on average. 
</P>
<P>
	The study combined exercise and diet with the hormone treatment.  
</P>
<P>
	Some, however, gained weight, pointing out the need for further  
study. 
</P>
<P>
	``There really is no magic bullet,'' lead author Dr. Steven B.  
Heymsfield of St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital in New York told 
science reporters Tuesday at a conference of the American Medical 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it is possible that scientists may one day be able to  
``switch off appetite,'' Heymsfield said, ``diet and exercise are 
ultimately the mainstay of treatment'' for obesity. 
</P>
<P>
	The study began with 70 adults, but only 47 lasted through the  
study. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers said only three people dropped out of the study  
because of adverse reactions -- two had injection site reactions and 
one had heart palpitations.The authors believe patients who 
withdrew did so because they didn't like having to repeatedly 
inject themselves with leptin. Patients who received the highest 
doses were most likely to drop out. 
</P>
<P>
	Those on leptin lost from about 1.5 pounds on average for the  
lowest dosage, to 15.6 pounds on average for the highest dosage; 
subjects who received a placebo lost about 3 pounds on average. 
</P>
<P>
	A few gained from about 2 to 10 pounds, apparently because their  
bodies resist leptin, Heymsfield said 
</P>
<P>
	Preliminary results of the study were reported last year. The  
study was partly funded by California-based leptin manufacturer 
Amgen. 
</P>
<P>
	Research on humans remains preliminary and clinical use of  
leptin is still years away. 
</P>
<P>
	The study results are ``ambiguous'' because the doses of leptin  
given were relatively high compared to natural levels, the weight 
losses were small, and some people did not respond to the treatment 
at all, an outside leptin researcher said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a glass half full or half empty. ... We don't know if  
these levels and type of leptin are really safe,'' said Dr. Luciano 
Rossetti, professor of medicine at Albert Einstein College of 
Medicine in New York. ``This raises both hope and concern at the 
same time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leptin is produced by fat cells. It is supposed to signal the  
brain to stop eating but the signal does not get through in some 
overweight people. It is one of at least a half-dozen hormones that 
``tightly regulate'' food intake in animals and probably humans, 
Heymsfield said. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that in the study, the highest weight losses involved  
injecting the equivalent of several tablespoons of leptin daily, 
and presumably the hormone would have to be taken for life in order 
to maintain its benefits. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
