<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Plans Worldwide Commercial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. hopes to reach a billion viewers  
Monday evening in a rare global advertising gamble aimed at raising 
its corporate profile as the millennium approaches. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's second-biggest automaker has cobbled together an  
unusual collection of television networks that will carry an 
unusually long two-minute commercial at about 9 p.m. local time in 
most markets around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's strategy is to get the widest possible exposure for a  
single airing of a commercial. 
</P>
<P>
	The commercial subtly showcases all seven of Ford's automobile  
brands, suggesting in a montage of emotional vignettes that its 
products fit seamlessly into people's lives around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, it shows a war veteran riding in a Ford Mustang  
convertible in a homecoming parade, an Italian couple embracing in 
front of a Volvo, a well-dressed woman putting her sleek dogs in 
the back seat of a Jaguar and Japanese girls playing in cherry 
blossoms near a Mazda. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad from the agency J. Walter Thompson carries the Ford logo  
near the start and at the end but there is no narrator. 
</P>
<P>
	The often disconnected images, shot in nine countries, are held  
together by the song ``Just Wave Hello,'' written expressly for 
Ford and sung by the 14-year-old soprano Charlotte Church. Waving 
people appear in many scenes, their actions sometimes matching the 
lyrics. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad is being shown two months ahead of the year 2000, and  
Ford officials said the timing signals their intent to make the 
company the global leader in automotive products and services. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are serious about trying to understand people and their  
lives and their needs in an emotional way so we can design vehicle, 
products and services they opt to choose,'' James C. Schroer, vice 
president of global marketing for Ford, said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	He hopes viewers ``come to the conclusion that Ford Motor Co.  
has a heart and soul and has the kind of people and products that 
people will want to get to know better and will trust us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schroer declined to say how much it cost to run the ad globally  
but he said one published estimate of $10 million was conservative. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Grubbs, who oversees the ad agency BBDO's purchases of  
national commercial time for clients like Pepsi-Cola, Visa and 
Federal Express, said Ford's plans represented ``a pretty big 
idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the most difficult things today is how to break through  
the clutter and get impact,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Monday nights typically attract TV's biggest audiences  
of the week, and he said a two-minute commercial is bound to get 
attention simply because it is four times longer than the typical 
30-second ad. Announcing the plans in advance will also help. 
</P>
<P>
	``You may actually get some people to tune in for curiosity's  
sake to see what is up with this,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad will run on 38 different networks in the United States  
alone, including the broadcast networks ABC, CBS, NBC, FOX and WB. 
Due to the time differences across the U.S., viewers on the West 
coast could see the commercial on some cable networks as early as 6 
p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroer said he expects the ad will reach 300 million households  
and one billion people globally the first night. 
</P>
<P>
	After its initial run, Ford plans to continue running shortened  
one-minute versions of the ad through the new year. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad wasn't designed to trigger an immediate sales surge,  
Schroer said. 
</P>
<P>
	He intends to watch how many people go to Ford's Web sites for  
more information after the commercial runs and how many people 
mention the ad when they visit dealers selling Ford's brands which 
also include Lincoln, Mercury, and Aston Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	He also hopes Ford moves up in the ranking of most-trusted  
companies around the world, which he said will be key to competing 
in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are on the first page'' of such listings, he said. ``We  
would like to be at the top.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
