<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights From Gore-Bradley Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Highlights from Wednesday's debate between Democratic  
presidential candidates Al Gore and Bill Bradley: 

</P>
<P>
	On leadership and the presidency:  
</P>
<P>
	GORE: ``A president is the only person in our constitutional  
system who has the responsibility to fight for the welfare and 
well-being of all of our people. Senators and congressmen have 
constituency groups, and they look to the national interest, but a 
president is charged with fighting for all the people. That's what 
I want to do; to bring into being a vision of a bright future for 
our country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BRADLEY: ``I think there are three values that are important  
that a leader has to have. One is absolute integrity -- honesty and 
integrity. There I think of Jimmy Carter. Second, I think that a 
leader has got to have the ability to see around the corners, to 
see the future before it's here ... And next, I think a leader has 
to have courage. Example of that, I would pick somebody who's not 
an American, Mikhail Gorbachev, who saw that the world was change, 
and had the courage to make that change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	On expanding gay rights:  
</P>
<P>
	GORE: ``I'm for domestic partnerships having legal protections,  
but not the same sacrament, not the same name, because I favor 
protecting the institution of marriage as it has been understood 
between a man and a woman. But I think that a partner should have 
legal protection and contractual rights and health care and the 
rest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BRADLEY: ``I support gays being able to serve openly in the  
military. If a gay American can serve openly in the White House, in 
the Congress, in the courts, in the Treasury Department and in the 
attorney general's office, why can't they serve openly in the U.S. 
military? It doesn't make sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	On campaign finance reform:  
</P>
<P>
	GORE: ``I think it's very important to set a higher standard  
because what I want to do as president -- if you elect me president, 
I promise you I will fight my heart out to get meaningful campaign 
finance reform and get the influence of big money out of our 
political system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BRADLEY: ``From my perspective, there is no issue that is so  
linked to other issues as campaign finance reform. That's why it is 
an imperative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	On expanding health care coverage:  
</P>
<P>
	GORE: ``The availability of treatment for diabetes and the  
availability of treatment for depression or schizophrenia ought to 
be the same in my view ... I promise you, give me a chance to roll 
up my sleeves and go to work on this. This is one that I will fix 
for you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BRADLEY: ``One of the things that I've offered as a part of the  
health care plan was to allow Medicare to pay not only for health, 
but also for plans that would cover health and provide the social 
services to people who were in their homes. Now, it wouldn't be 
quite the special services that an Alzheimer's patient needs, but 
it would give relief to someone who is caring for an Alzheimer's 
patient in the home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	On U.S. intervention in foreign conflicts:  
</P>
<P>
	GORE: ``We are the natural leader of the world. I don't think  
that is a chauvinist American statement. I think that's a statement 
of fact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BRADLEY: ``There is no way we have the resources or the wisdom  
to be involved in all 32 ethnic wars in the world. What we need to 
do is we need to find ways of using multilateral institutions like 
the U.N. or regional institutions like NATO ... we don't take the 
full responsibility, but we play a part.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	On protecting the environment:  
</P>
<P>
	GORE: ``We, in our country, have a lot of work to do. Global  
warming is a real problem. Air pollution is a real problem. Water 
pollution is a real problem. We've got to clean up the toxic waste 
sites.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BRADLEY: ``You protect the natural world from pollution or you  
clean up that which has been polluted so that individuals may 
encounter something that is bigger than they are and lasts longer 
than they do. Every time I have some moment on a seashore, or in 
the mountains, or sometimes in a quiet forest, I think that this is 
why the environment has to be preserved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	On education reform:  
</P>
<P>
	GORE: ``I favor tough teacher testing for new teachers including  
in the subjects that they teach. Tough peer evaluation for existing 
teachers. I think that one of the reasons we do need more teachers 
is to reduce the class size so there's more one-on-one time between 
teachers and students who might learn in a different way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BRADLEY: ``When FDR was president of the United States and we  
were in a depression, he said 'I'm going to try this, I'm going to 
try that, I'm going to try something else. But we are going to get 
out of this depression.' And I say to the American people that if 
I'm president of the United States, when it comes to urban public 
education, we're going to try this, we're going to try that, we're 
going to experiment here, experiment there. But we are going to 
improve urban public education.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 12:50:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Rejects Helms Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House today rejected an offer by  
Sen. Jesse Helms for a hearing next week on the ambassadorial 
nomination of former Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun in exchange for 
sensitive documents. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart called Helms' request  
``completely unreasonable and unmeetable.'' But he said the White 
House was not inclined to circumvent the committee process to 
install Moseley-Braun as ambassador to New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to continue to work through the relevant  
committees to try to get movement,'' Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	The stalemate increased the likelihood that Clinton would give  
Moseley-Braun a so-called ``recess appointment'' when the Congress 
recesses next month, Democratic congressional officials suggested. 
</P>
<P>
	That would enable the Illinois Democrat, the nation's first  
black female senator, to serve until the end of this Congress, when 
Clinton leaves office anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	The Constitution allows the president to make such appointments  
-- and bypass the usual Senate confirmation process -- during 
congressional recesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Another White House spokesman, Barry Toiv, said earlier today  
that ``we don't discuss the possibility of recess appointments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the White House hopes that Helms would change his mind  
and not seek to delay the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Helms, R-N.C., offered to hold a hearing on her nomination as  
soon as next week. But, in exchange, he demanded sensitive 
documents from the Justice Department and Internal Revenue Service 
on her background by ``no later than Monday, Nov. 1.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The documents are ``vital'' to the consideration of the  
nomination by the Foreign Relations Committee, which he chairs, 
Helms wrote in a letter to President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	But Toiv said that the request ``asked for an extraordinary  
amount of information, including materials on anybody who has ever 
worked for the nominee or in her campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The deadline is not a serious deadline,'' Toiv said. ``So we  
don't think this was a real request designed to move the nomination 
forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At issue are allegations, never proven, that Moseley-Braun used  
leftover 1992 campaign funds to pay for personal luxuries. The 
accusations were raised during her unsuccessful 1998 re-election 
campaign against Republican Peter Fitzgerald. 
</P>
<P>
	Helms last week said her nomination was under an ``ethical  
cloud'' and suggested Senate action on it wouldn't come anytime 
soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Helms clashed with Moseley-Braun during her one term in  
Congress, most memorably on the Senate floor over use of the 
Confederate Flag. She later accused Helms of taunting her in an 
elevator by singing ``Dixie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Civil rights groups and congressional Democrats condemned Helms'  
apparent efforts to block the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Helms made his offer to hold a hearing next week -- in  
exchange for the IRS and Justice Department documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Marc Thiessen, a spokesman for Helms, said that Helms' offer was  
a legitimate one, not a ruse as charged by Democrats, and that the 
North Carolina Republican was ``willing to have a hearing'' and 
that her nomination could go ahead in the Senate ``if she has a 
clean bill of health.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
