<HEADLINE> Buchanan Courts S.C. Backers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Presidential candidate Pat Buchanan  
said Wednesday that leaving the GOP to seek the Reform Party 
nomination has not alienated one of his biggest backers, South 
Carolina textile executive Roger Milliken. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan also courted support at a West Columbia barbecue  
restaurant run by Maurice Bessinger, one of the state's most 
visible Christian conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan's positions that include renegotiating the North  
American Free Trade Agreement have the potential of helping textile 
makers and other manufacturers. He said his sister had spoken with 
Milliken, who was not unhappy about the party switch. 
</P>
<P>
	Bessinger, a Korean War veteran, also supported Buchanan in his  
failed bid for the 1996 Republican presidential nomination. ``He's 
a patriot. He's not going to sell us out like the rest are doing on 
this globalism stuff,'' Bessinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Buchanan shook hands and fielded questions while  
touring a textile plant in Gaffney, where workers asked what he 
would do to help save their jobs through tougher trade policies. 
</P>
<P>
	``What you got to say is whatever has been gone from that  
manufacturing base, we are not going to let more of it go. You'd 
have trade policy which was rooted in nationalism and patriotism,'' 
Buchanan said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
