<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Courts Michigan Voters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WARREN, Mich. (AP) -- Reform Party presidential contender Pat  
Buchanan says he would still be a Republican if the GOP gave 
Americans a true alternative to Democratic politics. 
</P>
<P>
	``They talk about a two-party system,'' Buchanan said during a  
Tuesday night fund-raising appearance in this Detroit suburb. 
``What we've got is a one-party establishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Today's Republican leaders don't oppose President Clinton and  
congressional Democrats on most issues because they're too 
comfortable with power and perks, Buchanan told about 400 
supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``They won't fight, and I'm tired of a party that won't fight,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday was Buchanan's first full day as a candidate for the  
Reform Party nomination, and he went straight to Macomb County and 
its Reagan Democrats -- voters who supported the former president 
even as they continued to elect and re-elect Democrats further down 
the ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday, Buchanan spoke at Lutheran North High School in  
Macomb Township -- where he first spoke during his unsuccessful 1992 
run for the GOP presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	The former co-host of CNN's ``Crossfire'' and former  
communications director for Reagan won more delegates in Michigan 
than in any other state during his failed 1996 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	In his return visit Tuesday, Buchanan focused most of his  
criticism not on Democrats but on the Republican Party to which he 
belonged for nearly 40 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``They pretend to be two separate parties, battling parties. But  
it is a lot like professional wrestling, where one guy wins one 
night and they go on to another town and the other guy wins,'' 
Buchanan told students, teachers and a handful of supporters at the 
high school. 
</P>
<P>
	He called Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the front-runner for the  
Republican presidential nomination, a ``redneck cowboy'' who was 
ducking debates with him; poked scornful fun at Reform Party 
founder H. Ross Perot and billionaire developer Donald Trump, his 
potential rival for the Reform nomination; and dismissed the theory 
of evolution as ``preposterous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by a student about Trump's critical response to his book,  
``A Republic, Not an Empire,'' Buchanan said: ``He hasn't read my 
book. I'm not sure he read the book he wrote about himself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan drew more laughter from the audience when he described  
a visit with Perot: ``I went down to Texas to see him. I didn't 
come out any wiser than when I went in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan's combative messages impressed Larry Lilly, 46, of  
Sterling Heights, a real estate broker who attended Tuesday night's 
speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt that he touched on a lot of issues that ought to be  
touched on, but aren't because they're not politically correct,'' 
Lilly said. ``He's a good, God-fearing Christian man. I just think 
he's the man for the job right now.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
