<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Cuts Number of Airline Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- China will cut domestic airline flights  
by nearly 8 percent on Sunday, the second reduction this year to 
reduce excess capacity in the troubled industry, state media said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But international flights will increase nearly 3 percent during  
the next five months to meet rising demand for travel abroad, the 
official Xinhua News Agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	China's airlines expanded rapidly after the breakup of the  
monopoly carrier in the early 1990s, but the increased capacity led 
to heavy losses when a slowing economy cut into air travel. 
</P>
<P>
	The national regulator, the Civil Aviation Administration of  
China, cut flights by 5 percent for a three-month period beginning 
May 1 in an attempt to shore up prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The report Wednesday did not say whether the new flight  
reductions were in addition to the earlier cuts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
