<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some Opposed to Financial Overhaul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and  
President Clinton's top economic adviser met today with Democratic 
congressional lawmakers, some of whom have expressed opposition to 
sweeping legislation, backed by Clinton, that would overhaul 
financial services laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure there will be a divided vote'' among Democrats,  
Summers said after the closed-door meeting with House Democrats. 
But he insisted that the legislation would protect consumers' 
financial privacy -- the main concern for one group of Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	``This hard-fought compromise ... represents a very significant  
step forward for the American economy and for American consumers,'' 
said Summers, who was accompanied by Gene Sperling, Clinton's 
economic adviser. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration is pushing on with the bill, hoping it soon  
will be enacted by the Republican-controlled Congress. Some 
Democrats opposed to the measure are calling on Clinton to veto it, 
but many others in the House support it. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would lift Depression-era barriers and allow  
banks, securities firms and insurance companies to merge and sell 
each other's products. The newly affiliated companies would be able 
to share customers' financial data with each other. With the White 
House having lifted its long-standing veto threat and now 
supporting it, the measure is being given the best chance ever of 
adoption after 20 years of battling. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., a leader in the fight on the  
privacy issue, said after today's meeting he was unconvinced by the 
administration officials' defense of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no protection'' for consumers, he said. ``Their  
privacy is now for sale.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., told The Associated  
Press he hadn't yet decided whether he would endorse the 
legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Markey on Tuesday enlisted the aid of Rep. John Dingell of  
Michigan, senior Democrat on the House Commerce Committee, and 
Reps. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., and Bill Luther, D-Minn., in circulating 
among House colleagues a letter to Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The overhaul legislation ``does not go nearly far enough in  
ensuring that American consumers receive strong privacy 
protections,'' the letter says. ``We do not believe the bill ... 
adequately protects American consumers from the wholesale 
networking of their personal, private information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Barry Toiv had no immediate comment on the  
letter. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would allow banks to share customers' data with  
affiliated financial companies under the same corporate ownership 
but not telemarketers. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharing data is a major reason financial companies want to  
merge, opening numerous opportunities to market a range of products 
and services under one umbrella. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer activists, including Ralph Nader, are alarmed at the  
prospect that people's personal financial data could be shared by 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	A broad coalition of consumer groups, privacy advocates, the  
American Civil Liberties Union and Phyllis Schlafly's conservative 
Eagle Forum sent its own letter to Clinton Tuesday urging his veto. 
</P>
<P>
	``This bill fails to give consumers real choice about the  
sharing, selling or using of their personal information among 
(financial) affiliates,'' they said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., has broken with  
Banking Committee Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, over the privacy 
issue and said he would vote against the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelby served notice on Monday that he will try to force changes  
in the privacy provisions and failing that, attempt to derail the 
measure. Under Senate rules, a single senator can hold up action 
for hours or days if he chooses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
