<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pet Store Recalls Dog Chews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A pet store is recalling a brand of  
Canadian-made dog chews because they may be contaminated with 
salmonella. 
</P>
<P>
	Salmonella-tainted treats are not considered a risk for dogs.  
But pet owners who hand their dogs the treats could become infected 
if they then touch their mouths or their own food before thoroughly 
washing their hands. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Food and Drug Administration already was warning dog  
owners to wash after touching any dog chews made from pork- or 
beef-derived materials, including pig ears, beef jerky and pigskin. 
That is because Canadian health authorities have reported at least 
30 dog owners sickened apparently by salmonella-tainted chews. 
</P>
<P>
	But Wednesday, Pet Valu International Inc. took the additional  
step of recalling certain Rollover brand dog chews from its stores 
in New Jersey, Delaware, Pennsylvania, Maryland and Virginia. The 
Pennsylvania-based pet chain cited Canadian testing that determined 
that brand, made by Farm Meats Canada Ltd, could be contaminated. 
Pet Valu asked consumers to return recalled chews to the store of 
purchase for a refund or exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Recalled are the following Rollover products: garlic-flavored  
pig ears bearing UPC code 6076688023; cheese-flavored pig ears, UPC 
6076688022; five-inch chews, UPC 6076688005; lambie chunks, UPC 
6076688102; and dog chew hooves, smoked or plain, sold in bulk. 
</P>
<P>
	Pet Valu said it sells other dog chews supplied by a different  
manufacturer that are not affected. 
</P>
<P>
	Salmonella can cause flulike symptoms in healthy people, but can  
be lifethreatening in the elderly, young children and people with 
weakened immune systems. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
