<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Oct. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Gunmen Open Fire in Armenia Gov't  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Unidentified gunmen opened fire today in the  
chamber of the Armenian parliament and some witnesses said there 
were casualties, according to local journalists. The gunmen opened 
fire while Prime Minister Vazgen Sarkisian was addressing a session 
of the parliament, the journalists said. Several shots were fired, 
they said. Armenia became an independent republic following the 
Soviet collapse in 1991. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore, Bradley To Meet in 1st Debate  
</P>
<P>
	HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore and Bill Bradley  
will meet tonight in the first debate between the Democratic 
presidential front-runners. The meeting falls short of what Gore 
had hoped for. The Vice President wanted weekly, head-on debates. 
This one, at Dartmouth College, is a televised town hall forum, 
with the candidates answering questions from an audience. Gore is 
making headway in national polls, widening his lead over Bradley 
and narrowing his deficit against Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the 
prime Republican candidate for 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	New Probe of Suharto Planned  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's new attorney general said  
today he intends to reopen a corruption investigation into former 
President Suharto but said the 78-year-old autocrat might 
eventually end up with a pardon or amnesty even if wrongdoing is 
uncovered. New President Abdurrahman Wahid said Suharto should be 
questioned again about his wealth and that Marzuki Darusman is 
entitled to pursue the case. Suharto was Indonesia's authoritarian 
ruler from 1966-98. Critics of his iron-fisted regime accuse him of 
abusing his power to enrich his family and of stashing away 
billions of dollars in foreign bank accounts. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Troops Seize Four Villages  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian jets bombed downtown Grozny today  
in some of the heaviest airstrikes against the Chechen capital 
since federal troops invaded the breakaway republic. It was the 
most serious attack on the city since a rocket strike on a downtown 
market last Thursday killed at least 150 people. President Boris 
Yeltsin said Russian forces would ``destroy the center of 
international terrorism in Chechnya and let people live calmly and 
peacefully.'' Russian troops entered Chechnya in September, with 
the stated mission of wiping out Islamic militants who twice raided 
a neighboring Russian region this summer and are blamed for four 
apartment blasts in Russian cities that killed 300 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Palestinians Protest Vendor's Death  
</P>
<P>
	BETHLEHEM, West Bank (AP) -- Breaking away from a funeral  
procession, 200 Palestinians hurled stones at Israeli soldiers 
today in a third day of protests over the army's shooting of a 
Bethlehem souvenir vendor. Israeli troops responded with tear gas 
and rubber-coated steel pellets. Three demonstrators were hit by 
rubber bullets and two were treated for tear gas inhalation, 
Palestinian paramedics said. The vendor, Mousa Abu Hilail, was 
fatally shot Monday by a soldier near Rachel's Tomb, a Jewish 
shrine revered as the burial site of the biblical matriarch. The 
soldier claimed Abu Hilail had tried to stab him, but Palestinian 
officials have alleged that the soldier opened fire without 
provocation. 

</P>
<P>
	China Police Seek End to Protests  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Chinese police stepped up patrols and  
surveillance of Tiananmen Square today, trying to put an end to 
three days of low-key protests by members of the banned spiritual 
movement Falun Gong. Group members staged no overt demonstrations 
and were not easily distinguished from the hordes of Chinese 
tourists normally wandering the square. But their presence there in 
defiance of a three-month crackdown against Falun Gong assured that 
they would be arrested, as dozens of others have been in the square 
in recent days. 

</P>
<P>
	Lung Cancer Detection Study Urged  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Doctors and scientists are urging the federal  
government to immediately begin studying a new method of detecting 
lung cancer in its earliest stages, The New York Times reported 
today. The method, spiral CT scanning, can find lung cancers when 
they are about as small around as a pea. Chest X-rays find lung 
cancers when they are about the size of a quarter. The scanning 
method is so new that doctors are still learning what it can do, 
including whether it can help save lives. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Share Prices Fall Sharply  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices fell sharply today with  
investors discouraged by the U.S. dollar's weakening against the 
yen and an overnight decline on Wall Street. The Nikkei dropped 
289.43 points to close at 17,382.36. 

</P>
<P>
	Yankees Push Braves to Brink  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chad Curtis, making his first start in a World  
Series, hit two home runs, including the game-winner in the 10th 
inning as the New York Yankees beat the Atlanta Braves 6-5 to take 
a 3-0 lead in the best-of-7 series. No baseball team has ever 
overcome an 0-3 deficit in any playoff series. The Braves knocked 
out Yankees starter Andy Pettitte in the 4th inning with a 5-1 
lead, but New York got home runs from Curtis and Tino Martinez to 
cut the gap to 5-3. Chuck Knoblauch's two-run homer off Tom Glavine 
tied the game in the eighth, and Curtis won it against Mike 
Remlinger leading off the 10th. The Yanks go for their record 25th 
championship tonight. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
