<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bears' QB Matthews Practices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- After missing the last two games with a  
pulled hamstring, Chicago Bears quarterback Shane Matthews ran in 
practice for the first time Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring any setback, he plans to play Sunday against the  
Washington Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm ready to go,'' he said. ``I'm not 100 percent, but I feel  
like I'm good enough to go out there and play. I'm ready to get 
back into it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews' return couldn't come at a better time for the Bears  
(3-4). After upsetting the Minnesota Vikings at the Metrodome on 
Oct. 10, Chicago had a two-game winning streak and playoff talk 
didn't seem so farfetched. 
</P>
<P>
	But with Matthews on the sidelines and rookie Cade McNown  
starting, the Bears stumbled. They dropped two straight, and 
Sunday's 6-3 loss to Tampa Bay was ugly enough to bring back 
memories of the Dave Wannstedt days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I could have made a difference, but I don't know  
if that's true or not,'' Matthews said. ``I just want to get back 
to playing. We had a little bit of a rhythm going before the 
injury, and we let a couple of games get away. 
</P>
<P>
	``We lost them, and it's over with,'' he added. ``But we've got  
to get back on the winning track and try to end up the first half 
of our season at 4-4.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While McNown has more speed and mobility and can throw further  
downfield than Matthews, he's still a rookie. Matthews may not have 
as much experience as Brett Favre or Brad Johnson, but he's a lot 
more seasoned than McNown. 
</P>
<P>
	Before he was injured, Matthews was 111-for-177 (62.7 percent)  
for 1,043 yards. His quarterback rating of 86.9 was third-best in 
the NFC, and tops in the NFC Central. McNown is 45-for-90 for 553 
yards with a 59.2 QB rating and was benched after throwing an 
interception against Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shane's calm. Things don't rattle him. He understands what  
he's trying to do with the offense and what he's capable of doing 
inside our offense,'' Bears coach Dick Jauron said. ``And he also 
understands what the opponent is trying to do. That doesn't come 
easy in our league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews' absence wasn't the only reason for Chicago's slump.  
Receiver Curtis Conway has been out since the Minnesota game with a 
sprained ankle. He didn't practice Wednesday and probably won't 
play Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	But getting Matthews back might give the Bears a spark.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're optimistic that with his return, we will have more  
control of our offense,'' Jauron said. ``It's not meant as a slight 
to Cade or Jim (Miller) at all. Shane's got the most experience at 
the helm, he's got experience in the league and he's a smart guy. 
He understands what we want and what he can do, also.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews' return means McNown drops back to No. 2, although  
he'll continue to play a series or two every game. While not 
getting more playing time is always disappointing, McNown said he 
knew his role as the starter was temporary. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like everybody came out and said, 'He's our guy.  
We're going with him,''' McNown said. ``It was like, 'Get in there. 
Do a good job and get better.' But unless you blow everybody's 
socks off, you're going to be back in the same situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And McNown knows he could be right back in the game if Matthews  
reinjures the hamstring. Although he ran in practice, Matthews 
didn't move around as much as he'll probably have to in a game. 
</P>
<P>
	He doesn't plan to give his gimpy leg that kind of a test before  
Sunday, either. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of dumb to come out here and run around and reinjure  
it in practice,'' he said. ``If I'm going to reinjure it, it's 
going to be in a game.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
