<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Canada Reveals Stiff Penalties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Air Canada disclosed Wednesday it would have to  
pay stiff penalties -- as much as $169 million in the first year 
alone -- if it leaves the Star Alliance of United Airlines and 
Lufthansa for rival Oneworld of American Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	The penalty provision was part of a 10-year deal Air Canada  
signed last week with the Star Alliance to help fight off a hostile 
takeover bid by Onex Corp., one of Canada's largest companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Onex, which is backed by American Airlines, insists the  
penalties are a ``poison pill'' designed to thwart its offer to 
merge Air Canada with Canadian Airlines to create a single national 
airline linked with the Oneworld alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada shareholders are scheduled to vote on the $1.2  
billion Onex offer on Nov. 8. To try to block the takeover, Air 
Canada has offered a $628 million package that includes buying back 
35 percent of the airline's shares at a premium price. 
</P>
<P>
	In a report to Canadian securities officials Wednesday, Air  
Canada for the first time revealed the penalties it would incur if 
Onex takes it over and breaks the agreement with the Star Alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada said in the event it withdrew from the alliance, it  
agreed to pay liquidated damages to (United) and Lufthansa in 
amounts declining over a 10-year period. from a maximum of $169 
million the first year to $25 million if it pulls out after January 
1, 2009. 
</P>
<P>
	United Airlines and Lufthansa have offered financial backing  
worth more than $450 million for Air Canada's package, which 
includes the purchase of rival Canadian Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada has agreed to refund up to $57 million to United and  
Lufthansa if it cannot buy Canadian and bring it into the Star 
Alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	Onex is reportedly considering increasing its offer in response  
to the Air Canada package announced last week. The corporation 
controls a variety companies, including Sky Chefs airline catering, 
Lantic Sugar Ltd. and American Buildings Co. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
