<DOCNO> APW19991027.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 17:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Questions NATO Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and its European allies  
should do more to help Russia avoid becoming ``a failed state,'' 
including help in safeguarding its nuclear arsenal, the prospective 
new NATO commander said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Force Gen. Joseph Ralston, nominated by President Clinton to  
replace Army Gen. Wesley Clark as supreme allied commander in 
Europe, told a Senate confirmation hearing that Russia's economic 
decline poses one of the biggest challenges to NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important that we do not just wish the problem away,''  
Ralston told the Senate Armed Services Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Ralston, now vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, is  
considered close to Defense Secretary William Cohen. Cohen stood by 
Ralston when his nomination for the top Joint Chiefs job sank two 
years ago over his admission of a long-ago affair. 
</P>
<P>
	The subject of the affair did not come up at Wednesday's  
confirmation hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark, who ran the 78-day NATO air campaign to drive Serb forces  
from Kosovo, is leaving in April, two months earlier than planned. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee chairman, Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said the  
announcement in July that Clark would leave early caused ``some 
confusion about that process and misunderstanding, particularly 
abroad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ralston repeated the administration's position that the early  
job change was driven by a bureaucratic quirk and was not a slap at 
Clark. 
</P>
<P>
	His present term at the Pentagon expires Feb. 29 and by law he  
must assume another four-star position within 60 days -- or retire. 
</P>
<P>
	Ralston said that he had worked closely with Clark over the  
years and ``in my judgment, he has served this nation extremely 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clark argued strenuously to keep open the option of using ground  
troops in Kosovo, although the Pentagon ruled it out. He chafed at 
the graduated air campaign dictated by the 19-member NATO alliance, 
saying he felt hamstrung. 
</P>
<P>
	That made him popular with Warner, who had advocated a more  
aggressive prosecution of the war, but often put him at odds with 
Cohen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think General Clark did a superb job of keeping 19 nations  
together,'' Ralston said. In the end, ``We had 19 nations that were 
hanging together. That was a major factor in getting the successful 
outcome that we got.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about biggest threats now facing NATO, Ralston put dealing  
with an economically and socially weakened Russia high on the list. 
</P>
<P>
	He voiced support for increased international security  
assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	In particular, Ralston said NATO allies should be encouraged to  
join U.S. efforts to help Russia in making sure its aging arsenal 
of nuclear and other weapons of mass destruction ``remains safe and 
secure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to do everything we can to make sure Russia does not  
become a failed state,'' Ralston said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that the current situation in Russia is impairing the  
nation's military, affecting readiness, morale and discipline. 
</P>
<P>
	Worsening conditions could ``pose the added dilemma that as  
conventional capabilities erode, they will rely more on their 
nuclear forces,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also conducted confirmation hearings for Air Force  
Gen. Richard B. Myers, to replace Ralston as vice chairman of the 
Joint Chiefs; Army Gen. Thomas A. Schwartz to command allied forces 
in South Korea; and Air Force Gen. Ralph E. Eberhart to be 
commander of the U.S. space command. 
</P>
<P>
	All the military nominations were expected to win Senate  
confirmation. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwartz told the panel he did not believe allegations of a  
Korean War massacre of civilians by U.S. soldiers had poisoned 
relations between U.S. forces there now and South Koreans. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is a theater that we fought together, bled together. I  
think everybody understood the contest in which that all took 
place,'' Schwartz said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sept. 30, The Associated Press reported accounts by American  
veterans, corroborating those of South Korean villagers, that their 
unit killed hundreds of civilians at No Gun Ri, South Korea, during 
the early days of the 1950-53 war. A subsequent AP report said the 
Army a short time later destroyed two strategic bridges as South 
Korean refugees streamed across, killing hundreds of civilians. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will work through this, we will study it, we'll find the  
facts, and we'll do the right thing as a result,'' said Schwartz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
