<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Drug Adviser Raps IOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The White House drug adviser on  
Wednesday derided as ``crazy'' the IOC's plan for a drug agency. He 
said the proposal shows the organization has yet to change its 
autocratic ways. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry McCaffrey, head of the U.S. drug policy office, spoke at  
the European Union's headquarters in support of an independent 
agency to combat the use of performance-enhancing drugs in sports. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the IOC agency, which could start as early as Nov. 10,  
would undercut democratic decision-making and the input of 
governments. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is nuts,'' he said in an interview with The Associated  
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-six nations are to discuss drugs and sports at meetings  
in Australia on Nov. 14-17. McCaffrey said that would be the ideal 
time to discuss a drug agency. He called the IOC's plans to preempt 
that meeting unacceptable. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's crazy,'' he said. ``It's not the way we work in  
the international community. We consult, we listen to each other's 
viewpoints.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since the Olympic corruption and bribery scandal broke last  
winter, the EU and the United States have been highly critical of 
the IOC and its president, Juan Antonio Samaranch. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC contends it does not intend to monopolize the new  
agency, which is to supervise worldwide drug testing and policy. 
The Olympic group says it has requested only three of the 24 seats 
on the executive board. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite such assurances, McCaffrey says he won the backing of  
the EU to keep the agency out of the IOC's grasp as much as 
possible. The EU has said it will try to remove the agency as soon 
as possible from the IOC's home base of Lausanne, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's stinging criticism dampened hopes the IOC and its  
critics were finally reconciling differences. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffrey said the EU had not even seen the draft of the drug  
agency's medical code. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the agency starts in November, McCaffrey wants the  
governments to listen to the outcome of the drug meetings in 
Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffrey met with the EU commissioner responsible for sports,  
Viviane Reding, who will meet with Samaranch on Tuesday in an 
attempt to bring both sides closer. 
</P>
<P>
	The governments and sports organizations still have to discuss  
funding for the agency. The EU nations have been unable to propose 
a site for the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	There are seven candidates: Athens, Greece; Bonn, Germany;  
Lille, France; Lisbon, Portugal; Luxembourg; Madrid, Spain; and 
Vienna, Austria. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
