<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Series Win Is Sweet for Torre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Joe Torre knew coming back was right the first  
time he realized the knot in his stomach had more to do with the 
fear of losing a baseball game than his battle with cancer. And 
Wednesday night, for the first time in months, he didn't have to 
worry about either. 
</P>
<P>
	Healthy since May and manager of the world champions for the  
third time in four years, Torre hung back in the dugout for a few 
moments after the last out of a 4-1 win disappeared into left 
fielder Chad Curtis' glove. 
</P>
<P>
	And then, he made his way up the steps and into that waving,  
screaming, joyous jumble of players on the pitcher's mound, 
disappearing into the middle of a celebration that would have been 
impossible without him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't put into words,'' Torre said, ``what this feels  
like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Measured by numbers, this season was less impressive than last.  
The Yankees won fewer regular-season games, scored less and gave up 
more runs. But measured by the adversity they overcame to reach the 
pinnacle of the game a second straight year, this one was more 
impressive. Much more. 
</P>
<P>
	Their tribulations began early in spring training, when Torre  
was diagnosed with prostate cancer, and didn't end with the last 
game. Right fielder Paul O'Neill played that one with a heavy 
heart, having lost his father, Charlie, to a continuing heart 
problem some 18 hours earlier. Those were the bookends, but hardly 
the only misfortunes these Yankees had to deal with. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past week, reserve infielder Luis Sojo left the club to  
take the body of his father, Ambrosio, back to Venezuela for 
burial. Last month, it was Scott Brosius, returning to Oregon to 
bury his father, Maury. 
</P>
<P>
	Before that, the New Yorkers had to find a way to bring wayward  
native son Darryl Strawberry back into the fold, to honor two 
fallen heroes -- Joe DiMaggio and Catfish Hunter -- from their past 
and honor that glorious tradition by doing more than wearing 
commemorative patches on their sleeves. 
</P>
<P>
	But through it all, they never took their eyes off the prize.  
</P>
<P>
	``There was a lot of emotion on this club this year,'' Torre  
began before paying tribute to the sons among them who had lost 
fathers and played on. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will never be another first,'' he continued, ``but even  
after what we accomplished last year, I think this might be a 
better team -- only because we had to do it again to validate last 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like that edition, this year's was a team you had to admire.  
</P>
<P>
	It was self-assured, yet loaded with guys who never quit  
striving. There was only one real personnel change, a swap of 
starters, in which Roger Clemens replaced David Wells; otherwise, 
it was complete and harmonious enough that even George Steinbrenner 
knew to stay out of its way. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a mentally tough team that depicts New York,'' The Boss  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	That was a particularly appropriate salute, since the two times  
Steinbrenner was tempted to meddle -- threatening to unload starter 
Andy Pettitte and reliever Ramiro Mendoza, both of whom figured 
prominently in the postseason -- Torre stood up to him, backed by 
general manager Brian Cashman and chief scout Gene Michael. 
</P>
<P>
	And a willingness to take on The Boss wasn't the only thing  
different about the Yankees since Torre took over in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``For years, they bought the highest-priced talent and couldn't  
quite put it together,'' Braves Game 4 starter and loser John 
Smoltz said admiringly. ``But now, the last three or four years, 
there's no selfishness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The glue all along was Torre. He had more veterans than lineup  
spots to fit them into, a rehab project like Strawberry to work 
back into the mix and a fire-breathing owner to keep at arm's 
length. 
</P>
<P>
	And then came something to make the balancing act even tougher:  
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Three years ago, Torre got through the pressure of chasing the  
World Series by focusing on the plight of his older brother Frank, 
a former big-leaguer who was awaiting a heart transplant. That 
story had a happy ending. At the start of this year, the tables 
were turned. 
</P>
<P>
	``When he found out about his cancer, I was flat on my back in  
the hospital with a setback I had with my new heart,'' Frank, in 
town for the series, recalled the other day. ``The first call I got 
was from Joe. That's the way he is; he didn't want me to hear about 
it first from the TV.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once Torre returned to the club in mid-May, he picked up right  
where he left off. Somehow, he got his starters to accept sitting 
on the bench some days, and he kept his role players confident 
enough to step in at the big moments. In short, he kept everybody 
on the club happier most of the time than they had a right to be. 
</P>
<P>
	And no one realized how special this campaign was more than  
Clemens, who outdueled Smoltz on Wednesday night to win his first 
World Series game and ring. 
</P>
<P>
	``I finally know what it's like to be a Yankee. You talk about  
heavy hearts and guys who are warriors,'' he paused, ``I just feel 
very blessed to be part of this bunch.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated  
Press. Write to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
