<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Plant Emissions Up Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- For the third consecutive year, emissions from the  
14 oldest power plants across New England increased, according to a 
report issued Wednesday by a coalition of environmental groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings were especially disturbing to environmentalists  
because the emissions decreased in the first half of the decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've eroded half the gains we've made, if not a little  
more,'' said Rob Sargent, spokesman for MassPIRG. 
</P>
<P>
	Old plants don't have to meet the same emissions standards as  
new plants because of a loophole in the federal Clean Air Act. 
</P>
<P>
	The study shows emissions from New England's oldest plants in  
the first half of 1999 have increased 5.5 percent for sulfur 
dioxide, 3.6 percent for nitrogen oxide and 4.7 percent for carbon 
dioxide, compared to the first half of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Sargent has spent a good part of the last three years organizing  
demonstrations against the dirtiest power plants. Lately, political 
leaders have begun to respond. 
</P>
<P>
	The six New England states and New York sent a petition Tuesday  
to the federal Environmental Protection Agency asking for stiffer 
emission regulations to fight acid rain. And several states have 
plans to clean up their dirty plants. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
