<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 01:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Seeks Better Race Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrat Bill Bradley has placed improving  
race relations at the center of his campaign for the White House, 
highlighting a career in professional basketball and calling racial 
unity ``the defining moral issue of our time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet his appeal seems not to be resonating among one seemingly  
ripe audience. 
</P>
<P>
	Numerous polls show Vice President Al Gore holding a bigger lead  
over Bradley among black voters than among Democrats overall. One 
recent poll by the Pew Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press 
gave Gore a 3-1 lead among black voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew center, said the results are  
not surprising because black voters generally are loyal Democrats -- 
and loyal Democrats support the vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a trend that still could change,'' Kohut said, ``but  
we don't see any sign of that now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has been endorsed by 20 of the 38 members of the  
Congressional Black Caucus; Bradley by none. And Bradley's proposal 
to expand Civil Rights Act protections to gay Americans drew 
criticism from black leaders, including the Rev. Jesse Jackson and 
Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., who said reopening the landmark 1964 
law would be risky. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign spokesman Eric Hauser predicted that Bradley's ``depth  
of commitment to racial justice'' will produce support from people 
of all races -- eventually. 
</P>
<P>
	``People in most parts of the country are still getting to know  
him,'' Hauser said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stump, Bradley often talks of his own experiences with  
race, including how his Little League team in Crystal City, Mo., 
couldn't stay at certain hotels because some of the players were 
black. 
</P>
<P>
	He pledged that, as president, he would evaluate federal  
employees on the basis of ``how your department or agency has 
furthered tolerance and racial understanding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say there is no doubt about Bradley's commitment to  
improving race relations, but critics question why he didn't do 
more during his 18 years in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	``He made some memorable speeches on race on the floor and, I  
believe, is respected by African-Americans as sincerely committed 
on race. (But) he is not remembered for spearheading legislation,'' 
said District of Columbia Del. Eleanor Holmes Norton, a nonvoting 
House Democrat who backs Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	She added: ``Gore has proved that he's there when the going gets  
tough. This is a man from the South who was not afraid to be a 
leader on civil rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One problem for Bradley is that he often chose to pursue his  
interest in race relations in small settings, sometimes even in 
private. 
</P>
<P>
	He traveled to a Chicago public housing project in 1987 after  
reading a series of Wall Street Journal articles on Lafeyette 
Walton, a black 12-year-old struggling to survive the atmosphere of 
violence and despair. Squeezing his 6-foot-5-inch frame into a 
child-sized chair, Bradley talked to mothers about what it was like 
raising their families. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, then a senator from New Jersey, was accompanied by a  
single aide on the visit to the Henry Horner Homes. He held no news 
conference afterward, and made no speech. 
</P>
<P>
	As a New York Knick, Bradley refused commercial endorsements in  
part because of discomfort about being hailed as basketball's 
``great white hope.'' Between basketball seasons, he worked for the 
Office of Economic Opportunity in Washington and the Urban League 
street academies in Harlem. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of Bradley's prominent black backers say the candidate's  
own history of grappling with race is more important than any 
political pronouncement or legislative initiative. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornel West, a professor of Afro-American studies and philosophy  
of religion at Harvard University, said Bradley ``understands that 
listening and being open to others is part and parcel of 
leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley's campaign compiled a list of his Senate efforts related  
to civil rights, including his opposition to the nominations of 
Robert Bork and William Rehnquist to the Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	But much of his Senate record on race consisted of speeches in  
his third and final term. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Senate floor in 1992, Bradley rapped a pencil against the  
lectern 56 times to dramatize the beating of black motorist Rodney 
King by Los Angeles police officers. 
</P>
<P>
	As a presidential candidate, Bradley repeatedly has told the  
story of wincing at racist comments uttered by a beloved aunt. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pledge that it will be your generation that will put these  
stupid attitudes behind us,'' he told college students during an 
April speech on race in New York City. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
