<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Up at Midday / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices rose moderately Thursday  
morning, helped by gains on Wall Street. The dollar slipped against 
the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 69.35  
points, or 0.40 percent, to 17,451.75 at the end of the morning 
session. On Wednesday, the average closed down 289.43 points, or 
1.64 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 104.16 yen, down 0.16 yen from late Wednesday  
and marginally below its late New York level of 104.17 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In stock trading, prices opened higher Thursday as players were  
encouraged by a sharp rise in U.S. stocks Wednesday in New York. 
The Dow Jones industrial average gained 92.76 points to close at 
10,394.89. 
</P>
<P>
	The rise in Tokyo came as market players were awaiting the  
release of U.S. gross domestic product data for the July-September 
quarter, due out later Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 4.94 points, or 0.32 percent, to 1,528.32. The 
TOPIX closed down 19.71 points, or 1.28 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar stayed in a narrow range as  
traders remained apprehensive over possible dollar-buying 
intervention by Japan's central bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's administrative vice finance minister, Nobuaki Usui, said  
Thursday morning that Japanese finance authorities will take firm 
steps in the foreign exchange market if needed. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen has been gaining ground against the greenback in recent  
trading sessions on expectations that the Japanese government will 
spend a significant amount of money to buoy the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese officials have said the government will submit a second  
supplementary budget in the upcoming parliamentary session, which 
begins Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Total spending in the package is estimated at between $95.2  
billion and $123.8 billion, according to Japanese news reports. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 109.55 yen, down  
from 110.69 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.8400 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.8300 percent. Its 
price fell 0.09 point to 99.65. 
</P>
</TEXT>
