<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Readiness Discussed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A smaller and busier U.S. military remains  
ready to fight in two major foreign battles at the same time, but 
with an increased risk in the potential second conflict, the Joint 
Chiefs of Staff told Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will take longer to respond to hostilities which, in turn,  
means territory lost and an increased potential for casualties,'' 
the chiefs' chairman, Army Gen. Henry Shelton, said Tuesday at a 
Senate Armed Forces Committee hearing on the readiness of the 
military. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton, in three hours of testimony flanked by the chiefs of  
the Army, Air Force, Navy and Marines, said officers rate the risks 
of fighting a single conflict as ``moderate,'' a second conflict as 
``high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This does not mean that U.S. forces would not prevail in  
either contingency,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He ascribed the increased risk to diminished readiness in both  
strength of U.S. forces and the condition of their equipment. 
Difficulties in recruiting and in getting personnel to stay in the 
military are major factors, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent increases in outlays for the military should begin to  
solve the problems, Shelton said, but all five chiefs complained of 
budgets that fall billions of dollars short of needs to maintain a 
ready, modern force. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no doubt that the force is much smaller than it was a  
decade ago, and also much busier,'' Shelton said. The total force 
is down 40 percent, yet faces increased requirements, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A major challenge cited by all four service chiefs is how to  
increase the number of soldiers and officers who make long-term 
commitments and step up recruitment at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton said proposals in congressional budget negotiations for  
across-the-board budget cuts would be ``devastating'' for the 
military, and cuts in the number of personnel available it would be 
``disastrous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the military is ``walking a personnel tightrope,'' but  
pay and retirement improvements are beginning to increase 
retention. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, we are better off today than we were last year,''  
Shelton said. But he said recruiting has been held back by a 
job-rich economy, larger numbers of high school students going to 
college and ``the smallest cohort of 18- to 23-year-olds to recruit 
from in the history of the all-volunteer force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adm. Jay L. Johnson, the chief of naval operations, said world  
events in the last few months ``should dispel any misconception 
that the demands on our Navy have diminished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Our battle force is getting older, and there is no  
shock-absorbency left,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force chief, Gen. Michael E. Ryan, cited a ``slow but  
steady decline'' in Air Force readiness -- down 5 percent since last 
year, 23 percent since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Eric K. Shinseki, the Army chief of staff, said there  
remains in his service ``a mismatch between what we are asked to 
do, and the troops we have to do it with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marine Commandant Gen. James L. Jones said the Marines face  
increased commitments with force reductions that have cut ``well 
into the muscle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he said, ``The cumulative effect of repeated  
short-notice deployments could result in continued degradation in 
overall readiness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite budget increases this year, the service chiefs each  
complained of shortfalls below needs to increase readiness: $2.6 
billion for the Navy, $2.5 billion for the Air Force, $2.4 billion 
for the Army, $1.4 billion for the Marines. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Starts Debate on His Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- Al Gore staged a bit of political theater  
reminiscent of Ronald Reagan in 1980, seizing the initiative -- if 
not the microphone -- to begin debating rival Bill Bradley 15 
minutes before the debate officially began. 
</P>
<P>
	``What do we do now?'' the vice president asked Wednesday night  
after he and the former New Jersey senator were introduced to the 
in-studio audience. It was an awkward period before airtime -- the 
candidates were fidgeting on their stools -- and Gore knew exactly 
what he wanted to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why don't you start asking some questions while we're  
waiting?'' he told the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	They did as he suggested. And the debate began on Gore's terms,  
just as he had planned. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a tactic borrowed from former President Reagan, who broke  
the format in a 1980 debate and, when a moderator threatened to 
turn off his microphone, shot back: ``I paid for this microphone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reagan looked strong and in charge.  
</P>
<P>
	Advisers said Gore's strategy was to solicit questions from the  
get-go. It is part of what they hope is a new-and-improved 
candidate, one eager to answer every question, shake every hand and 
solicit every vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's trying very hard to connect with voters,'' said  
Vanderbilt University political science professor Erwin Hargrove. 
``Notice that he was asking people for their names, how many kids 
they have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like a fighter throwing the first punch before the opening bell,  
Gore never let up -- raising questions about Bradley's education, 
health care and spending plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``The numbers have to add up,'' said the vice president.  
</P>
<P>
	``The cost is way excessive.''  
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to shred the safety net'' that protects the poor.  
</P>
<P>
	Bradley calmly rebutted Gore and passed up chance after chance  
to lash out. ``I'm not going to get into the details at this point 
of the game,'' he said after being served a softball-sized chance 
to criticize Clinton-Gore fund-raising excesses in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley made sweeping promises filled with vision and few  
specifics, saying it was time to reduce poverty, reform campaign 
finance laws and provide affordable health insurance to almost 
every American. 
</P>
<P>
	While Gore all but begged for votes -- ``give me a chance to roll  
up my sleeves'' -- a typically understated Bradley said, ``If you 
agree, then you'll vote for me. I hope you do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first head-to-head encounter of their presidential campaign  
underscored the differences in styles. Gore was combative and 
coached, trying hard to look more homespun and drive down Bradley's 
rising poll numbers. The former New Jersey senator said voters are 
tired of political sniping and slick campaigning, so he avoided 
direct criticism and worked hard not to look like he's working 
hard. 
</P>
<P>
	``It thought Gore was as good as I've ever seen him,'' said  
Democratic consultant Jim Duffy. ``He was trying desperately to 
look like a guy who is a friend, look like a guy who is 
intelligent, look like a guy who is compassionate. And yet, he 
pressed Bradley.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duffy, who is not tied to either campaign, said Bradley came  
across as a soft-spoken, nontraditional candidate ``in an era where 
that might be very welcome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Bradley talked about big ideas and handled them well,''  
Hargrove said. ``Gore seemed over eager at times -- kind of 
frantic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Time will tell whether voters welcome the change or not. ``I  
wonder if people will see him in this format and forget about his 
ties to President Clinton. It's possible,'' Hargrove said. ``It's 
nice to see him try.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And try. And try.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to stick around,'' Gore said, as the television  
lights dimmed, ``and answer some more questions.'' Which he did, 
for 90 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Ron Fournier is chief political reporter for The  
Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
