<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Up 28.49 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as the continuing watch  
over inflation kept most investors from making any big commitments. 
</P>
<P>
	In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 28.49 at 10,330.62. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was up 5.74 at 1,287.65, and the Nasdaq composite index was 
down 9.96 at 2,801.51. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks got a short-lived lift from a Commerce Department report  
that showed orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured 
goods fell 1.3 percent in September, the first decline in five 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline was sharper than many analysts had expected, and  
offered some indication that the pace of U.S. economic growth may 
be tapering off. Stocks have stumbled in recent weeks amid worries 
that the economy is growing fast enough to convince the Federal 
Reserve to raise interest rates for the third time this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher rates would slow economic growth by making it more  
expensive to borrow money to finance growth. They could also hurt 
stocks, however, by cutting into corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks hovered in a narrow range as investors awaited two pieces  
of economic data viewed as better gauges of inflation. On Thursday, 
the government will report on the employment cost index and the 
gross domestic product. 
</P>
<P>
	Online auctioneer eBay fell 14 3/16 to 137 13/16. The company  
said after the close of trading Tuesday its quarterly operating 
profits rose, beating analysts' expectations, after it signed up a 
record number of new users and expanded its offerings. But the 
company's profit margin fell, which caught some investors by 
surprise. EBay also recorded fewer transactions for new users, 
raising concerns about future growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq Computer rose 1/2 to 20 after reporting earnings of $117  
million, or 7 cents a share in the recent quarter. Analysts 
surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial expected Compaq to earn 5 
cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past two weeks, corporate earnings reports have provided  
a distraction from the lingering worries about inflation. But as 
the tide of profit reports begins to slow, the market may remain 
stuck in a relatively narrow range, said Brian G. Belski, chief 
investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City, Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	``With most of the third-quarter earnings news out, stocks will  
likely return to an interest rate and Fed-watch stance over the 
next several days,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 260.83 million 
shares, behind Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.91 to 416.70.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
