<DOCNO> APW19991027.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 04:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Songwriter Accused of Child Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Child advocates say they hope charges that a  
successful songwriter abused some of his adoptive and foster 
children won't scare others away from adoption. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't let this tragedy make us afraid,'' said Frank  
Cervone, executive director of the Support Center for Child 
Advocates, a Philadelphia-based program for abused and neglected 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Cusick, the adoptive and foster father of 28 children,  
surrendered to police Tuesday after five boys in his care accused 
him of sexual abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	He was charged with multiple counts of corruption of a minor,  
indecent assault and child endangerment. If convicted, he could 
receive up to 35 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Cusick, 47, was released on $300,000 bail. A preliminary hearing  
date was set for Nov. 4, said his lawyer, Kevin M. Zlock, who 
declined further comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Child advocate Cervone said he is concerned the case against  
Cusick ``is going to do some damage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We live in a world where there are thousands of families who  
have opened their homes to children, but that's not enough by a 
factor of many thousand,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cusick's songs include ``Don't You Go,'' recorded by Ricky  
Martin, and others by have been recorded by artists including 
Lionel Richie, Tony Orlando, Barry Manilow and Neil Diamond, 
prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1972, Cusick has been an adoptive or foster father to 24  
boys and four girls in Pennsylvania and New York, police said. He 
began taking in children when he lived on New York City's Staten 
Island, Bucks County District Attorney Alan M. Rubenstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since January 1998, Cusick and several boys and young men have  
lived in a seven-bedroom house in an affluent subdivision of 
Langhorne, about 20 miles northeast of Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Cusick was married briefly in the early 1980s but adopted most  
of the children when he was single, authorities said. He received 
several awards and letters of commendation from adoption advocacy 
groups and community service programs, Rubenstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation started a month ago when a 17-year-old adopted  
son made the first allegations to police, Rubenstein said. 
Authorities then interviewed four other boys, between the ages of 8 
and 16, who reported similar assaults, Rubenstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	The five were among 11 boys, all minors, who were removed from  
the house shortly after the investigation began and placed in 
foster care, Rubenstein said. Two other adopted sons, both 19, 
moved out of the house Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
