<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Journal Scooped on Its Own Story? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The changes in the makeup of the Dow Jones  
industrial average may have been made by senior editors at The Wall 
Street Journal, but news of the additions didn't appear there 
first. 
</P>
<P>
	It may seem ironic that the Journal -- which prides itself on  
breaking major business stories -- appeared to have missed out on a 
big scoop, especially since the paper's top brass knew about it. 
</P>
<P>
	But since news of those changes can cause big swings in the  
stock prices of companies being added and dropped to the widely 
quoted indicator, officials at the Journal's publisher, Dow Jones &AMP; 
Co., said they wanted to make sure the announcement Tuesday was 
made in the fairest possible manner. 
</P>
<P>
	Had news of the changes appeared first in the Journal, it would  
have been available throughout the wee hours of the morning, 
allowing an investor who got the paper early or visited the 
Journal's Web site to trade on the information via an after-hours 
system like Instinet. 
</P>
<P>
	``As wonderful as our distribution system for the paper is, some  
people get it at different times,'' said Paul Steiger, the 
Journal's managing editor. ``Since it's such an up-to-the minute 
thing, it seems fairer to blow it out over the wires than to hold 
it as an exclusive for the paper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Jones decided to release the news electronically at 9:15  
a.m. over several outlets -- its own real-time news wire, the 
Journal's Web site, a news release distribution system and the CNBC 
business cable channel, which has a news partnership with Dow 
Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	By making the announcement this way, there was ``complete  
dissemination'' of the news by the time trading opened on the New 
York Stock Exchange 15 minutes later, company spokesman Dick Tofel 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Jones used to make announcements of changes in the Dow 30  
after the close of stock trading on Wednesdays. But with more 
trading occurring after regular market hours, Tofel said the early 
announcement gave all investors a better chance of getting an equal 
shot at the information. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
