<HEADLINE> Rite Aid Restructures Bank Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP HILL, Pa. (AP) -- Rite Aid Corp. has restructured its $2.7  
billion in bank debt, giving it an extra year to pay off $1.3 
billion tied to the purchase of PCS Health Systems Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's No. 3 drugstore chain also said Wednesday it has  
consummated the sale of $300 million of its convertible preferred 
stock to an affiliate of Leonard Green &AMP; Partners, which made the 
extension of its credit possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Both actions had been expected since last week's management  
shakeup, which included the resignation of Martin L. Grass as 
chairman and chief executive officer, the appointment of Timothy 
Noonan as his interim successor, and the establishment of an 
executive committee to oversee operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The one-year extension of the credit deadline to Nov. 1, 2000,  
affects more than half of Rite Aid's bank debt, including the $1.3 
billion associated with the acquisition of PCS, the nation's 
largest pharmacy-benefits manager, and $300 million in 
due-on-demand bank debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The chain, which owns more than 3,800 stores in 38 states and  
the District of Columbia, recorded $12.7 billion in sales in 1999. 
But earnings have sagged recently, particularly since it acquired 
PCS in January, and Rite Aid has acknowledged it is considering 
selling at least part of its interest in that company. 
</P>
<P>
	The Camp Hill-based company recently reported a second-quarter  
loss of $67.9 million, or 26 cents per diluted share. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid's stock has tumbled from more than $51 a share in  
January to below $10. Shares rose 87 1/2 cents to $9.25 Wednesday on 
the New York Stock Exchange. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
