<HEADLINE> Purer Form of Claritin Submitted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Schering-Plough Corp., maker of Claritin, has  
applied for U.S. and European approval for a next generation form 
of the popular prescription allergy drug, the company said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Desloratadine, which does not yet have a brand name, is a purer  
form of Claritin, and like its chemical cousin, it is a 
non-sedating, once-a-day antihistamine, according to David 
Southwell, chief financial officer of Sepracor, the specialty 
pharmaceutical company which helped develop the new medication. 
</P>
<P>
	Desloratadine is vital for Schering-Plough because the first  
patent on Claritin expires 2002, making the blockbuster medicine 
subject to competition from cheaper generics. 
</P>
<P>
	Madison, N.J.-based Schering-Plough has conducted four large  
studies using desloratadine, but has yet to release the findings. 
</P>
<P>
	With minimal side effects, Claritin has a strong following among  
doctors and patients. Analysts say Schering-Plough may have a tough 
sell persuading patients to switch to a newer version of the drug. 
The most likely ways the drug could be improved would be to speed 
its onset time and increase its potency. 
</P>
<P>
	Claritin, expected to have at least $2.5 billion in sales in  
1999, controls about 45 percent of the prescription allergy market. 
Its dominance, though, has fallen in recent years due to 
competition from Hoechst Marion Roussel's Allegra and Pfizer's 
Zyrtec. 
</P>
<P>
	Sepracor, based in Marlboro, Mass., is also developing its own  
new antihistamine, which could be on the market in the next two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough has been lobbying Congress to pass a bill that  
would extend the patent life of Claritin three years beyond its 
expiration date. But the bill has met resistance among consumer 
groups and generic drugmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Schering-Plough on Tuesday fell $2.25 to $45.81 1/4 in  
New York Stock Exchange trading. Sepracor rose $2.43 3/4 to $75.18 3/4 in 
trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
