<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 16:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amazon.com Results Top Estimates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Amazon.com's losses widened in the third quarter  
as the giant Internet retailer significantly boosted its spending 
to expand its online offerings. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the steep losses, which were less than analysts were  
expecting, Amazon.com's sales grew by 132 percent from the year-ago 
period and its customer base climbed by 2.4 million to 13.1 
million, three times larger than it was in September 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com reported Wednesday that it lost $197 million, or 59  
cents a share, in the three months ended Sept. 30, compared with a 
loss of $45.2 million, or 15 cents a share, last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding $111.3 million of merger, acquisition,  
investment-related costs and stock-based compensation charges, 
Amazon.com lost $85.8 million, or 26 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	That loss was smaller than the 28-cents-a-share loss expected by  
Wall Street analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that the third-quarter number was right on target,''  
said Sara Zeilstra, an analyst at Warburg Dillion Read. ``The 
concern right now has to do with the fourth quarter and year 2000 
and how much the losses will widen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sales in the quarter rose to $355.8 million, up from $153.7  
million a year ago. Since the start of the year, sales are $963.8 
million, well above the $608 million in sales that Amazon.com 
tallied during all of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	In its four years in business, Amazon.com has yet to turn a  
profit. Yet, the company hasn't stopped spending money to build 
itself into a bigger and more diversified online retailer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle-based company not only seeks to woo shoppers to its  
site, but it wants people to keep coming back. Repeat customer 
orders represented more than 72 percent of its orders during the 
third quarter, compared with 70 percent in the second quarter of 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past two years, Amazon has moved from being exclusively  
an online bookseller into an Internet shopping superstore, offering 
music, videos, auctions and electronic greeting cards. 
</P>
<P>
	During the third quarter, it added a wide array of toys and  
electronics to its Web site. It also started allowing anyone -- from 
major manufacturers to enterprising grandparents -- to sell 
merchandise on Amazon.com through its new zSHOPS program. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com has also invested millions of dollars this year in a  
number of online merchants with big growth potential. Those include 
online pharmacy drugstore.com, Internet pet shop Pets.com and Web 
wedding-gift registry Della &AMP; James. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we find new opportunities, we will investment in them, and  
we think that is the right thing to do,'' Jeff Bezos, Amazon.com 
founder and chief executive officer, said during a conference call 
with analysts late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	While Amazon.com has aggressively built itself up, its costs  
have soared. During the third quarter, the company spent $86 
million on marketing and advertising and $44 million on product 
development. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said costs are likely to continue increasing. In the  
fourth quarter, Amazon.com expects its marketing expenses to rise 
as well as its costs to fulfill orders. It also expects that that 
the profits it makes off each item to decrease. Revenue is expected 
to soar, however, as shoppers buy gifts for the holidays. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Amazon.com said that it expects its U.S. book  
business -- long the anchor of the company -- to make a profit during 
the fourth quarter, though it will contribute less than half of its 
total revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	As Amazon.com moves into 2000, the company said might not renew  
its contracts with some Internet portals because the advertising 
and marketing deals are expensive and not as effective as 
Amazon.com had hoped they would be. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that each company has been looking at its own internal  
measures of what advertising and marketing is effective,'' Ms. 
Zeilstra said. ``Some portals are paying off and others aren't, and 
everyone is evaluating what to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the nine months ended Sept. 30, Amazon.com lost $396.8  
million, or $1.23 a share, compared with $78.1 million, or 27 cents 
a share, a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding merger and acquisition, investment and stock-based  
compensation costs, Amazon.com lost $204.9 million, or 63 cents a 
share, compared with a loss of $51.6 million, or 18 cents, a year 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Amazon.com fell $5.31 1/4 to $75.93 3/4 in trading Wednesday  
on the Nasdaq Stock Market. In after-hours trading, shares fell to 
$72.75. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
