<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Unfazed by Dollar's Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar's renewed weakness against the Japanese  
yen didn't phase Japan's top economic planner, who said Thursday he 
wasn't concerned about the greenback's latest decline. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen's appreciation was not rapid enough to cause alarm,  
Taichi Sakaiya, director-general of Japan's Economic Planning 
Agency, told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	He added, however, that that if the dollar falls below 100 yen,  
the government will need to take steps to support the Japanese 
currency. 
</P>
<P>
	In late morning trading, the dollar was quoted at 104.16 yen,  
down 0.16 yen from its late Wednesday level in Tokyo and also 
marginally below its level in late New York trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar had traded as high as 104.90 yen on Wednesday in  
Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar has sunk by more than 9 percent against the Japanese  
currency since Aug. 2, when it traded at 114.04 yen. A variety of 
factors have encouraged investors to buy yen, including 
expectations of economic recovery in Japan and concerns about 
inflation in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Also supporting the yen Thursday were expectations that the  
Japanese government will spend a significant amount of money to 
buoy the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have said the government will submit a second  
supplementary budget in the upcoming parliamentary session, which 
begins Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Total spending in the package is estimated at between $96.2  
billion and $125 billion, according to Japanese news reports. 
</P>
<P>
	An unduly strong yen worries officials here because it can make  
Japanese exports more expensive abroad, and thus less competitive 
in world markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan is struggling to emerge from its worst economic downturn  
in 50 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
