<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Nortel Networks Corp., up 2 1/2 at 58    	
</P>
<P>
	Nortel said late Tuesday that it earned 28 cents per share in  
the third quarter, up from 21 cents in the year-ago quarter, and 
above analysts' estimates of 26 cents per share. The networking 
company said its fiber-optic business contributed to strong growth. 

</P>
<P>
 *Stone &AMP; Webster Inc., down 9 1/2 at 15 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	The construction company lost $6.9 million, or 52 cents per  
share, in the third quarter. Stone &AMP; Webster attributed the loss to 
a provision of $10.4 million to cover costs of three major projects 
and the impact of hurricanes and floods in the Southeast. 

</P>
<P>
 *Inacom Corp., down 4 3/16 at 3 15/16    	
</P>
<P>
	The company expects to lose 10 cents to 20 cents per share in  
the fourth quarter due to customers' concerns over the Year 2000 
computer bug. Inacom is a major reseller of computers that run on 
Microsoft Windows and Intel microprocessors. 

</P>
<P>
 *CVS Corp., down 4 1/2 at 39    	
</P>
<P>
	The drugstore chain reported third-quarter earnings of $121.6  
million, or 30 cents per share, matching analysts' expectations. 
CVS said same-store sales, which measure results at stores open for 
at least a year, rose 12.2 percent in the quarter. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *eBay Inc., down 13 5/16 at 138 11/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Although the online auction house beat analysts' expectations  
for third-quarter operating profits, eBay said it faces rising 
expenses to expand its computer systems. Also, many new users are 
conducting fewer transations on the Web site. 

</P>
<P>
 *Aspen Technology Inc., up 4 1/16 at 13 1/4    	
</P>
<P>
	The software and service designer for manufacturing plants  
reported software license revenue of $21.5 million, a 34.2 percent 
increase compared with a year ago. Aspen narrowed its losses to 11 
cents per share, from 26 cents per share in 1998. 

</P>
<P>
 *F5 Networks Inc., up 37 7/8 at 137    	
</P>
<P>
	The Internet traffic management company earned 11 cents per  
share in its fiscal fourth quarter, beating analysts' estimate of a 
loss of 5 cents per share. F5 said it received net proceeds of 
about $31.4 million from a public offering of stock earlier in 
October. 

</P>
<P>
 *CellNet Data Systems Inc., down 3 11/32 at 2 3/32    	
</P>
<P>
	The company, a wireless communications service provider, has  
been unable to raise the additional capital it needs to continue 
operating. CellNet said potential investors have been reluctant to 
invest in CellNet because it carries a large amount of debt. 




  	   	
</P>
