<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 15:50:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GAO Cites Broken Army Trailers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army spent $50.6 million for 6,700  
two-wheeled trailers that now cannot be used unless the jeeps and 
trucks that pull them are modified, congressional investigators 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the 6,700 high-mobility trailers the army has  
purchased are not usable because of a safety problem and not 
suitable because they damage the trucks towing them,'' said the 
General Accounting Office, the auditing and investigative arm of 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army plans to pay an additional $640 per trailer to correct  
the flaw, the GAO said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't rocket science, these are simple trailers. If the  
Army couldn't properly manage this contract, how can we expect them 
to handle high-tech missiles and other weapons,'' said Sen. Tom 
Harkin, D-Iowa, who requested the study. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO study said the Army found that the trailers could break  
causing a safety problem. They can also damage the trucks that pull 
them. Most of them have been stored until modifications are made. 
</P>
<P>
	George Schneiter, director of strategic and tactical systems for  
the Defense Department, said the Pentagon would follow GAO's 
suggestion that the Army ``demonstrate the design will meet 
requirements and will not damage the trucks'' before acquiring more 
trailers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army wants to purchase 18,000 additional trailers.  
</P>
<P>
	The trailers were built my Silver Eagle Manufacturing Co. of  
Portland, Ore., to be used for active guard and reserve Army units. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
