<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 15:50:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hatchette Gives Vikings Options </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- Jeff George wasn't the only elixir  
for Minnesota's offense. 
</P>
<P>
	The return of wide receiver Matthew Hatchette from a lingering  
ankle injury opened up the running lanes for the Vikings on Sunday 
and freed up Cris Carter, Jake Reed and Randy Moss for their share 
of single coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	With four wideouts, the Vikings (3-4) spread out San Francisco's  
defense, taking away the blitz, and helped fill-in Leroy Hoard post 
a 100-yard rushing game and George to throw for three touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	George, who replaced the ineffective Randall Cunningham as the  
Vikings' starting quarterback, won the NFC offensive player of the 
week award, in no small part because of Hatchette's return. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hatchette didn't just harm the 49ers by his presence. His  
play hurt them, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatchette's 80-yard touchdown catch put Minnesota ahead to stay  
in the second quarter and propelled the Vikings to their 40-16 rout 
they hope signals a turnaround after six weeks of poor play. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter noted that Hatchette's not 100 percent because of his  
high ankle sprain, ``but, as you can see, he can run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatchette said he's 95 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	``It feels better and better every day,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	And so do the Vikings, thanks to Hatchette.  
</P>
<P>
	Dennis Green hoped to employ his four-wideout set early and  
often this season, but Hatchette, a third-year pro from Langston, 
severely sprained his right ankle during training camp and 
re-injured it against the Chicago Bears three weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	When healthy, ``he'll help us bring an even more potent offense  
to the field,'' Green said. ``He gives us a good stretch receiver. 
Matthew has outstanding speed, he has good hands. He gives us a 
chance to go four wide. You can put in a lot of pressure for them 
to bring in six defensive backs, which breaks down the 
two-linebacker concept and give us some running lanes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The strategy so confounded the 49ers that they repeatedly got  
caught in wrong formations Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``One time, we had five linemen to block four guys,'' Hoard  
said. ``Jeff just looked at me and smiled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then, he changed the play to a rush, handed off and watched  
Hoard break another long run. 
</P>
<P>
	When the 49ers adjusted and played the run, that freed up one of  
the receivers, all of whom are 6-foot-3 or taller and can outjump 
or outrun almost any safety or cornerback. Also, George fires the 
ball faster than just about any quarterback in the NFL except Green 
Bay's Brett Favre. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatchette hopes to force defenses to stop double-teaming his  
fellow receivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I can keep performing well, then they'll have to take some  
of that coverage off the other guys,'' Hatchette said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Moss said if teams continue to play six defensive backs,  
``we'll just run and make those six tackle Leroy, and I don't think 
there's many guys out there that want to tackle Leroy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Against San Francisco, Hoard hit the holes faster than Robert  
Smith, out with a hernia that's slowed him all season, and George 
released the ball faster than Cunningham, who was plagued by slow 
windups and tardy decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was Hatchette's return that allowed the Vikings to score  
their most points of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hatchette brings another weapon,'' Moss said. ``He probably  
had the best offseason workout that I've ever seen a guy have. I 
was anxious to see him get on the field with the three of us. ... 
And then he was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I think he's almost 100 percent healthy, so it feels good  
to see a lot of guys out there that you can count on to make a big 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moss, who constantly complained for more attention from  
Cunningham, insisted he didn't mind catching just one pass Sunday. 
He said he was eager to see what the Vikings could do if Hatchette 
stays healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think for the past two years, people have praised how  
explosive the Minnesota Vikings are, but thus far we haven't really 
had a real explosive game,'' Moss said. ``I still believe we can 
put up maybe 60 points, 70 points.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
