<HEADLINE> Boyfriend in Starve Case Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINDEN, La. (AP) -- The boyfriend of a Missouri woman accused of  
starving to death her two 8-year-old sons -- two of a set of 
triplets -- has been charged with child abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony B. Dixon, 36, of Kansas City, Mo., was arrested Tuesday  
night in northwestern Louisiana. Prosecutors today charged him in 
Kansas City with two counts of child abuse and four counts of 
endangering the welfare of a child. 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas City Police spokesman Steve Young said Dixon was stopped  
on another matter by Louisiana police, who ran his name through a 
computer and found warrants for him in Kansas City. 
</P>
<P>
	Dixon was questioned and released last week pending further  
investigation into the deaths of Larry and Gary Bass. 
</P>
<P>
	Their mother, Mary Bass, pleaded innocent to assault, abuse and  
neglect. Police said she admitted punishing the boys by putting 
their feet in scalding water, locking them in a room and depriving 
them of food except bread and water for up to two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry died Oct. 20 and Gary died early Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	The third triplet was not abused and was placed in foster care,  
along with two other children who were not abused -- a 12-year-girl 
and a 10-year-old boy. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a police complaint, Dixon said he did not seek  
medical attention for either child because he was scared he would 
be arrested for child abuse. He also was aware that the boys had 
been locked in a room and deprived of food for extended periods of 
time, the complaint said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
