<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Oct. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Armenian Premier Killed in Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	YEREVAN, Armenia (AP) -- Gunmen assassinated Armenia's prime  
minister and several other officials and lawmakers today, spraying 
Parliament with automatic weapons fire during a debate and saying 
they were staging a coup. Hours after they burst into the chamber 
and shot Prime Minister Vazgen Sarkisian, the attackers remained in 
control of the building and were holding dozens of hostages, police 
said. Hundreds of police and army soldiers ringed the building in 
central Yerevan as officials negotiated with the assailants. 
Sarkisian was number two in the government, behind President Robert 
Kocharian. Armenia, which became an independent republic following 
the Soviet collapse in 1991, has endured years of political and 
economic turmoil. 

</P>
<P>
	NTSB Probing Payne Stewart Crash  
</P>
<P>
	MINA, S.D. (AP) -- Crash investigators are back at work today,  
looking for clues as to what killed golfer Payne Stewart and five 
others. They are concentrating on removing wreckage from the 
10-foot deep crater caused when Stewart's Learjet crashed into a 
field. Tissue samples from the victims were taken for testing 
yesterday. No one was apparently conscious at the controls for four 
hours on Monday, when the jet flew 1,400 miles across the country 
on autopilot before running out of fuel. Authorities are focusing 
on a theory that the plane may have suffered sudden cabin 
depressurization, which could have caused the crew and passengers 
to black out or die. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S.: Iraq Guilty of Major Crimes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department said today that Iraqi  
authorities have engaged in nine ``major criminal episodes'' that 
qualify as crimes against humanity and pushed for an international 
war-crimes tribunal for Iraq. Among the nine are the use of poison 
gas against Iraqi Kurds in 1988, killing an estimated 5,000 people, 
and use of gas during the 1980-88 war with Iran. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Concerned About Population  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The executive director of the U.N.  
Population Fund says a serious drop in income is requiring program 
cuts that will result in an additional 1.4 million unwanted 
pregnancies. Dr. Nafis Sadik said the fund is scrambling for 
resources and cutting programs. Dr. Sadik said the funding crisis 
has delayed plans to include family life education in the school 
curriculum in Tanzania, postponed plans for operations in remote 
villages in India, suspended training of health workers in Vietnam, 
and canceled the purchase of contraceptives for some 200,000 women 
in Ecuador. 

</P>
<P>
	Re-Enactment Offends Columbine High  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- A Halloween display at a Texas church featuring a  
re-enactment of the massacre at Columbine High School has offended 
and shocked some of those connected to the attack. The ``Hell 
House'' at Trinity Church in Cedar Hill, Texas, features a skit in 
which young actors dressed in trench coats re-enact the shooting in 
which 15 were killed and more than 26 were wounded. The skit ends 
with the gunmen being sent to Hell. One parent of a Columbine 
student said she was ``repulsed'' by the act. Trinity's youth 
pastor, Tim Ferguson, has said he must scare teen-agers in order to 
save them from sin and another attack like the one at Columbine. 

</P>
<P>
	North Korea Still Has Food Shortage  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korean officials say North Korea  
needs millions of tons in food aid to avert starvation, despite an 
upswing in food production. The Korea Agricultural Economy 
Institute said the impoverished North would reap up to 3.6 million 
tons of food this year -- an increase of 20 percent from last year. 
But the country needs about 6.6 million tons a year to feed its 22 
million people. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 21.85  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 21.85 to 10,323.98. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,581-1,297. The Nasdaq is down 26.43 to 
2,785.04. 

</P>
<P>
	Kafelnikov Leads Exit of Seeds  
</P>
<P>
	STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- Yevgeny Kafelnikov, No. 2 in the  
world, and three other seeded players -- Tim Henman, Cedric Pioline 
and Karol Kucera -- were upset in the Eurocard Open today. Mariano 
Zabaleta beat Kafelnikov 6-3, 6-3 and reached the third round of 
the $2.45 million tournament. Daniel Vacek, No. 54 in the world, 
defeated the 10th-ranked Henman 6-3, 6-1. Another Czech, Jiri 
Novak, surprised the 14th-seeded Pioline 6-4, 3-6, 6-3, and Sjeng 
Schalken of the Netherlands, No. 55, downed the 15th-seeded Kucera 
7-5, 6-1. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
