<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Up 16.78 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as the continuing watch  
over inflation kept most investors from making any big commitments. 
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 16.78 at 10,318.91. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was up 3.45 at 1,285.36, and the Nasdaq composite index was 
down 27.76 at 2,783.71. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks got a short-lived lift from a Commerce Department report  
that showed orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured 
goods fell 1.3 percent in September, the first decline in five 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline was sharper than many analysts had expected, and  
offered some indication that the pace of U.S. economic growth may 
be tapering off. Stocks have stumbled in recent weeks amid worries 
that the economy is growing fast enough to persuade the Federal 
Reserve to raise interest rates for the third time this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher rates would slow economic growth by making it more  
expensive to borrow money to finance growth. They could also hurt 
stocks, however, by cutting into corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks hovered in a narrow range as investors awaited two pieces  
of economic data viewed as better gauges of inflation. On Thursday, 
the government will report on the employment cost index and the 
gross domestic product. 
</P>
<P>
	Online auctioneer eBay fell 14 to 138. The company said after  
the close of trading Tuesday its quarterly operating profits rose, 
beating analysts' expectations, after it signed up a record number 
of new users and expanded its offerings. But the company's profit 
margin fell, which caught some investors by surprise. EBay also 
recorded fewer transactions for new users, raising concerns about 
future growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq Computer slipped 1/4 to 19 1/4 after reporting earnings of  
$117 million, or 7 cents a share in the recent quarter. Analysts 
surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial expected Compaq to earn 5 
cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online rose 1 to 117 3/4. The company will report its  
profits after the close of trading today. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past two weeks, corporate earnings reports have given the  
market some sporadic relief from the lingering worries about 
inflation. But as the profit reports end and are no longer a 
distraction, the market may remain stuck in a relatively narrow 
range, said Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at George 
K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City, Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	``With most of the third-quarter earnings news out, stocks will  
likely return to an interest rate and Fed-watch stance over the 
next several days,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 554.16 million 
shares, ahead of Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.11 to 415.68.  





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 11:10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bengals' Guard Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONG BEACH, N.Y. (AP) -- Matt O'Dwyer, a guard for the Cincinnati  
Bengals, has pleaded guilty to disorderly conduct and third-degree 
assault in connection with a July bar brawl. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Dwyer, formerly of the New York Jets, originally was charged  
with assaulting police officers, harassment and disorderly conduct 
after an altercation that also involved the Jets' two starting 
offensive tackles, Jumbo Elliott and Jason Fabini. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Dwyer will be sentenced Dec. 21 by Long Beach City Court Judge  
Roy Tepper. The judge has told O'Dwyer he will not serve time in 
jail, Nassau County District Attorney Frank Schroeder said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Dwyer could be fined or ordered to perform community service.  
</P>
<P>
	Police said that the 6-foot-7, 308-pound Elliott triggered the  
brawl by urinating in a sink in the women's bathroom in the bar, 
then punching two patrons. He was charged with misdemeanor assault, 
harassment and public lewdness and faces up to a year in jail and 
fines. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Dwyer kicked out the window of a police car, sending shattered  
glass onto two officers, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fabini was charged with disorderly conduct, a misdemeanor, and  
faces a maximum sentence of 15 days in jail and a fine. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
