<DOCNO> APW19991027.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves Miss Plays and Pay the Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Baseball scouts believe that when a major  
leaguer gets to a ball, he ought to be able to make a play. That's 
what makes them major leaguers. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice in the pivotal third inning of Wednesday night's Game 4 of  
the World Series, Atlanta infielders got to the ball but failed to 
make the play. The result was three runs as the New York Yankees 
completed their sweep of the Braves, winning 4-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither play was scored an error. Either could have been.  
</P>
<P>
	The first play came when Chuck Knoblauch led off the inning with  
a shot in the hole between shortstop and third base. Walt Weiss, 
one of the best fielders in the league, got to the ball but it 
glanced off his glove, putting the leadoff man on base. Official 
scorer Red Foley ruled it an infield single. 
</P>
<P>
	When Derek Jeter singled to right, Knoblauch took third. Then,  
as Paul O'Neill struck out, Jeter stole second. Bernie Williams was 
walked intentionally to load the bases. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Tino Martinez hit a ball to the right of first baseman Ryan  
Klesko. The runner seemed to block his view for an instant and the 
ball glanced off Klesko's arm and into the outfield. Two runs 
scored on the play, which also was scored a hit. 
</P>
<P>
	In each case, the play could have gone either way -- hit or  
error. Both balls were hit sharply, but neither was a line drive. 
They were plays that needed to be made, especially by a team facing 
elimination. 
</P>
<P>
	The contrast with the Yankees' infield was dramatic, especially  
in the sixth inning. 
</P>
<P>
	With one out, shortstop Jeter ranged far to his left on a ball  
hit up the middle by Gerald Williams, crossed second base and made 
the play cleanly. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, after Bret Boone walked, Chipper Jones hit a bouncer to  
third base. Scott Brosius, playing him to pull, got a good jump and 
backhanded the ball at the bag. Then he pivoted, jumped like an 
old-time quarterback throwing a pass and retired the runner. 
</P>
<P>
	Two plays missed.  
</P>
<P>
	Two plays made.  
</P>
<P>
	They were the difference in the deciding game of the World  
Series. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
