<HEADLINE> Sosa: Baylor May Be Next Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sammy Sosa met on the field with Don Baylor  
prior to Game 4 of the World Series on Wednesday and assumes the 
Atlanta Braves hitting coach will be the next manager of the 
Chicago Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor, who managed Colorado from 1993-98 and guided the Rockies  
to their only postseason berth, already has interviewed with 
Chicago, Anaheim and Milwaukee. The Cubs are thought to have the 
inside track. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pretty much understand that the strongest candidate we have  
is Don Baylor,'' Sosa said after receiving the Hank Aaron Award as 
the top hitter in the National League. ``I believe that Don Baylor 
would be a good decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs fired Jim Riggleman after finishing last in the NL  
Central with a 67-95 record. Baylor's name has been mentioned for 
virtually every opening after just one season on the Braves' 
coaching staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa said he has not been consulted by the Cubs' front office  
during the search, and hasn't closely followed the dealings with 
Baylor and other candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just waiting for the announcement,'' he said. ``I think it  
will be soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor denied he has reached an agreement to manage the Cubs,  
saying he hasn't talked with team officials in a week. But he is 
fully aware of all the speculation. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what I'm hearing, too,'' he said while walking back to  
the clubhouse after batting practice at Yankee Stadium. ``I'm sure 
I will get bombarded with this as soon as the Series is over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An announcement that Baylor had been hired as Cubs manager was  
discovered last week by a Chicago Tribune reporter on a hidden area 
of the team's Web site. Apparently, a Cubs employee prepared a 
profile and news release in case Baylor got the job. 
</P>
<P>
	Cubs general manager Ed Lynch denied that Baylor had been hired;  
the information was removed from the site. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know he's a great manager and a great person,'' Sosa said.  
``We're not going to rebuild this team from one day to the other. 
We need to get a manager first, then we can go forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor would like to make a decision by the first week of  
November. The Braves already have conceded that Baylor will not 
return as their hitting coach next season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
