<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Insurance Settlement Gets Early OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) -- Two insurance companies that sold policies  
to people seeking to protect themselves against future steep 
nursing care costs have agreed to pay $14.7 million to settle a 
lawsuit alleging fraud, an attorney says. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement, which has been given preliminary approval by a  
magistrate, could benefit hundreds of people in North Dakota and 
two other states. It would affect those who either dropped their 
long-term care insurance policies or continue to pay high premiums, 
said Thomas Dickson of Bismarck, one of the lead attorneys for the 
plaintiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement arose from a lawsuit filed by three North  
Dakotans. They accused Ohio-based Acceleration Life Insurance Co. 
and Kentucky-based Commonwealth Life Insurance Co. of fraudulently 
selling long-term care insurance policies at prices that were too 
low and then dramatically raising rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The average premium increase in North Dakota between 1989 and  
1996 was 629 percent, Dickson said. As a result, many policyholders 
were forced to dump their coverage, according to the lawsuit, which 
was granted class-action status. 
</P>
<P>
	Acceleration and Commonwealth denied the accusations in court  
filings, saying the coverage was priced properly and that the 
policies did not violate North Dakota insurance law. 
</P>
<P>
	Marvin Tepper, an attorney for Acceleration Life, declined to  
comment on the settlement Wednesday. An attorney for Commonwealth 
Life did not immediately return a phone call seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the settlement, people who dropped their policies will be  
partially reimbursed. Dickson said the percentage of premiums they 
will get back depends on how many people submit claims. He did not 
immediately know how many people bought policies from the two 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Premiums also will be reduced for people who held onto their  
policies, Dickson said. The reduction in premiums is valued at $2.1 
million, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The case was to have gone to trial Oct. 4, but was postponed  
days before when lawyers began working on a settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought we had a case, but the class we were representing  
was extremely elderly,'' Dickson said. ``We wanted to get some 
relief for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Magistrate Karen Klein has given preliminary approval to  
the deal. People who bought the policies in question must decide in 
the next month and a half whether to participate. A final hearing 
on the settlement is scheduled for Dec. 7 in Fargo. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement also applies to residents of Wyoming and Florida  
who bought the policies in question. Similar lawsuits were filed in 
those states by Allan Kanner, a New Orleans lawyer who is one of 
the lead attorneys in the North Dakota case. 
</P>
<P>
	Long-term care insurance covers a certain amount of custodial  
care for the elderly or sick in their own homes, or in nursing 
homes. The policies are a popular way for older people to protect 
their estates from being depleted by high nursing care costs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
