<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Voters Undecided on Philly Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- With less than a week left before the city's  
mayoral election, nearly one-quarter of likely voters are still 
undecided and the candidates are running neck-and-neck, according 
to a poll released today. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrat John F. Street has 39 percent of the vote and  
Republican Sam Katz 38 percent, with a margin of error of plus or 
minus 4 percentage points, according to the Keystone Poll by the 
Center for Politics and Public Affairs at Millersville University. 
</P>
<P>
	Katz, who is white, is seeking to become the city's first  
Republican mayor in 52 years. Street is trying to be the city's 
second black mayor. More than 40 percent of Philadelphia's 1.4 
million residents are black. The city has seven Democrats for every 
two Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll found 23 percent of likely voters said they were still  
undecided. Of those, 74 percent are registered Democrats, 64 
percent are female and 47 percent are black, said G. Terry Madonna, 
the poll's director. 
</P>
<P>
	National Democratic leaders have mobilized on Street's behalf.  
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Tipper Gore, wife of Vice President Al Gore, visited  
Philadelphia to campaign for Street, and President Clinton plans to 
do the same Friday. Clinton also called a local talk radio show 
from the White House on Monday to discuss how the election could 
affect politics across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Katz has not brought in any GOP leaders to help his campaign.  
</P>
<P>
	The poll was based on a telephone survey conducted Oct. 22-24  
among a random sample of 606 likely voters. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
