<HEADLINE> Oil Overflow Spills Into Del. River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DELAWARE CITY, Del. (AP) -- A storage hold overflowed on a barge  
loading oil from a refinery dock early Wednesday, spilling about 
100 barrels of oil into the Delaware River. 
</P>
<P>
	A sensitive bird rookery on Pea Patch Island, located less than  
a mile from the Motiva refinery, wasn't threatened by the spill, 
officials said. But about a dozen mallards were caught in the oil, 
and a firm that rescues animals from oil spills was called to 
assist the cleanup. 
</P>
<P>
	A barge crew was pumping oil into the barge before dawn  
Wednesday and didn't notice the hold was overflowing until about 
100 barrels had spilled, said Jan Morrill, a spokeswoman for 
Motiva, operated jointly by Shell, Texaco and Saudi Armaco. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers tried to contain the spill with booms, but the oil  
spread several miles down the coast from Delaware City, officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Teams from the refinery, the Delaware Bay and River Cooperative,  
and the state Department of Natural Resources and Environmental 
Control expected to have the oil cleaned up Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The barge's owner did not return a message seeking comment.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
