<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ovitz Signs Jeeves the Butler </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Hollywood dealmaker Michael Ovitz, whose  
clients include Robin Williams and Cameron Diaz, said Wednesday 
he's taking on some new talent: the fictional Internet gofer Jeeves 
the butler. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz has teamed up with Ask Jeeves Inc., which uses the  
butler's character on its Ask.com search site as a kind of 
Web-surfing domestic servant to track down information for computer 
users. 
</P>
<P>
	Ask Jeeves has retained Ovitz's Lynx Technology Group LLC and  
his talent agency, Artists Management Group, to help take the 
butler beyond the Internet with potential merchandising, animation 
and placement in movies and television shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz said ``kind, sweet or acerbic butlers'' have a long  
history in entertainment, including Lurch from ``The Addams 
Family'' and John Gielgud's regal character in the movie 
``Arthur.'' Jeeves has potential to become a hit with fans outside 
the World Wide Web, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not going to be a full-length movie about him. That's  
unrealistic,'' Ovitz said. ``But there's a lot of opportunity for 
tie-ins using the character.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike search engines that require users to enter key words that  
can bring up links to hundreds of Web sites, Ask Jeeves operates a 
site that allows Internet browsers to type in real-language 
questions. Jeeves then directs users to an appropriate site chosen 
by the company's editors. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, someone who types in a question seeking information  
about Mark Twain is taken to a site about the author created by the 
University of Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	The company operates similar search sites for children and  
corporate users. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole notion of having this butler there to help get  
things and aggregate information is very appealing to people,'' 
said Ted Briscoe, senior vice president and general manager of 
Ask.com's consumer question answering service. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without sounding flip, we don't know how far this extends,''  
Briscoe said. ``The more we get into it, the more we'll see what 
kind of legs this character has.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The character is similar to, but not based on, the valet Jeeves  
in humorist P.G. Wodehouse's novels, Briscoe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz's background as a Hollywood superagent will allow Ask  
Jeeves to tap into his contacts and insider knowledge of the 
entertainment industry, Briscoe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ask Jeeves would not disclose financial specifics of its deal  
with Ovitz. Briscoe said Ovitz's companies would receive consulting 
fees plus a cut of revenues depending on the performance of Ask 
Jeeves' business. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
