<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Psychologists Seek Help for Anxiety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- This time, the psychologists are seeking  
professional help to relieve anxiety. 
</P>
<P>
	Psychologists in New York upset over their treatment by managed  
care plans have chosen a unique therapy: allying with unionized 
teachers. The New York State Psychological Association will be 
fully affiliated with the American Federation of Teachers and its 
state chapter by Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	It might seem strange for a group of professionals who tend to  
be independent. But the alliance is a move designed to strengthen 
both parties. The 3,200-member state professional group gains 
instant clout for lobbying and battling HMOs. And the union gains 
what could be a valuable toehold in expanding its membership base. 
</P>
<P>
	In a time when professional insecurity is rising to the level  
where even doctors are unionizing, analysts say the move by the New 
York psychologists could be a bellwether. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you're going to see more and more of this rather than  
less and less,'' said labor expert Alan Draper of St. Lawrence 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was inked Oct. 4 to ally the psychological association  
with AFT and its 420,000-member state chapter, the New York State 
United Teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	The psychologists do not become union members with collective  
bargaining rights. But the psychologists hope the alliance is 
enough to strengthen their hand with health maintenance 
organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Horror stories about HMOs are common among psychologists -- extra  
paperwork, low reimbursements, patient treatment cut short. New 
York City psychologist Noemi Balinth recalls a suicidal teen-ager 
being approved for only five sessions with her. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's infuriating to have denials on patients where there very  
clearly is a continuing need to see them,'' said Balinth, 
president-elect of NYSPA. ``And the clerk on the other end of the 
line is saying `No, you've seen them enough now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By linking with the union, the psychologists increase their  
government lobbying power. New York State United Teachers is a 
powerhouse in Albany, annually among the top statewide campaign 
contributors. 
</P>
<P>
	The union already represents school psychologists and other  
professional health care workers. But AFT President Sandra Feldman 
said the move keeps the union ``on the cutting edge'' as labor 
conducts expansion into new areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Psychologists are hardly the only health care professionals  
flirting with unions. The American Medical Association made 
headlines this summer by backing a union of doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	There is other evidence that union ideals are gaining ground in  
the health care field: 
</P>
<P>
	--Texas recently approved a measure that allows doctors to  
bargain collectively with health plans. 
</P>
<P>
	--Some 74,000 homecare workers who tend to the sick and elderly  
in the Los Angeles area in February voted overwhelmingly to 
unionize. 
</P>
<P>
	--The American Nurses Association voted in June to create a new  
entity to support collective bargaining efforts by state nurse 
associations. The ANA also is exploring AFL-CIO affiliation. 
</P>
<P>
	There has been no word on other psychological associations  
affiliating with unions. However, Russ Newman of the American 
Psychological Association said other state groups are watching to 
see how the New York experiment works out. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornell University labor studies professor Richard Hurd warns it  
could be ``torturous'' for professional associations and unions to 
figure out how much they have in common. 
</P>
<P>
	Already, Balinth said some of the psychologists have had to be  
disabused of the stereotype of unions as a ``blue-collar thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hurd also noted: ``This might be the future of labor.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 13:50:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Says `No' to 2000 Question </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Gov. Jesse Ventura tried again Wednesday to  
clear up questions about his presidential ambitions by issuing a 
resounding ``no.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A day earlier, the Reform Party governor had told Harvard  
Current magazine that he would consider running if Minnesotans 
mobilized behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said that I'm not running, that I won't run and they said to  
me, 'Well what if it means saving the third-party movement?''' 
Ventura told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``And I said, if indeed it got to that point, it would require  
the people of Minnesota to come out and say, 'It's OK, governor, 
run for president.''' 
</P>
<P>
	He emphasized, ``It does not mean I'm doing it. I said that  
would simply be one thing that would have to happen, but the 'nos' 
preceded that. No no no. I'm not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura also acknowledged his long-standing policy of never  
saying never to anything, and blamed the media for contorting his 
comments to make something out of them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, I don't know if tomorrow, anything can happen  
tomorrow. But I tell you no means no and you don't believe me for 
whatever reason,'' Ventura said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Harvard student interviewers were ``really begging''  
him to run in an attempt to save the third party and that he was 
clear he wouldn't run. 
</P>
<P>
	Before climbing into his Lincoln Navigator and riding off,  
Ventura joked that he might quickly change his mind, turn around 
and say, ``Yes, I'm running!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Buchanan, who joined the Reform Party on Monday and is  
seeking its presidential nomination, plans several stops in 
Minnesota on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the possibility of meeting with Buchanan, Ventura said,  
``It's not on my schedule.'' Would he support Buchanan as the 
party's nominee? ``I plan to have no comment,'' Ventura said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 10:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UConn Favorite in Big East Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Connecticut, the defending NCAA and Big East  
champion, was the runaway No. 1 choice by the league's coaches in 
the preseason poll released Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Huskies, who return three starters from the team that beat  
Duke for the national championship last season, received 10 of a 
possible 13 first-place votes. Coaches do not place their own teams 
on their ballots. 
</P>
<P>
	Syracuse received the remaining No. 1 votes and 131 points, nine  
fewer than Connecticut. St. John's was third with 119 points and 
Miami, which got the other first-place vote, was fourth with 114. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgetown was fifth with 97 points and was followed by  
Villanova (82), Seton Hall (73), Rutgers (68), Notre Dame (60), 
Providence (45), West Virginia (34), Pittsburgh (30) and Boston 
College (19). 
</P>
<P>
	Guard Khalid El-Amin was chosen as the preseason player of the  
year, the second straight season a Connecticut junior received the 
honor. It is the fourth time a Connecticut player was tabbed for it 
with Richard Hamilton last season, Donyell Marshall in 1993-94 and 
Corny Thompson in 1981-82. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining El-Amin on the preseason first team were seniors Johnny  
Hemsley of Miami and Etan Thomas of Syracuse and sophomores Troy 
Murphy of Notre Dame and Erick Barkley of St. John's. 
</P>
<P>
	Hemsley was selected the conference's most improved player last  
season, while Thomas was the defensive player of the year and 
Murphy the rookie of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the first time more than one sophomore was voted to the  
first team since 1982-83 when Patrick Ewing of Georgetown, Chris 
Mullin of St. John's and Ed Pinckney of Villanova were selected. 
</P>
<P>
	The second team was all seniors, forwards Kevin Freeman of  
Connecticut, Isaac Hawkins of Pittsburgh and Marcus Goree of West 
Virginia and guards Bootsy Thornton of St. John's and Jason Hart of 
Syracuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut's Ajou Deng, a 6-foot-11 sophomore who sat out last  
season to concentrate on academics, was chosen the preseason rookie 
of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	El-Amin and Deng are the first teammates to be chosen for the  
individual preseason awards since 1990-91 when Syracuse's Billy 
Owens and freshman Adrian Autry were selected. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 08:11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russian Jets Bomb Downtown Grozny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Diving Russian jets bombed downtown Grozny  
today in some of the heaviest airstrikes against the Chechen 
capital since federal troops invaded the breakaway republic. 
</P>
<P>
	Large plumes of smoke rose over Grozny and houses were damaged  
on the eastern side of the city. Pairs of Russian jets roared over 
the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Chechen officials said 38 civilians were killed and about 100  
injured in the strikes. The numbers could not be confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the most serious attack on the city since a rocket strike  
on a downtown market on Oct. 21 killed at least 150 people. Russian 
jets bombed industrial targets in Grozny's suburbs in September. 
</P>
<P>
	President Boris Yeltsin said today that Moscow was determined to  
press ahead with its campaign. He said Russian forces would 
``destroy the center of international terrorism in Chechnya and let 
people live calmly and peacefully.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Russian soldiers and officers are bringing peace back to the  
long-suffering Chechen land. Every day and hour they display 
courage and heroism, cleansing Chechnya of bandits,'' he said in 
his most extensive comments yet on the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the homes destroyed was the residence of Chechen warlord  
Shamil Basayev, who led Islamic militants in two attacks against 
the neighboring Russian region of Dagestan this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will force Russian prisoners of war to restore all those  
houses,'' Basayev said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Russian forces in eastern Chechnya took control of  
four villages and surrounded two others, Russian Defense Ministry 
spokesman Gennady Alyokhin said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian forces in the region were focusing air and artillery  
raids on the nearby city of Gudermes, Alyokhin said. 
</P>
<P>
	The four captured settlements -- Azamat-Yurt, Stepnoye, Nizhni  
Gerzel and Kadi-Yurt -- lie along a strategically important highway 
running east to Dagestan and just a few miles from Gudermes, the 
Russian military command said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gudermes, Chechnya's second-largest city, is 20 miles east of  
Grozny. Seizing it would be a major step toward full Russian 
control of eastern Chechnya, but the city has been well fortified 
by militants. 
</P>
<P>
	The Interfax news agency, citing the Russian air force, said  
Russian jets had flown 34 missions over the region, killing an 
estimated 100 militants. The death toll could not be independently 
confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Militant leaders said they had killed more than 400 Russians in  
fighting Tuesday, but that number was believed to be exaggerated. 
</P>
<P>
	The offensive in the east came as Russian tanks and soldiers  
closed in on Grozny from the north. Chechen militants traded fire 
with them two miles from the city's outskirts and battled Russian 
forces in Tolstoy-Yurt village, to the north. 
</P>
<P>
	Chechen commanders appeared confident about defending the  
capital, where guerrillas inflicted severe losses on the Russian 
army in street fighting during the 1994-96 Chechen war. The 
Chechens say they have built concrete bunkers and other sturdy 
defenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has sent mixed messages over whether it will try to take  
Grozny. After early successes, the Russian military now appears to 
be trying to occupy all of the republic and end its de facto 
independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscow Interior Ministry troops commander Arkady Baskayev said  
today that the capital would definitely be taken. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, of course, and not only Grozny. Time doesn't matter, the  
main thing is to be well-prepared for the operation and take 
(Grozny) without big losses,'' he said in an interview on the Echo 
of Moscow radio station. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian troops entered Chechnya in September, with the stated  
mission of wiping out Islamic militants who twice raided a 
neighboring Russian region this summer and are blamed for four 
apartment blasts in Russian cities that killed 300 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chechen government has no control over the militants, but  
its forces are fighting side by side with the rebels against the 
Russian offensive. 
</P>
<P>
	Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov said today that the bomb  
attack Oct. 21 at a Grozny market had been aimed at his 
presidential palace. He said the Russians had used a tactical 
missile with cluster bombs for maximum casualties, and claimed that 
282 people had been killed in the attack. Earlier Chechen reports 
gave a death toll of about 150. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian officials have issued contradictory statements on the  
attack, with some denying it occurred and others saying it had been 
directed at arms-sellers in Grozny. Others have said the casualty 
figures were exaggerated. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 10:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Daly's Fear of Flying Heightened  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Miss. (AP) -- While more at ease with life since he  
ended two years of sobriety, John Daly still has an almost 
overwhelming fear of flying that got worse when Payne Stewart was 
killed in a plane crash. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really not even wanting to get on a plane to go anywhere  
right now,'' Daly said playing a practice round Tuesday at the 
Southern Farm Bureau Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know they are safer and it's the best way to travel, but  
I've always said I like my chances in a car wreck before I do a 
plane crash, because nobody is going to live.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daly arrived at Annadale Golf Club by car after driving more  
than six hours from the Dallas area rather than taking a one-hour 
flight. 
</P>
<P>
	The fact that Stewart and five others were killed while  
traveling in a Learjet only worsened Daly's fears. 
</P>
<P>
	``You expect some other kind of plane to go down before a  
Lear,'' Daly said. ``It was the only plane that I really felt safe 
in because of all of the safety features that it had. It was just 
like it was crash-proof.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for other aspects of his life, Daly insists he is more at  
ease since he ended his sobriety June 11 after missing the cut at 
the St. Jude Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	That cost Daly his endorsement with Callaway Golf and his  
primary source of income, but he says the freedom to make his own 
decisions has been more valuable. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel a lot better. I felt like I was trying to do everything  
for everybody else instead of myself, and it was bringing me 
down,'' Daly said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if the decision I made is right or wrong, but I  
still feel a little better about being able to make my own 
decisions and not having somebody over my shoulder all of the time 
watching every move I make.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daly's five-year deal with Callaway, signed after he left rehab  
in April 1997, included a provision that he not drink or gamble. 
Chairman Ely Callaway offered to send Daly to an addiction 
specialist earlier this year, but Daly left after arriving at the 
undisclosed clinic. 
</P>
<P>
	Callaway, the 80-year-old chairman, was something of a father  
figure to Daly. Callaway said he had no choice but to drop the 
long-hitting golfer, who stood to earn about $3 million in the 
final two years of the contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. C basically made it too easy for me. The money was great,  
and I kind of backed off on practicing, and I think I was more 
worried about not drinking and not gambling than I was trying to 
play,'' Daly said. ``It took all of the energy out of me just 
trying not to do those two things. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now I've got a hunger in my belly to go out and play good  
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he played in the Las Vegas Invitational this month, Daly  
said he gambled only for about an hour during the seven days he 
spent in the gambling mecca. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't even hardly gamble,'' Daly said. ``The drinking  
aspect of it, I feel like I've been doing great. I haven't even 
hardly drank to tell you the truth. It's not something I want to do 
every day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Knowing that I can now and knowing that most everybody knows  
that I can, I'm not really doing it. The pressure's kind of gone. 
Now I can just go out and practice and play golf, and that's all 
I've got to worry about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daly hasn't won since the 1995 British Open and is 163rd on the  
money list ($176,565) this year. He is not in danger of losing his 
PGA Tour card because of the 10-year exemption that came with his 
last win. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 08:11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
