<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Plans 100,000-Rupiah Note </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia will start issuing its first  
100,000 rupiah bank notes in anticipation of possible increased 
demand for cash by the end of the year on Y2K fears, central bank 
officials said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	At the current exchange rate, the note would be worth $15.  
</P>
<P>
	The face of Sukarno, Indonesia's founding president and father  
of new Vice President Megawati Sukarnoputri, adorns the new 
currency to be in circulation starting Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Aulia Pohan, deputy governor of the Bank Indonesia, said demand  
for bank notes has increased. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we know, the highest nominal value of the bank note is  
50,000 rupiah ($7.50) and, after the high inflation rate, the 
purchasing power of the note is decreasing,'' Aulia said. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been concerns that the Y2K, or ``millennium bug,''  
could cause some computers to malfunction if they misinterpret the 
final 00 digits in dates as 1900 instead of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second major currency move in five months. The  
central bank began replacing the 50,000 rupiah notes in June 
because they carried the portrait of former President Suharto, who 
resigned last year amid bloody pro-democracy protests and riots. 
</P>
<P>
	He has been accused of massive corruption and blamed for the  
worst economic crisis in a generation. A graft investigation 
against him is being reopened. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
