<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Protest Vendor's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *By SAMAR ASSAD    	
</P>
<P>
                      *Associated Press Writer    	
</P>
<P>
	BETHLEHEM, West Bank (AP) -- Breaking away from a funeral  
procession, 200 Palestinians hurled stones at Israeli soldiers 
today in a third day of protests over the army's shooting of a 
Bethlehem souvenir vendor. 
</P>
<P>
	Masked protesters twirling slingshots hurled rocks and empty  
bottles at soldiers guarding Rachel's Tomb, an Israeli enclave in 
Palestinian-run Bethlehem. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli troops responded with tear gas and rubber-coated steel  
pellets. Three demonstrators were hit by rubber bullets and two 
were treated for tear gas inhalation, Palestinian paramedics said. 
</P>
<P>
	The vendor, Mousa Abu Hilail, was fatally shot Monday by a  
soldier near Rachel's Tomb, a Jewish shrine revered as the burial 
site of the biblical matriarch. The soldier claimed Abu Hilail had 
tried to stab him, but Palestinian officials have alleged that the 
soldier opened fire without provocation. 
</P>
<P>
	Abu Hilail was buried today in Beit Sahour, a town adjacent to  
Bethlehem. His body was wrapped in a Palestinian flag. Hundreds of 
mourners followed the procession, some firing guns in the air and 
others waving Palestinian flags. 
</P>
<P>
	After the burial, several hundred young men broke away and  
headed to Rachel's Tomb, where they threw stones at soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	Bethlehem, the town where tradition says Jesus was born, was  
already tense before Monday's shooting because of Israeli plans to 
turn a makeshift checkpoint at the town's entrance into a large, 
reinforced border station. 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinians need special entry permits to go to nearby  
Jerusalem, five miles away. They fear Israel is trying to make 
travel even more difficult by setting up the new checkpoint. 
Palestinian officials have also accused Israel of trying to scare 
off tourists during the millennium season. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel has said it was only trying to reduce traffic jams at the  
checkpoint. 
</P>
<P>
	The violence in Bethlehem came just days before Palestinian  
leader Yasser Arafat, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and 
President Clinton's scheduled summit in Oslo, Norway, to try and 
launch talks on a final peace treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak has asked the United States to scale down its involvement  
in the negotiations. However, Arafat said today that he seeks a 
``full role'' for Clinton and his mediators. The Palestinians feel 
they are the weaker party and need the Americans' help in facing 
Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's chief Mideast mediator, Dennis Ross, arrived in  
Jerusalem today to lay the groundwork for the Oslo summit. Ross 
said the peace process was at a delicate moment of great potential. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now is the time to try to get down to business in a way that  
gives us a chance to realize that potential and turn what is a hope 
into a reality,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
