<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Cop Fired in Police Beating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A police officer accused in the beating of a black  
undercover officer who was mistaken for a murder suspect was fired 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston Police Commissioner Paul Evans fired officer James Burgio  
after a department hearings officer upheld internal charges against 
him in connection with the January 1995 beating. 
</P>
<P>
	Burgio was terminated after charges of excessive force, failing  
to provide emergency care and failing to come to the aid of a 
fellow officer were sustained by the hearings officer, the 
department said. 
</P>
<P>
	Burgio, 39, is the first of five officers who have been accused  
in the attack on Officer Michael Cox -- or a cover-up that allegedly 
followed -- to be terminated from the force. They had all been 
suspended without pay. 
</P>
<P>
	Burgio's attorney, Thomas Drechsler, said that his client would  
appeal the decision to a civilian arbitrator. 
</P>
<P>
	``My client has always denied causing injuries to Mr. Cox,''  
said Drechsler. ``We're confident he will be exonerated after an 
appeal. My client feels as if he has been made a scapegoat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cox was working undercover in the city's Roxbury neighborhood  
when he was allegedly mistaken for a murder suspect during a foot 
chase and beaten severely by several offices. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox suffered a concussion, egg-sized contusions on his head,  
multiple facial cuts and kidney damage and spent the next six 
months out of work. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, the city of Boston agreed to pay nearly $1.3  
million to Cox to settle a civil rights lawsuit against the city 
and the police department. 
</P>
<P>
	Sgt. Detective Margot Hill, a Boston Police spokeswoman, said  
there would be no comment in the Burgio termination because 
decisions in the cases of the other officers were still pending. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
