<DOCNO> APW19991027.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Hemingway's Son Shares Dad's Poetry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Admirers of Ernest Hemingway rarely think of  
him as a poet -- just not that kind of guy -- but his eldest son John 
was at the Library of Congress on Wednesday to present the author's 
first book: ``Three Stories and Ten Poems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was published in Paris in 1923 when Hemingway, later to win  
the Nobel prize for his novels, was 24. This copy is dedicated to 
his first wife, Hadley -- John's mother. 
</P>
<P>
	John, 76, was born the same year. Now he wears a rounded white  
beard, much like Ernest Hemingway's in his later years. 
</P>
<P>
	John told a news conference that his father had never spoken to  
him about his verses. ``But you know that a great deal of his early 
work was in poetry,'' he recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	Six poems were published in ``Poetry: A Magazine of Verse,'' and  
editor Harriet Monroe described the author then as ``a young 
Chicago poet now abroad who will soon issue in Paris his first book 
of verse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, many were written to Mary, Hemingway's fourth and last  
wife. One threatens jokingly to ``hang myself from your Christmas 
tree'' if she doesn't accept him as a Valentine. 
</P>
<P>
	Another poem, written earlier, is clouded with thoughts of  
death. It includes the lines: 
</P>
<P>
	``Eternity is scarcely found  
</P>
<P>
	``Until we're underneath the ground  
</P>
<P>
	``Where thudding hooves will never sound.  
</P>
<P>
	Hemingway killed himself at 61.  
</P>
<P>
	At age 12 he was rhyming about baseball:  
</P>
<P>
	``With Chance on first and Evers on third,  
</P>
<P>
	``Great things from the Cubs will soon be heard.''  
</P>
<P>
	He was bitter about World War I, in which he was wounded on the  
Italian front. He wrote: 
</P>
<P>
	``Soldiers never do die well;  
</P>
<P>
	``Crosses mark the places,  
</P>
<P>
	``Wooden crosses where they fell;  
</P>
<P>
	``Stuck above their faces.  
</P>
<P>
	John said his father also wrote many poems about World War II,  
when he was a correspondent, ``mostly about separation from his 
girl friend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A. E. Hotchner, a close friend for the last 14 years of  
Hemingway's life, also gave the library a large collection of 
photos, manuscripts, home movies and 15 spools of magnetized wire 
recordings. He was not sure of the contents of the recordings, he 
said, but knew they included Hemingway reciting two long poems to 
Mary. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the wires have not yet been transcribed.  
</P>
<P>
	Alice Birney, an historian of American literature at the  
library, said that Hemingway's poems have no claim to be considered 
great verse. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of them are pretty raunchy,'' she pointed out.  
</P>
<P>
	According to ``Advice to a Son:''  
</P>
<P>
	``Always put paper on the seat,  
</P>
<P>
	``Don't believe in wars,  
</P>
<P>
	``Keep yourself both clean and neat.  
</P>
<P>
	``Never marry whores.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0345 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 20:16:01 </DATE_TIME>
