<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patriots Add Linebacker Kopp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Jeff Kopp was cut by the Baltimore Ravens,  
failed a tryout with the lowly Atlanta Falcons and was unemployed 
for three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, he could be starting at linebacker for the New  
England Patriots, whose 5-2 record is one of the NFL's best. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great country, isn't it?'' Kopp said Wednesday before  
going through his first practice with his new team. 
</P>
<P>
	It sure is, especially when a team is as desperate for  
linebackers as the Patriots. They had just two healthy players at 
that position at the end of last Sunday's 24-23 win over Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	They were looking for linebackers to play Sunday at Arizona, and  
Kopp was looking for a job. 
</P>
<P>
	A sixth-round draft choice out of Southern California by Miami  
in 1995, he spent one season there, 2 1/2 with Jacksonville and signed 
with Baltimore last Oct. 28. The Ravens cut him Oct. 5 but, at age 
28, he wasn't ready to give up the game. 
</P>
<P>
	So he tried out last week with the Falcons. They told him they  
would make some decisions after their game last Monday night 
against Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't going to wait around for them. The Patriots said, `we  
want to sign you.' I said `great,' '' Kopp said. 
</P>
<P>
	He shared his good fortune in a phone call Tuesday night with  
his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `man, this is fun,' '' Kopp said. ``You go from being  
released, to a team that obviously doesn't want you, then the next 
thing you know you've got an opportunity to play every play on 
special teams and an opportunity to start. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be crazy to tell you I'm not looking forward to it. I love  
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Tedy Bruschi, listed as questionable after missing the last  
two games with a knee injury, is healthy enough to play, he'll 
start rather than Kopp, coach Pete Carroll said. 
</P>
<P>
	If not?  
</P>
<P>
	``He may have to start in this game,'' Carroll said of his  
newest player. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's athletic, his attitude is upbeat all the time,'' said  
Patriots defensive end Willie McGinest, a college teammate of 
Kopp's. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been in our conference and we played against him many  
years,'' said Chris Slade, one of the Patriots healthy linebackers. 
``We know the guy can play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If he can stay awake after late nights spent studying the New  
England defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Kopp, who has started just three of his 57 NFL games, began his  
crash course after beating out four players at Tuesday afternoon's 
tryout and continued Tuesday night and Wednesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll put in a lot of extra time,'' he said. ``I got here the  
first thing this morning, probably before everybody else. ... I 
have to learn the system in four or five days and go out there and 
be ready to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Without his wife and 16-month-old daughter in town, he can  
concentrate on his studies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like I want to hang out at the hotel,'' Kopp said.  
``I'd just as soon stay here and study all night if I have to. ... 
I'm preparing that I'm going to play every play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots added another linebacker, Ron Merkerson, to their  
practice squad. He was their fifth-round draft pick last year out 
of Colorado but was waived last Sept. 20 when the Patriots 
activated defensive back J'Juan Cherry. 
</P>
<P>
	Cherry was put on injured reserve Wednesday to clear a roster  
spot for Kopp. The Patriots also released running back Marques 
Brigham from the practice squad. 
</P>
<P>
	Those were the final steps New England took to add Kopp. First,  
he had to survive Tuesday's tryout. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was pretty intense. There were a lot of people out there, a  
lot of coaches, a lot of scouts,'' Kopp said. ``I feel like I won a 
lottery.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
