<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Freeze Indian Tribe's Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTEE, Neb. (AP) -- Federal prosecutors have frozen the bank  
accounts of the Santee Sioux Tribe in an attempt to shut down its 
casino. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Attorney Tom Monaghan said he intends to seize the assets  
to help pay more than $1 million in fines the tribe owes the 
government for operating its casino in defiance of court orders. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the first step in the collection process,'' he said  
Tuesday. ``The tribe has not made any effort to pay those 
court-ordered fines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Santee leaders said the money included federal funds earmarked  
for health-care and social service programs. None of the money was 
generated from the casino, tribal chairman Butch Denny said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an attack on our elderly and children,'' Denny said.  
``We are not going to let him get away with this. We are ready to 
fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was the latest development in a three-year effort by state  
and federal officials to close the casino on the Santee reservation 
near the South Dakota border in northeast Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribe opened the Ohiya Casino in 1996 even though the state  
refused to approve it. Casino-style gambling, including slot 
machines, is illegal in Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indian Gaming Regulatory Act of 1988 requires states to  
negotiate agreements with tribes to set rules and limits on 
gambling. The tribe sued the state, alleging it failed to negotiate 
in good faith. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribe says the casino's 23 jobs are much needed on the  
reservation -- where the unemployment rate is 74 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the tribe or Monaghan knew exactly how much money was in  
the frozen accounts at two banks. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge started fining the tribe $3,000 per day in  
February for refusing to close the casino. The fine was doubled in 
July. None of the fines have been paid. 
</P>
<P>
	Monaghan also seized about $87,000 from a Santee account in  
South Dakota in 1997. The tribe responded by filing a lawsuit and 
opening secret accounts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 13:40:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baffert Has Hot Breeders' Cup Hand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Trainer Bob Baffert will take dead aim at  
winning four of the eight Breeders' Cup races with two star fillies 
and a pair of talented colts. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, Baffert pre-entered a total of eight horses in six races  
at Gulfstream Park Wednesday. Barring injury or illness, all eight 
are assured of starting Nov. 6. Official entries will be made Nov. 
3. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Watchmaker, the national handicapper for the Daily Racing  
Form, made the Baffert-trained 3-year-old filly Silverbulletday the 
2-1 early favorite to win the Distaff and unbeaten Chilukki the 9-5 
choice to win the Juvenile Fillies. Baffert has another early 
favorite, the colt Forest Camp, 3-1 in the Juvenile. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert will try to win the $4 million Classic with the  
3-year-old colt General Challenge, the 5-1 second pick, and the 
Sprint with Forestry, a 3-year-old colt, who is the 9-2 second 
choice. Baffert also trains River Keen, a 7-year-old and the 6-1 
third choice in the Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Baffert-trained horses pre-entered were Tuzla in the Mile  
on the grass and Captain Steve in the Juvenile. 
</P>
<P>
	The favorite in the showcase Classic is Behrens (3-1). who lost  
his last two starts after winning four straight stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically we started the year at Gulfstream and we will end it  
in Gulfstream and I hope it will end on a positive note,'' Jim 
Bond, Behrens' trainer, said in a conference call. A victory by the 
5-year-old Behrens likely would make him Horse of the Year. 
</P>
<P>
	Other early favorites are Artax (7-2) in the Sprint, Hawksley's  
Hill (4-1) in the Mile, Britain-based Daylami (7-2) in the Turf and 
Soaring Softly (4-1) in the Filly &AMP; Mare Turf. 
</P>
<P>
	Each race is limited to 14 starters and six of the races drew  
from 18 to 25 pre-entries, meaning they will have also-eligible 
lists. The Juvenile Fillies drew 10 pre-entries, and the Distaff 
drew 11. There were a total of 128 horses pre-entered. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those assured of starting in the 1 1/4-mile Classic besides  
Behrens, General Challenge, winner of the Pacific Classic, and 
River Keen, winner of the Woodward and Jockey Club Gold Cup, are 
3-year-olds Lemon Drop Kid, winner of the Belmont Stakes and 
Travers; Vision and Verse, second in both those races, and Ecton 
Park, winner of the Jim Dandy and Super Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Distaff, Silverbulletday will be seeking her ninth win in  
11 starts this year in her second race against older fillies and 
mares. Two of her rivals will be 4-year-old Beautiful Pleasure, who 
beat Silverbulletday in the Beldame in the slop, and Banshee 
Breeze, second in the Distaff last year. 
</P>
<P>
	A victory in the Juvenile Fillies would make Chilukki 6-for-6.  
One of her rivals will be Surfside, winner of three of four starts, 
trained by D. Wayne Lukas, who is expected to have seven starters 
in five races. 
</P>
<P>
	Two rivals of Forest Camp, winner of two of three races, will be  
Greenwood Lake, winner of the Champagne, and Dixie Union, who beat 
Forest Camp in the Norfolk. 
</P>
<P>
	Horses who won Breeders' Cup races last year include  
Silverbulletday in the Juvenile Fillies and Buck's Boy in the 
Breeders' Cup Turf. Buck's Boy's start in this year's Turf will be 
only his second since he won last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
