<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House on Record Against Tax Raise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In case anyone missed it the first time, the  
Republican-led House has gone on record again as opposing a tax 
increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Exactly a week after the House voted against $19.2 billion in  
specific tax increases sought by President Clinton to balance the 
fiscal 2000 budget, lawmakers on Tuesday approved a nonbinding 
resolution expressing general opposition to raising taxes in order 
to boost government spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``It forces us to focus on the choices we need to make in order  
to maintain fiscal discipline,'' said Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz. 
``We cannot continue to burden working Americans with higher and 
higher and higher taxes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since Clinton vetoed their cherished $792 billion tax cut,  
congressional Republicans have fought against several Clinton tax 
increase and other revenue proposals, including a 55-cent-a-pack 
cigarette tax and a plan to close corporate tax shelters. 
Republicans are seeking cuts in spending to balance the fiscal 2000 
budget instead of raising revenue elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	With these negotiations entering a key stretch, some Democrats  
said Tuesday's vote on the nonbinding resolution amounted to a 
Republican anti-tax press release given an endorsement by the full 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Speaker, this is stupid,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel of New  
York, ranking Democrat on the tax-writing Ways and Means Committee. 
``This is no way to deal with the problems that we face as a 
nation. You legislate in the House. You have hearings and you do 
something about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rangel's choice of words brought Republicans indignantly to  
their feet. ``I don't believe I have heard so much hot air released 
at once since the Hindenberg went down,'' huffed Rep. John Sununu, 
R-N.H. 
</P>
<P>
	Rangel apologized but later issued a statement saying the GOP is  
using the House floor ``as a public relations tool'' to bolster the 
party's effort at keeping the majority in the 2000 elections. 
``This is just a feel-good resolution,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, it passed 371-48 with 154 Democrats in favor.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite the partisan flare-up, the House had no trouble agreeing  
to support the Clinton administration's proposal that a one-year 
ban on global Internet tariffs and taxes be made permanent by the 
World Trade Organization. The 132-nation WTO meets Nov. 30 in 
Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``A tariff retains an element of piracy,'' said Rep. Christopher  
Cox, R-Calif. ``This trade today is conducted free of piracy. The 
aim of this resolution is to keep it that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Congress last year enacted a three-year moratorium on new  
Internet taxes in this country and created a public-private 
commission to recommend future tax policy for e-commerce. That 
panel is now accepting proposals for taxation of Internet 
transactions to determine whether such a system is possible, let 
alone desirable. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. James Moran, D-Va., warned that Congress would eventually  
have to confront how to keep the Internet tax burden low while 
ensuring e-commerce does not siphon tax dollars needed for schools, 
roads and public safety. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have also got to listen to the state and local officials  
who can see what is coming,'' said Moran, a former mayor of 
Alexandria, Va. ``We have to deal with this.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
