<HEADLINE> Fired Manager Backs Teamsters Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- A fired manager for Overnite Transportation  
Co. has gone to bat for the Teamsters union, which is striking the 
shipper in a dispute over a new contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale Watson said Tuesday that employees sympathetic to the union  
were singled out for discipline and dismissal. Watson is a former 
operations manager at the trucking company's Memphis, Tenn., 
terminal. 
</P>
<P>
	His comments came in a conference call coordinated by the  
Teamsters, who struck the Richmond-based company on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnite met all deliveries and pickups Tuesday for the second  
straight day, the company said. Teamsters strike coordinator David 
Cameron said 2,000 Overnite workers stayed home. 
</P>
<P>
	The Teamsters and Overnite have been trying for several years to  
negotiate a contract for 22 terminals where the union represents 
company workers. The company has 166 terminals in the United 
States, Canada, Mexico, Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnite contends a major issue is control of the company's  
pension fund for employees. The union contends that Overnite hasn't 
negotiated in good faith. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnite said the 22 locations account for 14 percent of the  
company's 13,000 employees. Picketing was reported Tuesday at 
terminals in Tennessee, Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, Georgia, 
Arkansas, Missouri, Louisiana, Ohio, Pennsylvania and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson said he filed an affidavit with the National Labor  
Relations Board because he wanted ``the truth to be known. There's 
too much injustice being done to employees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Overnite spokesman Ira Rosenfeld disputed Watson's account,  
saying the manager's disciplinary practices were so harsh that the 
company had to step in. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Memphis service manager refused to let him discipline  
employees last summer because he was disciplining them too much. 
The company had to rein him in,'' Rosenfeld said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosenfeld said Watson was fired for poor performance. Watson  
said he was dismissed for ``Mickey Mouse reasons,'' including 
arguing with another manager and showing an employee the wrong way 
to move equipment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
