<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Rise Amid Strong Demand / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose Wednesday as strong investor  
demand at the government's auction of $15 billion in two-year 
Treasury notes spread into the broader market. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 5/8 point,  
or $6.25 per $1,000 invested. Its yield, which moves inversely to 
the price, fell to 6.33 percent from 6.37 percent late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The government sold the two-year notes at a yield of 5.94  
percent, drawing a strong $40.3 billion in bids that helped buoy 
demand in the broader market for Treasury securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Also supporting the market was a government report that orders  
for big-ticket manufactured goods, such as cars and airplanes, fell 
a greater-than-expected 1.3 percent in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The report helped ease speculation that the Federal Reserve will  
raise interest rates again to check any inflationary growth in the 
U.S. economy. Higher rates would hurt the value of existing 
fixed-rate securities. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices for short-term securities rose  
3/32 percent, while intermediate treasury securities rose 5/32 
percent to 9/32 percent, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.13 percent as the  
discount was unchanged at 4.99 percent. Six-month yields were 5.31 
percent, as the discount fell 0.02 percentage point to 5.10 
percent. One-year yields were 5.50 percent as the discount fell 
0.02 percentage point to 5.21 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.38 percent from 5.19 percent on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds was unchanged at 108 5/32. The average yield 
to maturity held at 6.16 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
