<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Accuses Mo. Gov. of Lying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Democratic Gov. Mel Carnahan is again  
apologizing for appearing in blackface in the 1960s, after 
Republicans accused him of lying about how recently he put on the 
makeup for hometown minstrel shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Carnahan said the GOP is distorting an explanation he offered  
Monday for his blackface appearance in a barbershop quartet. Still, 
the 65-year-old governor renewed his apologies for small-town 
racial insensitivity almost four decades ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I regret having been in them and I regret the insensitivity  
that's shown, but I do think that I have grown,'' Carnahan said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that as a young state representative, ``I grew rather  
quickly, sponsoring civil rights legislation in 1965.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Carnahan acknowledged and apologized for his  
blackface role in an October 1960 minstrel show by the Kiwanis Club 
in his hometown of Rolla. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Missouri Republican Party's executive director,  
John Hancock, provided a photo from an October 1961 minstrel show 
showing Carnahan singing in blackface. 
</P>
<P>
	Another photo showed Carnahan without makeup singing in an  
October 1962 minstrel show that included other performers in 
blackface. All of the photos first appeared in the '60s in the 
Rolla Daily News. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just see this as setting the record straight,'' Hancock  
said. ``I don't believe Mel Carnahan is a racist. I do believe he 
has a fair difficulty with the truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carnahan is challenging Republican Sen. John Ashcroft for his  
Senate seat in 2000. Ashcroft has had no comment about the 
blackface photos. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP also issued a news release headlined: ``Carnahan Lied in  
his `Apology.''' Hancock said the photographs proved that Carnahan 
was trying Monday to minimize his experiences wearing blackface. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, when Carnahan was asked when the Kiwanis Club had  
stopped sanctioning fund-raising minstrel shows, he replied: 
</P>
<P>
	``In the early 60s -- I don't know whether it was '60 or '61.  
There may have been one other, I do not know. I have not had the 
benefit of all the research my opponents have had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A reporter then asked whether he had performed at any other time  
with a Kiwanis barbershop quartet while wearing blackface. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think so,'' Carnahan replied.  
</P>
<P>
	The two-term governor, who has also served as lieutenant  
governor and state treasurer, said he should be judged on his 
record since the 1960s. He said that includes his appointment of 
the first black Missouri Supreme Court judge in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	That judge, Ronnie White, was rejected for a federal district  
judgeship on Oct. 5. Ashcroft helped defeat White's nomination, 
calling the judge soft on the death penalty and ``pro-criminal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Margaret Bush Wilson, a St. Louis lawyer and former national  
board chairman of the National Association for the Advancement of 
Colored People, called the new attention to the old photographs 
``absurd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Thirty-nine years ago a lot of people were bigoted, including  
a lot of people who dredged this stuff up. I think we need to get 
on with the business of today and stop this nonsense,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
