<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> National Geographic Goes High Tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Combining more than a century of traditional  
mapping with modern technology, the National Geographic Society is 
issuing a massive new world atlas and making its maps available on 
the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great day for maps,'' the society's chief cartographer,  
Allen Carroll, said in announcing the steps Wednesday at a news 
conference at 38 degrees 54 minutes 18 seconds north latitude, 77 
degrees 2 minutes 18 seconds west longitude. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not too many years ago, maps were pretty passive things. Back  
then, maps were kind of like nouns, now they've become active 
verbs,'' Carroll said of the book-Internet combination. 
</P>
<P>
	The new seventh edition of the atlas includes such changes as  
the breakup of Yugoslavia, the creation of the native territory 
Nunavut in Canada, new provincial boundaries in Poland and changing 
country names in Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	It also marks the completion of a three-year $3 million effort  
to computerize all society maps -- a project that allows them to be 
put on the Internet at www.nationalgeographic.com/mapmachine. 
</P>
<P>
	The book costs $125 while the Internet is free -- supported by  
advertising and sponsors. But society officials are confident a 
market exists for both. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think they are a perfect combination,'' Carroll said.  
``They are not redundant, they are complimentary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book gives better resolution, looks better on a coffee  
table, is quicker and easier to use and makes a nice gift, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But any map book is out of date the minute it's printed, while  
the Internet can be kept up to date. 
</P>
<P>
	So, when there are changes that affect the printed atlas, people  
will be able to find the corrected map on the Web site, print it 
out at the correct scale, and paste it in their book, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, it's already happened. The Black Canyon of the Gunnison,  
formerly a national monument, is now a national park. The printed 
correction can be pasted on plate 39 of the atlas. 
</P>
<P>
	Every map in the new atlas has been redone from the sixth  
edition, Carroll said, adding improved shaded relief. The volume 
also contains a new satellite mosaic map of the world, a 136-page 
index and an expanded section providing flags and descriptions of 
the countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The volume will generate complaints, Carroll admitted, as have  
all the society's past atlases, because of the many disputed areas 
in the world. He said the society receives angry letters from 
people ``who want us to show the world as they think it should 
be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The society's policy is to show the world as it is, listing  
which country is in actual control of an area, even if that control 
is disputed by some other country, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	East Timor, for example, which recently voted for independence  
from Indonesia but has not yet become a recognized country, 
generated discussion, Carroll said. The atlas shows the island as 
part of Indonesia with a notation in red that, as of 1999, 
authorities were finalizing plans to give the island's eastern 
section political autonomy. 
</P>
<P>
	Areas generating the most letters, he said, are Cyprus, Taiwan,  
East Timor and Kashmir. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 12:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High-Ranking Soldier Faces Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army took a step Wednesday toward the  
possible court-martial of its most senior enlisted soldier in 
Europe, appointing an officer to hear evidence against Sgt. Maj. 
Riley C. Miller, who is accused of sexual assault and kidnapping. 
</P>
<P>
	The controversy -- the latest in a string of highly embarrassing  
sex cases in the U.S. military -- was disclosed last week when 
commanding Gen. Montgomery C. Meigs of U.S. Army Europe declared 
Miller unfit to continue in the post of command sergeant major 
representing the interests of all enlisted soldiers in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, a 30-year veteran, has been reassigned to other duties.  
Jim Boyle, a spokesman at U.S. Army Europe headquarters in 
Heidelberg, Germany, said neither Riley nor his attorney would 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, 51, is married. He served as an infantry platoon  
sergeant in Vietnam, where he received a campaign medal with three 
bronze stars. He also has a Legion of Merit and Defense Meritorious 
Service Medal. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations against him were made by an unidentified female  
soldier in Hanau, Germany, just outside Frankfurt, and stem from 
unspecified events of April 13 and 14. Following a preliminary 
investigation, the Army last Thursday announced that Miller faced 
charges of mistreating a subordinate, kidnapping, forcible sodomy, 
indecent assault and fraternization. At the same time, Meigs 
announced Miller was being reassigned. 
</P>
<P>
	In remarks to a reporter outside U.S. Army Europe headquarters  
in Heidelberg on Wednesday, Army Capt. Cleveland Murphy said 
military officials were setting a good example by investigating a 
high-ranking soldier like Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to give the man a fair shake,'' he said. ``If it's not  
true, we don't want to slander him. If it is true, the Army is 
going to go through its course and do the right thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement last week, Meigs said he had no opinion on the  
charges but had begun looking for a replacement for Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's announcement said Meigs had appointed a lieutenant  
colonel to hear the evidence against Miller as prescribed by 
Article 32 of the Uniform Code of Military Justice. An Article 32 
hearing is the rough equivalent of a grand jury proceeding in the 
civilian justice system. 
</P>
<P>
	No hearing date was announced.  
</P>
<P>
	After hearing the evidence, the lieutenant colonel in charge  
will recommend to Meigs whether to convene a court-martial. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, the Army took the highly unusual step of  
court-martialing David Hale, who had retired in March 1998 as a 
two-star general serving as the Army's deputy inspector general. 
Hale had been allowed to retire in the face of allegations that he 
had sex with the wives of four subordinates while serving as a NATO 
commander in southern Europe. The resulting furor led the Pentagon 
to change its rules to bar top officers from retiring while facing 
allegations of wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Gene C. McKinney, the sergeant major of the Army -- the  
service's highest-ranking enlisted position -- was accused by a 
former female public affairs aide of sexual harassment. Other women 
came forward with similar charges. In March 1998, a military court 
acquitted McKinney of most of the charges but convicted him on one 
count of obstructing justice. He was reprimanded and demoted. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army has disclosed few details of the case against Miller  
beyond the specific formal charges. It has said only that his 
accuser is a female soldier in Hanau and that the alleged 
misconduct occurred ``on or about April 13 and 14'' in Hanau. The 
Washington Post last Saturday quoted an unidentified senior 
military officer as saying the accuser was a sergeant who served as 
Miller's driver. 
</P>
<P>
	An Army spokesman at the Pentagon, Col. Edwin Veiga, said  
Wednesday he could not confirm the Post report. 
</P>
<P>
	Hanau is home to the Army's 104th Area Support Group, which  
provides medical, educational and other support to troops and their 
families. The 414th Base Support Battalion also is headquartered in 
Hanau. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
