<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Daly May Be Next Dodgers Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Dodgers on Thursday will name  
former Warner Bros. executive Bob Daly as chairman and chief 
executive officer. Daly also will purchase a minor stake in the 
club, a source close to the team told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers would only say a ``major executive appointment'' was  
planned for 10 a.m. PDT at the Staples Center. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the first moves Daly could make in his new position,  
according to the source who spoke on condition of anonymity, would 
be the rehiring of former Dodgers president and CEO Bob Graziano, 
who was fired last month. Graziano was at Daly's home on Wednesday, 
the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly, 62, will buy a stake in the team that amounts to about 10  
percent, sources told the Los Angeles Times. Once Daly takes over, 
the Fox Group will have no involvement in day-to-day operations, 
the newspaper reported in Thursday's editions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fox Group, a division of Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., bought  
the team from Peter O'Malley's family in March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Sources told the Times that the stake Daly is buying and the  
price are still being negotiated. Any purchase remains subject to 
approval by major league baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	The price will probably be at cost, which would make Daly's  
investment about $31 million, the Times reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly and Terry Semel quit as chairmen and co-chief executives of  
Warner Bros. and Warner Music Group in July. At the time, both men 
said they wanted to pursue new ventures, declining to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly grew up in the New York City borough of Brooklyn where he  
attended Dodgers games at Ebbets Field, developing a lifelong 
passion for the team before it moved to Los Angeles in 1958. He is 
a season ticket holder. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly tried to form a group to buy the team shortly after  
O'Malley put it up for sale, but he never made a bid. 
</P>
<P>
	He and Semel, who started with the studio 20 years ago, guided  
the film and television division and Warner Music Group to combined 
revenues of an estimated $10 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The duo's successful films include the ``Lethal Weapon'' and  
``Batman'' movies, ``The Killing Fields,'' ``Driving Miss Daisy'' 
and ``Unforgiven.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers have been underachievers since their sale to Fox.  
Last year, they finished 83-79 and in third place in the NL West. 
This year, as prohibitive favorites in the division with a $79.2 
million opening-day payroll -- second highest in the majors -- they 
wound up 77-85 and 23 games behind first-place Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Graziano, 41, was fired shortly before the end of the season.  
</P>
<P>
	He joined the Dodgers in January 1986, and became president and  
CEO when the Fox Group bought the team. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
