<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Durable Goods Orders Fall 1.3 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Slackening demand for cars and airplanes in  
September helped drive down overall orders for big-ticket 
manufactured goods by 1.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it was the first decline since April -- and worse than  
the 0.4 percent drop many analysts were expecting -- economists 
still believe manufacturers are recovering from the darkest days of 
the global financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Orders for all durable goods -- items expected to last at least  
three years -- declined last month to a seasonally adjusted $204.9 
billion, the Commerce Department said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists cautioned against reading too much into one month of  
data and said September's drop doesn't signal an end to the rebound 
manufacturers have been enjoying this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing to worry about in the manufacturing sector,''  
said Russell Sheldon, chief economist for MCM MoneyWatch. 
Manufacturing slowed moderately last month, but data so far this 
year ``point to a pretty healthy manufacturing sector,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of 1999, durable-goods orders are 7  
percent higher than the same period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve policy-makers meet Nov. 16 to decide whether to  
raise interest rates a third time this year to slow the economy and 
keep inflation under control. ``I don't think the report sways them 
one way or the other,'' said economist Clifford Waldman of Waldman 
Associates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 92.76 at 10,394.89 as  
a rally in the bond market carried over to stocks. Much of the 
rally came in the final hour of trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the Business Council, in its economic outlook  
released Wednesday, said chief executive officers of some of the 
nation's largest companies expect next year to bring a faster pace 
of global economic activity, slower U.S. economic growth and tame 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Business Council also said that most big companies expect no  
problems with domestic suppliers because of the Y2K computer bug, 
but many expect some disruptions because of overseas vendors. 
</P>
<P>
	The council, which was releasing the outlook at its fall meeting  
in Boca Raton, Fla., said its economic consultants saw less than a 
50 percent chance that the current expansion, already the longest 
in peacetime history, will dip into recession during the next two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	But they cited several possible causes for one, including rising  
U.S. interest rates, higher U.S. inflation and a stock market 
plunge, Citigroup Chairman Sanford I. Weill said in a report on the 
findings. 
</P>
<P>
	September's decrease in durable goods orders was led by a 3.9  
percent drop in orders for transportation equipment, also the first 
decline since April, reflecting weaker demand for airplanes and 
aircraft parts and automobiles and car parts. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were some spot shortages of the most popular models from  
American and offshore producers, so you're seeing some moderation 
in sales because inventory is down and selection is limited,'' said 
Paul Taylor, chief economist for the National Automobile Dealers 
Association. Showroom traffic was down too. Still, the auto 
industry expects a record 16.8 million cars and light trucks to be 
sold this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Transportation often is volatile from month to month because it  
includes such big-ticket purchases as airplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, orders rose 0.4 percent for both industrial machinery  
-- including computers and machine tools -- and electronic and other 
electrical equipment -- including semiconductors and home 
appliances. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding transportation, overall orders for durable goods fell  
0.5 percent, the first such decline since a 1.4 percent drop in 
May. 
</P>
<P>
	The global financial crisis has cut sharply into manufacturers'  
overseas sales and opened them up to stiffer competition from 
cheaper imports. 
</P>
<P>
	Primary metals, the category that includes steel, saw orders  
fall 0.8 percent in September. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipments of big-ticket durable goods, a good sign of current  
demand, also fell a sizable 1.9 percent in September, the first 
decrease since April. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
