<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clemens Proves Skeptics Wrong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Roger Clemens had spent his entire life waiting  
for this moment. 
</P>
<P>
	He couldn't win the big one, they said. Didn't have the heart,  
didn't have the guts. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen years after he first stepped on a major league field, he  
finally proved them wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	With a chance to make history, Clemens didn't just beat the  
Atlanta Braves, he smothered them, never gave them a chance. 
</P>
<P>
	On baseball's greatest stage, the mound of Yankee Stadium with  
the World Series title just one win away, he threw four-hit ball 
for 7 2-3 innings and led the Yankees to a 4-1 win Wednesday night 
that gave them their second straight Series sweep. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tonight, I kind of feel what it's like to be a Yankee for  
sure,'' Clemens said. 
</P>
<P>
	About a half-hour after the game, he returned to the field from  
the clubhouse and jumped on top of the Yankees' dugout, leaning 
into the front row of the stands to hug and high-five fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens came to New York in February, looking for a ring. Those  
five Cy Young Awards were nice -- more than enough for each kid in 
the family -- but he couldn't flash one on a finger and proclaim 
himself a winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he can. Here he was, bounding off the mound like a kid to  
field three comebackers. 
</P>
<P>
	He might not admit it, but he was juiced. He didn't allow a fly  
ball to an outfielder, didn't allow a runner past first base until 
the eighth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew he was going to do it,'' Series MVP Mariano Rivera  
said. ``This guy was pumped up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On his way to the mound, he stopped by Monument Park to give  
Babe Ruth's plaque a little pat. And then he gave a performance 
that would make Ruth proud. 
</P>
<P>
	Keith Lockhart in the fifth was the only batter to reach leading  
off an inning. He was quickly erased when Eddie Perez bounced into 
a double play. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens pumped his right fist, then pointed his right index  
finger, the one that has released so many fastballs, at second 
baseman Chuck Knoblauch as if to say, you can do it. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't allow another hit until the eighth, when Walt Weiss  
reached on an infield hit -- replays showed first base ump Gerry 
Davis blew the call, that Clemens had caught the ball and had his 
right foot on the bag before Weiss stepped on the foot. 
</P>
<P>
	The trainer came out, but Clemens stayed in, allowing a clean  
single to Gerald Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	That was it, with manager Joe Torre deciding Clemens should call  
it a night, even though players on the Yankees bench seemed to want 
Clemens to stay in. 
</P>
<P>
	Slowly off the mound, Clemens walked. He waved his cap to the  
crowd, then waved his right hand. Teammates hugged him as he made 
his way down the dugout, then walked into the runway and back to 
the clubhouse as Jeff Nelson allowed a single to Bret Boone that 
drove in Atlanta's lone run. 
</P>
<P>
	The fans had stood and cheered, those same fans who spent the  
season questioning the decision to acquire him from Toronto for Mr. 
Perfect, David Wells. 
</P>
<P>
	He had brought so much baggage with him to New York, including  
the hatred of Boston fans who felt he turned traitor when he left 
the Red Sox after the 1996 season to sign with Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	After pitching seven shutout innings against the Rangers in the  
first round, he was bombed in Boston, didn't get out of the third 
inning. The Fenway fans said that was the real Clemens, the one 
with the 2-3 postseason record, not the one who went 247-134 during 
the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	Forget that, Clemens said Wednesday night. This is me.  
</P>
<P>
	He came to New York for his ring, and he got it, did it on his  
own. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel very blessed to be a part of the team,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	His career may not be complete, but his mission is.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
