<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 12:00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Tolerates Dishonesty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- About cheating, stealing and lying, most parents  
know exactly what to teach their kids. But when it comes to 
dishonesty in baseball, it's not always an easy call. 
</P>
<P>
	The truth is, the national pastime not only tolerates  
untruthfulness, it often rewards it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have never seen an instance when a player's had a call go  
his way when he knew it was wrong and he's fessed up,'' says Ken 
Burns, maker of the acclaimed, nine-part PBS documentary on 
baseball. ``If it's to your team's advantage, you don't say 
anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Simone Mordas, a mother of five who coaches children's  
baseball, soccer and ice hockey, was confronted with the ethical 
dilemma as her young sons stayed up late this month watching the 
Boston Red Sox unsuccessfully battle the New York Yankees for the 
American League title. 
</P>
<P>
	Blown calls by umpires in the first and fourth games of the  
series went against the Red Sox, and the umpires later admitted 
they were mistaken. But the beneficiary of the mistakes -- Yankees 
second baseman Chuck Knoblauch -- kept quiet, later saying he hadn't 
known the calls were bad. 
</P>
<P>
	And if he had? It wouldn't have mattered. Umpires, and not  
players, are responsible for making the call. Unlike, say, golf, 
baseball does not work on the honor system. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard -- you feel conflicted,'' says Ms. Mordas, 34, of  
Wayland. ``You tell your kids to be honest, and the players aren't 
always.'' At the same time, ``I try to teach (the children) you 
can't question the referees or umpires.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The phenomenon can be confusing for young fans, says Richard  
Lapchick, director of Northeastern University's Center for the 
Study of Sport in Society. ``I think the implication for children 
is you're telling them it's OK to not do something honest -- if you 
can get away with it,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	There's also the ``what goes around comes around'' rationale:  
For every erroneous call that goes a player's way, there's probably 
at least one that has gone against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Benefiting from a blown call in baseball is not considered a  
dishonest or dirty victory. In fact, Burns says, ``That would be a 
point of pride.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to say I'd feel guilty'' about benefiting from an  
umpire's mistake, says Red Sox star Nomar Garciaparra. ``(Baseball) 
can't work with an honor system. Tell me any sport that can work 
with an honor system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the idea that you should get away with whatever you can  
carries over into sports like hockey, basketball and football. 
Honesty may be the best policy, but even Michael Jordan didn't call 
fouls on himself. 
</P>
<P>
	In golf, however, professionals for a century have penalized  
themselves for infractions unseen by their opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	Midway through the Greater Hartford Open in 1996, Greg Norman  
learned the ball he used the first two rounds was not properly 
labeled. Despite being five strokes off the lead, the defending 
champion turned himself in and was disqualified. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, two-time U.S. Open tennis champion Patrick Rafter  
stunned the crowd and his opponent, Andrei Cherkasov, during a 
second-set tiebreaker at a tournament in Australia. Rafter -- 
already down a set -- overturned a call that was in his favor. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `No, no, the linesman is wrong. It's your point,'''  
recalls ATP spokesman Joe Lynch. Rafter went on to lose the next 
point and the match. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, incidents like that are rare, even in the so-called  
country club sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a sense of fairness and a sense of decency which no  
longer exists,'' says retired tennis player Ted Schroeder, who won 
Wimbledon in 1949 and the U.S. Open in 1942. 
</P>
<P>
	With the World Series under way this week, parents may want to  
explain that baseball -- like life -- has its share of hard work, 
victory, loss and, yes, tough breaks, Burns says. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember playing ball and having a call go my way when I was  
clearly out and going, `Great!''' he says. ``Sometimes they go 
against you, sometimes with you, and that's just the way it is. 
There's human fallibility built into every aspect of the game, and 
that's a glorious thing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
