<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Oct. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Two Hostages in Armenia Released  
</P>
<P>
	YEREVAN, Armenia (AP) -- At least two of the captives being held  
in Armenia's parliament were released early Thursday, nearly 10 
hours after gunmen killed Prime Minister Vazgen Sarkisian and at 
least six other people before holing up in the building with dozens 
of hostages. The attackers demanded to see the president. ``This 
shake-up is needed for the nation to regain its senses,'' said a 
man identified as the gunmen's leader, Nairi Unanian. He said the 
deaths were unintended except for Sarkisian, who he claimed had 
failed to serve the nation. 

</P>
<P>
	News of Surplus Sparks Budget Fight  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States posted a record $123 billion  
federal budget surplus last year, marking the first back-to-back 
surpluses since Dwight Eisenhower was president. The announcement -- 
exceeding all estimates -- sparked a battle for bragging rights 
today between the White House and the Republican-led Congress, with 
both sides hoping to reap political dividends in next year's 
elections. President Clinyon, battling Republicans over spending, 
accused the GOP of writing a budget that siphons $18 billion from 
the Social Security surplus. Republicans also claimed credit for 
the surplus. 

</P>
<P>
	Ventura Says `No' to 2000 Question  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Gov. Jesse Ventura tried again today to clear  
up questions about his presidential ambitions by issuing a 
resounding ``no.'' A day earlier, the Reform Party governor had 
told Harvard Current magazine that he would consider running if 
Minnesotans mobilized behind him. But Ventura acknowledged his 
long-standing policy of never saying never to anything, and blamed 
the media for contorting his comments to make something out of 
them. ``Certainly, I don't know if tomorrow, anything can happen 
tomorrow. But I tell you no means no,'' Ventura said. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore, Bradley To Debate in N.H.  
</P>
<P>
	HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- Al Gore and Bill Bradley will hold their  
first debate of the Democratic presidential campaign tonight. The 
stakes were highest for the vice president, who has watched a 
commanding lead in polls dwindle in the face of Bradley's 
surprisingly strong campaign. The former New Jersey senator is 
rated even or slightly ahead in New Hampshire, where the nation's 
first primary is scheduled for Feb. 1. Audience members will 
furnish the questions in tonight's 60-minute televised forum. 

</P>
<P>
	Houston Is Smoggiest City in U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Houston has moved past Los Angeles to become the  
smoggiest city in America. Houston and Los Angeles were running 
neck-and-neck in air pollution stakes until Oct. 7, when the 
nation's fourth-largest city surpassed the second-largest by 
recording its 44th smog day of the year. Texas is staring at an EPA 
deadline next month to come up with a plan to clean its skies by 
2007. The government has threatened to take away money for Texas 
highway construction if the state doesn't start making progress 
soon. 

</P>
<P>
	FDA Approves New Flu Pill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Flu sufferers won their first effective pill  
against both types A and B flu today, as the Food and Drug 
Administration approved Tamiflu. The pill, manufactured by Hoffman 
La-Roche, helped reduce the duration and severity of flu symptoms 
in unvaccinated adults who agreed to be infected to test the drug. 
The decision means flu sufferers this year have two new treatment 
choices. The FDA earlier approved an inhaled flu drug called 
Relenza that also works against both A and B flu. 

</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com Results Top Estimates  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Amazon.com's losses widened in the third quarter  
as the giant Internet retailer significantly boosted its spending 
to expand its online offerings. The steep losses were less than 
analysts were expecting. Amazon.com's sales grew by 132 percent 
from the year-ago period and its customer base climbed by 2.4 
million to 13.1 million. Amazon.com lost $197 million in the three 
months ended Sept. 30. Sales in the quarter rose to $355.8 million, 
up from $153.7 million a year ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Mixed; Dow Up 92.76  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A bond rally today carried over to stocks,  
lifting financial shares. The Dow Jones industrial average ended 
92.76 higher at 10,394.89. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 
1,735-1,310. The Nasdaq fell 8.95 to 2,802.52. 

</P>
<P>
	Spinal Condition Threatens Irvin  
</P>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Tests for the herniated disc the Dallas  
Cowboys wide receiver Michael Irvin sustained earlier this month 
have uncovered a narrow spinal cord, a genetic condition that 
increases risk of serious injury if he takes another blow to the 
head or neck. In 1986, Green Bay cornerback Tim Lewis and Houston 
Oilers linebacker Frank Bush learned they had the same genetic 
condition. Both retired. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  



  	   	
</P>
