<HEADLINE> Kofi Annan Offers Help in NBC Flap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- After throwing out the first ball at the  
World Series, Secretary-General Kofi Annan jokingly offered his 
peacemaking skills Wednesday in the dispute between the New York 
Yankees and NBC over Pete Rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Annan, who threw out the first ball at Yankee Stadium Tuesday  
night, wouldn't comment on his pitching prowess, saying, ``What I 
think is more important is the performance of the teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Annan was asked about ``a bit of a diplomatic controversy''  
sparked by NBC reporter Jim Gray asking former Cincinnati Reds star 
Pete Rose some tough questions. Gray's interview angered the 
Yankees and led to a team boycott of the reporter following the 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	Did Annan think a little diplomacy was needed?  
</P>
<P>
	Chuckling, the secretary-general replied, ``If they need a bit  
of peacemaking, this is what we are here for. I will give them 
whatever help we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NBC was deluged by complaints from fans Sunday night after  
Gray's interview with Rose at Turner Field in Atlanta. It centered 
on Rose's lifetime ban from the sport for gambling, and came 
minutes after he returned to a major league field for the first 
time in 10 years as a member of baseball's All-Century team. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
