<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Starts Debate on His Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- Al Gore staged a bit of political theater  
reminiscent of Ronald Reagan in 1980, seizing the initiative -- if 
not the microphone -- to begin debating rival Bill Bradley 15 
minutes before the debate officially began. 
</P>
<P>
	``What do we do now?'' the vice president asked Wednesday night  
after he and the former New Jersey senator were introduced to the 
in-studio audience. It was an awkward period before airtime -- the 
candidates were fidgeting on their stools -- and Gore knew exactly 
what he wanted to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why don't you start asking some questions while we're  
waiting?'' he told the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	They did as he suggested. And the debate began on Gore's terms,  
just as he had planned. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a tactic borrowed from former President Reagan, who broke  
the format in a 1980 debate and, when a moderator threatened to 
turn off his microphone, shot back: ``I paid for this microphone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reagan looked strong and in charge.  
</P>
<P>
	Advisers said Gore's strategy was to solicit questions from the  
get-go. It is part of what they hope is a new-and-improved 
candidate, one eager to answer every question, shake every hand and 
solicit every vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's trying very hard to connect with voters,'' said  
Vanderbilt University political science professor Erwin Hargrove. 
``Notice that he was asking people for their names, how many kids 
they have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like a fighter throwing the first punch before the opening bell,  
Gore never let up -- raising questions about Bradley's education, 
health care and spending plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``The numbers have to add up,'' said the vice president.  
</P>
<P>
	``The cost is way excessive.''  
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to shred the safety net'' that protects the poor.  
</P>
<P>
	Bradley calmly rebutted Gore and passed up chance after chance  
to lash out. ``I'm not going to get into the details at this point 
of the game,'' he said after being served a softball-sized chance 
to criticize Clinton-Gore fund-raising excesses in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley made sweeping promises filled with vision and few  
specifics, saying it was time to reduce poverty, reform campaign 
finance laws and provide affordable health insurance to almost 
every American. 
</P>
<P>
	While Gore all but begged for votes -- ``give me a chance to roll  
up my sleeves'' -- a typically understated Bradley said, ``If you 
agree, then you'll vote for me. I hope you do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first head-to-head encounter of their presidential campaign  
underscored the differences in styles. Gore was combative and 
coached, trying hard to look more homespun and drive down Bradley's 
rising poll numbers. The former New Jersey senator said voters are 
tired of political sniping and slick campaigning, so he avoided 
direct criticism and worked hard not to look like he's working 
hard. 
</P>
<P>
	``It thought Gore was as good as I've ever seen him,'' said  
Democratic consultant Jim Duffy. ``He was trying desperately to 
look like a guy who is a friend, look like a guy who is 
intelligent, look like a guy who is compassionate. And yet, he 
pressed Bradley.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duffy, who is not tied to either campaign, said Bradley came  
across as a soft-spoken, nontraditional candidate ``in an era where 
that might be very welcome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Bradley talked about big ideas and handled them well,''  
Hargrove said. ``Gore seemed over eager at times -- kind of 
frantic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Time will tell whether voters welcome the change or not. ``I  
wonder if people will see him in this format and forget about his 
ties to President Clinton. It's possible,'' Hargrove said. ``It's 
nice to see him try.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And try. And try.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to stick around,'' Gore said, as the television  
lights dimmed, ``and answer some more questions.'' Which he did, 
for 90 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Ron Fournier is chief political reporter for The  
Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
