<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Houston Tops L.A. As Smog Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *By MEGAN K. STACK    	
</P>
<P>
                      *Associated Press Writer    	
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- It was probably just a chemical belch at a  
factory on the edge of town. But it was enough to push Houston past 
Los Angeles to become the smoggiest city in America. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston and Los Angeles were running neck-and-neck in air  
pollution stakes until Oct. 7, when the nation's fourth-largest 
city surpassed the second-largest by recording its 44th smog day of 
the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The day that will live in infamy,'' Houston Health Department  
spokeswoman Kathy Barton said. ``Really.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As of Wednesday, the Houston count had reached 46. Los Angeles  
was still at 43. A smog day is when the ozone level rises above a 
certain mark set by the Environmental Protection Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Exactly what caused the smog remains a mystery.  
</P>
<P>
	Researchers know that large clouds of ethylene and propylene  
billowed over the city Oct. 7, and believe the gases were the 
product of one of the industrial plants on the edge of town. But 
they don't know which one. 
</P>
<P>
	The search has been narrowed down to 25 factories, all clustered  
around the Houston Ship Channel, home of the nation's largest 
concentration of petrochemical plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles has had smoggy air for decades and has long been the  
butt of jokes about it. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers said unusually dry weather played a part in trapping  
dirty air over Houston, and Los Angeles may very well reclaim the 
title. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll probably pass it back and forth with each other for a  
few more years,'' said Gene McMullen, who has been monitoring 
pollution levels for the Health Department in Houston for decades. 
``It'll depend on whose weather is worse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas is staring at an EPA deadline next month to come up with a  
plan to clean its skies by 2007. The government has threatened to 
take away money for Texas highway construction if the state doesn't 
start making progress soon. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0389 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 13:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Overhaul Bill Defended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Top administration officials on Wednesday  
defended sweeping legislation to overhaul the financial services 
industries but failed to win over liberal Democrats in the House 
who assail the bill as a threat to consumers' privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would lift Depression-era barriers and allow banks,  
securities firms and insurance companies to merge. It appears 
headed toward enactment by the Republican-controlled Congress and a 
likely signature by President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	It has vocal opponents who are disturbed by provisions that  
would allow affiliated businesses of the newly merged companies to 
share customers' personal financial data as they offer one-stop 
shopping for loans, insurance and investments. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and Clinton's top economic  
adviser, Gene Sperling, met with the Democrats in the House as 
several prominent liberals among them called on Clinton to veto the 
legislation. Many moderate House Democrats support it, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure there will be a divided vote'' among Democrats,  
Summers said after the closed-door meeting on Capitol Hill. But he 
insisted that the legislation would protect consumers' financial 
privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``This hard-fought compromise ... represents a very significant  
step forward for the American economy and for American consumers,'' 
Summers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks would not be allowed to provide customers' data to  
telemarketers under the new legislation, but would be able to share 
it with affiliated financial companies under the same corporate 
roof. 
</P>
<P>
	With the White House having lifted its long-standing veto threat  
and now supporting it, the financial overhaul measure is being 
given the best chance ever of adoption after 20 years of 
congressional battles and intense lobbying by the financial 
industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Edward Markey of Massachusetts, a leader in the fight for  
liberal House Democrats on the privacy issue, said after 
Wednesday's meeting he was not persuaded by the administration's 
defense of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no protection'' for consumers, he said. ``Their  
privacy is now for sale.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House Democrats' leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., told The  
Associated Press he has yet to decide whether he would endorse the 
legislation. Gephardt voted for a similar financial overhaul 
measure when it passed the House with a veto-proof vote, 343-86, in 
early July. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer activists, who have complained bitterly about the  
privacy impact of the legislation, continued their criticism. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it's a crying shame that the secretary of the  
Treasury is a cheerleader now for Wall Street,'' said Frank Torres, 
legislative counsel for Consumers Union. ``This bill isn't about 
helping consumers, it's about giving the industry what it wants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Markey, Rep. John Dingell of Michigan, senior Democrat on the  
House Commerce Committee, and Reps. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., and Bill 
Luther, D-Minn., on Tuesday started circulating a letter among 
colleagues that urges Clinton to veto the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Privacy is a pivotal issue in the transformation of the  
financial services industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Data sharing is a major reason why financial companies want to  
merge, as it opens numerous opportunities for the companies to 
market a range of products and services. Proponents of the 
legislation maintain it will save American consumers billions of 
dollars a year by providing them more financial choices. 
</P>
<P>
	Many consumers are alarmed, however, at the prospect that their  
personal financial data could be shared and sold by companies. 
</P>
<P>
	A broad coalition of consumer groups, privacy advocates, the  
American Civil Liberties Union and Phyllis Schlafly's conservative 
Eagle Forum sent its own letter to Clinton on Tuesday urging his 
veto. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, conservative Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., has  
broken with Banking Committee Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, over 
the privacy issue and said he would vote against the bill. Shelby 
served notice on Monday that he will try to force changes in the 
privacy provisions and failing that, attempt to derail the measure. 
Under Senate rules, a single senator can hold up action for hours 
or days if he chooses to. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0390 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 15:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Visits Crisis Pregnancy Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBUQUE, Iowa (AP) -- Touring a crisis pregnancy center  
Wednesday, Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush touted 
``the beauty of adoption'' but said he wasn't prepared to offer 
direct federal help to churches that finance such programs. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bush, the Texas governor, said he saw no conflict with  
taxpayer support for programs to which women are referred from the 
3,000 such centers nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of my job, should I become president, is to herald the  
beauty and love of adoptions and to recognize that in centers like 
this women find loving alternatives,'' Bush said at the Tri-State 
Pregnancy Center in blue-collar, heavily Catholic Dubuque -- the 
heart of the state's anti-abortion movement. Financed by local 
churches, the center counsels women who have had abortions as well 
as those who continue their pregnancies. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second straight day that Bush has focused on reducing  
the number of problem pregnancies. On Tuesday, he urged high school 
students to practice abstinence. 
</P>
<P>
	``These events show where my heart is,'' Bush said when  
reporters asked what signal he was trying to send. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said that, if elected, he would use the power of the White  
House to bring attention to such centers, but offered no specific 
programs to help finance them. 
</P>
<P>
	He ruled out any backing for churches that ban together to  
support such centers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we ought to fund the programs or individuals who are  
trying to help, not the church from which the program draws its 
strength,'' said Bush. ``That would step over the separation of 
church and state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's focus is aimed squarely at social conservatives in the  
party who are leery of his commitment to oppose abortion. Bush 
insisted Wednesday that he's ``strongly pro-life'' but has said the 
nation isn't ready for a constitutional amendment banning abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	He also says he would refuse to apply litmus tests in appointing  
only judges who oppose abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	In touring the crisis center, Bush said he was focusing on  
pragmatic ways to reduce the number of abortions, including 
adoption. He pointed to Texas laws making it easier to place 
children for adoption as a model he would follow if elected. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our society must recognize the beauty of adoption,'' Bush  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush did say his position on supporting such crisis centers was  
evolving. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an amazing accomplishment,'' said Bush. ``I don't have  
a specific role in mind yet, but I'm willing to listen to ideas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Bush is the solid front-runner in the race for Iowa's  
leadoff precinct caucuses, he is being challenged by rivals making 
a strong appeal to the GOP's social and religious conservatives. 
Best financed among those is publisher Steve Forbes, who routinely 
attacks Bush for not taking a tougher stand against abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	Those conservatives complain that Bush doesn't really support a  
constitutional amendment banning abortion, but Bush argued that 
distorts his position. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would support one, I recognize America is not prepared to  
pass one,'' said Bush. ``America will be ready when we value 
life.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0391 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 14:40:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Losing Getting to Lou Holtz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Lou Holtz studies the Bible. Bill Parcells  
gets fed up. Joe Paterno calls friends and colleagues asking, 
``Why?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Losing gets to everyone, even coaches whose offices are lined  
with national championship plaques and filled with Super Bowl 
trophies. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter how much you win, no matter how well things have  
gone for you, they're not going well now, so I'm miserable,'' said 
Parcells, whose New York Jets fell short of going to last year's 
Super Bowl by one bad half but are 1-6 this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Holtz knows the feeling. His best-selling book is titled,  
``Winning Every Day.'' His office is filled with pictures and 
slogans -- among them a bumper sticker that says, ``How do you spell 
relief? H-O-L-T-Z'' -- testifying to his winning legacy at five 
previous schools the past 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	But none of that has stopped South Carolina's free fall this  
season. The Gamecocks are 0-8, their losing streak the country's 
longest at 18. 
</P>
<P>
	So after the playbooks are put away and the practice tapes  
rewound, Holtz looks for comfort in the Bible. And he can't help 
but compare himself at times to Job, a farmer who saw his life 
overturned to test his faith. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't get up and say I hurt, I'm in pain. That's not my  
job,'' he said. But ``I've never been through anything as painful 
as this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paterno has won 315 games and two national titles at Penn State  
and earned the respect of the sports world. But if his Nittany 
Lions falter -- as they did in 1988 going 5-6 or 1992 at 7-5 -- the 
72-year-old Paterno is first to pick apart his style. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you're always questioning your methods,'' he said.  
``When you're losing, I talk to friends, other coaches to see what 
they have to say. That doesn't mean you change things or lose your 
confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Dorsal, a sport psychologist at Francis Marion University in  
South Carolina, said successful coaches question themselves quicker 
if proven plans fail, but they usually stick with those plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``The theory's called anchoring,'' Dorsal said. ``If you've got  
some success experience and can learn to tap into it, it may pull 
you through difficult times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holtz and others who are used to tremendous winning face two  
choices in defeats, Dorsal said, ``get depressed about it or stay 
positive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A depressed person tends to internalize problems and blame  
themselves, see problems as stable or permanent and think those 
problems apply to everything they do, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``From what I see, (Holtz) hasn't done any of that so far,''  
said Dorsal, a Notre Dame graduate who has followed the coach's 
career. ``He has stayed positive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holtz has changed his tactics, his running backs and his  
quarterbacks. He has clapped and cried, cajoled and coddled. 
</P>
<P>
	It has not helped that his wife of 38 years, Beth, whom he  
credits for bringing new enthusiasm to his life, is in Orlando, 
Fla., recuperating from major surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	``You wonder how in the world can everything be going wrong,''  
Holtz said. 
</P>
<P>
	He once lost seven straight games during his first two years at  
William &AMP; Mary, but he still took the Tribe to a bowl game in his 
second year there. 
</P>
<P>
	Holtz opened 1-4 his first season at Notre Dame in 1986 and a  
year later lost his final three games with the Fighting Irish. 
</P>
<P>
	``What it did at that time, it caused you to sit down and  
evaluate and think about the future and where you're going and how 
you're going to get there,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The next season, Holtz went undefeated and won the national  
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Holtz's son and offensive coordinator, Skip, says his father  
becomes more driven when he loses. Skip says the Gamecocks, who 
have used six quarterbacks and 15 offensive linemen this year, have 
not had time to mature with his dad's system. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing I admire the most about him as a coach and as a  
father is the standards he holds everyone to, including himself,'' 
Skip said. 
</P>
<P>
	So Holtz draws on his past to reshape the Gamecocks' future.  
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever doesn't kill you makes you stronger,'' he says.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
