<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Entertainment highlights during the week of Oct. 31-Nov. 6:  
</P>
<P>
	60 years ago: James Cagney's new contract with Warner Bros.  
raised his salary from $5,000 to $12,500 per week, but he did not 
get the script approval he demanded. 
</P>
<P>
	30 years ago: ``Suspicious Minds'' was Elvis Presley's first No.  
1 hit on the U.S. singles chart in seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	25 years ago: Elton John released his ``Greatest Hits'' album.  
</P>
<P>
	And George Harrison was the first Beatle to go on a solo world  
tour. The 30-date North American tour was to promote his ``Dark 
Horse'' album. 
</P>
<P>
	20 years ago: The movie version of the Who's ``Quadrophenia''  
was released. Sting made his acting debut in the film. 
</P>
<P>
	And Bob Dylan performed in San Francisco. It was the first city  
on a national tour to promote his religious album, ``Slow Train 
Coming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	15 years ago: Sam Waterston, Haing S. Ngor and John Malkovich  
starred in ``The Killing Fields.'' Ngor won a best supporting actor 
Oscar for his acting debut. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: Bruce Springsteen's ``Born in the U.S.A.'' was  
tied as the second biggest-selling LP in the country. The Recording 
Industry Association of America said the 1984 album had reached 14 
million in domestic sales, joining Fleetwood Mac's ``Rumours'' as 
runner-up to Michael Jackson's ``Thriller,'' which had sold 24 
million copies. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken five years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``My face and neck -- I guess from the stress of everything that  
had been going on -- broke out in a really bad way. In a rash. It's 
never happened to me before. The doctor asked me, `Are you under 
any stress?''' -- Jimmy Smits, on his new ``NYPD Blue'' role. 

</P>
<P>
	``People are still trying to figure out what the words are to  
some of those songs. I hate to break it to them, but ... it's just 
utter nonsense, it's sounds, and it doesn't make sense sometimes, 
and it doesn't have to.'' -- Michael Stipe of R.E.M., referring to 
the band's earlier albums. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken one year ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``I see people all the time who are better rappers than me,  
better actors than me, better-looking and stronger than me. But my 
ace in the hole is my dangerously obsessive drive, you know? I'm a 
terminator. I absolutely, positively will not stop until I win.'' -- 
Actor-rapper Will Smith. 

</P>
<P>
	``I thought that fame and success would solve your problems,  
that there would be a sense of peace or self-esteem raised by 
having all this external success. So the question became, `If not 
this, then what can make me feel connected?''' -- Alanis Morissette, 
explaining that she battled depression after her album ``Jagged 
Little Pill'' became a hit. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
