<HEADLINE> Tokyo Share Prices Fall Sharply / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices fell sharply today with  
investors discouraged by the dollar's weakening against the yen and 
an overnight decline on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 289.43 points,  
or 1.64 percent, to end the day at 17,382.36 points. On Tuesday, 
the average closed up 23.00 points, or 0.13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 104.32 yen at 5 p.m. (5 a.m. EDT), down 0.82  
yen from late Tuesday and also below its late New York level of 
104.69 yen overnight. During the day, it ranged from 103.71 yen to 
104.90 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In stock trading, prices started lower following Tuesday's  
moderate decline in New York, where the Dow Jones industrial 
average lost 47.80 points, or 0.5 percent, to 10,302.13. That fall 
came on worries about rising U.S. inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline in Tokyo was led by sharp drops in export oriented  
issues, including high technology shares and bank shares. Exporters 
are particularly vulnerable to the stronger yen, as it can reduce 
dollar denominated earnings of Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many players kept to the sidelines to monitor dollar yen  
movements,'' said Hiroichi Nishi, deputy general manager at Nikko 
Securities Co. Nishi said that some were also awaiting U.S. gross 
domestic product data expected Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 19.71 points, or 1.28 percent, to finish at 
1,523.38. The TOPIX closed up 8.82 points, or 0.57 percent, the 
previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section was estimated at 506 million shares,  
down from 598.02 million shares Tuesday. Retreating issues 
outnumbered advancers 834 to 377, while 130 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar fell against the yen amid hopes  
of a larger than expected Japanese supplementary budget, which will 
be submitted in the upcoming session of Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Total spending is expected to be between 10 trillion yen and 13  
trillion yen ($95 billion and $124 billion). 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Duke, foreign-exchange strategist at Citibank in Tokyo,  
said the dollar could dip even lower, toward 101 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government is getting more bang for each yen spent because  
the entire economic backdrop is more favorable now,'' Duke said. 
</P>
<P>
	The market shrugged off apprehension about the outcome of a Bank  
of Japan policy meeting today. Players seem to have decided that 
the central bank will not step in to stem the yen's further rise 
and that economic factors generally support a stronger yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 110.69 yen, down  
from 111.80 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.8300 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.8850 percent. Its 
price rose 0.46 point to 99.74. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
