<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tony Banks Gets Chance With Ravens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OWINGS MILLS, Md. (AP) -- Tony Banks received no guarantees upon  
joining the Baltimore Ravens in April, yet he fully expected to be 
the starting quarterback in the season opener. 
</P>
<P>
	And why not? Banks was a starter in high school, junior college  
and at Michigan State before getting 43 starts in three seasons 
with the St. Louis Rams. 
</P>
<P>
	Imagine his surprise when he began his first year in Baltimore  
as the No. 3 quarterback behind Scott Mitchell and Stoney Case. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a new experience for me, something I didn't expect,''  
he said Wednesday. ``I struggled with it for a while, feeling sorry 
for myself. Every sport I played, I never sat. But I found strength 
I never knew I had and was able to get through it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His patience was rewarded this week when Ravens coach Brian  
Billick made Banks his starter in Sunday's game against the Buffalo 
Bills. Banks plans to succeed where Mitchell and Case failed. 
</P>
<P>
	``My receivers have a lot of confidence in my ability to throw  
the ball down the field and in tight spots,'' Banks said. ``I'm not 
saying Stoney and Scott weren't able to do that, but I think with 
the reps I've taken in practice I've showed my receivers I'm 
capable of doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Banks proved that in St. Louis, where he had three 300-yard  
games and threw 36 touchdown passes. He puts plenty of zip on the 
ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can throw the 18-yard outs on a rope,'' wide receiver  
Justin Armour said. ``I was in Denver last year during John Elway's 
last season, and both he and Tony have similar range.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Billick has coached several talented quarterbacks, and he likes  
what he sees in Banks. With Banks it never was a question of 
talent, but rather a matter of him adjusting to his new role as a 
backup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tony hadn't been in that position before,'' Billick said.  
``You have to learn the game plan even when you don't get the reps 
in practice. It was process he had to get used to, and he got 
better at it every week. But Stoney understood that role almost 
immediately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's why Case got the call when Mitchell faltered in the  
second game of the season, even though Banks had 42 more career 
starts in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks threw seven touchdown passes as a rookie, 14 in his second  
season and 15 last year. He also had 554 yards rushing in those 
three years. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I like about Tony is what everybody has liked about him  
since he came out of college,'' Billick said. ``He's big, he's 
physical, a good athlete and has an extremely strong arm. Like a 
lot of strong-armed quarterbacks, he has to learn to temper his 
throws from one pass to the next.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Banks' other problem is holding onto the football. He fumbled 21  
times as a rookie, 15 times in 1997 and 10 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Early in my career that was a problem, holding onto the too  
long,'' Banks said. ``But if you look at the numbers last year, out 
of the games I started, I didn't have many fumbles. I think I've 
corrected that. It's a matter of better technique and getting rid 
of the football.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
