<DOCNO> APW19991027.0404 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 22:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Shows Off New Campaign Style </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- Al Gore couldn't claim to have paid for the  
microphone at his debate with Bill Bradley, but he took it over 
anyhow to get the first word and the last, determined to upstage 
his Democratic rival and put his new-look campaign style on 
televised display. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley debated by the rules, stuck to his message, and defended  
his proposals, particularly a health insurance expansion plan, 
against Gore's charges that it would spend away the next decade's 
budget surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	``I dispute the cost figure that Al has used,'' Bradley  
countered. That was as vehement as he got. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore quipped, chatted with questioners, told a joke -- obviously  
bent on erasing the image of the stiff and wooden vice president 
and creating one of a friendly, freewheeling candidate. He said 
later he'd been liberated, in part when the formidable challenge 
Bradley is waging forced him to re-examine his whole campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The impact of Wednesday night's debate -- actually a question and  
answer session in which the candidates took turns -- wasn't clear 
despite the rival claims of victory posted afterward by their 
cheerleaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley's spokesman said he came across as presidential.  
</P>
<P>
	The Gore campaign flew in three Cabinet members to praise his  
performance. ``I think people saw the real Al Gore, the man I know 
in private,'' said Energy Secretary Bill Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, a Gore supporter, had said  
the debate probably wouldn't change many minds, especially this far 
in advance of the state's Feb. 1 presidential primary. Gore has 
said he's probably behind; the polls indicate Bradley has gained 
strength to pull even or marginally ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	So Bradley stuck to his game plan, steady, not confrontational.  
Gore was the candidate out to change things. 
</P>
<P>
	He started before the debate did, as soon as the two men entered  
the Dartmouth College theater to be introduced to the audience of 
500 people chosen by lottery. It was 15 minutes to air time on CNN 
and WMUR of Manchester. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now what?'' the vice president said, and took over. ``Why  
don't you start asking some questions while we're waiting?'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a ploy reminiscent of the 1980 Republican debate in  
Nashua, N.H., and Ronald Reagan's retort when the moderator 
threatened to shut off his microphone for breaking the format. The 
Reagan campaign had hired the hall. 
</P>
<P>
	``I paid for this microphone, Mr. Green,'' Reagan snapped,  
taking charge and mispronouncing the moderator's name. Rival George 
Bush sat by in silence, although he could have had the audience to 
himself while Reagan was off stage, haggling about the rules. They 
finally debated, but Bush had lost before he began, outmaneuvered 
in what he later described as the low point of his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Now it was Gore taking center stage in a lull.  
</P>
<P>
	First question: How could a new Democratic president work with  
Congress. ``Build personal bridges,'' Gore concluded. Then he 
played moderator. ``Bill,'' he invited, and Bradley answered the 
question. ``It's a matter of reaching out to people,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three more questions before the cameras went on.  
</P>
<P>
	Then the hourlong forum, in which Gore and Bradley disagreed  
most directly on how to expand health care, and at what cost. On 
most of the agenda, they differed only on details. Gore even 
praised Bradley as eloquent in urging equal rights for gays. 
</P>
<P>
	One recurrent question was campaign finance reform. Both  
candidates said they'd work to achieve it. Bradley passed up an 
opportunity to criticize the White House for illicit campaign 
contributions taken by the Democrats for the 1996 campaign. ``I'm 
not going to get into the details at this point of the game,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, in contrast, volunteered criticism of President Clinton  
for his conduct in the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal. He was asked 
what he would do to restore confidence in the American political 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	He answered:  
</P>
<P>
	``I understand the disappointment and anger that you feel toward  
President Clinton and I felt it myself.'' At the time, Gore said, 
he felt it his duty to try to strive for continuity and stability. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore got the final debate question, about overcoming cynicism.  
``That's one reason why I'd like to have a debate every week on a 
different issue,'' he said, repeating the challenge Bradley has 
declined. Bradley has agreed to seven debates this year and early 
next year, but Gore insists that isn't enough. They meet next on 
Dec. 17. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gore also had a postscript invitation. He said he'd stick  
around to answer more questions as long as anybody wanted to ask 
them. Bradley shook hands on the way out. Gore stayed, for an hour 
and a half, until the last questioner. He said it fit the open 
meeting style he's adopted, prompted by the tightening race. 
</P>
<P>
	``And it feels liberating,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
