<DOCNO> APW19991027.0405 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 09:20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Something Familiar on Morning TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When CBS launches ``The Early Show'' Monday from  
a studio overlooking Central Park, network television's three-way 
battle for the morning news audience begins in earnest. 
</P>
<P>
	Early risers may have their own show in mind: The Attack of the  
Morning Clones. 
</P>
<P>
	The breakfast-hour competitors -- ``Today'' on NBC, ``Good  
Morning America'' on ABC, and ``The Early Show'' -- are eerily 
similar, a bow to what some television executives say is the 
conservatism of a morning audience. Others suspect it has more to 
do with the conservatism of television executives. 
</P>
<P>
	Each show starts at 7 a.m. and runs for two hours. Each has a  
man and woman as co-hosts, while a colleague reads news headlines. 
Each has a black man delivering the weather. Each cuts away to 
local news from affiliates at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS's story mix won't become clear until well after Monday, but  
it isn't expected to deviate from formula: Hard news reports early, 
light features as 9 a.m. approaches and the audience becomes 
predominantly women. 
</P>
<P>
	Each show has a midtown Manhattan storefront studio so  
passers-by can peer in and maybe get on camera. And they're close 
enough to one another so you can walk from show to show in a single 
morning: Start at Times Square for ``GMA,'' head up Sixth Avenue to 
``Today'' in Rockefeller Center, then north on Fifth Avenue to see 
what CBS built. 
</P>
<P>
	You might even see the same newsmaker guest. After the U.S.  
Open, women's champion Serena Williams batted tennis balls with 
Katie Couric on ``Today,'' and within an hour she was chatting with 
Diane Sawyer on ``GMA.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only the hosts set the programs apart: Couric and Matt Lauer on  
``Today,'' Sawyer and Charles Gibson on ``Good Morning America,'' 
Bryant Gumbel and Jane Clayson on ``The Early Show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morning television has a rhythm that should be not be tampered  
with, says Steve Friedman, executive producer of CBS's new entry. 
``I don't think we have to go out there and reinvent the wheel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friedman is one example of the incestuous nature of morning TV.  
He's a former executive producer of ``Today,'' where Gumbel spent 
15 years. Diane Sawyer was once a morning anchor at CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	With so much the same, why compete?  
</P>
<P>
	Money, that's why.  
</P>
<P>
	Morning may be the last remaining gold rush open to networks,  
the one time period when audiences are growing instead of 
shrinking. ``Today'' is so dominant in the ratings that it netted 
more than $100 million for NBC last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've established a program that the others are trying  
to copy,'' says Jeff Zucker, ``Today'' executive producer. 
</P>
<P>
	It wouldn't be the first time; imitation is television's  
favorite compliment because it signals success. For example, 
networks are rushing to develop game shows now after ABC's ``Who 
Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' dominated the ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anything, the morning shows are moving in the direction of  
becoming more similar because the `Today' show has been so 
successful,'' says Mike Greco, who monitors the morning television 
market for the New York City advertising firm BBD&AMP;O. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS has been the morning doormat for decades, and ``The Early  
Show'' represents the network's boldest competitive move in years. 
ABC put great effort into improving ``Good Morning America'' in the 
past year, installing Sawyer and Gibson and opening its flashy 
Times Square studio. 
</P>
<P>
	During the depths of ratings trouble at ``GMA,'' it briefly sank  
to third behind CBS early last winter. And at times, the two shows 
combined couldn't match the ``Today'' audience numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC News President David Westin groped for ways to halt the long  
decline at ``Good Morning America,'' but he never really considered 
trying something completely different. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a reason why the basic formula for morning programs  
are somewhat similar,'' Westin says, ``and it's because that's 
what's worked and it's worked for many, many years. I'm sure it's 
possible to come up with a radical new format that nobody else has 
ever thought of, but the chances are against that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Therefore, he says, success lies in building a stronger program,  
not in changing the format. 
</P>
<P>
	Ratings provide ammunition for his theory: ``Good Morning  
America'' doesn't have anywhere near the audience that ``Today'' 
has, but for the first time in years it's gaining viewers instead 
of losing them. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives say that morning, more than any other time, is when  
viewers yearn for the familiar. They want to know what happened 
while they slept; they want to hear about the weather. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are just waking up and running around in their  
underwear with toothpaste dripping out of their mouth,'' says 
Zucker. ``It's the time of day when the audience neither wants to 
be irritated nor jolted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The experience of veteran TV producer Bob Shanks is a cautionary  
tale. Shanks honed the traditional format to great success in the 
late 1970s with ``Good Morning America,'' but failed miserably at 
trying to develop something new for CBS in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Actress Mariette Hartley and newsman Rolland Smith were hosts of  
``The Morning Program,'' a show with a studio audience that 
featured comedians like Jerry Seinfeld and Ellen DeGeneres -- unsual 
programming for the time slot. The show also offered a TV critic 
and personal ads. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to break the mold,'' Shanks says.  
</P>
<P>
	``The Morning Program'' annoyed viewers and CBS's  
traditionalists. It was off the air in less than a year, yet is 
still cited as the last real network attempt to try something 
different. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Shanks smells the fear of TV executives. ``Maybe it's my  
example,'' he says. ``They saw it was a plane crash, and they don't 
want to do something like that. The risks are so high and the 
failures so public, that most of them are afraid to take chances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just this month, NBC News President Andrew Lack expressed  
concern about too much sameness. It was unusual, since TV 
executives usually avoid public criticism of rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's actually a terrible indictment of television that we've  
ended up with three programs now that look so much like each 
other,'' Lack told reporters at a celebration of the ``Today'' 
ratings success. 
</P>
<P>
	There are, of course, obvious differences in what stories each  
network does. And, at least for now, ABC and NBC are different in 
how they use their windows for public interaction. ``Good Morning 
America'' uses the public as a studio audience for cooking 
demonstrations and town meetings with presidential contenders. NBC 
uses fans to lend a festive air to events like outdoor concerts. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS, in touting ``The Early Show,'' says it wants more  
information than personalities -- a dig at NBC's attempts, through 
advertising, to depict its team as ``America's First Family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There is something of a creeping narcissism in the morning  
shows that we would like to be an antidote to,'' says CBS News 
President Andrew Heyward. 
</P>
<P>
	Can three shows succeed, given their sameness? It's certainly  
not unprecedented. The same three networks have been running 
similar evening news shows in the same time slot for decades. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
