<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knight Discusses Hunting Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Indiana coach Bob Knight held center  
court once again -- discussing fan support, Luke Recker and 
occasional tiffs with officials -- as he addressed about 3,000 
people during a speech at the university Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight also made a quick reference to his latest public incident  
-- accidentally shooting a friend while hunting grouse earlier this 
month in Spooner, Wis. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight was cited last week for failure to report a hunting  
accident and for hunting without a nonresident small game license. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday night, a student asked Knight for a seat at the end  
of the bench during one game this season. Knight granted the 
student his wish, on one condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can sit at the end of the bench, but if I hear the first  
word, you're gone,'' Knight said. ``I don't mean gone for the day, 
I've been known to shoot people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The response brought a round of applause.  
</P>
<P>
	After lecturing for 30 minutes, Knight opened the floor to any  
student who had a ``highly intelligent question.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first student asked two questions, including whether the  
coach was bothered when Luke Recker transferred while Knight was 
away in Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as where I was when the decision was made, I don't  
think that's a big deal,'' Knight said. ``I think when a guy has an 
announcement, make the announcement. I didn't really care, I still 
caught a lot of fishes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Recker transferred to Arizona in April after two seasons at  
Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've given 117 scholarships since I've been at Indiana for 28  
years,'' Knight said. ``And of that 117, 37 kids for one reason or 
another have left. Eighty have stayed and played all four years. 
That's about 30 percent that we've lost. 
</P>
<P>
	``The national average is about 38 percent. That is never  
mentioned when somebody talks about a kid leaving Indiana. Not only 
are we not near the bottom, we are well into the upper half of 
schools relative to retaining scholarship players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Knight also took a jab at the officials while discussing fan  
behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every once in a while even I get upset at the officials,''  
Knight said. ``So I don't mind you adding in your two bits 
occasionally when there is a bad call.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This was the second consecutive year Knight addressed students  
and members of the Bloomington community. Knight's lectures had 
been an Indiana tradition, but he took a five-year hiatus starting 
in 1993. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
