<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NatWest Defends Against Hostile Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- National Westminster PLC took steps today to  
defend itself against a $34.4 billion hostile bid by the Bank of 
Scotland, announcing plans to sell several businesses, cut 1,650 
jobs and return cash to shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest scoffed at its Scottish rival's claim that $1.7 billion  
could be saved by merging the two companies and advised 
shareholders to spurn the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bank of Scotland is attempting to hijack cost savings that  
belong to NatWest shareholders and is claiming unrealistic merger 
benefits,'' chief executive David Rowland said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I urge NatWest shareholders to reject the offer which is  
ill-conceived and significantly undervalues NatWest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest unveiled its strategy in documents sent to shareholders  
and the London Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland shocked the genteel British banking  
establishment last month when it announced a takeover bid for 
NatWest and harshly criticized the London-based bank's executives 
for their performance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Scottish bank's aggressive move triggered speculation that  
other bidders for NatWest might emerge with offers of their own. So 
far, none has done so. 
</P>
<P>
	Responding to NatWest's announcement, Bank of Scotland said the  
defense plan does nothing to detract from the logic of its takeover 
offer. The Scottish Bank said that NatWest's latest ideas even 
concede the merits of key elements of its own proposed strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The credibility of NatWest's claims is undermined by its  
history of failure to deliver under substantially the same 
management team,'' Bank of Scotland said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest plans to sell its institutional fund management arm,  
Gartmore; its capital market business, Greenwich NatWest; its 
venture capital unit, NatWest Equity Partners; and a bank in 
Northern Ireland, Ulster Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest will return money from the asset sales to its  
shareholders in an effort to keep them loyal. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland, for its part, has said it intends to unload  
Gartmore, Greenwich and Ulster Bank if its bid succeeds. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its defense, NatWest stressed its goal of  
streamlining management and focusing on services for retail 
customers, business clients and wealthy individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	It plans to reduce the number of its business units to five from  
13 and ``de-layer'' management to allow for speedier 
decision-making. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank also plans to cut 1,650 jobs, most of them by year's  
end. These would be in addition to a planned reduction of 10,000 
jobs announced previously. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest fired chief executive Derek Wanless earlier this month  
and replaced him with Rowland. It also hired former Lloyd's of 
London trouble-shooter Ron Sandler as chief operating officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the Bank of Scotland made its bid on Sept. 24, NatWest  
share prices have traded well above the Scottish bank's offer 
price. Analysts have said that investors were probably holding out 
for a higher bid from Bank of Scotland or a counterbid from another 
buyer. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest is currently valued at around $38.8 billion, some $4.37  
billion more than what Bank of Scotland has offered. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest stock was trading down 2 percent while Bank of Scotland  
shares were up 1 percent in midday trading on London. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
