<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Art Reaching the Masses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Julie Fergang always loved art but found buying  
intimidating -- until she got on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	She bought a $1,700 Mario Giacomelli photograph last spring from  
the comfort of her New York City apartment. It went so well, she 
has been checking the Net once or twice a week for more items to 
buy. 
</P>
<P>
	High-end art priced at $1,000 or more is reaching the masses.  
With the Internet, no longer are buyers required to visit galleries 
or auction houses, where newcomers complain they do not always feel 
welcome unless they carry checkbooks with large balances. 
</P>
<P>
	Artstar.com will join the growing list of art-auction sites  
Thursday. Last week, mass-market auction site eBay created a 
special section for higher-priced artwork and antiques. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the old-line auction houses such as Christie's and  
Sotheby's are preparing to go online. Sotheby's has more than 
10,000 pieces lined up for two sites later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fergang, who used artnet.com for her purchase, said the Net  
opens up art to ``a whole different class of buyers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a very old-world charm to running into Christie's or  
Sotheby's,'' she said, ``but there the eyes are on you, and there's 
an old-world intimidation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Artnet.com has sold some 350 pieces worth more than $1 million  
to Ms. Fergang and other collectors since March. During the past 
two weeks, the site sold a 1967 Andy Warhol screenprint for $34,650 
and a 1980 Marc Chagall lithograph for $16,800. 
</P>
<P>
	Hans Neuendorf, a former gallery owner who started Artnet, said  
he is trying to change the traditionally exclusive art world by 
giving customers privacy and access to information. ``That 
liberates them and makes it easier for them to buy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Galleries that have sold online agree that the Net is changing  
the industry for the better. 
</P>
<P>
	William Bartman, who runs Art Resources Transfer in New York,  
said galleries and art dealers are generally in big cities such as 
New York and Los Angeles. Through the Internet, he has received 35 
orders from such locales as Gulfport, Miss., and Austin, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are coming from places we would never normally have  
contact with,'' he said. ``They never would have walked into the 
space we have in New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The inability to actually touch the art is not necessarily a  
drawback. Long before the Internet, art collectors bought without 
first seeing the work in person. Galleries and auction houses 
published catalogs and accepted bids by telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, the Internet raises concerns about the potential  
for fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	Long-time collector Ken Raboy in Dallas said he bought an Warhol  
print through eBay for about $1,200, and it arrived with a two-inch 
tear. He contacted the seller and was told the warranty lasted only 
three days. He still buys on the Internet, but with caution. 
</P>
<P>
	Many art auction sites now offer authentication services and  
guarantees for the higher-priced goods. Even eBay, which considers 
itself no more than a pipeline to connect buyer with seller, now 
offers guarantees for the higher-end items sold at its Great 
Collections section. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before you write a ten- or maybe a hundred-thousand-dollar  
check, you want a guarantee. You want to chat with an expert,'' 
said Steve Westly, eBay's vice president for marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	David Redden, executive vice president for Sotheby's in New  
York, can no longer ignore the Internet. When Sotheby's held an 
online auction last year, 40 percent of customers were new. 
</P>
<P>
	Redden said he does not think the Internet will entirely replace  
the traditional auction house, particularly for the items priced in 
the millions of dollars, but he is not ruling anything out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been an auctioneer for 24 years, and I don't really want  
to be redundant yet,'' he said. ``But one thing I've learned is 
that no one will speculate too far ahead. You just don't know 
what's going to be coming down the road in terms of technology.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0413 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 21:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Inventor of Ear Thermometer Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Theodore H. Benzinger, inventor of the ear  
thermometer and a pioneer in the field of biothermodynamics, died 
Tuesday at Maplewood retirement community in Bethesda, Md. He was 
94. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Stuttgart, Germany, Benzinger became director of  
aero-medical department of the German air force in 1934. During the 
next decade he studied decompression and physiology in pilots and 
was a test pilot himself. 
</P>
<P>
	After World War II, Benzinger joined the U.S. Naval Medical  
Research Institute in Bethesda, where his discoveries included the 
thermodynamic quantities of biochemical reactions and the mechanism 
for measuring temperatures in humans. 
</P>
<P>
	His invention 40 years ago of a highly accurate ear thermometer,  
later modified by other researchers, made it possible to zone in on 
the ``human thermostat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Benzinger held patents for a dozen inventions and authored 136  
scientific papers and chapters in 12 books. He retired from the 
Naval Research Medical Institute in 1970 as director of its 
bioenergetics division but continued working at the National 
Institutes of Standards and Technology. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0414 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 14:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Falcons' Anderson Aches for Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUWANEE, Ga. (AP) -- As the Atlanta Falcons' 1-6 season continues  
to unwind, Jamal Anderson feels helpless. 
</P>
<P>
	The All-Pro running back can only massage his surgically  
repaired knee and watch each week as his teammates find new ways to 
lose. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the hardest part -- knowing you can't help,'' Anderson  
said Wednesday. ``The thing for me is watching all this -- we did so 
much to build up football in this town. Now it's going down the 
tubes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons are at the bottom of the NFC as they prepare to play  
Carolina (2-4) at the Georgia Dome on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson reflected on last season as if it happened in another  
lifetime. On their way to a 14-2 regular season and a 
franchise-first trip to the Super Bowl, the Falcons captured the 
state's attention by winning their first division title in 18 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	At the center of it all was the flamboyant and talkative  
Anderson. Though tight end O.J. Santiago originated the notorious 
Dirty Bird moves, most of the credit went Anderson, who broke into 
the dance every time he scored. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to come back to a ship that's sinking and have to  
pull out all the water,'' said Anderson, whose season ended Sept. 
20 with a knee injury at Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of guys with a lot of pride in this room. We're  
so close (to finding ways to win).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ranking 29th in the NFL with an average of 69.3 yards per game,  
Atlanta's ground game has bottomed out. Running backs Ken Oxendine 
and Byron Hanspard are averaging a meager 2.7 yards per carry. 
Neither has scored a touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	The longest run for an active player belongs to a quarterback.  
Chris Chandler broke off a 14-yard run in the season opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Worse yet, backup quarterback Tony Graziani has the team's best  
average per carry at 5.8 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	How badly does this team need a 100-yard effort from one of its  
running backs? 
</P>
<P>
	``That's like asking what $100 would do for a homeless person,''  
right tackle Ephraim Salaam said. ``We've got to find some 
confidence, that's the biggest thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The situation is bleak enough that Atlanta is considering former  
Carolina return specialist Winslow Oliver, who was cut by the 
Panthers and then signed to the Falcons' practice squad when 
Anderson was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliver's claim to fame is owning the NFC's third-best punt  
return average in his rookie year of 1996. The 5-foot-7, 180-pound 
former New Mexico standout has carried the ball one time since the 
beginning of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to try everything we can,'' said Falcons coach  
Dan Reeves. ``I think Winslow is familiar enough now that we could 
utilize him some, but we have got to try something. We can't 
continue to run the football averaging 2.7 a carry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, who signed a five-year deal worth $32 million in  
August, traces the problems to a breakdown in communication and a 
lack of familiarity. 
</P>
<P>
	A Falcon since 1994, Anderson played his entire career with left  
tackle Bob Whitfield and center Robbie Tobeck. He spent four years 
running behind right guard Gene Williams and two behind left guard 
Calvin Collins. Salaam was a rookie last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The principal names this year are the same -- despite Collins  
shifting to a backup role and Greg Bishop splitting time with Bob 
Hallen at left guard. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew how Tobeck and Gene would lean on a certain play, which  
way they tended to go,'' Anderson said. ``When you play that long 
together, you become like family.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991027.0415 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-27 15:30:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Probe of Starr May Be Reviewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress may delve into the details of the  
difficult relationship between Independent Counsel Ken Starr and 
the Justice Department, Sen. Arlen Specter said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Specter's statement followed an Associated Press story that  
Attorney General Janet Reno had informed Starr just four days 
before his impeachment testimony that the department would review 
allegations against his office's conduct of the Monica Lewinsky 
investigation. Unknown to Starr, word of Reno's plans had already 
leaked to the news media before the Sunday afternoon meeting 
between the prosecutor and the attorney general. 
</P>
<P>
	Specter said he was ``a little surprised'' by the timing of  
Reno's decision to review the conduct of Starr's office, so close 
to the independent counsel's testimony before the House impeachment 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The senator, a member of the Senate Judiciary Committee, said  
the panel might want to examine the situation of ``the investigator 
being investigated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Specter also said the committee might want to evaluate new  
Justice Department regulations that are replacing the Independent 
Counsel law that expired June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Starr stepped down this month after five stormy years of  
investigating President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, the results 
of Justice's internal review remain secret. Any findings still 
could affect how the public ultimately views Starr's work, which 
will be summarized in a final report to be written by his 
successor, Robert Ray. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior Justice official said the department took two steps in  
deference to Starr's inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	First, department officials waited until after Starr had  
completed the Lewinsky grand jury investigation and had sent his 
report to the House to discuss the issue of the review with him 
again, the official said, speaking only on condition of anonymity. 
Second, Starr was told the department was prepared to work with his 
office to find a way to conduct a review ``in the least intrusive 
way possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Iran-Contra prosecutor Lawrence Walsh, a critic of the  
Lewinsky sex-and-cover-up investigation, said he sympathized with 
Starr and ``would hate to have the Justice Department doing that to 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he added, ``As long as the attorney general has the power to  
remove an independent counsel, she has the power to investigate his 
questionable activities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh said friction between an independent counsel and the  
department is inevitable because the department ``feels a duty to 
assist bona fide prosecutions, but at the same time it's counsel 
for the government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Excerpts from letters provided to AP show the relationship  
between Justice and Starr only grew worse behind closed doors as 
the impeachment drama played out in public last winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Within weeks of the meeting, Starr's office became convinced  
Justice had made its move in order to give Democrats fresh fodder 
to attack Starr as the House drew closer to the impeachment vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``The timing'' of the review ``raises more starkly than anything  
in our relationship to date -- the specter of politically motivated 
interference,'' Starr deputy Robert Bittman wrote the office of 
Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder on Dec. 2, 1998. ``You decline 
to apprise us of even the nature of the allegations against us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Justice Department -- which could not investigate the  
president owing to the obvious conflict of interest -- proposes at 
this most delicate juncture to investigate the investigator,'' 
Bittman wrote, adding a complaint about the leak. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's prosecutors, at Reno's suggestion, had met with Justice  
officials on Nov. 23 and Dec. 1 to explore ways of working together 
to review the allegations, which had been flooding into the 
department from Clinton supporters on Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them:  
</P>
<P>
	--Starr should have told the Justice Department of his 1994  
contacts with Paula Jones's lawyers in her sexual harassment 
lawsuit against Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	--Starr's prosecutors should not have discussed an immunity deal  
with Ms. Lewinsky without her lawyer present. 
</P>
<P>
	--Starr's office wired Linda Tripp to record a conversation with  
Ms. Lewinsky before Starr had jurisdiction from Reno to proceed 
with the Lewinsky probe. 
</P>
<P>
	For six weeks after the Dec. 1 meeting, there was no contact.  
Then came a reply Jan. 14. 
</P>
<P>
	``I reject in the strongest terms'' the ``charge that the  
department has engaged in 'politically motivated interference,''' 
Holder's office wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Holder's office said the letter from Starr's office was ``wholly  
unjustified'' and that the department would list the allegations it 
intended to review. 
</P>
<P>
	The friction with Justice weighed heavily on Starr, who has  
flashed his bitterness at Reno in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our relations soured over the last 18 months,'' Starr wrote in  
The Wall Street Journal last week. ``At times, political appointees 
in the department actively interfered with our investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, discussions resumed between Justice and Starr. On  
May 28, Starr supplied the department's Office of Professional 
Responsibility a point-by-point rebuttal to the allegations 
totaling several hundred pages. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office never heard back.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
